[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Welcome to Swiercz's 1. d4 - "]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D35"]
[PlyCount "22"]

{[Welcome to Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1.d4 Part 2] This course completes my two part Lifetime Repertoire on 1. d4 . In Part 1 I covered 1... Nf6 lines, while in this Part 2 , I cover 1... d5 and some of the remaining loose ends.  I have always been interested in all these lines, and I am happy to share my knowledge as a player and coach, given it is good to analyze them from both perspectives.   I played 1.d4 nearly all my life, and after I created this course I improved my knowledge. I believe my recommendations here are great opening weapons against QGD, QGA, Slav, and others.   As a coach, I have studied these lines with other players, many top Grand Masters, and my students at University; training with them for almost two years, I managed to understand the positions from a coaching perspective, answering questions such as what students need.  I am the kind of person who searches for the truth of positions to understand the best way to play them, so that is the reason I have analyzed all of these lines in-depth. Also, in the process, I have found many interesting ideas I want to share with you.  With this course, I decided to accept the challenge and find a way to face sharp openings and lines that made me feel uncomfortable in the past as Carlsbad Structures after 2...e6 . Let's see...} 1. d4 d5 ({After} 1... e6 2. c4 b6 {the advance,} 3. e4 {, is simply the way to go. During the course I explain how to put Black under pressure.}) 2. c4 e6 {This is the Queen's Gambit Declined, before writing this course, of course, I knew many ideas but I wasn´t too sure about how to play these positions. I had some games there but it wasn´t the most common response by my opponents.} ({Of course, Queen's Gambit Accepted is included in the course too:} 2... dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 {, we'll see what happens after all these modern lines} 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 {. However, sidelines are covered as well:} ({• Chigorin Variation:} 6... Nc6 {.}) ({• Albin Counter-Gambit:} 6... e5 {.})) 3. Nc3 Nf6 ({Probably} 3... c6 {is one of the sharpest lines in chess, which invites White to play} 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Qxd4 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+ 8. Be2 {This is the line I was always interested in. Based on what I have learned in this course, I believe we can put a lot of pressure here. Actually, it is more difficult to play with Black than with White. For example, after} Na6 {I discovered that the most challenging move is . The bishop is very well placed because it prevents Black's castle.}) 4. cxd5 {The most classical approach.} exd5 5. Bg5 {Black can play many options here.} Be7 ({Something I learned is how to react after} 5... Bb4 {, which is a really sharp continuation, but after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 {we have this very good move} 9. a3 $1 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 h5 11. f3 Nxg3 12. hxg3 {this pawn structure looks good for White. We can always have the king safe on f2 . Playing g3 - g4 and Nh3 is a good plan for White.}) ({After} 5... c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. Qf3 Bg6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6 {there is an endgame where I learned how to play properly and put some pressure on Black's position} 10. Nf3 Nd7 11. Nh4 Be7 12. Ne2 f5 {. We will cover this line in more detail in the course.}) 6. e3 c6 7. Bd3 ({I want to share how to place the pieces, especially the bishop in f1 and the night in g1 . In general, I discovered that} 7. Bd3 {and} Z0 8. Nge2 {are the best way to develop them.}) 7... O-O 8. Nge2 h6 ({Playing with} 8... h6 {or not doesn´t make any difference.}) 9. Bh4 {Somehow 8... h6 helps us to continue with f2 - f3 , Bf2 , and e3 - e4 . That pawn advance is going to be the plan even if Black doesn´t play h7 - h6 .} Re8 10. O-O a5 {Probably Black is going to play this move, as it's the best one.} ({One of my main discoveries here is that after} 10... Nbd7 {, it's possible to completely prevent Blanck's plan with . It looks absolutely ridiculous at first because we are taking away our possibility of doing any minority attack after a5 but in fact, it stops b7 - b5 , now we can play f2 - f3 and e3 - e4 very quickly.}) 11. f3 b5 {Black may try b5 - b4 and c6 - c5 , while White wants to push e3 - e4 after preparing it with Rc1 , Bf2 , Kh1 , h2 - h3 , Ng3 and Nce2 I cover these ideas in the course. I recommend you to study the course starting from the 'Quickstarter' chapters because they offer an overview of the entire course. At the same time, you have the 'Move Trainer' mode that can teach you the proper move order, while you can test yourself. Finally, I recommend you to watch the video, where I explain our plans in-depth, listening to the explanation is always useful!   Creating this course was a great experience for me, and I'm really happy to share my discoveries with you. Please, remember there is a forum where you can share any ideas and where I can answer all your questions.   I would like to thank you for purchasing this course and I wish you a happy study!} *

