[Black "3...a6 with 5...Bb7 6.b3 cxb3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D22"]
[PlyCount "31"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 a6 4. e3 b5 {This variation attempts to defend the c4 -pawn, but White's resources of a4 and b3 are sufficient to get it back.} 5. a4 Bb7 6. b3 {Challenging the entire pawn chain.} cxb3 {This may be tempting, as it leads to simplifications, and one may think this should equalize. It is not true, however.} 7. axb5 axb5 8. Rxa8 Bxa8 9. Bxb5+ c6 ({Otherwise, Black has serious problems with his king along the light squares.} 9... Nd7 $2 10. Qxb3 Ngf6 11. Ne5 e6 12. Qa4) (9... Bc6 10. Bxc6+ Nxc6 11. d5) 10. Bc4 e6 11. Qxb3 Nf6 12. O-O {Black has issues completing his development here. The pressure on the a2 - g8 diagonal is a serious problem.} Be7 13. Ne5 {This looks the most promising - White goes immediately after the weaknesses on f7 and e6 .} O-O 14. Nxf7 Kxf7 15. Bxe6+ Ke8 16. Nc3 {Black's position is, of course, very shaky here. His king is unsafe and it is hard to imagine that it will get to safety anytime soon. White has long-lasting compensation. White's main idea is Bd2 and Ra1 , but there are also ideas of Na4 . For the purposes of the Quickstarter, the line ends here. The extended version of this variation can be found in chapter 2 .} *

