[PlyCount "35"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 a6 4. e3 b5 {This variation attempts to defend the c4 -pawn, but White's resources of a4 and b3 are sufficient to get it back.} 5. a4 Bb7 6. b3 {Challenging the entire pawn chain.} e6 ({Black can play} 6... Nf6 {as well but it would sooner or later transpose anyway. One thing is for sure, though - As we've seen, Black should not play cxb3 .}) 7. bxc4 bxc4 ({Necessary. Black needs to simplify the position and play for ...c5 . After} 7... b4 $6 {, White plays} 8. c5 {gaining space, similarly to Bb4+?! Bd2 Bxd2+ Nbxd2 b4 c5!± .}) 8. Bxc4 Nf6 ({Other moves that were played here are} 8... Nd7 {or c5 , but they would likely transpose either way as ... Nf6 sooner or later must be played.}) 9. O-O {White has a fairly simple plan here: Nbd2 , the bishop may go to b2 or a3 (say, Qb3 - Ba3 is an idea), while Rb1 is often useful, pretty much depending on what Black does. Black has many options now, but I don't think he can equalize.} c5 10. Nbd2 Nbd7 {The most solid response. Black should keep the tension in the center and support the c5 -pawn.} 11. Rb1 Qc7 12. Ba3 Be7 {White has a lot of options here. If you turn on the engine, anything gives White an advantage. I would like to recommend an idea that feels the best to me.} 13. Bd3 ({White wants to play Qc2 and Rfc1 and apply lots of pressure on the c -file. In that way, the a4 -pawn is guarded by the queen, which is a problem after both} 13. Qe2 {and Qb3 (see the informational in chapter )}) 13... cxd4 ({Probably Black should clarify the situation in the center before he gets tied up, as shown here after} 13... O-O {.}) 14. Bxe7 Kxe7 15. Rc1 ({An important move to destabilize Black's queen.} 15. Nxd4 Rhc8 {is fine for Black!}) 15... Qb8 16. Nxd4 Rc8 17. Qb3 Kf8 18. a5 {White retains better chances due to the weak pawn on a6 , which we will try to exploit in the future.} *

