[Result "*"]
[ECO "D11"]
[PlyCount "35"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 {In chapter 3, I look at lines where Black can try to hold on to the c4 -pawn but, as we will see, without success. White's main ideas are a4 and b3 , and Black does not have a proper way to respond to them.} b5 (3... c6 4. e3 b5 5. a4 {is another move order.}) 4. a4 c6 5. e3 {White plays here for b3 , either immediately or first axb5 and then b3 . Black is unable to keep the extra pawn, and White will have some positional advantage, as the analysis shows.} e6 (5... Nf6 {is roughly the same, but it leaves Black fewer options - now, Black does not have an option of ... Bb4 as in the main line.} 6. axb5 cxb5 7. b3 {with an inevitable transposition as White gets the pawn back.}) 6. axb5 {I would recommend trading on b5 first. That way, the pawn on b5 is less stable, and in case the c4 -pawn moves, we can play Bxb5 with a check.} (6. b3 {is another option, but after} Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ {, White cannot play} 8. Nbxd2 {due to} c3 $1 {For this reason, Nfxd2 should be played, but it is kind of passive.}) 6... cxb5 7. b3 {Black can play here with ... Bb4 or without.} Nf6 {This is probably more solid.} 8. bxc4 bxc4 9. Bxc4 {White got his pawn back. Such positions are typically better for White due to the pawn majority, while the a -pawn has a serious chance of becoming a liability for Black.} Bd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Ba3 {White should trade dark-squared bishops as then Black's dark squares will become weak.} Bb7 12. Nbd2 a5 {Black should try to push his pawn, but White manages not only to block it but also attack it.} 13. Qb3 Ra7 {Here, White has many options. I like the direct approach the most.} 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Qa3 {By trading the bishops and offering the queen trade, White wants to double rooks on the a -file.} Qxa3 16. Rxa3 Nbd7 17. Rfa1 Rfa8 18. Bb5 {Making space for the knight on c4 . Generally, Black here is on the defensive side, and White will enjoy his advantage for a long time.} *

