1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Be6 {Holding on to the c4 -pawn in this artificial way does not lead to anything good for Black.} 5. Nc3 {White prepares Ng5 in order to meet ... Bd5 with e4 .} ({Nc6} 5. e4 Bg4 6. Be3 {is covered in Part 1 of the course in the section on the Tango! See here.}) 5... c6 6. Ng5 ({Going after the pair of bishops and wanting to recapture the c4 -pawn. The bishop has to move, as Qd7?! looks very awkward for Black.} 6. e4 h6 {Nxe6 Qxe6} 7. e5 {is a sample continuation.}) 6... Bd5 {Necessity. We are now entering a long sequence of moves, but White, in the end, will have a very promising position.} 7. e4 h6 8. exd5 hxg5 9. dxc6 Nxc6 10. d5 Ne5 {There were some games like this, but White has been scoring well here for a reason. White has a choice now between Bg5 and the alternative  Qd4 .} 11. Bxg5 {Without their light-squared bishop and behind in development, Black's position is difficult to play.  For the purposes of the Quickstarter, the line ends here. The extended version of this variation can be found here .} *

