1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A somewhat forgotten line, not played that often on the top level, but nonetheless, White should know what to do against it.} 5. Bxc4 {Recapturing the pawn, but also creating a threat of Bxf7 !} e6 6. Nc3 Nc6 {This is one of the pet lines of Baadur Jobava, who employed it successfully numerous times. The idea is to play ... Bd6 , ... O-O and ... e5 ASAP. White has many options here and despite Baadur's success, engines don't share his optimism for this line.} 7. h3 Bh5 (7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 {does not require much analysis - White is clearly better.}) 8. O-O Bd6 9. Re1 {An interesting move that essentially prepares g4 and e4 .} O-O 10. g4 Bg6 11. e4 e5 12. dxe5 {I like this the most. White enters a pleasant endgame leaving Black with a very bad Bg6 .} (12. d5 {is OK too, of course.}) 12... Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. f3 {White is much better in this endgame. The Bg6 is completely out of play.} *

