1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 a6 6. O-O b5 {Generally, playing ... b5 this early is not advised. White can play via a4 and challenge Black's queenside pawn structure. Additionally, White does not have to retreat to e2 , and Bd3 is a good option now, choosing plans connected with e4 !} 7. Bd3 {In many situations, White retreats to e2 and goes for a more positional battle. Here, however, White has an option of supporting the e4 push.} Bb7 {Black should begin with this move to prevent White from immediately playing e4 .} 8. a4 {Weakening Black's pawn structure.} b4 {In such positions, Black generally seizes some space on the queenside. Here, White needs to choose the right plan.} 9. Nbd2 {White wants to place the knight on c4 and prepare e4 push. Very often, a5 is also useful.} (9. b3 $2 {is what I played here once in Titled Tuesday, and it is not a correct plan here. It is much stronger to go for e4 ideas.}) 9... c5 10. Nc4 Nbd7 11. a5 {Fixing the pawn structure on the queenside. Black's pawn chain is somehow disrupted, and White may try to attack Black's weak pawns.} Be7 12. Re1 ({White is ready to push e4 . I like this more than} 12. Qe2 {, as after White plays e4 and e5 , Black does not have ... Bxf3 ideas here.}) 12... O-O (12... cxd4 13. exd4 {As we will explain next,  we recapture with the pawn.}) 13. e4 cxd4 14. e5 Nd5 15. Nxd4 Nc5 16. Bf1 {Bringing the bishop to safety and keeping everything defended. One may argue that Black is fine here: the knights are well-placed, no imminent weaknesses, etc. However, the same thing can be said about White's position, and we are the ones with more space. This gives further possibilities for improving his position, while Black progress here is quite limited. White may play Bd2 , Rc1 , and there are ideas of Qg4 or Qh5 as well.} ({White is definitely better. Rc8} 16. Bd2 {Rc7 Rc1 Rd7 Qg4± is a sample continuation.}) *

