1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 ({This move is slightly rarer than} 6... a6 {, but it is also quite common at the top level.}) 7. Nc3 cxd4 ({Another move order is} 7... Be7 8. Qe2 cxd4 9. Rd1 O-O 10. exd4 {.}) 8. exd4 Be7 {Generally, trading on d4 so early is not advised to Black. Here, White has a variety of setups from which to choose.} 9. Qe2 {I would recommend this setup because of its flexibility, but I admit many other setups are OK as well.} O-O ({Black needs to castle as soon as possible.} 9... Nxd4 $2 {is way too premature with the king in the center.} 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Rd1 {and Bb5 + is going to be very awkward to meet.}) 10. Rd1 ({White potentially may be threatening d5 , so Black needs to do something about it. According to the theory, the main moves are Na5 , Nb4 and} 10. Nd5 {, and I will focus on them.}) 10... Na5 {Pushing the bishop away and intending ... b6 -... Bb7 . But the knight will be a bit awkward on a5 now.} 11. Bd3 b6 {This is an important position.} 12. Qe5 {A bit unorthodox approach but a very strong idea - the queen simply goes towards the kingside, and White will soon launch an attack.} Bd6 13. Qg5 Bb7 14. Ne5 Nd5 (14... Nc6 15. Qh4 {with the idea Bg5 .}) 15. Qg3 {Of course, not trading queens. One of the ideas could be Ne4 , so Black can try to stop it.} f5 ({This weakens the e5 -square, but} 15... f6 16. Bxh7+ Kxh7 17. Qh3+ Kg8 18. Qxe6+ {is obviously worse.}) 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Bf4 {Of course, White is much better here.} *

