1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 ({This move is slightly rarer than} 6... a6 {, but it is also quite common at the top level.}) 7. Nc3 a6 {Black pretty much needs to play this move here. Otherwise, we will most likely enter an IQP position in a good version for White.} 8. d5 {One of the most challenging options here. I decided to recommend this line as it forces Black to either memorize or find lots of only or difficult moves, which may not be easy!} exd5 {This move is already an inaccuracy.} 9. Nxd5 {White has a very pleasant position here.} Be7 {Black may try to complete development in this way. We need to react energetically.} (9... Nxd5 10. Bxd5 {I find this position to be hardly advisable for Black. White wants to trade on c6 , and Black's pawn structure will be terrible. There is no good way for Black to prevent it. We explore the variation in more detail starting here .}) 10. e4 ({White quickly plays in the center. The e4 -pawn is untouchable.: Nxe4?} 10. Re1 {. Some sample lines: Nf6 Ng5} Nxd5 {Nxf7!!} ({Or} 10... O-O 11. Nxe7+ Nxe7 12. Bxf7+ $1)) 10... O-O 11. Bf4 {Again, the most precise move.} Bg4 ({Again, grabbing the e4 -pawn is a bad idea:} 11... Nxe4 12. Bc7 {followed by Re1 and the pressure on the e-file is too strong.}) 12. Nxe7+ Nxe7 ({After this, White gets a very comfortable endgame. Instead, after} 12... Qxe7 $5 13. Bd6 {White wins an exchange here, but things are far from clear. The extended version of this variation can be found here .}) 13. Qxd8 Rfxd8 14. Ng5 Bh5 15. f3 {Thanks to the pair of bishops, White is clearly better.} *

