1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 ({This move is slightly rarer than} 6... a6 {, but it is also quite common at the top level.}) 7. Nc3 a6 {Black pretty much needs to play this move here. Otherwise, we will most likely enter an IQP position in a good version for White.} 8. d5 {One of the most challenging options here. I decided to recommend this line as it forces Black to either memorize or find lots of only or difficult moves, which may not be easy!} Na5 {The most popular move here.} 9. b3 b5 10. Bd3 {White sacrifices the d5 -pawn for the initiative, as Black's king is unsafe in the center.} Nxd5 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. Bb2 {An instructive moment: after sacrificing a pawn, White continues the game as if nothing happened. Black cannot really comfortably complete his development (the Bf8 needs to keep defending the g7 -pawn), and White will open the center sooner or later. When that happens, it will be clear that Black's king will be in danger. Black tried many moves here, but nothing equalizes.} Bg4 (12... Be6 13. Qe2 {looks difficult for Black.}) 13. h3 Bh5 {This pin looks like a natural play for Black, but it does not solve Black's problems.} 14. Rc1 Nc6 15. Be2 {It is still uneasy to complete the development. White may even want to trade the bishops with Ne5 or Nd4 and then pressure Black's central pawns by placing another rook on d1 .} ({Qd7} 15. Qd2 Be7 16. Ne5 Nxe5 {Bxh5 O-O} 17. Bxe5 {Qf5 Bxg7 Kxg7} Bf3 {is a sample continuation.}) *

