1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} b5 {This weakens the queenside and is subject to a4 .} 8. Be2 {We need to retreat here, unlike in the 6... b5  line, as we already have b3 on the board, and plans with e4 here are not that great. With Be2 , however, we want to play Ne5 - Bf3 in the future.} Bb7 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. Nbd2 Be7 11. a4 {Finally, challenging the queenside and fighting for the c4 -square.} b4 {Black gains some space on the queenside and potentially will try to make use of c3 -square with ... Nd5 -... Bf6 .} (11... bxa4 12. Rxa4 {is far from optimal for Black.}) 12. Ne5 ({I would begin with this move, even though} 12. Nc4 {is fine, of course, too. The idea is Bf3 , and sometimes we may try Ne4 .}) ({After} 12. Ne5 {, trading would be a serious strategic error.} Nxe5 $2 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Nc4 {with a fantastic knight on c4 .}) 12... cxd4 13. Nxd7 Nxd7 14. Bxd4 O-O 15. Nc4 {White's position looks promising. Black's knight is far away from reaching the c3 -square, and our own Nc4 is pretty strong. Next, Bf3 is on our agenda, placing rooks on c1 and d1 and applying pressure in the center. Additionally, playing a5 could be on our agenda to fix the a6 -pawn as a weakness.} ({Nc5?! was tried in some games, but after} 15. Qc2 {I am not sure where this knight is headed, as after Ne4?!} Bf3 {, the pressure on the long diagonal is a big problem.}) ({Another try is Rc8} 15. Bf3 Qc7 16. a5 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Bf6 18. Bb6 Qb8 19. Rac1 {, which is also fine for White.}) *

