1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} Nc6 {I find this move to be imprecise. Now, we get a good version of the dxc5 line as the Nc6 is misplaced - most of the time it should go to d7 .} 8. dxc5 Qxd1 (8... Bxc5 {does not change much:} 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bb2 Ke7 11. Rc1 Bd6 12. Nbd2 {and the bishop will retreat to e2 to free the c4 -square for the knight.}) 9. Rxd1 Bxc5 10. Bb2 {White's position is simply better.} O-O 11. Be2 {Waiting with the development of the Nb1 , keeping the ideas of Nbd2 or Nc3 open.} ({Please note that Black cannot play Bd7 and comfortably complete development due to} 11. Bxf6 {winning a piece.}) 11... Be7 (11... Rd8 {Played by Aronian and probably the best move here, but still White's position is preferable. The extended version of this variation can be found here .}) 12. Nbd2 {With the b6 -square weakened, we can try to exploit it now and develop the knight to d2 . And if ... b5 , then of course a4 comes.} *

