1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} cxd4 {Trading on d4 right away is the main line here, as played numerous times by players like Nakamura, Dominguez, or MVL. However, the many alternatives need to be covered as well.} ({Note that} 7... Be7 $6 {is inaccurate as right now, White can trade on c5 , which results in a 7.dxc5 line but with an extra tempo for White. E.g.} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bb2 {or Qxd1 Rxd1 Bxc5 Be2!?⩲ intending Ne1 - Nd3 and Bf3 .}) 8. Nxd4 Bd6 {This is another option, alternative to ... Be7 , keeping the bishop a bit more active but also a bit more exposed. Now, not only can it run under some Nc4 ideas, but also a pin on the d-file might be unpleasant one day.} 9. Bb2 O-O 10. Nd2 e5 {Typically Black plays here via ... e5 , making use of the Bd6 .} 11. N4f3 Nc6 12. Be2 {White's position looks better. We will put immediate pressure on the e5 -pawn and the Bd6 . Generally, we don't mind when Black plays ... e4 as then, we will get the d4 -square.} Bc7 {Keeping the bishop and making Nc4 less strong.} ({After} 12... Be6 13. Nc4 Bxc4 14. bxc4 {, White gets the bishop pair. Rb1 and Qc2 come next.}) 13. Qc2 {By simply completing the development, White retains his edge.} Qe7 14. Rac1 h6 15. Rfd1 {Next, we will improve our knights with Nd2 - Nf1 - Ng3 and Nf3 - Nh4 , putting pressure on the f5 -square.} *

