1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 ({I would recommend going for the most principled line here. The resulting positions strike me as promising for White, and they require a lot of accuracy from Black to stay in the game. I should mention, though, that there have been many games played with} 6. Nc3 {as well, most notably a game Carlsen-Anand in the World Championship Match 2013, but the arising positions are generally speaking less promising than after Bd2 .}) 6... Qxd4 (6... Bxd2+ $6 {cannot be taken seriously - White immediately gets a fantastic position.} 7. Qxd2 Nf6 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Nf3 {Black will suffer here due to bad Bc8 and being less developed. White has clear advantage.}) 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+ 8. Be2 ({Not taking any prisoners - White goes for the maximum out of this crazy line.} 8. Ne2 {is a possible alternative; however, it is less challenging and Black should not have any issues equalizing there.}) 8... Na6 {The only good move in this position. Everything else simply fails.} (8... Ne7 $2 {is not a good way to complete development.} 9. Qd2 Ng6 10. Nh3 {preventing ... Qf4 . Next, O-O-O comes.} Na6 11. O-O-O f6 12. f3 Qe5 13. Bd6 Qh5 14. f4 Qh4 15. Rhf1 {and White is winning.}) 9. Bd6 ({Along with} 9. Ba5 {, this is the strongest move, but for this course I decided to focus on Bd6 as personally it feels the most challenging. The bishop is fantastic on d6 of course, crippling Black's development and ability to castle. White has here two main ideas: Qd2 and O-O-O , or Nf3 and O-O . Depending on what Black does, White should choose either of these accordingly.}) 9... Qxg2 {Black needs to accept the bait and grab the g2 -pawn to justify his risky opening choice. If White manages to play Nf3 , O-O for instance and Black is not in time to complete his development or generate counterplay, White can win in a miniature.} (9... Bd7 $2 10. Nf3 O-O-O 11. O-O {The plan of castling queenside here does not really work. White will simply crush on the queenside with b4 - b5 , or play more positionally with c5 .}) 10. Bf3 {A very interesting rare line that poses a lot of practical problems to Black. The first one is right there - where should Black retreat with the queen?} Qg5 {The queen is the most active here and it supports ... e5 . In some lines, Black has an idea of ... Qa5 +.} 11. Ne2 Ne7 (11... e5 {is not good due to} 12. Rg1 $1 {± with unpleasant pressure. Both e5 and g7 are weak.}) 12. Ng3 {A very rare move in this position that is recommended by the engines. The most popular move is Rg1 instead, but Black has easier task consolidating his position. And as this move is rare, people playing it with Black may be immediately out of book! The knight is headed to e4 . Here, Black has some choice but it is not an easy choice by any means. There are three decent moves that Black can play, but White is able to put Black under serious pressure everywhere, and often Black just makes it out of it alive with only moves.} (12. Rg1 $6 Qa5+ $1 {is good for Black:} 13. b4 Nxb4 14. Kf1 Na6) 12... e5 {This is probably the strongest reply by Black. The idea is to make a path for the Bc8 to develop.} (12... Nf5 {This is a human move which must be considered as it attempts to simplify the position. White has some choice here.} 13. h4 $5 {An interesting practical try that I decided to keep as main - you can find it analyzed in detail, starting here .}) 13. Qb3 {Developing the queen and at the same time keeping an eye on the b7 -pawn. We can keep the ideas of Ne4 and h4 for the future.} O-O {Here, White can increase the initiative with precise dynamic play.} 14. h4 Qf6 15. Ne4 Qe6 16. O-O-O {With Rhg1 next and a strong initiative. The pin is very annoying, so it makes sense for Black to untangle. The extended version of this variation can be found here .} *

