1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 {A very sharp line in which Black sacrifices a pawn for activity. We should be definitely familiar with it as if caught off guard, it can be really tricky to meet.} 5. Qa4+ (5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd1 exd5 7. Qxd5 {is another option that I was seriously considering here. But I found that after} Bd6 $5 {, it is not so easy to show an advantage. Still, the position is quite playable and relatively not explored so some ideas could be found there.}) 5... Bd7 (5... b5 $4 {was played in some games, but it is simply losing.} 6. Nxb5 Bd7 7. e4 $1 {and, thanks to the pin on the a-file, White does not lose a piece even if Black continues with ... a6 . Actually, White is just a pawn up, threatening d6 .}) 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6 {White has two options now: Qd1 or Qb3 . In this course, I cover 8. Qd1 , which, I think, is more challenging.} 8. Qd1 (8. Qb3 Na6 $1 {was played in a critical game for the line, Shankland-Carlsen (2022). I think Black should equalize quite comfortably with a few accurate moves, but as they were already played in the aforementioned game, I think many people will be familiar with what Magnus went for. Because of that, 8. Qd1 is my choice here.}) 8... Bc5 {The bishop typically belongs on the c5 -square in these positions. Black needs to quickly castle and look for active counterplay for the pawn.} 9. Nf3 O-O ({For} 9... Nc6 {, see 8... Nc6 line here .}) 10. e3 Nc6 (10... Qe7 {is simply another move order.} 11. Be2 Rd8 12. O-O Nc6 {with a transposition to chapter 12 . Nc6 O-O also transposes.}) 11. Be2 Qe7 12. O-O ({The main position in this line. Black has three main options now: Rfd8 , Rad8 , or quite popular lately,} 12. Ne5 {, which is the one we will examine in the Quickstarter.}) 12... Ne5 {This is not the most common move here, but the trend shifted towards it recently as it was played many times by Aryan Tari, and also Magnus Carlsen tried it a few times. That's why I decided to keep it as main.} 13. Qb3 {This is a new move here, but it is recommended by engines. I think it poses certain problems for Black. So far, the b7 -pawn needs attention.} Be6 {It seems like this is the most obvious move here - but this is precisely what White wants, as the bishop is not well placed on e6 .} 14. Qc2 {Now Black needs to decide what to do with the Ne5 .} Bg4 {This may seem logical but it runs into trouble.} 15. Ng5 ({With big advantage for White. For instance, Rad8 directed against White's Nd5 to decoy the defender of h7 . Bxg4 Nexg4} 15. h3 {Ne5 Bd2± with a healthy extra pawn.}) *

