1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 {Black uses this move order when he wants to avoid the Bg5 lines and navigate towards the g3 lines. Right now, the Bg5 lines are not good enough (there is no pin), while g3 is not in our repertoire. Fortunately, there is another good option.} 6. dxc5 {This line is perhaps the simplest solution to the Tarrasch.} Nf6 7. Be3 {This may look a bit awkward, but the move defends an important pawn which will become relevant later on. For now, White will fianchetto the kingside bishop.} Be7 {Instead of recovering the pawn immediately, Black hopes to complete development and recover the c5 -pawn at a later time.} 8. g3 O-O 9. Bg2 Ng4 {Black should try to get the dark-squared bishop even at the cost of the d5 -pawn. White has many good options here.} 10. Qxd5 {With this move, White comfortably retains the extra material.} Nxe3 11. fxe3 Be6 12. Qe4 {Giving away the c5 -pawn, but with Rd1 and Nd4 next, we will stabilize the situation in the center.} Bxc5 13. Rd1 Qf6 (13... Qb6 $6 {and, despite the double attack on b2 and e3 , after} 14. Ng5 $1 {White has the advantage.}) 14. Nd4 Rae8 15. Qf4 {I don't think Black has sufficient compensation, even though White's pawns are doubled. White should have an advantage due to the pressure on the long diagonal, the extra pawn and a strong knight on d4 which can never be traded unless Black wants to straighten out our pawn structure for us.} *

