[ECO "D32"]
[PlyCount "37"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 {Black uses this move order when he wants to avoid the Bg5 lines and navigate towards the g3 lines. Right now, the Bg5 lines are not good enough (there is no pin), while g3 is not in our repertoire. Fortunately, there is another good option.} 6. dxc5 {This line is perhaps the simplest solution to the Tarrasch.} d4 {Black pretty much must play this move - otherwise, he will be down a pawn.} ({After} 6... Bxc5 $2 7. Qxd5 {White is just a pawn up. For example:} Qb6 8. e3 Nf6 9. Qb3) 7. Na4 Bxc5 (7... b5 $6 {This is a typical resource in the Tarrasch, and one might get scared seeing it, as it looks like the Na4 can get trapped in some lines. However, there is nothing to worry about. You can find the extended version of this variation here .}) 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Qxc5 10. b4 ({A slightly less common move than} 10. Rc1 {followed by} Qb6 11. e3 {, which is relatively well-known. Many of the players that go for the Tarrasch will surely know 10.Rc1 , but 10.b4 is less explored, and there is a chance that it will cause certain practical problems.}) 10... Qb6 11. Qa4 {Here, Black needs to be very accurate in order not to become much worse. The threat is obviously b5 , so Black's next move is obvious.} a6 12. e3 dxe3 13. fxe3 {Unfortunately, White cannot recapture with the bishop, as it would have hung the b4 -pawn. But now, b5 is again a threat that Black cannot ignore.} Rb8 {Stepping aside from the a -file, reducing the strength of the b5 idea. White should go for it anyway, though.} 14. b5 axb5 {Now White has a choice.} 15. Bxb5 {A new move here, which I decided to recommend due to its surprise value and objective strength.} ({Of course, White is also slightly better after} 15. Qxb5 Qxb5 16. Bxb5) 15... Nge7 16. Qb4 {Black faces some problems here.} Bd7 {Other moves are worse.} 17. Bxc6 bxc6 ({After} 17... Qxc6 18. O-O {, Black cannot castle due to the e7 -knight.}) ({And} 17... Qxb4 $4 {loses to the in-between check} 18. Bxd7+ {.}) 18. Qxb6 Rxb6 19. a4 {I think White has a risk-free edge in this endgame. The a -pawn will always cause some practical problems for Black, while the c -pawn can be easily blocked. It is like playing for two results here: either Black manages to hold or not.} *

