1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 {Black uses this move order when he wants to avoid the Bg5 lines and navigate towards the g3 lines. Right now, the Bg5 lines are not good enough (there is no pin), while g3 is not in our repertoire. Fortunately, there is another good option.} 6. dxc5 {This line is perhaps the simplest solution to the Tarrasch.} d4 {Black pretty much must play this move - otherwise, he will be down a pawn.} ({After} 6... Bxc5 $2 7. Qxd5 {White is just a pawn up. For example:} Qb6 8. e3 Nf6 9. Qb3) 7. Na4 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Qxc5 10. b4 ({A slightly less common move than} 10. Rc1 {followed by} Qb6 11. e3 {, which is relatively well-known. Many of the players that go for the Tarrasch will surely know 10.Rc1 , but 10.b4 is less explored, and there is a chance that it will cause certain practical problems.}) 10... Nxb4 {Accepting the pawn sacrifice is probably the most critical for this line.} 11. Rc1 {Black has two options now: Qe7 or Qd6 .} Qd6 {Black tries to keep the d4 -pawn defended.} 12. e3 {A venomous move as it contains a devious trap.} Ne7 {Black needs to ignore what White's doing and just complete his development. The knight should go to e7 , while the other knight may retreat to c6 in some lines, and this would require support.} 13. Nxd4 O-O {Here, White has some choice.} 14. Nb5 ({This is the most challenging. It forces Black to find lots of only moves just to stay in the game.} 14. Be2 {is more positional and totally acceptable as well. White enjoys the pair of bishops.}) 14... Nd3+ 15. Bxd3 Qxd3 16. Nc7 {What to do with the rook?} Qg6 {Nothing, at least for now! We cannot take the rook yet, as ... Qxg2 is an issue.} (16... Rb8 $2 {This would be a huge mistake already. You can find the line analyzed in detail here .}) 17. O-O Bh3 18. Qf3 Bg4 {With these moves, Black can stay in the game, but Qg6 requires some good thinking on Black's end. Here, White has two good options.} 19. Qg3 {The most tricky for Black. White retains the idea of Bb4 and provokes the 'liberating' ... Nf5 , which actually only helps White.  We analyze the line in depth at the end of chapter 13, starting here .} *

