1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 {The main move here is, of course, Be6 , but it is important to consider alternatives as well. However, they are inferior to the main line.} cxd4 {Voluntarily declaring the situation in the center is unlikely a good solution for Black. Now, White gets a comfortable position against the IQP.} 7. Nxd4 Be7 {There is probably not much difference in move orders, as Black will need to play ... Be7 , ... Nc6 and ..O-O eventually. The only potential difference that comes to mind is that Black may try ... Bb4 , but as we have already seen in previous variations, it should not be good.} 8. e3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O {We achieved a standard position with the isolated pawn. White should be comfortable here, especially since the bishop is out on g5 , which is much better than when it was on c1 ...} h6 11. Bh4 {The inclusion of these moves does not change much.} Be6 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Rc1 {Such a position reminds me of a Karpov-Kasparov 1985 game, in which Karpov masterfully exploited weak light squares on the kingside. Check out that game if you are unfamiliar with it!} Rc8 14. Bd3 {The bishop belongs on the b1 - h7 diagonal, where it can potentially exploit the weakened light squares.} Bd6 15. Bb1 {Black will have long-term problems with his central and kingside pawn structures.} *

