1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 ({An alternative approach involves playing} 6. g3 {, which is also challenging. In this course, I focus on .}) 6... Be6 {This is a recent trend in the Tarrasch Defense. Black supports the center.} 7. e3 ({I would recommend this positional approach.} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. e4 $5 {is an interesting alternative that can cause Black problems as well. Initially, I had planned on recommending this...but I encountered some obstacles, and my final conclusion was that Black should be fine with correct defense. Still - it is quite challenging, and Black needs to know his lines. At the end of the day, e3 is much simpler and has more playability. There is no way for Black to force a draw with this choice!}) 7... Nc6 {This is an option here, but in fact, it is just bad for Black. However, it has been played many times - and for this reason, it should be investigated as well.} 8. Bb5 ({The best way to put pressure on Black. Case in point: h6?} 8. Bxf6 $1 Qxf6 9. Qa4 {is completely winning for White. Now, there are many options for Black but no sight of equality anywhere.}) 8... Be7 ({Probably the most solid. Black can begin with} 8... Rc8 {too. Very likely, a transposition here will occur after} 9. O-O cxd4 10. Nxd4 Be7 11. Qa4 {.}) 9. dxc5 {A standard reaction, trying to make Black waste a tempo on ... Bxc5 .} Bxc5 ({Black may begin with} 9... O-O {too, but it does not really matter as next ... Bxc5 needs to be played anyway.}) 10. O-O O-O {This is worse than ... Be7 due to the following sequence.} (10... Be7 {is analyzed starting here .}) 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Nxd5 Qxb2 13. Nc7 {The key move that gives White a serious advantage.} Rac8 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Bc4 {With a multitude of weaknesses that are going to be targeted very soon.} *

