1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 ({An alternative approach involves playing} 6. g3 {, which is also challenging. In this course, I focus on .}) 6... Be6 {This is a recent trend in the Tarrasch Defense. Black supports the center.} 7. e3 ({I would recommend this positional approach.} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. e4 $5 {is an interesting alternative that can cause Black problems as well. Initially, I had planned on recommending this...but I encountered some obstacles, and my final conclusion was that Black should be fine with correct defense. Still - it is quite challenging, and Black needs to know his lines. At the end of the day, e3 is much simpler and has more playability. There is no way for Black to force a draw with this choice!}) 7... c4 ({Having supported the center, Black goes for a standard idea of gaining space on the queenside. Black wants to play ...Bb4 , which resembles the Ragozin. I would argue, though, that White has some advantage here in two ways.} 7... Nc6 $6 8. Bb5 {is good for White.}) 8. Be2 Bb4 ({Black can begin with} 8... Nbd7 9. O-O Bb4 {, move order. It avoids the e4 ideas, but it does not change much.}) 9. O-O {White has two main ideas here: 1) the e4 breakthrough, or 2)  Ne5 with some pressure in the center or an attack on the kingside with f4 , etc.} O-O ({I think we should keep it simple and play Ne5 as e4 leads to unnecessary simplifications (see next). In his course, Jorden Van Foreest recommends the} 9... Nbd7 {move order. It avoids e4 ideas, but in reality, it does not change much, as anyway} 10. Ne5 {seems to be the most promising, with a likely transposition after Black castles.}) 10. Ne5 ({Black needs to solve the problem of the Nb8 . Of course, they can play Nbd7 now with a transposition to the main line. h6?!} 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 {f4± with ideas of Bf3 or f5 , is just bad for Black.}) 10... Qa5 {The most popular 10th move. It allows Bxf6 , which may seem like a good thing for White, but actually White has no way to capitalize on it.} 11. f4 ({Passing on the opportunity of Bxf6 for now and going for the direct attack on the kingside! I find it the most challenging from a human point of view, but in case you are not in the mood for such sharp play,} 11. Bxf6 {is calmer, and I cover it as an alternative as well.}) 11... Bxc3 {Sooner or later, Black needs to eliminate the Nc3 before occupying the e4 -square.} 12. f5 {But we are not recapturing the bishop! Black has the first of many chances to go wrong.} Bd7 ({Inaccurate. Black's best move,} 12... Bc8 $1 {, is analyzed starting here .}) 13. bxc3 Ne4 (13... Qxc3 $2 {This is a wrong option because it allows White to take f6 (at the right time) and destroy the king's defense.} 14. Rc1 $1 Qa3 15. Bxf6 $1 Qxe3+ ({(Or} 15... gxf6 16. Ng4 Qd6 17. Qe1 {is overwhelming.)}) 16. Kh1 gxf6 17. Bg4 Qg5 18. Rc3 $1 {With Rg3 following and a crushing attack.}) 14. Be7 Ba4 {The only way to justify ... Bd7 .} 15. Qb1 {Again the b7 -pawn is loose, as well as the Rf8 . The extended version of this variation can be found here .} *

