1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} c6 6. Qc2 Bd6 {Here, White has two good options: e4 and Bg5 . The first one is more complex and dynamic; the other is more positional. I decided to recommend both, but I keep one as an alternative to keep things clean and organized.} 7. e4 {Rare, but very challenging.} dxe4 8. Nxe4 Bb4+ 9. Nc3 {This would be my main recommendation here. This leads to an interesting position with the IQP, where White will seek dynamic play.} Nf6 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O {Generally, due to the pawn on a6 being rather useless, White should be able to develop some initiative.} Bg4 ({By far the best move.} 11... h6 $6 {is risky for Black. Apart from} 12. h3 {, which would just transpose, there are additional options: a3} Bd6 13. Bc4 $1 {with both bishops aiming at Black's castle.}) (11... Nbd7 $6 12. Bg5 {gives White a very good attacking position.} Be7 13. Rae1 h6 14. Bh4 Re8 15. Qe2 {is a sample line.}) 12. Ng5 {White needs to play this move to retain the initiative.} h6 13. h3 {The bishop needs to go back as ... hxg5 is way too risky.} Bc8 14. Nf3 {There was no need to play Nh7 and trade knights. It is better to keep more pieces on the board. White now wants to complete development and look for ways to develop some initiative on the kingside or in the center.} ({For instance, Re8} 14. Bd2 Be6 15. Rfe1 Nbd7 16. Re2 {Bf8 Rae1 With multiple ideas, for example Qc1 , Bb1 and g4 .}) *

