1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} Nf6 ({This position can arise also from d4} 5... Nf6 {c4 e6 Nf3 d5 Nc3 a6 cxd5 exd5 , which is the standard way of reaching this position. However, in our repertoire, we do not necessarily allow any other move orders - Nc3 is my recommendation for this course. And if d5 , then cxd5 , not Nf3 . Apart from 5...Nf6 , Black can also try to play either 5...c6 or 5...h6 , as we have seen.}) 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e3 ({White should go for the most classical approach. Recently, there was some development after} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 {targeting the b7 -pawn. Black is fine here, however, after} Ra7 $1 {. For this reason, I would recommend playing 7.e3 .}) 7... Nbd7 8. Bd3 h6 9. Bf4 {Normally, I would recommend retreating to f4 in many of these positions. Especially now - when Black has not played ... Bd6 , it makes even more sense.} {If Black plays g5 (the most critical move), it is, in fact, the same as 9.Bh4 , but other moves here are worse for Black.} g5 10. Bg3 Nh5 {Black goes after the pair of bishops. White has many options here.} 11. Qb3 ({Pressuring the b7 -pawn, which is not so easy for Black to handle. It is quite similar to} 11. Qc2 {but a bit better, in my opinion. Additionally, White keeps the option of castling on either side.}) 11... Nxg3 {Black will need to trade on g3 sooner or later, but the issue with the b7 -pawn will remain.} 12. hxg3 Nb6 {This move is logical - but the Nb6 is far from being optimally placed. Normally, it should be kept on d7 to control the e5 -square and support a potential ... c5 . Another success of 11.Qb3 !} ({Other alternatives are analyzed in chapter 16:} 12... c5 {, b5 and especially Rb8 , which is the best move according to the engine.}) 13. O-O Bg7 14. Rae1 {White prepares a potential e4 -break, but he keeps the other rook on f1 for potential ideas of f4 if Black should castle kingside.} Qd6 15. Qc2 c6 {Black keeps his options wide open.} 16. b3 {A very interesting idea. The point is not necessarily stopping ... Nc4 or restricting the black knight. In fact, White prepares Na4 !?, which is quite unusual but can be extremely useful in a number of positions, especially if Black castles queenside.} O-O (16... O-O-O 17. Na4 $1 {and Black is suddenly in big trouble as the just-castled king is unsafe!}) 17. e4 {Everything is ready for the pawn break!} dxe4 (17... g4 $2 18. e5 $1) 18. Nxe4 Qb4 19. Nc5 {With obvious pressure.} *

