[PlyCount "31"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 {Black has a choice of possible plans here. One of them is to play plans with ... c5 , another is the standard ... c6 to enter a Carlsbad structure, and finally ... Bf5 !? which is a way to improve the light-squared bishop.} O-O 7. Bd3 c5 8. Nge2 {The knight is much more flexible on e2 than f3 . White can bring it to f4 in the future, but the idea of f3 - e4 may be played one day - especially if Black plays ... c4 .} Nc6 (8... c4 9. Bc2 {should not change much, as it is hard to imagine Black playing without ... Nc6 .}) 9. O-O {There is no need to rush with dxc5 , as we are happy if Black changes the pawn structure with ... c4 or ... cxd4 .} c4 10. Bc2 a6 {A standard idea for Black is to expand on the queenside and make use of his pawn majority.} 11. b3 {A standard response by White - undermining the pawn chain and trying to weaken it. Surprisingly, it is a novelty!} ({cxb3?!} 11. Bb3 {is generally a favorable trade for White. The d5 -pawn is a weakness.}) 11... b5 12. bxc4 bxc4 13. h3 {Making sure the bishop has the h2 -square at its disposal.} ({White can start with} 13. a3 $5 {as well. Sooner or later, this move will be useful as ideas of ... Bb4 or ... Nb4 may be annoying.}) 13... Nb4 14. Bb1 Be6 15. a3 Nc6 16. Bc2 {White has a nice position here, with many potential ways to continue. In the long run, our main idea is to play f3 and e4 . However, we should prepare it with Qd2 and Rfd1 , for example. Sometimes, e4 can also be played immediately - depending on the position.} *

