1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bd6 {Black forces the trade of bishops but also loses a tempo (... Be7 -... Bd6 ). For this reason, we should not worry about it.} 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. Bd3 Ne7 9. Qc2 {We are getting a standard Carlsbad pawn structure. White has a couple of plans available (like the minority pawn attack or f3 - e4 ). Choosing one and sticking to it should be sufficient, but sometimes we may maneuver around trying to combine them and confuse our opponent.} b6 ({Given that Black's Bc8 is not great, it makes sense to trade these bishops. The move} 9... b6 {is a common method of achieving this goal but also weakens the c6 -pawn. White can proceed with either the Nf3 or the Nge2 setup.}) 10. Nf3 {Here, as the b6 -pawn weakens the queenside, I would probably stick with this way to develop the knight and focus on the queenside.} Ba6 11. O-O Bxd3 12. Qxd3 O-O {White has some choice here. I would double up the rooks on the c -file and put pressure on the c6 -pawn. If Black ever plays ... c5 , then after trades, the d5 -pawn will be weak.} 13. Rac1 Nd7 14. Rc2 Rfd8 ({As usual, ideas and plans matter more than concrete move orders. We can meet} 14... a5 {with} 15. b3 {stopping ... a4 .}) ({After} 14... Qg6 15. Qd2 {, we continue with the same plans. Of course, Black has many different moves and it's impossible to cover all of them but, as long as we understand the ideas, we're fine.}) 15. Rfc1 {With maneuvering play ahead. Black is chronically worse due to the soft c6 -pawn. White's plans involve Ne2 - Ng3 , sometimes Qa6 can be good too to put pressure on Black's queenside, and Ne1 - Nd3 could be an interesting maneuver as well.} ({Nf8} 15. Qa6 {Ne6 h3 White is better. It is not clear what Black is doing. White will prepare a3 - b4 , perhaps Na4 followed by Nb2 - Nd3 etc. And if} c5 {then} 16. b3 {and the b5 -square becomes weak.}) *

