1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 {By far, the most popular move in this position. The idea is to quickly develop the bishop, before White plays Bd3 and stops Black from doing so. If Black does not play this move, he may face issues with the Bc8 in the long run.} ({Still, there are some alternatives:} 6... Bd6 {has been covered earlier and for Nf6} 7. Bd3 {, see the 5... Nf6  lines .}) 7. Nge2 Nd7 {The main move here. Generally, Black delays ... Nf6 to keep the h4 -square under control.} 8. h4 {An interesting try to seize space on the kingside, despite the e7 -bishop looking at the h4 -square. There are potential issues with the Bf5 as it will run under Ng3 . The idea of h4 is to prevent Black from playing ... Bg6 and force the bishop to e6 . Then, Bd3 can be played, followed by Nf5 . Additionally, the h4 -pawn can be used to play h5 and weaken Black's kingside.} h5 {This move is a bit risky. We get exactly what we want - targets on the kingside!} (8... Bxh4 $2 {This does not work. You can find it starting here .}) 9. Ng3 Bg6 10. Bd3 {White trades light-squared bishops in order to weaken the f5 and h5 -squares. If Black plays ... Bxd3 and ... g6 , we argue that this is a waste of time and will try to take advantage of it dynamically.} Bxd3 11. Qxd3 g6 ({Preventing Nf5 , but it is also slow. After} 11... Ngf6 12. Nf5 {, White is clearly better.}) 12. e4 {Immediately hitting in the center and attempting to get some dynamic play going as we have more pieces in play.} Ngf6 13. O-O-O {I would not rush e5 as taking on e4 does not solve Black's problems here.} dxe4 {So far, only this was played.} 14. Ngxe4 O-O 15. f3 {This looks very scary for Black. White intends g4 next with a strong attack.} Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Nf6 17. g4 {Launching an immediate attack. This looks really bad for Black, even though the engine actually manages to keep it together...   For the purposes of the Quickstarter, the line ends here. The extended version of this variation can be found in chapter 19 , where both 17... Qa5 and 17... hxg4 are analyzed.} *

