1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 {By far, the most popular move in this position. The idea is to quickly develop the bishop, before White plays Bd3 and stops Black from doing so. If Black does not play this move, he may face issues with the Bc8 in the long run.} ({Still, there are some alternatives:} 6... Bd6 {has been covered earlier and for Nf6} 7. Bd3 {, see the 5... Nf6  lines .}) 7. Nge2 Nd7 {The main move here. Generally, Black delays ... Nf6 to keep the h4 -square under control.} 8. h4 {An interesting try to seize space on the kingside, despite the e7 -bishop looking at the h4 -square. There are potential issues with the Bf5 as it will run under Ng3 . The idea of h4 is to prevent Black from playing ... Bg6 and force the bishop to e6 . Then, Bd3 can be played, followed by Nf5 . Additionally, the h4 -pawn can be used to play h5 and weaken Black's kingside.} Ngf6 {The main move here. Black completes the development, ignoring White's expansive ambitions on the kingside.} 9. Ng3 {Chasing the bishop away. Please note that the bishop cannot go to g6 now (as it would normally want), which definitely is good news for White.} Be6 (9... Bg4 $6 {only helps White as the pawn on f3 is useful in many similar positions.} 10. f3 Be6 11. Bd3) 10. Bd3 {White creates an idea of Nf5 , trying to get the pair of bishops.} O-O 11. Nf5 Bb4 {The most critical move - otherwise, White gets the pair of bishops, and he should be better.} 12. a3 Ba5 13. Rc1 {There is no need to rush things. White will recapture with the rook if ... Bxc3 ever occurs.} Bxf5 14. Bxf5 Re8 (14... Bc7 15. Bg5 $1 {is again uncomfortable for Black.}) 15. Bg5 Bxc3+ 16. Rxc3 Qc7 17. Rc2 {White is slightly better due to the pair of bishops. The key idea of 17. Rc2 is to cover the d2 -square in some lines.} ({For example, after h6} 17. Qf3 $1 Ne4 18. Bf4 Qa5 19. Kd1 {is possible, and the d2 -square is covered. White retains an advantage.}) *

