1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 {The most popular move here, but Black can try so many move orders that I tried to simplify what we are doing as White: our plan is Bd3 , Nge2 and O-O on nearly anything and there would be some transpositions.} ({Black can begin with} 7... h6 8. Bh4 {but we should anyway transpose as we play Nge2 on nearly anything.}) ({Beginning with} 7... Re8 8. Nge2 {should also transpose as Black needs ... c6 sooner or later.}) 8. Nge2 h6 {Recently, the main theory advocates for including this move. It is debatable whether it helps Black or not, but one thing for sure - now Black cannot play with ... g6 and White's bishop has faster path towards the f2 -square ( f3 - Bf2 ).} (8... Nbd7 {can be played too but after} 9. O-O {we transpose after either} h6 {or Re8 . And if Nh5 then Bxe7 Qxe7} 10. Qd2 {with the plan of f3 - e4 ; I analyzed similar positions in the section where Black delays castling.}) 9. Bh4 {Here Black has a huge choice.} Re8 (9... Nbd7 {can be played too but again after} 10. O-O {there should be a transposition.}) 10. O-O a5 {By delaying a bit the development of Nb8 Black keeps an option of ... Na6 if needed. This means that ideas of a4 are not a thing here.} (10... Ne4 $6 {is quite popular, but is already a serious inaccuracy. You can find it here .}) 11. f3 {Getting ready for e4 and bringing the bishop to f2 . In this way, we are preventing all ideas where Black trades the bishops.} b5 (11... Nbd7 $6 12. a4 $1 {see Nbd7 line .}) 12. Bf2 Nbd7 13. Rc1 {White obtained a comfortable setup. The e4 idea is almost ready - the only thing we need is the g4 -square covered in case there are trades on e4 . White has a relatively easy plan to follow: Ng3 (or Nf4 !? sometimes), Nce2 , maybe Kh1 or h3 , Re1 could be useful too. Preventing the ... c5 pawn break should be really taken into consideration. So far, Black played 13... Nb6 , 13... Ba6 and 13... a4 . Let's explore these moves.} Nb6 {The most popular move. The knight heads for the c4 square, while ... b4 is kept as an option, since Na4 would no longer be so dangerous.} 14. Ng3 {Here we go to g3 . We make space for the other knight on e2 . Once this happens, the e4 -pawn break can be potentially lethal.} (14. b3 b4 $1 {is equal as we have to go back with the knight to b1 .}) (14. Nf4 {is not great now as Black can play} Nc4 $1 15. Qc2 (15. Qe2 $2 Bd6 {is even worse.}) 15... Bd6 {with pressure, not only on the e3 -pawn but also on the Nf4 .}) 14... Nc4 ({A logical move, improving the knight. We should deal with it, without capturing it (or running into b3? Nb2! )} 14... Bf8 {was played in Ding-Bluebaum (2021). I would recommend the same approach as after 14...Bd6 and play} 15. b3 {(stopping ...Nc4 )} a4 16. Nce2 {with an advantage. White will be ready for e4 very soon.}) (14... Bd7 {was played in another game by Bluebaum, this time against Van Foreest. Here, instead of} 15. h3 $5 {as played by Van Foreest, I would also recommend b3} a4 16. Nce2 {with a tabiya similar to other lines.}) 15. Qe2 {A very strong move, if a bit unusual. The idea is pretty deep - the e3 pawn must be guarded right now that White can play b3 and chase the Nc4 out. For more details, check the following line.} (15. Qc2 {seems logical but in fact Black is fine after} Bb4 $1 16. Rfe1 (16. e4 dxe4 17. fxe4 Ng4 $1) 16... a4 $1 17. b3 axb3 18. axb3 Ra3 $1 {which is a highly tactical solution, leading to an unclear game.}) 15... Bf8 16. b3 (16. Rfe1 $5 {is what the engine likes, but the text move looks more natural.}) 16... Nd6 17. Qc2 {With a comfortable edge for White.} *

