1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 {When Black tries to play without ... c6 , there are two ideas for him to choose from: playing via ... c5 (say, ... Be7 , ... O-O , ... b6 and eventually ... c5 ) or ... Bb4 in the style of the Ragozin. The latter has become some sort of trend recently.} Bb4 {Black goes for a Ragozin-style position, looking for more unbalanced positions compared to the established QGD exchange lines. However, the lack of Nf3 makes White's options wider.  This line was chosen by Ian Nepomniachtchi in the game Caruana-Nepomniachtchi (2024), from the last round of the Candidates Tournament.} 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 9. a3 {A somewhat rarer move than the more popular 9. Nge2 , but since it is less explored, I think more playable positions can be obtained here. This move is by far GM Salem's favorite choice.} Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 {If Nxc3 then Qc1 or Qc2 winning back the pawn on c7 with a favorable structure.} h5 ({Black goes after the Bg3 . After} 10... c5 $6 11. Bd3 Nxg3 12. hxg3 {White gets a great version of the Ragozin.}) 11. f3 {Solving the problem immediately.} Nxg3 (11... h4 12. Be5 $1 {Looks unpleasant for Black.} Nf6 13. Bd3 Nc6 14. Ne2 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd7 16. f4) 12. hxg3 {The resulting pawn structure looks promising for White, especially with the Ng1 not developed yet. There are ideas of g4 followed by Nh3 . The king will feel very safe on f2 .} Qd6 {This looks like the main move, targeting the g3 -pawn.} 13. g4 h4 {This has been only played so far but this is just bad.} 14. Nh3 {A great square for the knight!} Qe7 (14... f6 15. c4) 15. Bd3 ({White does not care about the e3 pawn and wants to complete the development ASAP. I think White is much better. A good example is the game Salem-Indjic (2022) which you can see in the line following. Qxe3+ Kf1 Qe7} 15. Qd2 Rg8 {Re1! In the game, Kf2 was played, which is less good. Be6} 16. c4 $1 c6 17. cxd5 cxd5 18. f4 $1 {with threats on the e-file.}) *

