[ECO "D35"]
[PlyCount "33"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 {Here I analyze what happens when Black decides to go for the endgame with ... Bf5 . There are two ways Black can do this: either ... Bf5 immediately, or first ... h6 and then ... Bf5 . Although both are possible, I find it hard to believe that having the pawn on h6 improves Black's position. In fact, when the bishop retreats to g6 , it would be somewhat more vulnerable, as we shall see in the analysis.} Bf5 {In many Carlsbad positions it is believed that when Black takes his bishop to f5 , he should equalize. Here, however, White has the idea of Qf3 ! which damages Black's pawn structure.} 7. Qf3 Bg6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6 {So, it all starts here. The debate about whether Black's poor pawn structure gives White sufficient chances to win is still ongoing, and I do not expect it to be resolved soon. In my opinion, I think Black should objectively have enough resources to mitigate the problems associated with bad pawn structure, but we cannot forget that chess is still a game and people are prone to make mistakes. If we can get an easier game with some advantage, and we know what our plans and ideas are, we should be okay. And I think my viewpoint can give an idea of how to deal with these positions. White has many plans at his disposal. I am particularly fond of a plan played by Magnus Carlsen against Vladimir Kramnik in 2015.} 10. Nf3 {This is what Magnus played; more recently it was played by Ian Nepomniachtchi against Ding Liren in the GCT Superbet Romania. Ian, having played two World Championship matches, is one of the best prepared players in the world and the fact that he chose Nf3 - Nh4 idea says it all.} Nd7 {This is by far the most popular continuation.} 11. Nh4 Be7 12. Ne2 {Now, that f4 is met by ... f5 , White transfers the knight to g3 to occupy the f5 -square.} f5 {This is probably the best response as it was recently played by Leinier Dominguez.} 13. Nf3 {As the bishop on g6 is stuck, White simply retreats and will play for the control over the f4 -square. One of the main ideas for White is to bring Nf3 to d3 square.} (13. g3 {is possible too, but I'm a bit worried that after} Bxh4 14. gxh4 Nf6 {there is simply not enough here to win. If White could only secure Nf4 , then maybe.. But as it is Nf4 is met by ... Nh5 with further simplifications.} 15. Nf4 Nh5 16. Be2 Nxf4 17. exf4 h5) 13... Bb4+ 14. Kd1 Bd6 {Black stop Nf4 for now, and with the Kd1 , there is potential danger connected with ... Nf6 -... Ne4 idea. Fortunately, Levon Aronian played here a very nice idea.} 15. Ne1 {A great regrouping! The knight comes to d3 from where it enables Nef4 , while also it defends soft f2 -pawn. Next, Nd3 , Nef4 , f3 come and White should have a pleasant position. Black's Bg6 is out of play!} Ke7 16. Nd3 Bh5 17. f3 {Making sure that Black does not trade his bad bishop. However, I must admit that Black's position remains very solid, and it may not be so easy to break through. However, this position looks promising and certainly playable; slowly, White should be able to exert some pressure. In the game, Levon came incredibly close to victory, letting the advantage slip away at the very end. Many maneuvers can follow in this position: Ke1 - Kf2 , Nef4 , Be2 - Bd1 , rooks come into play on squares e1 and c3 . Potentially, White will try to break through on the queenside with a minority attack. See the clickable lines for more.} ({Bg6 Nef4 a5} 17. Ke1 Nf8 18. g3 Ne6 19. Rc1 Rhe8 {Kf2 Kf6 Be2 Re7 Bd1 Kg7 Re1 Ree8 Re2 Re7} 20. Rc3 Kf8 21. a3) *

