1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 {With this move, Black aims for a Meran pawn structure, with a small but significant difference that plays in White's favor: the Nb1 is still undeveloped, which gives White additional possibilities. For example, the knight can go to d2 . Or Nc3 can be played at an opportune time. The ideas of b3 - Bb2 help control the e5 square, and Black may find it difficult to successfully execute the pawn break ... e5 .} 5. Bd3 ({I would recommend delaying the development of Nb1 . If White plays} 5. b3 $5 {then Black has really huge choice. But one of the most critical lines follows} c5 $5 {immediately hitting the center. Although in the end White is perhaps a little better (and I am not sure that he is!) there is absolutely no reason to play 5. b3 immediately, because we simply have to learn many more lines than necessary.}) 5... Nbd7 {The most flexible move. Black retains the option of ... Bd6  (or perhaps another way to develop the bishop) along with the ideas ... b6 -... Bb7 or ... dxc4 .} ({Black can play} 5... dxc4 {immediately, with a chance of transposing to QGA if Black plays ... c5 on the next move, or 6... Nbd7 7. O-O , which is covered when Black starts with 5... Nbd7 6. O-O  dxc4 .} 6. Bxc4 {The only independent line now seems to be the quick ... b5 , but as we'll see, we transpose anyway.} b5 ({For} 6... c5 {see the QGA lines .}) ({While} 6... Nbd7 7. O-O {transposes to dxc4 Bxc4 Nbd7 O-O}) 7. Bd3 a6 8. a4 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 {transposes to the line we're studying.}) 6. O-O {Another option is 6. b3 , followed by Bb2 . Of course, these plans are also totally playable. These lines are beyond the scope of this course where I focus on the more classic Meran lines, but I encourage you to study them on your own if interested!} Bd6 7. Nc3 {White should go for the Meran here. Black has three possible plans: 1) the standard ... dxc4 and ... b5 ; 2) ... dxc4 followed by meeting e4 with ... e5 ; and 3) meeting e4 with ... dxe4 . They all lead to different positions. Let's take a look.} ({Please note that} 7. b3 $2 {is a serious error due to} e5 $1 {and Black begins to take over.}) 7... O-O 8. e4 dxc4 9. Bxc4 e5 {One of the classical ways to play the Meran as Black, which lost its popularity recently to ... b5 -... Bb7 lines. However, thanks to the 4. e3 move order, Black does not get to enter the main Meran lines, which makes 4. e3 an effective method to avoid certain variations.} 10. Be3 {I think this move is the most promising. The idea is to have an option to recapture on d4 with the bishop. Sam Shankland does not cover this line much, but it actually deserves some attention, so I decided to look into it.} exd4 {Black makes the situation clear in the center. I decided to keep it as the main line because there was a Giri-Ding (2019) game that is perhaps crucial for the whole line. The idea is to play ... Qc7 and ... Ne5 later. This is a good move order for Black, since the immediate ... Qc7 clashes with the ideas Rc1 and Nb5 !, whereas if Black plays with ... Qe7 he does not have enough control over the f4 square, allowing White to push f4 more easily.} 11. Bxd4 (11. Nxd4 {which is our move in the 10... Qe7 line, would be a mistake due to} Ne5 $1 12. Bb3 Neg4 $1) 11... Qc7 {Here, White has moves like 12. Bb3 or 12. h3 which are quite popular and engine claims they are OK too. But I like what Anish played.} 12. Kh1 {This was tried by Anish Giri and I like this a lot. The idea is of course to meet ... Ne5 and enable f4 after all trades on e5 , but there is an even deeper point behind it.} Ne5 {The most human move, against which our Kh1 was basically directed. This was also played by Ding.} (12... Bf4 $1 {This is the best reply, but far from intuitive. After all, we can just play even g3 and push the bishop away...}) 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Qxe5 15. f4 {Now we can play this move without running into ... Qc5 with check.} Qc5 {Black should play this move anyway. But now, we have another point behind Kh1 . White can play 16. Be2 or 16. Bd3 , instead of the 'standard' 16. Bb3 and avoid the bishop trade right away.} 16. Be2 ({I like this the most. White keeps majority of pieces on the board.} 16. Bd3 $5 {was tried by Giri and it is also interesting. I like it a bit less than 16. Be2 due to} Rd8 17. Qf3 Be6 18. h3 Rxd3 $1 {and Ding managed to simplify the position.} 19. Qxd3 Bc4 20. Qd2 Bxf1 21. Rxf1 {In this case, White is still slightly better, since e5 is coming and White controls the d-file. However, many pieces have been exchanged, and I expect that Black can defend himself with some accurate moves.}) (16. Bb3 {is what we should avoid now, due to} Be6 {and Black gets to trade the light squared bishops in a comfortable manner, followed by ... Rad8 .}) 16... Be6 17. Qe1 {Bringing the queen to the kingside. This position looks promising for White, as my analysis shows.} *

