[PlyCount "35"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} dxc4 {Black gives up control of the center, but intends to play ... Bg4 later and prepare for the pawn break ... e5 as soon as possible.} 8. Bxc4 b5 {This move was tried in some rare games by Dubov and Van Foreest. It is not great, but White should know how to react to it.} 9. Bd3 {White prepares e4 with this move.} Bb7 10. Qe2 ({But not} 10. e4 $6 c5 $1 {, and Black successfully strikes in the center with counterplay. Further preparations are needed.}) 10... a6 ({Black should prepare ...c5 anyway.} 10... Nbd7 11. e4 b4 12. Na4 {is also better for White.}) 11. e4 c5 {This pawn sac is typical for the Grünfeld. In the Schlechter, the bishop also goes to g7 , so the ... c5 pawn break sometimes happens, and in effect, we have Grünfeld-like positions.} 12. dxc5 b4 13. Na4 Nbd7 {Black sacrificed a pawn and will attempt to get it back by attacking the Na4 and surrounding the c5 -pawn. He may succeed in getting the pawn back, but White keeps an advantage anyway:} 14. a3 {It is useful to force the pawn go to b3 as it can be a weakness there one day.} b3 (14... bxa3 $2 15. Rxa3) (14... a5 $2 15. Bf4) 15. Rd1 Qa5 16. Nb6 {Returning the pawn but getting an initiative.} Nxb6 17. cxb6 Qxb6 18. Be3 {White is better as Black's queen is going to be chased around, and the b3 -pawn is a weakness.} ({For example Qa5 A logical move.} 18. Nd2 $1 {This gives White a nice edge, e.g. Qa4 Rac1} Rac8 19. Nc4) *

