1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A solid line for Black against the 4. e3 Slav. White has many interesting options here.} 5. Qb3 {Recently this move has been scoring well for White. White immediately puts pressure on the b7 -pawn and gets out of the pin, allowing Nf3 to move.} Qb6 {The most solid response by Black.} 6. Ne5 Qxb3 7. axb3 {This endgame (or queenless middlegame) is difficult for Black, since White, thanks to the open a-file, can immediately exert pressure on the queenside. The issue for Black is that he is not able to comfortably stop White's c5 - b4 - b5 idea. One way to deal with that is to give away the bishop pair, but that has its own issues...} Bf5 (7... Nbd7 8. Nxg4 Nxg4 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nc3 e6 11. f3 Ngf6 12. Nb5 {and Black is actually unable to hold the a-pawn.}) 8. Nc3 e6 9. c5 {It appears that Black is unable to stop b4 - b5 .} Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Kxd7 11. b4 a6 12. b5 ({And the game might continue with Be7 bxa6 bxa6} 12. f3 a5 13. g4 Bc2 14. Kd2 Bb3 15. Bd3) *

