1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A solid line for Black against the 4. e3 Slav. White has many interesting options here.} 5. Qb3 {Recently this move has been scoring well for White. White immediately puts pressure on the b7 -pawn and gets out of the pin, allowing Nf3 to move.} Qb6 {The most solid response by Black.} 6. Ne5 Bf5 {Black should preserve his bishop. There are alternatives but they are worse.} 7. cxd5 {An important move. White picks the right moment to take on d5 and avoid the Exchange Slav pawn structure, as Black cannot recapture with the pawn. And if the knight recaptures on d5 , White has a superior pawn structure in the center.} Qxb3 {The main move.} 8. axb3 Nxd5 9. Bd3 {White offers further trades as the Bf5 is kind of annoying and White's knight on d3 would be placed very well.} Bxd3 {Nearly everyone trades the bishops. If Black does not do that, his bishop is not going to be well placed.} 10. Nxd3 e6 11. Bd2 {This is what White wants in this line - the edge in the center, the opened a-file and a bit more active pieces. One might say that this is not the most exciting line, and perhaps that is true. On the other hand, however, White has a rather simple game and a comfortable, almost risk-free position in which Black has to be careful... Recently several games have been played in this line, and White has had good results.} Na6 {Black needs to fight for the control over the b4 square. Right now, White has two interesting ideas.} 12. Ke2 Nab4 {Surprisingly, this is not the most common move here!} 13. Ne1 {White should keep the knights on the board. As there is only one outpost on b4 and Black has two knights, one of the knights is going to be passive! In general, as long as Black cannot comfortably make a pawn break ... c5 or ... e5 , White should have an advantage.} ({We should not trade now.} 13. Nxb4 Bxb4 $1 {and Black gets to simplify the position which results in a roughly equal game. In comparison with 12... Ndb4 , Black's knight is now on d5 which does not allow for Rxa6 .}) 13... c5 {Probably the most logical move here. After all, if Black does not play this move at some point, his position will be cramped.} (13... f5 {stops e4 , but weakens Black's position.} 14. Nf3 {followed by Rhc1 , Na3 - c4 .}) 14. e4 Nc7 15. Bxb4 cxb4 16. Nd2 {I like White's position. The center is quite strong, and White can expand to the queenside as well. Again, because of some space advantage, there should be possibilities. One of White's main ideas is to play f4 . But moves such as Nc2 , Nc4 , Rhd1 , etc. also come to mind.} ({For example, Nb5} 16. Nc2 Rc8 {Nc4 Be7} 17. Rd1 {O-O f4} f5 18. e5) ({Or Be7} 16. f4 O-O-O 17. Nf3 Nb5 18. Ke3 {with Nc4 next.}) *

