1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 a6 ({One of the modern approaches to Chebanenko that gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The main idea is to improve on the standard Bf5 Nc3} 5... e6 {where White plays} 6. Nh4 {and gets the pair of bishops.}) {Here, Nh4 makes less sense, while Black's a6 is helpful to secure the b7 -pawn with either ... b5 or ... Ra7 if needed. White has many options, but I would like to recommend a line that I personally find very attractive.} 6. Qb3 {White targets the b7 -pawn, forcing Black to do something about it right away.} Ra7 {The most popular but not necessarily the best move.} (6... b5 {This is a human move - what could be more logical than gaining space on the queenside and defending the pawn at the same time? It is analyzed in detail starting here .}) 7. Bd2 {White plays this developmental move with intention of meeting ... e6 with Nh4 .} e6 8. Nh4 ({Getting the bishop pair. This is in some way similar to e3 Bf5 Nc3 e6} 8. Nh4 {line - with the difference that Qb3 and Bd2 moves are useful for White, while a6 and Ra7 do not necessarily help Black. Still, Black is pretty solid, so let's see what can happen.}) 8... Be4 {By far the main move here.} 9. cxd5 ({A well-timed move. It is important NOT to play} 9. f3 $2 {due to} dxc4 $1 10. Bxc4 Bd5 {and Black is absolutely fine.}) 9... cxd5 10. f3 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. O-O-O {This position closely resembles the line e3 Bf5 Nc3 e6 Nh4 Be4 f3 Bg6 , where White quickly plays Qb3 , Bd2 , cxd5 and O-O-O . The difference between that line and what we have here is that Black's moves a6 and Ra7 are not useful, so I can say that we have a pretty good version of a normal line. White's plan is simple: Kb1 , Rc1 , and g4 , h4 with expansion to the kingside. Sometimes e4 can also be played, but in general we should concentrate on the kingside.} Nc6 (12... b5 13. Kb1 Be7 14. g4 Nbd7 15. h4 Nb6 16. h5 gxh5 17. e4) 13. Kb1 Be7 14. Rc1 {Stabilizing the queenside, before the kingside attack becomes a thing.} O-O ({Sooner or later Black needs to castle.} 14... Na5 {is just a waste of time due to} 15. Qa4+ Nc6 16. Bd3) 15. h4 {Immediately beginning the attack. The extended version of this variation can be found here .} *

