1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} Nbd7 ({The main move.} 10... a6 11. O-O-O dxc4 12. Bxc4 {with an inevitable transposition.}) (10... a6 11. c5 $5 {is another option, followed by} Nbd7 12. Na4 $5 {with playing for the squeeze. However - there is no need to enter it, as 11. O-O-O will simply transpose to the main line.}) 11. O-O-O dxc4 {The main move, but there are numerous alternatives.} 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 a6 {This position can arise from various move orders. Black prepares ... c5 , which is a standard pawn break.} 14. Kb1 {I like this the most for White.} c5 15. d5 {This is the point. White sacrifices a pawn to open the d-file and put a lot of pressure on the center. Black has two moves: 15... exd5 or 15... Nxd5 .} exd5 {Recently, there were some more games here as well. The positions can get a bit confusing, as we will see shortly. I will make sure to clarify everything!} 16. Bc1 {Targetting the d5 -pawn.} Nb6 {Logical, defending the pawn. Here, f4 is pointless as d5 -pawn is very well-guarded. Therefore, g4 is the right idea now.} 17. g4 {The threat of g5 is very serious.} b4 ({Trying to deal with the g5 threat.} 17... c4 18. g5 Nfd7 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. Rxd5 Qc7 21. f4) (17... g5 $2 18. h4 $1) 18. Na4 c4 (18... Nxa4 19. Qxa4+ Qd7 20. Qc2 $1) 19. g5 Nfd7 20. h4 {Black's position looks unpleasant, despite the extra pawn. The ideas of e4 and f4 , which tear Black's center apart and open the position to the bishop pair, are really annoying. Moreover, castling to the kingside is not an option: White will checkmate after h5 !} *

