1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nf6 {This opening is often played by novice chess players who do not understand the concept of controlling the center. The d5 -pawn is not sufficiently supported now (as it is after 2... c6 or 2... e6 ), and White can play cxd5 and e4 , since Black cannot recapture the pawn. However, there are some hidden rocks that White needs to watch out for.} 3. cxd5 Nxd5 4. Nf3 {White should not rush with e4 as Black has no successful way of stopping it.} ({It is also OK to start with} 4. e4 {, but it runs into slight issues:} Nf6 {Perhaps White needs to play} 5. Bd3 {but Black can anyway play ... e5 .} ({•} 5. e5 Nd5 {is not ideal too - Black gets the outpost on d5 .}) ({•} 5. Nc3 e5 $1 {is the same as Qxd5 Nc3 Qd8 e4?!} 6. dxe5 $1) 5... e5 $1 6. dxe5 Ng4 7. Bb5+ c6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Be2 Nxe5 {and despite a clear advantage for White, I think it may not be so easy to prove.}) 4... Bf5 ({The only way to stop e4 .} 4... e6 5. e4 Nf6 6. Nc3 {Of course, Black's position is very difficult.}) 5. Nbd2 {Renewing the e4 idea. Black definitely should not allow it.} Nf6 6. Qb3 Qc8 7. g3 ({I am not sure if it makes sense to analyze it any further. White has an easy plan and clear advantage. Next Bg2 and O-O will be played with a great version of some Catalan. c6 Bg2 e6 O-O Nbd7} 7. Ne5 {followed by e4 .}) *

