1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6 {The Chigorin Defense is not much played nowadays at the highest level, but it does happen from time to time. In the 2000s it was taken up by Morozevich and later by Rapport, and both achieved good results, but in general it is a rather suspect opening for Black.} 3. Nf3 Bg4 ({If Black plays} 3... e6 {we get a Queen's Gambit Declined with an awkward ... Nc6 . I discuss this in section on Tango, in Part 1. I would recommend} 4. Nc3 Nf6 {and now either} 5. Bg5 {or a3 (see Part )}) 4. cxd5 Bxf3 5. gxf3 Qxd5 6. e3 {Intending Nc3 next, building a strong center. Black absolutely must fight for the center.} e5 (6... e6 $6 {is clearly worse:} 7. Nc3 Qd7 8. Qb3 O-O-O 9. Bd2 {with O-O-O next.}) 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Bd2 Bxc3 9. bxc3 {I like this line against the Chigorin Defense. The idea is to build a strong center and get the bishop pair. A slight drawback is that the pawn structure is a bit damaged and White's king may feel a bit insecure at times, but knowing the ideas can definitely solve these problems. White's ideas include the possibility of playing c4 - d5 . Assuming Black defends, White opts for the ideas Rb1 , Qb3 . Very often the idea of f4 and Bg2 (or f4 - exf4 - e4 !), even if it involves the sacrifice of a pawn, is a strong option. And of course, if White manages to exchange queens, his advantage will be indisputable.} Qd6 {The main move - Black prevents c4 and d5 .} 10. Qb3 {There are many options, but this is the one I like best. White immediately puts pressure on both pawns b7 and f7 .} Nge7 {Black should sacrifice the pawn and look for some compensation.} 11. Qxb7 {White takes a pawn, and it seems to me that Black's compensation is rather doubtful. However, because of the awkward pawn structure, White should know how to position his pieces to gain an advantage, so let's see a little more.} Rb8 ({Beginning with} 11... O-O {does not change much as ... Rab8 is inevitable, likely resulting in a transposition.}) 12. Qa6 O-O {When Black plays with ... Rb8 , he generally wants to control the b-file with ... Rb6 and ... Rfb8 .} 13. Rd1 {Centralizing the rook and anticipating the doubling on the b-file that would have potentially created a threat of ... Rb1 . Now, with Rd1 , this is no longer a problem. The extended version of this variation can be found here .} *

