1. d4 d5 2. c4 c5 {This is a rare line. It became quite popular in mid 2010s, and Shakhriyar Mamedyarov played it many times.} 3. cxd5 {I think this is the most challenging.} Qxd5 ({Black should recapture the pawn right away.} 3... cxd4 $2 4. Qxd4 {White is just up a pawn. Next, Nc3 and e4 follow with a winning position.}) 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nc3 Qa5 ({Other moves are just bad.} 5... Qd8 $2 6. Qxd4 $1 {is just terrible for Black due to the lag in development.}) 6. Nxd4 e5 {This move is most likely premature.} 7. Nb3 Qc7 {Here, White has choice of course, but Stockfish finds a very strong path.} 8. Nb5 {Black's queen is being harrassed and there is no good way to solve this issue.} Bb4+ {Black wants to quickly develop at least some of his pieces.} 9. Bd2 Qe7 10. Rc1 Nc6 {White has lots of good options here, but the strongest seems to be Na5 .} 11. Na5 (11. Nc7+ $5 Qxc7 12. Bxb4 Nge7 13. Bd6 {is similar.}) 11... Be6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Nc7+ Qxc7 14. Bxb4 {With an obvious advantage for White thanks to the pair of bishops. Next, e3 comes and White will simply complete his development.} *

