1. d4 d5 2. c4 c5 {This is a rare line. It became quite popular in mid 2010s, and Shakhriyar Mamedyarov played it many times.} 3. cxd5 {I think this is the most challenging.} Qxd5 ({Black should recapture the pawn right away.} 3... cxd4 $2 4. Qxd4 {White is just up a pawn. Next, Nc3 and e4 follow with a winning position.}) 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nc3 Qa5 ({Other moves are just bad.} 5... Qd8 $2 6. Qxd4 $1 {is just terrible for Black due to the lag in development.}) 6. Nxd4 Nf6 7. a3 {This is not the most common move, and at first I thought it was simply unnecessary - why should White play a3 when there is no need? However, after taking a closer look, I realized what is going on: it is simply prophylactic, since Black's main idea here is ... e5 and ... Bb4 .   In addition, White can also play b4 . Many high-level GMs have been using this line recently. Black now has some options.} e5 {A standard way of playing as Black, but we will be able to see a benefit of having a3 : Black cannot play ... Bb4 now.} 8. Nb3 Qc7 {Here, White has a pleasant choice between Nb5!? and Bg5 .} 9. Nb5 {I think that this novelty is really annoying for Black.} Qc6 {perhaps the best move, hitting the knight.} 10. e3 {Now, Na5 is a serious threat. Also, Bd2 - Rc1 could be an idea. Black must act fast in order to not be much worse.} Bg4 {Everything else is much worse. Provoking f3 weakens White's position a bit.} (10... Qb6 $2 11. e4 $1) 11. f3 Be6 12. Na5 Qb6 (12... Qd7 13. Qxd7+ Kxd7 14. Bd2 {is just as bad as after 10... Be6 .}) 13. Nc4 {White gets the light squared bishop from Black, which offers a considerable strategic advantage.} Bxc4 14. Bxc4 {This looks great for White. Without the light-squared bishop Black's position looks unpleasant. The extended version of this variation can be found here .} *

