[Black "Dutch Stonewall - 6...Bd6 7.N"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A90"]
[PlyCount "29"]

1. d4 e6 {If Black decides to play Stonewall, this is a tricky move order. We are pretty much obliged to play c4 (well, e4 is the French, which belongs to a 1. e4 repertoire!) while Nf3 is not necessarily part of our repertoire, as we play Nc3 against the Nimzo.} 2. c4 f5 {And now we reach Dutch. There are many available setups for White. My recommendation is to play g3 .} 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 d5 ({Here I only focus on Stonewall setups, but I will analyze moves like} 4... Be7 {and Bb4 in another section. Black can begin with c6 as well.}) 5. Nf3 c6 ({Black achieves a Stonewall pawn formation.} 5... Bd6 {The recent trend is to play without ... c6 , but I don't see much difference from the standard 5... c6 move order.} 6. Nc3 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Qc2 {and we are back at the main line.}) (5... Be7 {see 6... Be7 . I admit though that Black can play ... Ne4 , ... O-O in some various move orders, delay one thing or another, but we play nonetheless O-O and Nc3 which will pretty much result in a transposition.}) 6. O-O {Here, Black can develop the bishop either to d6 or e7 .} Bd6 {This looks a bit more active than 6... Be7 .} 7. Nc3 ({I do not recommend} 7. b3 {as Black plays} Qe7 {and to play Ba3 , we need to spend some time ( a4 - Ba3 for instance) but this not only seems like a waste of time, but it also weakens the b4 -square.}) 7... O-O 8. Qc2 {I recommend this configuration for White against the Stonewall. It can be reached by many move orders, making it very flexible and universal. White's idea is to play Rb1 , followed by b4 and b5 , and open the queenside. We can keep the idea of Bf4 for the future as well.} Ne4 {One of the popular moves, but there are a lot of alternatives.} 9. Rb1 Nd7 10. b4 {This position looks quite promising for White.} b6 {This move was tried in some games but it looks not so logical, as it seems to weaken the pawn chain.} ({•} 10... Ndf6 {This move reinforces Ne4 , but also weakens the e5 -square. We can play} 11. c5 Bc7 12. Bf4 $5 Bxf4 13. gxf4 {with an advantage.}) ({•} 10... a6 11. a4 {does not really change much.}) 11. b5 {Now Black has only one move that holds Black's position.} Qc7 {Everything else is much worse. Now, there is some tension on the c-file.} 12. Bd2 {Supporting the c-file and now the idea is Rfc1 . I think White is better.} Nxc3 {The most forcing line.} 13. Bxc3 cxb5 {We might try 14. cxb5 , but it is only marginally better for White, or go for maximum with cxd5 !} 14. cxd5 exd5 15. Nh4 {White takes advantage of weakened long diagonal and weak pawn d5 and f5 .} ({The line continues with Nf6! (only move) Nxf5 Bxf5} 15. Qxf5 Qxc3 {Bxd5+! Kh8 Bxa8 Rxa8} 16. e3 {with unbalanced material; however, White should be better as Black's minor pieces do not have outposts and White's central pawns may quickly move forward.}) *

