1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O d6 {This is the initial position of the Classical Dutch.} 7. b3 {I would recommend delaying Nc3 . Since Black intends ... Ne4 , I think it makes sense to initially develop the bishop to b2 and only then play Nc3 , Nbd2 or even Nfd2 to counter Ne4 . White's plan here is very simple: Bb2 , Nc3 or Nbd2 , Qc2 and prepare e4 . We can try to play on the queenside as well, but that is a rather secondary plan. Black should generally play ... Ne4 sooner or later, but there are other possible plans as well.} ({After} 7. Nc3 Ne4 {we risk messing up our pawn structure on the queenside and if we play} 8. Nxe4 fxe4 9. Nd2 d5 {things get complicated in the center, and I am not convinced we are ready for that.}) 7... Ne4 8. Bb2 Bf6 {Black intends to play ... Nc6 and ... e5 .} 9. Nc3 Nc6 {Here White has many good options. I especially like the following.} (9... Nxc3 10. Bxc3 Nc6 11. Re1 {followed by e4 .}) 10. Nxe4 {The simplest.} fxe4 11. Nd2 d5 12. e3 ({With f3 next, undermining the center. It is a better version than Nc3} 12. Nxe4 {Nxe4 fxe4 since we have already developed our bishop and connected the rooks, making us ready to strike in the center.}) *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
