[Black "Leningrad - 6...d6 7.Nc3 Nc6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A89"]
[PlyCount "23"]

1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {In the Leningrad Dutch I would choose the more classical line, where I think Black struggles even though he has many possible plans.} Nc6 {Just like after the lines with 7... Qe8 , Black intends to play ... e5 . But now the knight gets attacked.} 8. d5 ({Black can play either} 8. Ne5 {or} Na5 {.}) 8... Ne5 {This is the old main line of the Leningrad Dutch. It seems odd from a strategic point of view since White can simply take e5 and get a better pawn structure, but things are not entirely trivial. In his course, Sam Shankland argues that although 9. Nxe5 is probably the strongest, it may not be so easy to learn and recommends 9. Qb3 . I completely agree with him, and for that reason 9. Qb3 is also my recommendation.} 9. Qb3 Nfd7 {Probably the best move, bringing the knight to c5 and keeping Ne5 active.} 10. Be3 {Following Sam's recommendation. Black has here some choice.} Nc5 ({Probably the most solid option for Black.} 10... Ng4 $6 11. Bd4 {is just terrible for Black.}) 11. Bxc5 dxc5 12. Rad1 {White is clearly better. Even if we gave up the dark-squared bishop, it wouldn't matter. Black's pawn structure is rather poor, and Black would have preferred to have the pawn on f7 instead of f5 . White can play Ng5 and Ne6 , or simply take e5 and play f4 - e4 , crushing in the center.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
