1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+ {The Keres Defense can be considered a variant of the Nimzo or Bogo Indian. Before developing the Ng8 , Black quickly brings out the bishop, perhaps intending to make ... f5 in the future. But it is still worse than the standard Nimzo, since now White is not pinned.} 3. Bd2 ({An alternative is} 3. Nd2 {which is also good, but} Bxd2+ {is the simplest to learn in my opinion. Of course, White does not play Nc3 as there are better options than transposing back to the Nimzo!}) 3... Bxd2+ {This was recently tried by Magnus Carlsen, following up with ... f5 , which is one of the main benefits of playing without ... Nf6 . Please note that White wants to play e4 and quickly control the center, so Black should do something about it.} ({Alternatives involve} 3... a5 {, Qe7 and} 4. c5 {and are analyzed in depth in chapter 47 .}) 4. Qxd2 {Black must do something right now about e4 .} Nf6 5. Nc3 {Renewing the idea of e4 . This pretty much leaves Black with little choice.} d5 {The only way to stop e4 .} 6. e3 O-O (6... c6 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Bd3) (6... dxc4 7. Nf3 {White will be able to get the c4 -pawn in one move.}) 7. cxd5 {I think that this is the best move here. We will see why in a moment.} exd5 (7... Nxd5 {This cannot be good for Black. White will control the center comfortably.}) 8. Bd3 {The point of capturing early on d5 and delaying moving the Ng1 . Now, White will play Nge2 ! In the long run, White will play for a f3 - e4 pawn break. Apart from that, going for the standard minority pawn attack b4 - b5 also makes sense. An issue for Black is that the Bc8 is passive here and cannot be traded.} b6 9. Nge2 c5 ({One of the standard plans for Black here. Trading the bishops with} 9... Ba6 10. O-O Bxd3 11. Qxd3 {will leave the queenside pawn structure weak, as I analyze in many similar positions in the section on the Nimzo in Part 1.}) 10. O-O Bb7 11. Rac1 Nc6 12. Bb1 {Not the only good move, but a logical one. The point is that White should keep an option of playing against the IQP if Black takes on d4 . For that to happen, the d4 -pawn must be supported by the queen as well. Additionally, if Black decides to play ... c4 , the bishop it does not attack our bishop with tempo.} *

