[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Def"]
[Black "Philidor - 3...e5 4.Nf3 Nbd7"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C41"]
[PlyCount "25"]

1. d4 d6 {This move order allows White to immediately take control of the center with e4 . This definitely seems the right way, although Black can play 2... Nf6 , which unfortunately does not allow us to play c4 and transpose to the Pirc or Philidor. However, I think we should not fear these openings, and I think my recommendations are quite convincing! Therefore: 2. e4 !} 2. e4 {Don't worry about having to study too many lines: my suggestions are relatively easy to learn, and we have an edge almost everywhere because of the space advantage.} ({• I would have loved to recommend here} 2. Nf3 {but unfortunately in the event of a transposition to the King's Indian after} Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 O-O {we don't get the Be2 - Be3 system, which I covered in part 1, as we already have Nf3 on the board.}) ({• After} 2. c4 {Black can play} e5 $1 {and unfortunately, we cannot get our King's Indian setups with Be2 - Be3 . We never want to play d5 so early,} 3. Nc3 {is met by} exd4 {and recapturing with the queen is not ideal. So the only reasonable move here seems} 4. Nf3 {but now Black can play e4! Ng5} f5 {and this line is pretty good for Black.}) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 {Here, Black can choose between Philidor and Pirc.} e5 {The Philidor Defense does not have a great reputation and White should be better in many ways. My recommendation is fairly simple and easy to learn.} 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 {I would recommend the classical approach against the Philidor. It seems like there is a lot of theory but I will simplify it - in fact, there are only a couple of lines you need to know and it is mostly about navigating through these positions by ideas.} Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 {White supports his center in advance. Sometimes, we may make use of the f1 -square for the bishop. Black has many possible plans here, but White retains an edge everywhere.} c6 8. a4 b6 ({The main move.} 8... Qc7 {This move seems a bit weird to me as I am not sure what is the follow-up. Perhaps there could be some transposition, but this move order just seems a bit odd. Anyway, we go for same setups.} 9. h3 h6 10. Be3 Re8 11. a5 {or} d5) 9. Be3 {Not the most common move here, but I like it a lot. I don't think we need to worry about ... Ng4 for now, as Be3 has a certain tactical idea which h3 lacks.} ({•} 9. d5 {is a typical idea here, which I recommend after the inclusion of 9. Be3  a6 , because here White cannot hold comfortably a piece on the d5 square.} cxd5 10. Bxd5 (10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. Bxd5 Rb8 {and Nf6 is coming.}) 10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Nf6 {and in comparison with what we have in the main line, this would not be possible as thanks to inclusion of Be3 and ... a6 moves, the b6 -pawn would hang.}) ({• After} 9. h3 a6 10. d5 {(trying the same thing as in the main line)} cxd5 11. Bxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 {the b6 -pawn is not under pressure and this allows Black to play} Nf6 {and fight off the Nd5 . This is not the case after 9. Be3 . Still, White is a bit better here, but it feels like Black managed to deal with at least some of his problems...}) 9... a6 10. d5 {A common idea in the Philidor. We fight for the light squares, mainly d5 .} cxd5 ({There is hardly anything better. In the event of} 10... c5 $6 {(which in many similar positions is what Black tends to opt for) we should be happy with our position as we have some sort of improved version of the King's Indian as our pawn is on c2 . This allows us to use the c4 -square for the knight. In the future, we should try a pawn break on the queenside (b4) or kingside (f4).} 11. Bd3 {with previously described plans.}) (10... Bb7 $6 11. dxc6 $1 Bxc6 12. Qd3 {This looks bad for Black.}) 11. Bxd5 {It is important to recapture with the bishop to comfortably take control over the d5 square.} Nxd5 (11... Rb8 12. Bc4) 12. Nxd5 Bb7 13. c4 {White is clearly better. We have a powerful Nd5 and a bind on the queenside that makes Black's position very uncomfortable.} *

