[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Def"]
[Black "Pirc - 3...g6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B08"]
[PlyCount "29"]

1. d4 d6 {This move order allows White to immediately take control of the center with e4 . This definitely seems the right way, although Black can play 2... Nf6 , which unfortunately does not allow us to play c4 and transpose to the Pirc or Philidor. However, I think we should not fear these openings, and I think my recommendations are quite convincing! Therefore: 2. e4 !} 2. e4 {Don't worry about having to study too many lines: my suggestions are relatively easy to learn, and we have an edge almost everywhere because of the space advantage.} ({• I would have loved to recommend here} 2. Nf3 {but unfortunately in the event of a transposition to the King's Indian after} Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 O-O {we don't get the Be2 - Be3 system, which I covered in part 1, as we already have Nf3 on the board.}) ({• After} 2. c4 {Black can play} e5 $1 {and unfortunately, we cannot get our King's Indian setups with Be2 - Be3 . We never want to play d5 so early,} 3. Nc3 {is met by} exd4 {and recapturing with the queen is not ideal. So the only reasonable move here seems} 4. Nf3 {but now Black can play e4! Ng5} f5 {and this line is pretty good for Black.}) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 {Here, Black can choose between Philidor and Pirc.} g6 {Against the Pirc, I would recommend an aggressive plan, yet still quite easy to learn.} 4. Be3 {White wants to play Qd2 , O-O-O and attack on the kingside. However, there are also ideas connected with f4 and building a strong center. Using the move order 4. Be3 avoids many lines after the immediate 4. f4 that are considered OK for Black.} Bg7 {The main move but there are ideas here of delaying ... Bg7 as well.} 5. Qd2 c6 {Black should not rush with castling and begin some counterplay on the queenside with ... b5 , or some ... Qa5 .} (5... Nbd7 {is possible, but I am not sure if it makes sense to declare the knight's intentions so early.} 6. Bh6 O-O 7. O-O-O) 6. Nf3 {One of the rare instances in this Pirc course where I recommend playing Nf3 over f3 , but here it is in fact clearly stronger.} O-O (6... Ng4 {is again pointless:} 7. Bg5 {where h3 will kick out the knight soon.}) 7. Bh6 {Trading the bishops is a good thing for White. Now, we can either play positionally with Bd3 and O-O , or more aggressively with h4 - h5 and O-O-O . Possibly, the latter is a better choice.} d5 {Probably the best move, as played by Magnus Carlsen. But it is extremely rare and also leads to a stable advantage for White.} (7... b5 8. Bd3 {is better for White, as mentioned after 6... b5 . keeping an option of castling both kingside and queenside. The trade of dark-squared bishops should offer an advantage to White.}) 8. Bxg7 Kxg7 9. e5 Ne4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Ng5 Bf5 {Somewhat more solid than 11... c5 as played by Magnus.} 12. f3 {I did not find a way to win the e4 -pawn, but I think that after 12. f3 our strong center offers us an advantage anyway.} exf3 13. Nxf3 Qd5 14. Bd3 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 {Black still needs to work hard to earn equality and without a doubt, White is better.} *

