[ECO "D27"]
[PlyCount "13"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 {The Queen's Gambit Accepted (QGA) is one of the soundest openings for Black against 1.d4 . It has an extremely rich history, and today, it has been employed by many top players. To refute such an opening is pretty much impossible - but I believe I found interesting ideas and new paths that can cause a lot of practical problems to Black and, at the same time, give us good winning chances.} 3. Nf3 ({I decided to recommend the} 3. Nf3 {lines in this course as I personally prefer them over e4 , partly because I have more experience here.}) 3... Nf6 {Black usually begins with this move, but I cover sidelines as well.} (3... a6 4. e3 b5 {Black tries to hold on to the c4 -pawn, but we can get it quickly back thanks to} 5. a4 Bb7 6. b3 $1 {challenging the pawn chain. See here.}) ({After} 3... c5 {, I analyze} 4. e4 $5 {, which I think is the simplest, as the resulting endgame after} cxd4 5. Qxd4 Qxd4 6. Nxd4 {is not easy to play for Black. See here.}) 4. e3 e6 (4... Bg4 {is the major alternative to the standard 4...e6 . However, I find that positions after} 5. Bxc4 e6 6. Nc3 {are quite dubious for Black.}) (4... Be6 {again, holding onto the c4 -pawn is not great.} 5. Nc3 {Such setup will unlikely last for Black.}) ({You'll find both alternatives, as well as} 4... g6 {, in this chapter.}) 5. Bxc4 c5 (5... a6 6. O-O b5 {Systems with ... b5 before Black plays ... c5 are also not the best. The difference is that we can play with Bd3 (instead of Be2 , which normally happens when Black plays ... b5 later), which gives an opportunity for quick e4 - e5 ideas, as seen here.} 7. Bd3 $1 Bb7 8. a4 b4 9. Nbd2 {renewing the e4 idea. This looks great for White.}) 6. O-O a6 ({The main line in the QGA, played thousands of times.} 6... Nc6 {has become quite popular recently, but I put Black to the absolute test with the extremely challenging} 7. Nc3 a6 8. d5 $1 {, where Black needs to know a lot to keep the balance. See here.}) 7. b3 ({Given the complexity and popularity of this line, I decided to stick with the recently popular move 7.b3 as my main recommendation,  but as an alternative I cover} 7. Re1 {as well in this chapter.}) *

