1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 a6 4. e3 b5 {This variation attempts to defend the c4 -pawn, but White's resources of a4 and b3 are sufficient to get it back.} 5. a4 Bb7 6. b3 {Challenging the entire pawn chain.} cxb3 {This may be tempting, as it leads to simplifications, and one may think this should equalize. It is not true, however.} 7. axb5 axb5 8. Rxa8 Bxa8 9. Bxb5+ c6 ({Otherwise, Black has serious problems with his king along the light squares.} 9... Nd7 $2 10. Qxb3 Ngf6 11. Ne5 e6 12. Qa4) (9... Bc6 10. Bxc6+ Nxc6 11. d5) 10. Bc4 e6 11. Qxb3 Nf6 12. O-O {Black has issues completing his development here. The pressure on the a2 - g8 diagonal is a serious problem.} Nbd7 13. Ng5 {And Black's position is about to collapse. At the right moment, it is very likely that sacrifices on f7 or e6 should win, but an important resource is also e4 !} *

