1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 a6 4. e3 b5 {This variation attempts to defend the c4 -pawn, but White's resources of a4 and b3 are sufficient to get it back.} 5. a4 Bb7 6. b3 {Challenging the entire pawn chain.} cxb3 {This may be tempting, as it leads to simplifications, and one may think this should equalize. It is not true, however.} 7. axb5 axb5 8. Rxa8 Bxa8 9. Bxb5+ c6 ({Otherwise, Black has serious problems with his king along the light squares.} 9... Nd7 $2 10. Qxb3 Ngf6 11. Ne5 e6 12. Qa4) (9... Bc6 10. Bxc6+ Nxc6 11. d5) 10. Bc4 e6 11. Qxb3 Nf6 12. O-O {Black has issues completing his development here. The pressure on the a2 - g8 diagonal is a serious problem.} Be7 13. Ne5 {This looks the most promising - White goes immediately after the weaknesses on f7 and e6 .} O-O 14. Nxf7 Kxf7 15. Bxe6+ Ke8 16. Nc3 {Black's position is, of course, very shaky here. His king is unsafe and it is hard to imagine that it will get to safety anytime soon. White has long-lasting compensation. White's main idea is Bd2 and Ra1 , but there are also ideas of Na4 .} Na6 17. Bd2 Nc7 18. Bc4 Qd6 (18... Nfd5 $2 19. Ne2 {followed by e4 .}) 19. Na4 {Preventing ... c5 and opening the path for the bishop.} Nd7 ({Otherwise, ...c5 is not attainable.} 19... Ng4 20. Qb8+ Qd8 21. Qb1 $1 {hitting h7 .}) (19... Nb5 20. h3 Ne4 21. Be1) 20. Ba5 ({Intending to meet c5 with} 20. Nc5 {when a possible continuation is Qc6 f3} Nxc5 21. dxc5 {Bxc5 Kh1± White steps aside from the g1 - a7 diagonal and will play e4 . Black's king remains in the center, and despite achieving ... c5 , he is still in trouble. One of the main ideas for White here is to play Qb2 and make use of the a1 - h8 diagonal.}) *

