1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 a6 4. e3 b5 {This variation attempts to defend the c4 -pawn, but White's resources of a4 and b3 are sufficient to get it back.} 5. a4 Bb7 6. b3 {Challenging the entire pawn chain.} e6 ({Black can play} 6... Nf6 {as well but it would sooner or later transpose anyway. One thing is for sure, though - As we've seen, Black should not play cxb3 .}) 7. bxc4 bxc4 ({Necessary. Black needs to simplify the position and play for ...c5 . After} 7... b4 $6 {, White plays} 8. c5 {gaining space, similarly to Bb4+?! Bd2 Bxd2+ Nbxd2 b4 c5!± .}) 8. Bxc4 Nf6 ({Other moves that were played here are} 8... Nd7 {or c5 , but they would likely transpose either way as ... Nf6 sooner or later must be played.}) 9. O-O {White has a fairly simple plan here: Nbd2 , the bishop may go to b2 or a3 (say, Qb3 - Ba3 is an idea), while Rb1 is often useful, pretty much depending on what Black does. Black has many options now, but I don't think he can equalize.} Nbd7 {Black can delay ... c5 (or play without it) and play this first. I don't think it actually changes much.} 10. Nbd2 {Here, c5 , of course, is the same as the main line . Let's look at alternatives.} a5 {This move was tried in Grischuk-Ponkratov (2022). The idea is to secure the b4 -square. However, with only the bishop controlling that square, Black cannot really succeed with this plan.} 11. Qc2 ({Grischuk played} 11. Nb3 {, but it is less good due to} Bb4 12. Ba3 Ne4 {and Nb3 is not that useful as it blocks the b -file, which matters a lot - now, White cannot put much pressure on the b4 -square.}) 11... Bb4 12. Ba3 {Dealing with the strong Bb4 .} O-O (12... Bxa3 13. Rxa3) 13. Bxb4 axb4 14. Rfc1 c5 15. Qb2 {The b4 -pawn is a weakness and will likely fall.} *

