1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 a6 4. e3 b5 {This variation attempts to defend the c4 -pawn, but White's resources of a4 and b3 are sufficient to get it back.} 5. a4 Bb7 6. b3 {Challenging the entire pawn chain.} e6 ({Black can play} 6... Nf6 {as well but it would sooner or later transpose anyway. One thing is for sure, though - As we've seen, Black should not play cxb3 .}) 7. bxc4 bxc4 ({Necessary. Black needs to simplify the position and play for ...c5 . After} 7... b4 $6 {, White plays} 8. c5 {gaining space, similarly to Bb4+?! Bd2 Bxd2+ Nbxd2 b4 c5!± .}) 8. Bxc4 Nf6 ({Other moves that were played here are} 8... Nd7 {or c5 , but they would likely transpose either way as ... Nf6 sooner or later must be played.}) 9. O-O {White has a fairly simple plan here: Nbd2 , the bishop may go to b2 or a3 (say, Qb3 - Ba3 is an idea), while Rb1 is often useful, pretty much depending on what Black does. Black has many options now, but I don't think he can equalize.} Nbd7 {Black can delay ... c5 (or play without it) and play this first. I don't think it actually changes much.} 10. Nbd2 {Here, c5 , of course, is the same as the main line . Let's look at alternatives.} Be7 11. Qb3 Ra7 12. Ba3 {This position is simply a worse version of the main line.} c5 13. Rfc1 O-O 14. dxc5 {Not the only move but a fairly simple solution. The pressure on the c -file forces the trade of the dark-squared bishops.} Bxc5 (14... Nxc5 {just drops a pawn:} 15. Bxc5 Bxc5 16. Bxe6) 15. Bf1 Bd5 16. Qc3 Bxa3 17. Qxa3 {As usual, Black's a6 -pawn is a weakness. Black may try ... a5 , of course, but this does not really fully help Black's cause as then b5 will be a weak square, and the a5 -pawn anyway will run under pressure with Nd4 - N2b3 in the future.} *

