1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 a6 4. e3 b5 {This variation attempts to defend the c4 -pawn, but White's resources of a4 and b3 are sufficient to get it back.} 5. a4 Bb7 6. b3 {Challenging the entire pawn chain.} e6 ({Black can play} 6... Nf6 {as well but it would sooner or later transpose anyway. One thing is for sure, though - As we've seen, Black should not play cxb3 .}) 7. bxc4 bxc4 ({Necessary. Black needs to simplify the position and play for ...c5 . After} 7... b4 $6 {, White plays} 8. c5 {gaining space, similarly to Bb4+?! Bd2 Bxd2+ Nbxd2 b4 c5!± .}) 8. Bxc4 Nf6 ({Other moves that were played here are} 8... Nd7 {or c5 , but they would likely transpose either way as ... Nf6 sooner or later must be played.}) 9. O-O {White has a fairly simple plan here: Nbd2 , the bishop may go to b2 or a3 (say, Qb3 - Ba3 is an idea), while Rb1 is often useful, pretty much depending on what Black does. Black has many options now, but I don't think he can equalize.} c5 10. Nbd2 Nbd7 {The most solid response. Black should keep the tension in the center and support the c5 -pawn.} 11. Rb1 Ra7 {A clever move, making space for the queen on a8 .} (11... Rb8 $6 {is worse, as the a6 -pawn is a target after} 12. Qe2 {.}) 12. Ne5 ({A direct and concrete approach taking advantage of the lead in development. In 2012, I played} 12. Bb2 Be7 13. Qb3 O-O 14. Rfc1 Qa8 {, but White has only a minimal advantage here. This is Swiercz-Kuzmicz, 2012.}) 12... cxd4 13. exd4 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. Qg4 ({Black may have a hard time completing his development here. The e5 -pawn is irrelevant as Black's king is so unsafe... A sample continuation is Nxe5 Qg3 Ng6 Qe3 Qa8} 15. Bd3 $1 {and again Nc4 is coming. After} Bxg2 $6 {Qg3 Bb7} 16. Nc4 {we're strategically winning.}) *

