1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 a6 4. e3 b5 {This variation attempts to defend the c4 -pawn, but White's resources of a4 and b3 are sufficient to get it back.} 5. a4 Bb7 6. b3 {Challenging the entire pawn chain.} e6 ({Black can play} 6... Nf6 {as well but it would sooner or later transpose anyway. One thing is for sure, though - As we've seen, Black should not play cxb3 .}) 7. bxc4 bxc4 ({Necessary. Black needs to simplify the position and play for ...c5 . After} 7... b4 $6 {, White plays} 8. c5 {gaining space, similarly to Bb4+?! Bd2 Bxd2+ Nbxd2 b4 c5!± .}) 8. Bxc4 Nf6 ({Other moves that were played here are} 8... Nd7 {or c5 , but they would likely transpose either way as ... Nf6 sooner or later must be played.}) 9. O-O {White has a fairly simple plan here: Nbd2 , the bishop may go to b2 or a3 (say, Qb3 - Ba3 is an idea), while Rb1 is often useful, pretty much depending on what Black does. Black has many options now, but I don't think he can equalize.} c5 10. Nbd2 Nbd7 {The most solid response. Black should keep the tension in the center and support the c5 -pawn.} 11. Rb1 Qc7 12. Ba3 Be7 {White has a lot of options here. If you turn on the engine, anything gives White an advantage. I would like to recommend an idea that feels the best to me.} 13. Qe2 {This move, followed by Rfc1 is, of course, OK as well. I decided to keep it as an informational line due to issues with the a4 -pawn in the following line.} ({Also} 13. Qb3 Rb8 14. Qd3 {looks very tempting as well, but Black can ignore the a6 -pawn:} O-O {!} 15. Bxa6 Bxa6 16. Qxa6 Ra8 {and the a4 -pawn will fall sooner or later with an equal position.} 17. Qb5 Ra5 18. Qb3 Rfa8) 13... O-O 14. Rfc1 Bc6 {And it seems like Black should be doing quite OK.} 15. Nb3 Bxa4 16. Nxc5 Nxc5 17. Bxc5 Bxc5 18. Bd3 {White gets the piece back, but not only many pieces were traded, but the a4 -pawn is also lost, which reduces White's winning chances.} *

