1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 c5 ({A relatively rare line compared to the standard} 3... Nf6 {and e6 . Black immediately challenges the center and tries to make White decide on the pawn structure right away.}) 4. e4 {Not the most common move here - but by far the simplest.} cxd4 5. Qxd4 Qxd4 6. Nxd4 {I think this endgame is promising for White. The c4 -pawn is going to be recaptured. Nb5 is an unpleasant idea to face, and with quick development, White should be able to set some problems for Black to solve.} a6 {This is another option here.} 7. Bxc4 e5 {Given that Nb5 is no longer possible, this move makes a lot of sense. White has here a couple of options. Out of all of them, I like Nc2 the most.} 8. Nc2 ({I like this move the most. The idea is to reroute the knight to d5 in the future via the e3 -square, but also, Black cannot play ...Bb4 , which was normally the case after} 8. Nb3 {, for instance. White has a simple plan here: Nc3 , f3 , Be3 , and try to make use of the d5 -square or provoke some weakening of Black's queenside.}) 8... Nc6 9. Nc3 b5 10. Bb3 {This helps White as Black's queenside becomes more vulnerable and subject to potential a4 ideas.} *

