1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 c5 ({A relatively rare line compared to the standard} 3... Nf6 {and e6 . Black immediately challenges the center and tries to make White decide on the pawn structure right away.}) 4. e4 {Not the most common move here - but by far the simplest.} cxd4 5. Qxd4 Qxd4 6. Nxd4 {I think this endgame is promising for White. The c4 -pawn is going to be recaptured. Nb5 is an unpleasant idea to face, and with quick development, White should be able to set some problems for Black to solve.} Bd7 {A logical move, preventing Nb5 and preparing ... Nc6 .} (6... e5 7. Nb5 Na6 8. Bxc4) 7. Bxc4 Nc6 8. Be3 {There is an idea of bringing the knight from g8 to c6 as well:} Nxd4 9. Bxd4 e6 {Here, I would delay the development of the knight. Sometimes, the standard Nc3 is fine, but Nd2 may be more flexible in some positions.} 10. O-O Ne7 11. Rd1 {A useful move that prevents Black from castling kingside in the future as the Bd7 will be under pressure.} Nc6 12. Be3 Be7 13. Nc3 {White is obviously better in this endgame. The main plan involves f4 - e5 , dropping the bishop back to e2 and then to f3 . However, Nb5 is also an idea to be kept in mind.} *

