1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 c5 ({A relatively rare line compared to the standard} 3... Nf6 {and e6 . Black immediately challenges the center and tries to make White decide on the pawn structure right away.}) 4. e4 {Not the most common move here - but by far the simplest.} cxd4 5. Qxd4 Qxd4 6. Nxd4 {I think this endgame is promising for White. The c4 -pawn is going to be recaptured. Nb5 is an unpleasant idea to face, and with quick development, White should be able to set some problems for Black to solve.} Bd7 {A logical move, preventing Nb5 and preparing ... Nc6 .} (6... e5 7. Nb5 Na6 8. Bxc4) 7. Bxc4 Nc6 8. Be3 Nf6 {The most popular move here.} 9. Nxc6 Bxc6 10. f3 {White's pawn chain is set up directly against the Bc6 .} e6 11. Nd2 {A flexible development of the knight, going towards b3 or c4 squares.} Bd6 12. Be2 {liberating the c4 -square for the knight.} Nd7 13. Kf2 Ke7 14. Nc4 {Now Black has two possible retreats for the bishop.} Bc7 15. Rhc1 {White has a relatively simple plan of advancing pawns on the queenside with a clear advantage in this endgame.} *

