1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 {In this chapter, I look at lines where Black can try to hold on to the c4 -pawn but, as we will see, without success. White's main ideas are a4 and b3 , and Black does not have a proper way to respond to them.} c6 4. e3 Be6 {An artificial way of defending the c4 -pawn - but watch out, it comes with a trap!} 5. Nbd2 {I think this is the simplest. White attacks the c4 -pawn and provokes the weakening ... b5 . Additionally, now Ng5 ideas are available.} ({Trying to deal with ...Be6 by playing} 5. Ng5 $4 {loses due to} Qa5+) 5... Qa5 {This move temporarily defends the c4 -pawn tactically. But when White castles, Black will be in trouble.} 6. Be2 Nf6 7. O-O b5 8. a4 {Black holds onto the pawn for now, but at the cost of being undeveloped. White is much better.} a6 9. Qc2 g6 10. Ng5 Bc8 11. e4 {White has a lead in development and threatens to push e5 .} *

