1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 {In this chapter, I look at lines where Black can try to hold on to the c4 -pawn but, as we will see, without success. White's main ideas are a4 and b3 , and Black does not have a proper way to respond to them.} c6 4. e3 Be6 {An artificial way of defending the c4 -pawn - but watch out, it comes with a trap!} 5. Nbd2 {I think this is the simplest. White attacks the c4 -pawn and provokes the weakening ... b5 . Additionally, now Ng5 ideas are available.} ({Trying to deal with ...Be6 by playing} 5. Ng5 $4 {loses due to} Qa5+) 5... b5 ({According to the engine, this is not good for Black, but other moves pretty much make no sense as White can simply get the pawn back. For example,} 5... Nf6 6. Nxc4 {.}) 6. a4 Nf6 {Black needs to complete his development.} 7. axb5 cxb5 8. b3 {A standard idea. The bishop on e6 only stands in the way of developing Black's pieces.} c3 {Trying to keep lines closed.} 9. Bxb5+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 11. Nb1 ({The most precise.} 11. Nc4 {is good as well, but I like the idea of just attacking the c3 -pawn. On top of that, the a7 -pawn is also under pressure, which matters as Black may play ... Rc8 .}) 11... Rc8 12. Qd3 Qc7 13. Na3 Qb6 (13... e6 14. Nb5 {is losing.} Qb6 15. Ra6 $1 {followed by Nxa7 .}) 14. Qc2 e6 15. Nc4 {Winning a tempo on the queen.} Qb8 16. O-O Bb4 17. Ra4 {White will continue with Ba3 dislodging Black's bishop.} *

