1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 {In this chapter, I look at lines where Black can try to hold on to the c4 -pawn but, as we will see, without success. White's main ideas are a4 and b3 , and Black does not have a proper way to respond to them.} b5 (3... c6 4. e3 b5 5. a4 {is another move order.}) 4. a4 c6 5. e3 {White plays here for b3 , either immediately or first axb5 and then b3 . Black is unable to keep the extra pawn, and White will have some positional advantage, as the analysis shows.} e6 (5... Nf6 {is roughly the same, but it leaves Black fewer options - now, Black does not have an option of ... Bb4 as in the main line.} 6. axb5 cxb5 7. b3 {with an inevitable transposition as White gets the pawn back.}) 6. axb5 {I would recommend trading on b5 first. That way, the pawn on b5 is less stable, and in case the c4 -pawn moves, we can play Bxb5 with a check.} (6. b3 {is another option, but after} Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ {, White cannot play} 8. Nbxd2 {due to} c3 $1 {For this reason, Nfxd2 should be played, but it is kind of passive.}) 6... cxb5 7. b3 {Black can play here with ... Bb4 or without.} Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Nbxd2 {Here, White can recapture with the b1 -knight as there is no ... c3 .} a5 10. bxc4 b4 {Black's best chance is to go for a position similar to the Noteboom, hoping that the queenside pawns will become strong in the future. However, White's central pawns are strong too.} 11. Bd3 Nf6 12. g4 {Not the most common move here, but the idea is a standard one. If Black takes the g4 -pawn, he will lose the g7 -pawn, which is more important. I think White has a promising position here.} Bb7 (12... Nxg4 13. Rg1 f5 14. h3 Nf6 15. Rxg7 {is the point.}) 13. g5 Nfd7 14. h4 {White is clearly better. It is not clear what Black will do with his king, as White's potential attack on the kingside can be devastating.} *

