1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Be6 {Holding on to the c4 -pawn in this artificial way does not lead to anything good for Black.} 5. Nc3 {White prepares Ng5 in order to meet ... Bd5 with e4 .} ({Nc6} 5. e4 Bg4 6. Be3 {is covered in Part 1 of the course in the section on the Tango! See here.}) 5... h6 {Black prevents Ng5 , but on the other hand, it is a waste of a tempo in some way.} 6. e4 ({The most challenging move. In 2010, in my game against David Navara, I played here} 6. Ne5 c5 $1 7. Qa4+ Nbd7 8. Bxc4 Bxc4 9. Qxc4 e6 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. dxc5 Qc6 12. Qa4 Bxc5 13. Qxc6+ bxc6 14. Bd2 {with a better endgame. It is also possible, but it is a minimalistic approach. We can hope for much more with 6.e4 .}) 6... c6 7. Ne5 b5 8. a4 {Undermining the pawn chain.} b4 (8... Bd7 9. axb5 cxb5 10. d5 {looks terrible for Black.}) 9. Ne2 Nxe4 10. Nf4 {And White has a strong initiative. Stockfish claims White is simply winning here!} Bd5 11. Nxd5 cxd5 12. Qf3 Nf6 13. Bxc4 ({With a crushing initiative. A sample continuation is a6 O-O e6 Re1 Be7} 13. Bd3 {and Black has issues with their king. Qg3 is annoying.}) *

