1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Be6 {Holding on to the c4 -pawn in this artificial way does not lead to anything good for Black.} 5. Nc3 {White prepares Ng5 in order to meet ... Bd5 with e4 .} ({Nc6} 5. e4 Bg4 6. Be3 {is covered in Part 1 of the course in the section on the Tango! See here.}) 5... c6 6. Ng5 ({Going after the pair of bishops and wanting to recapture the c4 -pawn. The bishop has to move, as Qd7?! looks very awkward for Black.} 6. e4 h6 {Nxe6 Qxe6} 7. e5 {is a sample continuation.}) 6... Bd5 {Necessity. We are now entering a long sequence of moves, but White, in the end, will have a very promising position.} 7. e4 h6 8. exd5 hxg5 9. dxc6 Nxc6 10. d5 Ne5 {There were some games like this, but White has been scoring well here for a reason. White has a choice now between Bg5 and the alternative  Qd4 .} 11. Bxg5 {Without their light-squared bishop and behind in development, Black's position is difficult to play.} Qb6 12. Bxc4 Qxb2 ({White is winning after} 12... Nxc4 13. Qa4+ {.}) 13. Bb5+ Kd8 14. Rc1 {White's position looks winning, but Black can stay in the game thanks to the tactical nuance.} Ne4 15. Nxe4 Qxb5 16. Qe2 {White needs to trade queens to castle.} Nd3+ ({After} 16... Qxe2+ 17. Kxe2 {Black cannot complete the development. White will simply improve his position, and sooner or later Black's position will crack. For example, Bf4 would be a good start, followed by Rhd1 , Rc7 , etc.}) 17. Kd2 {Black loses the knight.} *

