1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A somewhat forgotten line, not played that often on the top level, but nonetheless, White should know what to do against it.} 5. Bxc4 {Recapturing the pawn, but also creating a threat of Bxf7 !} e6 6. Nc3 a6 {A flexible move, keeping options of ... Nc6 , ... Nbd7 and ... c5 . But it has a certain drawback - the e5 -square is not under Black's control, and White can exploit it immediately.} 7. h3 Bh5 {Generally necessary, as taking on f3 voluntarily gives the pair of bishops. I think White should go after this bishop anyway.} 8. g4 Bg6 9. Ne5 {After 6...Nbd7 , such an idea was not possible. Here, however, we can grab the pair of bishops with a promising position.} Nfd7 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Bf1 {This is a worse version of the 9...Nbd7  line.} *

