1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A somewhat forgotten line, not played that often on the top level, but nonetheless, White should know what to do against it.} 5. Bxc4 {Recapturing the pawn, but also creating a threat of Bxf7 !} e6 6. Nc3 a6 {A flexible move, keeping options of ... Nc6 , ... Nbd7 and ... c5 . But it has a certain drawback - the e5 -square is not under Black's control, and White can exploit it immediately.} 7. h3 Bh5 {Generally necessary, as taking on f3 voluntarily gives the pair of bishops. I think White should go after this bishop anyway.} 8. g4 Bg6 9. Ne5 {After 6...Nbd7 , such an idea was not possible. Here, however, we can grab the pair of bishops with a promising position.} Nbd7 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Bf1 {The bishop drops back to occupy the long diagonal.} c6 {Black should create some wall against the Bg2 .} 12. Bg2 {This position resembles a 4.e3 Slav but an amazing version for White. The pair of bishops and control over the center make Black's position difficult. White has a choice between either castling kingside or queenside; both options should be fine.} {Black's best bet is to play via ...Nd5 ASAP. Other moves, like Qc7 or Bd6 which are by far the most popular, are not good enough.} Bd6 13. Bd2 Qe7 {One of the most common setups here but it seems like it is just a bad plan. Black cannot really play via ... e5 , as d5 is always an option and now the b7 -pawn is also weak.} 14. Qb3 Rb8 15. O-O-O {White is clearly better as Black does not really have an active plan.} *

