1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A somewhat forgotten line, not played that often on the top level, but nonetheless, White should know what to do against it.} 5. Bxc4 {Recapturing the pawn, but also creating a threat of Bxf7 !} e6 6. Nc3 Nc6 {This is one of the pet lines of Baadur Jobava, who employed it successfully numerous times. The idea is to play ... Bd6 , ... O-O and ... e5 ASAP. White has many options here and despite Baadur's success, engines don't share his optimism for this line.} 7. h3 Bh5 (7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 {does not require much analysis - White is clearly better.}) 8. O-O Bd6 9. Re1 {An interesting move that essentially prepares g4 and e4 .} Qe7 {This was played by Jobava.} 10. Bd2 {This move is very strong I think. White keeps an idea of g4 , but also wants maybe Rc1 and put pressure on the queenside, anticipating that Black might castle queenside.} ({There is nothing wrong with going for} 10. g4 Nxg4 11. hxg4 Bxg4 {, as here Black gets some practical chances, even though objectively his position is dubious. There is no need to enter that.}) 10... O-O-O {Castling queenside is incredibly risky for Black as his king is going to be in danger immediately.} 11. Rc1 e5 12. d5 {The knight lacks a good retreat.} *

