1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A somewhat forgotten line, not played that often on the top level, but nonetheless, White should know what to do against it.} 5. Bxc4 {Recapturing the pawn, but also creating a threat of Bxf7 !} e6 6. Nc3 Be7 {This move was tried in Matlakov-Alekseenko (2018), and I really like how Matlakov reacted.} 7. h3 Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. h4 {A very aggressive approach, taking advantage of Black not having control over the e5 -square. Next, h5 is unstoppable, as Black should not play ... h6 or ... h5 himself.} h6 (9... h5 {is similar.}) 10. Ne5 {Black has issues with the light-squared bishop.} Bh7 {The attempt to save the bishop leads Black to tactical complications he would rather avoid.} 11. g5 Nfd7 (11... hxg5 12. hxg5 Nd5 13. g6 {White is winning.}) 12. Nxf7 Kxf7 13. Bxe6+ Ke8 (13... Kxe6 $2 {allows White to deliver mate in three.} 14. Qb3+ Kf5 15. e4+ Kg6 16. h5# ({Or Kg4} 16. Qd1)) 14. gxh6 {With an overwhelming advantage.} *

