1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A somewhat forgotten line, not played that often on the top level, but nonetheless, White should know what to do against it.} 5. Bxc4 {Recapturing the pawn, but also creating a threat of Bxf7 !} e6 6. Nc3 Be7 {This move was tried in Matlakov-Alekseenko (2018), and I really like how Matlakov reacted.} 7. h3 Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. h4 {A very aggressive approach, taking advantage of Black not having control over the e5 -square. Next, h5 is unstoppable, as Black should not play ... h6 or ... h5 himself.} Ne4 {Black must find a path for the bishop and liberate the e4 -square.} 10. h5 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Be4 12. Bd3 Qd5 {Only here I would recommend an improvement over Matlakov's play.} 13. Qa4+ ({Much stronger move than} 13. Rh3 {played by Matlakov. The queen steps aside from ... Bxf3 coming with a tempo and intends c4 next.}) 13... Nd7 14. c4 Qc6 15. Qxc6 Bxc6 16. Ke2 {Thanks to the space advantage, White is much better here.} *

