1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A somewhat forgotten line, not played that often on the top level, but nonetheless, White should know what to do against it.} 5. Bxc4 {Recapturing the pawn, but also creating a threat of Bxf7 !} e6 6. Nc3 c5 {A rare move here, especially given that ... Bg4 is not well suited for such plans (usually, ... a6 -... b5 -... Bb7 is played alongside ... c5 ). But it is perhaps not that bad, as it gained some attention from strong players recently.} 7. Qa4+ Nbd7 8. Ne5 {White immediately takes advantage of the slightly exposed position of Black's king and thanks to the pin puts pressure on him. But things are still not entirely easy if Black defends well.} cxd4 9. exd4 a6 {Black gives away the pair of bishops to resolve the more troubling problem of the pin. Also, ... b5 is a threat.} 10. Nxg4 Nxg4 11. Be2 {A logical tempo move, redirecting the bishop to f3 .} Ngf6 {This was played in Sarana-Demchenko, 2021. It allows White to put immediate pressure on the queenside.} 12. Bf3 Qb6 13. O-O Bd6 {If Black manages to castle his position may be sort of acceptable.} 14. Ne4 {Using dynamic methods, White prevents Black from getting his king to safety.} Nxe4 15. Bxe4 {Black has obvious issues with his king and development. If he was in time to complete it and set a blockade on d5 , he would be fine, but it is not attainable.} Qd8 {The game Sarana-Demchenko, 2021, went like this. Black relied on a tactic:} 16. Bxb7 Bxh2+ 17. Kxh2 Qc7+ {Getting the piece back. However White can play:} 18. Bf4 {With a winning position:} Qxb7 ({Or} 18... Qxf4+ 19. g3 Qh6+ 20. Kg1 Rd8 21. Bc6 $1) 19. Bd6 ({Black is unable to castle. Next, a rook will come to c1 , followed by Rc7 . The game continued Qd5 Ba3 f6} 19. Rac1 {Kf7 Rc7 Rhd8 Rfc1 Kg8 and now Kg1+- would be stronger. Even though Black managed to hide his king, White's pieces are way too active.}) *

