1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A somewhat forgotten line, not played that often on the top level, but nonetheless, White should know what to do against it.} 5. Bxc4 {Recapturing the pawn, but also creating a threat of Bxf7 !} e6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. O-O ({I would not rush with} 7. h3 {as there is no immediate benefit (like say, after} a6 {when we play h3 to follow with g4 and Ne5 , getting the pair of bishops) and additionally in some lines we can benefit from the bishop still being on g4 .}) 7... Bb4 8. Qb3 c5 9. Ne5 {We can see a huge benefit of not playing h3 . Now, Ne5 comes with an attack on the bishop! According to Stockfish, White simply wins here!} O-O {This loses:} 10. Nxg4 Nxg4 11. Bxe6 ({After Nxh2 Bxd7 Nxf1} 11. Bb5 Nxe3 12. Bxe3 cxd4 {Rd1!+- , White has a decisive advantage.}) *

