1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A somewhat forgotten line, not played that often on the top level, but nonetheless, White should know what to do against it.} 5. Bxc4 {Recapturing the pawn, but also creating a threat of Bxf7 !} e6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. O-O ({I would not rush with} 7. h3 {as there is no immediate benefit (like say, after} a6 {when we play h3 to follow with g4 and Ne5 , getting the pair of bishops) and additionally in some lines we can benefit from the bishop still being on g4 .}) 7... Bd6 {Alexander Delchev played this line against me in 2013; this is the most common move here. Yet, the bishop is misplaced on d6 .} 8. h3 Bxf3 {This was Delchev's choice but it gives White a very comfortable position with a strong center and the pair of bishops.} 9. Qxf3 c6 10. e4 ({Immediately taking control over the center. I played} 10. Rd1 {instead which is good too, but a bit unnecessary, as the e4 push does not require further preparation.}) 10... e5 11. d5 cxd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 {This looks bad for Black.} *

