1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A somewhat forgotten line, not played that often on the top level, but nonetheless, White should know what to do against it.} 5. Bxc4 {Recapturing the pawn, but also creating a threat of Bxf7 !} e6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. O-O ({I would not rush with} 7. h3 {as there is no immediate benefit (like say, after} a6 {when we play h3 to follow with g4 and Ne5 , getting the pair of bishops) and additionally in some lines we can benefit from the bishop still being on g4 .}) 7... Bd6 {Alexander Delchev played this line against me in 2013; this is the most common move here. Yet, the bishop is misplaced on d6 .} 8. h3 Bxf3 {This was Delchev's choice but it gives White a very comfortable position with a strong center and the pair of bishops.} 9. Qxf3 c6 10. e4 ({Immediately taking control over the center. I played} 10. Rd1 {instead which is good too, but a bit unnecessary, as the e4 push does not require further preparation.}) 10... e5 11. d5 Nb6 12. Bb3 cxd5 13. exd5 {If Black was on time to complete development and deal with the Bg5 idea, he would be fine, but that's not the case.} h6 {Otherwise, Bg5 is coming.} 14. Qg3 {But now Black cannot castle...} e4 {The best according to the engine but now the e4 -pawn is pretty much doomed.} 15. Qh4 Qe7 16. Bf4 Bxf4 17. Qxf4 Rd8 (17... O-O 18. d6) 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. Rfe1 {And White wins a pawn and most likely the game as well.} *

