1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A somewhat forgotten line, not played that often on the top level, but nonetheless, White should know what to do against it.} 5. Bxc4 {Recapturing the pawn, but also creating a threat of Bxf7 !} e6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. O-O ({I would not rush with} 7. h3 {as there is no immediate benefit (like say, after} a6 {when we play h3 to follow with g4 and Ne5 , getting the pair of bishops) and additionally in some lines we can benefit from the bishop still being on g4 .}) 7... Bd6 {Alexander Delchev played this line against me in 2013; this is the most common move here. Yet, the bishop is misplaced on d6 .} 8. h3 Bh5 9. e4 {In comparison with the 7...Be7 line, White immediately threatens e5 winning a piece.} e5 {The main move according to the theory, but is very risky...} (9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3 {is similar to the 8... Bxf3  line . The presence or absence of the move ... c6 does not change the evaluation of the position.} e5 11. Be3 O-O 12. Rad1 Qe7 13. Qe2 Rae8 14. Rfe1 {is a sample continuation.}) 10. g4 {Suddenly, Black has serious issues with the Bh5 .} Bg6 ({Sacrifices on g4 do not work, of course:} 10... Nxg4 11. hxg4 Bxg4 12. Be2) 11. dxe5 {White is just crushing here. After all trades on e5 White plays f4 and the Bg6 is nearly trapped.} Nxe5 (11... Bxe5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Be2 {and f4 .}) 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. f4 {We can see something went really wrong for Black here.} Bd4+ 14. Kh2 h5 {By creating chaos and going after White's king, Black has at least something to play for. But it is insufficient:} 15. f5 hxg4 16. fxg6 Rxh3+ 17. Kg2 {This is just hopeless for Black.} *

