1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A somewhat forgotten line, not played that often on the top level, but nonetheless, White should know what to do against it.} 5. Bxc4 {Recapturing the pawn, but also creating a threat of Bxf7 !} e6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. O-O ({I would not rush with} 7. h3 {as there is no immediate benefit (like say, after} a6 {when we play h3 to follow with g4 and Ne5 , getting the pair of bishops) and additionally in some lines we can benefit from the bishop still being on g4 .}) 7... Be7 {I think this is Black's best reply here, even if not the most common. Black completes his development without having to face ideas of e4 - e5 , as seen after 7...Bd6 .} 8. h3 Bh5 9. e4 {Even though it is not as strong as after Bd6 (well, Be7 is a better move!), this move is still good here.} Nb6 {This is another move here.} 10. Be2 {The simplest.} O-O ({Or} 10... Bg6 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Be3 {. Including the moves ... Bg6 and Bd3 does not change anything. White controls the center and the plan of Qe2 , Rfd1 and Rac1 should give us an easy game.}) 11. Be3 Rc8 {White has here many options, of course.} 12. Ne5 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 {White has here a clear advantage.} *

