1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A somewhat forgotten line, not played that often on the top level, but nonetheless, White should know what to do against it.} 5. Bxc4 {Recapturing the pawn, but also creating a threat of Bxf7 !} e6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. O-O ({I would not rush with} 7. h3 {as there is no immediate benefit (like say, after} a6 {when we play h3 to follow with g4 and Ne5 , getting the pair of bishops) and additionally in some lines we can benefit from the bishop still being on g4 .}) 7... Be7 {I think this is Black's best reply here, even if not the most common. Black completes his development without having to face ideas of e4 - e5 , as seen after 7...Bd6 .} 8. h3 Bh5 9. e4 {Even though it is not as strong as after Bd6 (well, Be7 is a better move!), this move is still good here.} O-O 10. g4 Bg6 11. Qe2 c6 {We reached a position that to some extent resembles the Slav but a pretty good version for White. White has full control over the center and Black, even though he is solid, does not have good enough ways to challenge it. There are ideas of ... b5 -... b4 , but they are not sufficient.} 12. Bf4 ({Simply completing development. In Ding-Yu, 2021, followed} 12. a4 $6 {but it is less clear due to} Bb4 $1 {and Black gets some counterplay.}) 12... b5 13. Bd3 a6 (13... b4 14. Na4 {is fine for White.}) 14. Rfd1 Qb6 ({Black prepares ...c5 , as the immediate} 14... c5 15. d5 {is good for White.}) 15. a4 ({Not the only good move here but it makes sense to stop ...c5 .} 15. e5 {is a bit premature:} Nd5 16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. h4 f5 $1 {is less clear even though White should still be a bit better.}) 15... Rfd8 16. Rac1 Rac8 17. Bg5 {White is clearly better due to the space advantage.} *

