1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 a6 6. O-O b5 {Generally, playing ... b5 this early is not advised. White can play via a4 and challenge Black's queenside pawn structure. Additionally, White does not have to retreat to e2 , and Bd3 is a good option now, choosing plans connected with e4 !} 7. Bd3 {In many situations, White retreats to e2 and goes for a more positional battle. Here, however, White has an option of supporting the e4 push.} Bb7 {Black should begin with this move to prevent White from immediately playing e4 .} 8. a4 {Weakening Black's pawn structure.} b4 {In such positions, Black generally seizes some space on the queenside. Here, White needs to choose the right plan.} 9. Nbd2 {White wants to place the knight on c4 and prepare e4 push. Very often, a5 is also useful.} (9. b3 $2 {is what I played here once in Titled Tuesday, and it is not a correct plan here. It is much stronger to go for e4 ideas.}) 9... c5 10. Nc4 Nbd7 11. a5 {Fixing the pawn structure on the queenside. Black's pawn chain is somehow disrupted, and White may try to attack Black's weak pawns.} cxd4 {Now, it is very important that White recaptures with the pawn:} 12. exd4 {It may seem surprising as White gives up control over the d5 -square and voluntarily gets an IQP, but it matters very little. White wants to play Bf4 and Re1 with active play. Additionally, the d4 -pawn controls the e5 -square, so if White plays Nfe5 in the future Black will unlikely want to trade it due to dxe5 ! And finally, Black does not have access to c5 -square here, which cramps his position.} ({Be7} 12. Qe2 $5 {is interesting and fine, but I prefer Bf4 O-O Re1} Nd5 {Bg3 N7f6} 13. Nfd2 $5 {with the idea Nb3 - Nc5 .}) *

