1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 ({This move is slightly rarer than} 6... a6 {, but it is also quite common at the top level.}) 7. Nc3 cxd4 ({Another move order is} 7... Be7 8. Qe2 cxd4 9. Rd1 O-O 10. exd4 {.}) 8. exd4 Be7 {Generally, trading on d4 so early is not advised to Black. Here, White has a variety of setups from which to choose.} 9. Qe2 {I would recommend this setup because of its flexibility, but I admit many other setups are OK as well.} O-O ({Black needs to castle as soon as possible.} 9... Nxd4 $2 {is way too premature with the king in the center.} 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Rd1 {and Bb5 + is going to be very awkward to meet.}) 10. Rd1 ({White potentially may be threatening d5 , so Black needs to do something about it. According to the theory, the main moves are Na5 , Nb4 and} 10. Nd5 {, and I will focus on them.}) 10... Nb4 {A standard idea in such positions is to install a blockade on d5 . But it does not work that well here either.} 11. Ne5 Nbd5 (11... Nfd5 12. Qg4 {looks very unpleasant too. The Nb4 is not really stable as White always can play a3 .}) 12. Rd3 {Swinging the rook to the kingside gives White a huge attack.} *

