1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 ({This move is slightly rarer than} 6... a6 {, but it is also quite common at the top level.}) 7. Nc3 a6 {Black pretty much needs to play this move here. Otherwise, we will most likely enter an IQP position in a good version for White.} 8. d5 {One of the most challenging options here. I decided to recommend this line as it forces Black to either memorize or find lots of only or difficult moves, which may not be easy!} exd5 {This move is already an inaccuracy.} 9. Nxd5 {White has a very pleasant position here.} Nxd5 (9... b5 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Bd5 Bb7 12. e4) 10. Bxd5 {I find this position to be hardly advisable for Black. White wants to trade on c6 , and Black's pawn structure will be terrible. There is no good way for Black to prevent it.} Bd6 {This was played in Moradiabadi-Lenderman, 2020.} 11. Bxc6+ {Even though there are other moves, I would recommend destroying Black's pawn structure on the queenside.} bxc6 {Here, Elshan tried b3 , which is also decent, but I prefer another approach.} 12. Bd2 O-O 13. Qa4 {White immediately targets the pawns.} Bf5 {Probably Black needs to sacrifice the pawn and look for some compensation for it.} 14. Ba5 {A useful tempo move.} Qb8 (14... Qf6 $6 {is inaccurate as the queen runs under a tempo:} 15. e4 Be6 16. Bc3 {with e5 next, and White is much better. Note there is no} Bg4 {due to} 17. e5 $1) 15. Qxc6 Re8 16. Rad1 Re6 {Black definitely has some compensation, but with the following exchange sacrifice, White obtains a risk-free position with good winning chances.} 17. Rxd6 Rxd6 18. Qxc5 Rf6 19. Rd1 {White is better. Even the endgame will be better for White as two pawns are a lot of pawns for the exchange! On top of that, the control over the dark squares can be unpleasant for Black.} *

