1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 ({This move is slightly rarer than} 6... a6 {, but it is also quite common at the top level.}) 7. Nc3 a6 {Black pretty much needs to play this move here. Otherwise, we will most likely enter an IQP position in a good version for White.} 8. d5 {One of the most challenging options here. I decided to recommend this line as it forces Black to either memorize or find lots of only or difficult moves, which may not be easy!} Nxd5 {A decent option for Black here. It was tried in the 2022 game Nakamura-Dominguez. If Leinier played it, it must be taken seriously. Still - the positions there look quite risky for Black...} 9. Nxd5 Na5 {This is very risky. I didn't find a clear refutation, however, from a human point of view, this looks pretty bad.} 10. e4 ({The direct approach.} 10. b3 {is a more positional alternative.}) 10... Nxc4 11. Bg5 Qd7 12. Qe2 (12. Rc1 $5 {deserves attention too - but I give enough resources here already!}) 12... b5 13. b3 exd5 14. exd5+ Be7 {As Black still has an extra piece and will play ... f6 , he should be able to castle. But still, White retains a positional advantage.} 15. bxc4 f6 16. Bf4 O-O 17. a4 {Declaring the situation on the queenside.} b4 {Black needs to play this move. He gets a passed pawn, sure, but White's center is also very strong right now.} ({After} 17... bxc4 $2 18. d6 $1 {, White wins in all lines, e.g.} Bxd6 19. Qxc4+ Kh8 20. Rfd1 {winning the bishop.}) 18. Nd2 {White is clearly better here.} *

