1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 ({This move is slightly rarer than} 6... a6 {, but it is also quite common at the top level.}) 7. Nc3 a6 {Black pretty much needs to play this move here. Otherwise, we will most likely enter an IQP position in a good version for White.} 8. d5 {One of the most challenging options here. I decided to recommend this line as it forces Black to either memorize or find lots of only or difficult moves, which may not be easy!} Nxd5 {A decent option for Black here. It was tried in the 2022 game Nakamura-Dominguez. If Leinier played it, it must be taken seriously. Still - the positions there look quite risky for Black...} 9. Nxd5 b5 10. Bb3 c4 {The key idea here. Black disconnects the bishop and the knight.} (10... exd5 11. Bxd5 {is similar to exd5 Nxd5 but the weakened long diagonal only adds to Black's problems.}) 11. Bxc4 {The most challenging option here. Other moves are most likely less promising.} bxc4 12. e4 {If someone looks at this position for the first time and without the engine, it looks pretty scary for Black: not only is his king in the center and White's pieces are in play, but also the pawn structure is shaky for Black. It looks very promising for White, but Dominguez showed that things are not that terrible for Black.} Bb7 {Completing the development. Now, Qa4 is no longer a concern, and perhaps ... exd5 may be played in the future. Here, White has some choice.} 13. Re1 Rc8 ({This is suggested by the engine as an alternative to} 13... Bb4 {, but it does not look very natural. For that reason, I will keep things short here, especially since White has a simple path to a nice position.}) 14. Be3 Nb4 (14... exd5 15. exd5 {Opening the e -file is, of course, horrible for Black.}) 15. Nb6 Qxd1 16. Rexd1 Rc7 17. Nd2 c3 18. bxc3 Rxc3 19. Nbc4 {Black faces some issues completing the development, as ... Be7 can be met with Bd4 . I prefer White.} *

