1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 ({This move is slightly rarer than} 6... a6 {, but it is also quite common at the top level.}) 7. Nc3 a6 {Black pretty much needs to play this move here. Otherwise, we will most likely enter an IQP position in a good version for White.} 8. d5 {One of the most challenging options here. I decided to recommend this line as it forces Black to either memorize or find lots of only or difficult moves, which may not be easy!} Nxd5 {A decent option for Black here. It was tried in the 2022 game Nakamura-Dominguez. If Leinier played it, it must be taken seriously. Still - the positions there look quite risky for Black...} 9. Nxd5 b5 10. Bb3 c4 {The key idea here. Black disconnects the bishop and the knight.} (10... exd5 11. Bxd5 {is similar to exd5 Nxd5 but the weakened long diagonal only adds to Black's problems.}) 11. Bxc4 {The most challenging option here. Other moves are most likely less promising.} bxc4 12. e4 {If someone looks at this position for the first time and without the engine, it looks pretty scary for Black: not only is his king in the center and White's pieces are in play, but also the pawn structure is shaky for Black. It looks very promising for White, but Dominguez showed that things are not that terrible for Black.} Bb7 {Completing the development. Now, Qa4 is no longer a concern, and perhaps ... exd5 may be played in the future. Here, White has some choice.} 13. Re1 Bb4 14. Bg5 {A useful move that forces ... f6 , which weakens Black's position.} f6 15. Bd2 Bxd2 16. Qxd2 {Here, Black is facing some choice.} Rc8 {Surely a preparation by Leinier. There is no need to castle just yet while supporting the c4 -pawn is definitely useful.} 17. Ne3 Qxd2 18. Nxd2 Ne5 {Black managed to defend the c4 -pawn, at least temporarily.} 19. Rec1 Ke7 20. f3 {Now, the c4 -pawn simply falls.} c3 {But if Black gives it away this way, he may hope to survive the endgame.} 21. Rxc3 Rxc3 22. bxc3 Rd8 ({Thanks to activity, Black may hope to survive here. But it is not so easy anyway. In the game, Hikaru Nakamura managed to create some chances and use his extra pawn to eventually win.} 22... Rc8 $5 {is met by} 23. Rb1 {winning a tempo to follow up with Rb3 .}) 23. Ndc4 {I would probably play this move here. By trading knights, we are reducing Black's counterplay.} Nxc4 24. Nxc4 Rc8 25. Na5 Ba8 26. Rc1 {White is just up a pawn. The plan of bringing the king to the center and advancing the c -pawn seems hard to meet. Black has only one way to stay in the game.} f5 {Black needs to activate the bishop and free the d5 -square.} 27. exf5 exf5 28. Kf2 Bd5 {But even here, White retains decent practical chances.} 29. Nb3 {The game goes on, and Black still needs to prove the equality...} *

