 {Nd2 Qf4 Ndxc4 O-O Nd6 Rc7 Nxb7 Rxb7} 19. Qc3 {, the game goes on, and objectively, the position is close to equal, but the 2 vs. 1 on the queenside gives White better practical chances.}) 14... f6 15. Qe2 Kf7 16. Ne3 Qd3 17. Qd1 {And Black faces here some issues with the c4 -pawn as well. According to my analysis, Black should hold in the end, but it's also good to keep in mind this option. I will just keep the main line here to give you an idea that if Black deviates from it, he should be in big trouble.} Qxd1 18. Rfxd1 Na5 19. Rd7+ Ke8 20. Rc7 e5 21. Rxc8+ Bxc8 22. Bg3 Be6 23. Nd2 {And Black loses the c4 -pawn. If he gives it away in a proper way, at the end of the day he may have chances to hold, but in general, we are playing for two results here.} *

