1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 ({This move is slightly rarer than} 6... a6 {, but it is also quite common at the top level.}) 7. Nc3 a6 {Black pretty much needs to play this move here. Otherwise, we will most likely enter an IQP position in a good version for White.} 8. d5 {One of the most challenging options here. I decided to recommend this line as it forces Black to either memorize or find lots of only or difficult moves, which may not be easy!} Na5 {The most popular move here.} 9. b3 b5 10. Bd3 {White sacrifices the d5 -pawn for the initiative, as Black's king is unsafe in the center.} exd5 11. e4 {White has a very strong initiative here.} d4 12. e5 Nd5 {This was played in some games, most notably Gelfand-Inarkiev, 2018. Even though it was a blitz game, it is still relevant for this line.} 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Re1 {With Be4 , Bd2 etc. coming next. White is simply winning here, as Black has a weak king and cannot complete his development.} ({Ra7} 14. Be4 Qd8 15. e6 Bxe6 16. Ng5 {Re7 Bd2} h6 17. Nxe6 {Rxe6 Bf5 Re7 Qf3+- was Gelfand-Inarkiev, 2018.}) *

