1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 ({This move is slightly rarer than} 6... a6 {, but it is also quite common at the top level.}) 7. Nc3 a6 {Black pretty much needs to play this move here. Otherwise, we will most likely enter an IQP position in a good version for White.} 8. d5 {One of the most challenging options here. I decided to recommend this line as it forces Black to either memorize or find lots of only or difficult moves, which may not be easy!} Na5 {The most popular move here.} 9. b3 b5 10. Bd3 {White sacrifices the d5 -pawn for the initiative, as Black's king is unsafe in the center.} b4 {The best move for Black here, I believe, even though there was only one game so far here, Esipenko-Van Foreest, 2020. Black needs to play this move before capturing the pawn.} 11. dxe6 ({There is this complex piece sacrifice available as well. As I checked, it does not really offer White an advantage, but I'll offer it as an alternative to} 11. Ne4 {, my main recommendation.}) 11... bxc3 12. exf7+ Kxf7 13. e4 {The best chance.} Be7 {Black must play this move to hold the balance.} 14. e5 ({The most principled.} 14. Qc2 $5 {could be tried, aiming for a long game, but I am not convinced by it at all, e.g.} Nc6 15. Rd1 Qc7 16. Qxc3 Rd8 17. Bb2 Kf8 18. Ng5 Ke8 19. e5 Ng4 20. Nxh7 Nd4 $1 {is absurdly messy and unclear.}) 14... Nd5 15. Be4 {Black has here some choice to make.} Be6 {This seems more logical from a human point of view, but it is a bit less good.} 16. Ng5+ Bxg5 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18. Bxd5 {The tension on the Be6 is a bit unpleasant for Black, and perhaps he needs to sac an exchange.} Rad8 19. Qf3+ Ke7 20. Bxe6 Kxe6 21. Qxc3 Nc6 22. Qxc5 {And White gets a lot of pawns while Black's king remains weak.} *

