1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 ({This move is slightly rarer than} 6... a6 {, but it is also quite common at the top level.}) 7. Nc3 a6 {Black pretty much needs to play this move here. Otherwise, we will most likely enter an IQP position in a good version for White.} 8. d5 {One of the most challenging options here. I decided to recommend this line as it forces Black to either memorize or find lots of only or difficult moves, which may not be easy!} Na5 {The most popular move here.} 9. b3 b5 10. Bd3 {White sacrifices the d5 -pawn for the initiative, as Black's king is unsafe in the center.} b4 {The best move for Black here, I believe, even though there was only one game so far here, Esipenko-Van Foreest, 2020. Black needs to play this move before capturing the pawn.} 11. Ne4 exd5 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. Rb1 {A critical position for this line. Black has a couple of options here.} Bg4 {Black intends to double White's pawns with ... Bxf3 . We should not worry about it.} 14. Bb2 Bxf3 {Otherwise, ... Bg4 makes no sense.} 15. gxf3 Qh6 {The best square for the queen - otherwise, it would be difficult to complete Black’s kingside development.} 16. Kh1 {I think White has good compensation here.} Be7 17. Rg1 Bf6 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Rc1 Nb7 20. f4 {White has full compensation for the pawn. It is not so clear where Black's king should castle, and the Nb7 is pretty passive. Both c5 and d5 -pawns are going to be attacked. The engine claims it to be equal, but in my opinion, it could be hard to play for Black. White's ideas are Be2 - Bf3 and Rg5 . Some sample lines:} ({g6} 20. Be2 O-O-O {Bf3=∞ , and White will open the queenside with a3 .}) ({O-O} 20. Rg5 Rd8 {Qh5 g6 f5↑ , and the other rook will join the attack via g1 .}) *

