1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 ({This move is slightly rarer than} 6... a6 {, but it is also quite common at the top level.}) 7. Nc3 a6 {Black pretty much needs to play this move here. Otherwise, we will most likely enter an IQP position in a good version for White.} 8. d5 {One of the most challenging options here. I decided to recommend this line as it forces Black to either memorize or find lots of only or difficult moves, which may not be easy!} Na5 {The most popular move here.} 9. b3 b5 10. Bd3 {White sacrifices the d5 -pawn for the initiative, as Black's king is unsafe in the center.} b4 {The best move for Black here, I believe, even though there was only one game so far here, Esipenko-Van Foreest, 2020. Black needs to play this move before capturing the pawn.} 11. Ne4 exd5 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. Rb1 {A critical position for this line. Black has a couple of options here.} Nc6 {This logical move, which improves the knight, was played by Van Foreest.} 14. e4 {The move played in the Esipenko-Van Foreest 2020 game. It is very logical, of course, but now Black can simplify to a roughly equal endgame:} Bg4 15. exd5 Bxf3 16. Re1+ (16. Qxf3 Qxf3 17. gxf3 Nd4 {and ... Bd6 next is roughly the same.}) 16... Be7 17. Qxf3 Qxf3 18. gxf3 Nd4 {And White is not in time to push d6 . Then, Black will install a blockade on d6 , and I don't imagine Black ever losing this.} 19. Kg2 Kd7 20. Be3 g6 21. Rbc1 Rhc8 {The game ended soon with a draw.} 22. Bxd4 cxd4 23. Rc6 Rxc6 24. dxc6+ Kd6 25. Re4 Bf6 26. Rf4 Ke5 27. Re4+ Kd6 28. Rf4 Ke5 29. Re4+ Kd6 30. Rf4 Ke5 {And a draw was agreed in Esipenko,A (2654)-Van Foreest,J (2667), Prague 2020.} *

