1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 ({This move is slightly rarer than} 6... a6 {, but it is also quite common at the top level.}) 7. Nc3 a6 {Black pretty much needs to play this move here. Otherwise, we will most likely enter an IQP position in a good version for White.} 8. d5 {One of the most challenging options here. I decided to recommend this line as it forces Black to either memorize or find lots of only or difficult moves, which may not be easy!} Na5 {The most popular move here.} 9. b3 b5 10. Bd3 {White sacrifices the d5 -pawn for the initiative, as Black's king is unsafe in the center.} b4 {The best move for Black here, I believe, even though there was only one game so far here, Esipenko-Van Foreest, 2020. Black needs to play this move before capturing the pawn.} 11. Ne4 exd5 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. Rb1 {A critical position for this line. Black has a couple of options here.} Nc6 {This logical move, which improves the knight, was played by Van Foreest.} 14. h3 {I like this novelty. Now, ... Bg4 ideas are gone and White can focus on e4 ! In fact, it is not easy to stop, and Black has some practical difficulties here.} Bb7 {The best response from what I analyzed. Black anticipates e4 and tries to meet it with ... Ne5 .} ({Other moves seem to be clearly worse, and we'll play e4 anyway:} 14... Be7 15. e4 {or} Bd6 {e4± or Be6 e4 d4} 16. Bg5 {.}) 15. e4 {It's time!} Ne5 {Everything else loses.} 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. Re1 {Black faces serious practical problems here.} Be7 {This move is also possible, and I haven't found an outright refutation - but White's chances are definitely promising here.} 18. f4 Qd4+ {After this, White recaptures the pawn and retains an advantage:} 19. Be3 Qf6 20. exd5 O-O 21. Qc2 g6 22. Bc4 {Black should not allow White to keep the d5 -pawn.} *

