[PlyCount "33"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} Nbd7 {This line was recommended by Benjamin Gledura in his QGA course. I think it is a good and solid choice for Black. However, my conclusions differ somewhat from Benjamin's, perhaps because I analyzed this line somewhat deeper, as we will see shortly.} 8. Bb2 Be7 (8... b6 {runs into} 9. d5 {and we have a much better version of the 7...b6 line.}) 9. dxc5 {A good moment to take on c5 as Black must waste a tempo with the bishop.} Bxc5 10. Nbd2 {Now White's main idea is Bd3 and Ne4 . Allowing it is very risky for Black, so he needs to be careful.} b6 {A very precise move. First, Black develops the bishop to b7 and does not allow White to realize his idea. However, we obtain a pretty symmetric position here in which White is up two tempi, which makes me believe that White should be better...} (10... b5 {is always suboptimal as a4 will be an issue for Black.} 11. Be2) 11. Bd3 Bb7 {As Ne4 is not a thing anymore, White needs to come up with another plan.} 12. e4 O-O 13. Qe2 {I like this plan for White. We gain some control over the center and obtain some space advantage. Next, e5 could potentially be an idea, followed by either Qe4 or some Ne4 ideas.} Qe7 {This is recommended by Benjamin, with the intention of trading the bishops.} 14. a3 {Threatening b4 .} a5 {This could be an alternative, cementing the bishop on c5 . But it looks like Black is under pressure in the following line:} 15. e5 Nd5 16. Qe4 g6 17. Qg4 {With better prospects for White, as Black has weakened his kingside and we have more space thanks to the e5 pawn.} *

