1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} b6 {I have always considered it as a risky option for Black due to Ba3 (which I cover in this course), but things are working out for Black quite well if he knows the lines. However, I would like to recommend an alternative option as well.} 8. Ba3 {This is considered the most venomous, and most likely, it is the best try. We put pressure on the c5 -pawn and pretty much 'force' ... Nbd7 .} Bb7 {After this, White obtains a position with strategic advantage due to Black's bad pawn structure:} 9. dxc5 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Bxc5 11. Bxc5 bxc5 12. Nc3 {Black has nothing to compensate for the worse structure.} *

