1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} b6 {I have always considered it as a risky option for Black due to Ba3 (which I cover in this course), but things are working out for Black quite well if he knows the lines. However, I would like to recommend an alternative option as well.} 8. Ba3 {This is considered the most venomous, and most likely, it is the best try. We put pressure on the c5 -pawn and pretty much 'force' ... Nbd7 .} Nbd7 ({Black needs to support the c5 -pawn.} 8... cxd4 9. Bxf8 Kxf8 10. Nxd4 {is clearly better for White too as Black can no longer castle.}) 9. d5 {The point of White's previous move.} exd5 10. Bxd5 {We opened the d -file and will try to make use of dynamic play to pose problems to Black.} Ra7 {This is not a great move for Black.} 11. Bb2 Be7 12. Bc4 b5 13. Be2 {Here, we can see the advantage of having the rook on b8 , as in the main line, which follows. The b5 pawn would be fully secured, whereas now it will be under pressure when White plays a4 .} *

