1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} b6 {I have always considered it as a risky option for Black due to Ba3 (which I cover in this course), but things are working out for Black quite well if he knows the lines. However, I would like to recommend an alternative option as well.} 8. Ba3 {This is considered the most venomous, and most likely, it is the best try. We put pressure on the c5 -pawn and pretty much 'force' ... Nbd7 .} Nbd7 ({Black needs to support the c5 -pawn.} 8... cxd4 9. Bxf8 Kxf8 10. Nxd4 {is clearly better for White too as Black can no longer castle.}) 9. d5 {The point of White's previous move.} exd5 10. Bxd5 {We opened the d -file and will try to make use of dynamic play to pose problems to Black.} Rb8 {The best square for the rook. The point is that Black will play via ... b5 in the future, and the b -pawn needs to be supported.} {Here, White can begin with Bb2 , e4 or Nc3 , and in general, all should lead to the same position, but I like the Nc3 move order the most (but it's just a personal choice).} 11. Nc3 Be7 12. e4 {I would recommend this.} O-O ({Black needs to castle as soon as possible.} 12... b5 {is not accurate due to} 13. Bc1 $1 {and Black is under pressure. And if} Qc7 {then} 14. e5 {is just crushing as Black's king is still in the center. Because of this, Black should castle instead of 12...b5 .}) 13. Bb2 ({Now the bishop belongs on the long diagonal.} 13. Bc1 $5 {intending to transfer the bishop to f4 is a possible alternative, but it is not as great as after 12...b5 due to} Qc7 {, and with Black's king hidden on the kingside, there is no e5 push. Nxd5 Nxd5 Bf6 is possible too.}) 13... b5 14. Re1 ({This seems to be a better try than Mamedyarov's} 14. Qc2 {(played against Aronian in 2022), after which Black is fine in numerous ways. However, it is not easy here.}) 14... c4 {This is the best move for Black, which leads to equality after a series of best (or even only) moves. That's why I would not worry much about the fact that, objectively, the position is equal - after all, it is people who play!} 15. bxc4 bxc4 16. Qc2 Nxd5 ({Not optimal, White's chances are slightly better after this move.} 16... Bb7 $2 17. Bxb7 Rxb7 18. e5) 17. Nxd5 {This is more comfortable for White.} *

