1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} b6 {I have always considered it as a risky option for Black due to Ba3 (which I cover in this course), but things are working out for Black quite well if he knows the lines. However, I would like to recommend an alternative option as well.} 8. Ba3 {This is considered the most venomous, and most likely, it is the best try. We put pressure on the c5 -pawn and pretty much 'force' ... Nbd7 .} Nbd7 ({Black needs to support the c5 -pawn.} 8... cxd4 9. Bxf8 Kxf8 10. Nxd4 {is clearly better for White too as Black can no longer castle.}) 9. d5 {The point of White's previous move.} exd5 10. Bxd5 {We opened the d -file and will try to make use of dynamic play to pose problems to Black.} Rb8 {The best square for the rook. The point is that Black will play via ... b5 in the future, and the b -pawn needs to be supported.} {Here, White can begin with Bb2 , e4 or Nc3 , and in general, all should lead to the same position, but I like the Nc3 move order the most (but it's just a personal choice).} 11. Nc3 Be7 12. e4 {I would recommend this.} O-O ({Black needs to castle as soon as possible.} 12... b5 {is not accurate due to} 13. Bc1 $1 {and Black is under pressure. And if} Qc7 {then} 14. e5 {is just crushing as Black's king is still in the center. Because of this, Black should castle instead of 12...b5 .}) 13. Bb2 ({Now the bishop belongs on the long diagonal.} 13. Bc1 $5 {intending to transfer the bishop to f4 is a possible alternative, but it is not as great as after 12...b5 due to} Qc7 {, and with Black's king hidden on the kingside, there is no e5 push. Nxd5 Nxd5 Bf6 is possible too.}) 13... b5 14. Re1 ({This seems to be a better try than Mamedyarov's} 14. Qc2 {(played against Aronian in 2022), after which Black is fine in numerous ways. However, it is not easy here.}) 14... c4 {This is the best move for Black, which leads to equality after a series of best (or even only) moves. That's why I would not worry much about the fact that, objectively, the position is equal - after all, it is people who play!} 15. bxc4 bxc4 16. Qc2 Nb6 {The first of many 'best moves' that Black must find to keep the balance. White has some choice now.} 17. Ne5 {Probably the best try - activating the knight and hoping to get Nc6 .} (17. Rad1 {is interesting, but Black holds here too.} Nbxd5 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. exd5 Bf5 $1 20. Qxf5 Rxb2 21. Ne5 Bc5 $1 {and unfortunately, here we need to play passive} 22. Rf1 {, after which Black has many paths to equality, e.g.} Qc8 23. Qxc8 Rxc8 24. Nxc4 Rc2 {or c3 Qd3 Qf6∞}) 17... Nfxd5 18. exd5 Bb7 {Otherwise, Nc6 comes.} 19. Rad1 (19. Nc6 {is possible too. Black must play} Bxc6 20. dxc6 Bf6 $1 21. Ba3 Qd3 {, which leads to an equal endgame by force.} 22. Qxd3 cxd3 23. Bxf8 Bxc3 24. Bc5 Bxe1 25. c7 Rc8 26. Bxb6 Bb4 27. Rd1 d2 28. a3 Bc3 29. Kf1 Kf8 30. Ke2 Ke7 31. Kd3 Be5 32. Rxd2 Bxc7 {is a sample continuation.}) 19... Qc7 {Another only move. Black must prevent Nc6 again. White has here many tries, but eventually, Black appears to simply hold.} 20. Ng4 (20. h4 Rbe8 21. Nf3 {is another try, with multiple ideas: Ng5 , Nd4 - Nf5 , or just h5 - h6 .}) 20... f5 {Another not obvious move.} 21. Ne3 Bc5 ({Here, White has many options, but we should not play Nxf5 due to} 21... Qf4 {with unpleasant pressure.}) 22. h3 {But we can play, for instance, this, which leads to an unclear game. We might take the f5 -pawn one day or try something like Na4 and weaken the c4 -pawn. Also, Qc1 - Ba3 could be an idea, or a4 - a5 . Generally, we are already very far out, and if someone finds all this and this position occurs, well, what to do? But generally, I would not worry about it because even if this happens, the position remains playable.} *

