1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} b6 {I have always considered it as a risky option for Black due to Ba3 (which I cover in this course), but things are working out for Black quite well if he knows the lines. However, I would like to recommend an alternative option as well.} 8. Nc3 {This move has not been played here so far, apart from one correspondence game. I think it is quite tricky for Black from a practical point of view as it is necessary to play via ... b5 , which is pretty much a waste of a tempo. Therefore, it may not be intuitive to go for it.} b5 ({Pretty much a necessity.} 8... Bb7 {is possible too, but we can reach the position from the main line after} 9. dxc5 $1 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 {and now} Bxc5 $2 11. Na4 {hitting c5 and b6 gives White a huge advantage. Black's only move is} b5 {and here, we simply transpose with} 12. Be2 {.}) 9. Be2 Bb7 10. dxc5 {Now Black has some choice and room to go wrong.} Qxd1 {This is slightly worse than ... Bxc5 .} 11. Rxd1 Bxc5 12. Bb2 Nbd7 13. Rac1 O-O 14. a4 bxa4 ({Not an obvious move. After} 14... b4 15. Nb1 {, the knight will be transferred to c4 .}) 15. Nxa4 Bb4 {White has some choice now.} 16. Nd4 ({This looks a bit better for White.} 16. g4 $5 {with the idea g5 is playable too.}) *

