1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} b5 {This weakens the queenside and is subject to a4 .} 8. Be2 {We need to retreat here, unlike in the 6...b5 line, as we already have b3 on the board, and plans with e4 here are not that great. With Be2 , however, we want to play Ne5 - Bf3 in the future.} Bb7 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. Nbd2 Be7 11. a4 {Finally, challenging the queenside and fighting for the c4 -square.} Qb6 {Black tries to keep the pawn on b5 and not allow Nc4 . But it is not possible, and the Qb6 will run under Nc4 in the future anyway:} 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Nd4 {If ... bxa4 or ... b4 then White looks clearly better in this version as the Qb6 will run under Nc4 .} e5 {The only way to keep the pawn on b5 , but this weakens Black's position as well.} 14. N4f3 {The e5 -pawn is a weakness.} *

