1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} b5 {This weakens the queenside and is subject to a4 .} 8. Be2 {We need to retreat here, unlike in the 6...b5 line, as we already have b3 on the board, and plans with e4 here are not that great. With Be2 , however, we want to play Ne5 - Bf3 in the future.} Bb7 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. Nbd2 Be7 11. a4 {Finally, challenging the queenside and fighting for the c4 -square.} b4 {Black gains some space on the queenside and potentially will try to make use of c3 -square with ... Nd5 -... Bf6 .} (11... bxa4 12. Rxa4 {is far from optimal for Black.}) 12. Ne5 ({I would begin with this move, even though} 12. Nc4 {is fine, of course, too. The idea is Bf3 , and sometimes we may try Ne4 .}) ({After} 12. Ne5 {, trading would be a serious strategic error.} Nxe5 $2 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Nc4 {with a fantastic knight on c4 .}) 12... O-O 13. Bf3 Nd5 {Here, White has some choice.} 14. Ndc4 ({The simplest.} 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. Ne4 $5 {is a decent alternative, e.g.} cxd4 16. Qxd4 f6 17. Rfd1) 14... cxd4 15. Bxd4 {With a stable advantage due to the weakening of Black's queenside.} *

