1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} Nc6 {I find this move to be imprecise. Now, we get a good version of the dxc5 line as the Nc6 is misplaced - most of the time it should go to d7 .} 8. dxc5 Qxd1 (8... Bxc5 {does not change much:} 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bb2 Ke7 11. Rc1 Bd6 12. Nbd2 {and the bishop will retreat to e2 to free the c4 -square for the knight.}) 9. Rxd1 Bxc5 10. Bb2 {White's position is simply better.} b5 11. Be2 ({The ...b5 advance seems to be helping White as now a4 challenges the queenside right away. Bb7} 11. a4 bxa4 12. Rc1 Be7 13. bxa4 O-O 14. Nbd2 {is a sample continuation.}) *

