1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} cxd4 {Trading on d4 right away is the main line here, as played numerous times by players like Nakamura, Dominguez, or MVL. However, the many alternatives need to be covered as well.} ({Note that} 7... Be7 $6 {is inaccurate as right now, White can trade on c5 , which results in a 7.dxc5 line but with an extra tempo for White. E.g.} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bb2 {or Qxd1 Rxd1 Bxc5 Be2!?⩲ intending Ne1 - Nd3 and Bf3 .}) 8. Nxd4 Bd7 ({This is a different way to complete development for Black. Please note that if Black begins with} 8... Be7 {, plans with ... Bd7 are there possible as well. For simplicity, I will keep the ... Bd7 lines here, while after 8...Be7 , I will mark the transpositions.}) 9. Bb2 Nc6 10. Nf3 {I like this idea for White. We keep more pieces on the board and avoid trades which generally help Black equalize. Right now, the Bd7 is also passive now, unlike in the main line when it goes to b7 .} Be7 11. Nbd2 O-O {In this position, White has many plans to choose from. I will recommend two options that I like the most.} 12. Rc1 Rc8 {Here, I like the idea of Bd3 and making use of the e4 -square for the knight or advancing e4 - e5 if possible, of course. However, to place the bishop there, we need to prepare it.} 13. a3 {A necessary prophylaxis against ... Nb4 .} b5 (13... Qa5 14. b4 {just helps White.}) 14. Bd3 Qb6 15. Ng5 {With an ongoing pressure.} *

