1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} cxd4 {Trading on d4 right away is the main line here, as played numerous times by players like Nakamura, Dominguez, or MVL. However, the many alternatives need to be covered as well.} ({Note that} 7... Be7 $6 {is inaccurate as right now, White can trade on c5 , which results in a 7.dxc5 line but with an extra tempo for White. E.g.} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bb2 {or Qxd1 Rxd1 Bxc5 Be2!?⩲ intending Ne1 - Nd3 and Bf3 .}) 8. Nxd4 Bd7 ({This is a different way to complete development for Black. Please note that if Black begins with} 8... Be7 {, plans with ... Bd7 are there possible as well. For simplicity, I will keep the ... Bd7 lines here, while after 8...Be7 , I will mark the transpositions.}) 9. Bb2 Nc6 10. Nf3 {I like this idea for White. We keep more pieces on the board and avoid trades which generally help Black equalize. Right now, the Bd7 is also passive now, unlike in the main line when it goes to b7 .} Be7 11. Nbd2 O-O {In this position, White has many plans to choose from. I will recommend two options that I like the most.} 12. Qb1 {I like this flexible move. White possibly threatens Ng5 with unpleasant threats on the kingside, but there are also ideas of Ne4 , Rd1 , etc. It is not the most common move here, but it has been scoring pretty well for White so far.} ({White can begin with} 12. a3 $5 {too.}) 12... Qa5 {The most popular move. But the queen here is misplaced when White plays a3 - b4 :} 13. a3 Rad8 14. b4 Qh5 {The queen seems to have found a safe haven, but that is actually not true.} 15. Be2 {Due to possible discovery attacks, Black is under pressure.} *

