1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} cxd4 {Trading on d4 right away is the main line here, as played numerous times by players like Nakamura, Dominguez, or MVL. However, the many alternatives need to be covered as well.} ({Note that} 7... Be7 $6 {is inaccurate as right now, White can trade on c5 , which results in a 7.dxc5 line but with an extra tempo for White. E.g.} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bb2 {or Qxd1 Rxd1 Bxc5 Be2!?⩲ intending Ne1 - Nd3 and Bf3 .}) 8. Nxd4 Bd6 {This is another option, keeping the bishop a bit more active but also a bit more exposed. Now, not only can it run under some Nc4 ideas, but also a pin on the d -file might be unpleasant one day.} 9. Bb2 O-O 10. Nd2 Qe7 {A favorite move of GM Timofeev. However, I find it simply inaccurate. Right now, Black's bishop lacks the comfortable e7 -square if needed, and ... e5 can be prevented too:} 11. Bd3 {Preparing Nc4 and intending to meet ... e5 with Nf5 .} e5 12. Nf5 {Winning the bishop pair.} Bxf5 13. Bxf5 Nc6 14. Ne4 ({Stronger than} 14. Nc4 {, played in Sargsyan-Timofeev, 2021.}) 14... Nxe4 15. Bxe4 {The bishop pair, together with unopposed Be4 , gives White a stable advantage.} *

