1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} cxd4 {Trading on d4 right away is the main line here, as played numerous times by players like Nakamura, Dominguez, or MVL. However, the many alternatives need to be covered as well.} ({Note that} 7... Be7 $6 {is inaccurate as right now, White can trade on c5 , which results in a 7.dxc5 line but with an extra tempo for White. E.g.} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bb2 {or Qxd1 Rxd1 Bxc5 Be2!?⩲ intending Ne1 - Nd3 and Bf3 .}) 8. Nxd4 Bd6 {This is another option, keeping the bishop a bit more active but also a bit more exposed. Now, not only can it run under some Nc4 ideas, but also a pin on the d -file might be unpleasant one day.} 9. Bb2 O-O 10. Nd2 e5 {Typically Black plays here via ... e5 , making use of the Bd6 .} 11. N4f3 Qe7 12. Ng5 {White exploits the weakened squares in Black's position. This looks better for us.} Bg4 {Other moves are clearly worse.} (12... Bf5 13. Qf3 {preparing Nde4 .}) (12... b5 $6 {allows the immediate} 13. Nde4 {.}) 13. Qc2 ({With multiple ideas. Black is clearly under pressure.} 13. Qb1 $5 {is similar.}) 13... Nc6 14. f4 Nb4 15. Qb1 h6 16. Nxf7 ({This looks very strong.} 16. Nge4 $5 {is playable too.}) 16... Rxf7 17. Bxf7+ Kxf7 18. Ne4 ({Black's kingside is opened, and the king is in danger. There are lots of practical problems for Black to solve. The best way to do it (not easy by any means) is following} 18. Ne4 {Qxe4} exf4 19. Rxf4 Bxf4 {Qxf4+ Kg8 Qxg4 Qxe3+} 20. Kh1 {Qe7 , where Black seems to have stabilized his position. However, the bishop versus knight in an open position gives White better chances: Qc4+ Kh7 Bc3} Nc6 {Re1↑ with initiative for White.}) *

