1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} cxd4 {Trading on d4 right away is the main line here, as played numerous times by players like Nakamura, Dominguez, or MVL. However, the many alternatives need to be covered as well.} ({Note that} 7... Be7 $6 {is inaccurate as right now, White can trade on c5 , which results in a 7.dxc5 line but with an extra tempo for White. E.g.} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bb2 {or Qxd1 Rxd1 Bxc5 Be2!?⩲ intending Ne1 - Nd3 and Bf3 .}) 8. Nxd4 Be7 {The main plan in this line for Black.} 9. Bb2 O-O (9... Bd7 {will transpose to  8...Bd7 lines sooner or later.}) {Now, let's figure out whether there is any difference between 10.Nd2 and 10.Be2 .} 10. Be2 ({The only difference between beginning with Nd2 and Be2 is that here White has the additional option of meeting b5 with} 10. a4 {- but I don't think it's anything great for White, as the recent game Ding-MVL (2023) showed.}) 10... b5 11. a4 bxa4 12. Rxa4 Bb7 13. Nd2 Nbd7 14. Qa1 Nc5 15. Ra5 h6 {A waiting move, which still was part of MVL's prep. If such much leads to a dead equal position, well, Black must be absolutely fine here.} 16. Rc1 Rc8 17. b4 Ncd7 18. Rxc8 Qxc8 19. Bxa6 Bxa6 20. Rxa6 Bxb4 {And after the queenside got cleaned out, a draw was only a matter of finding a threefold repetition. ½-½ (34) Ding, L (2788)-Vachier Lagrave, M (2741) Bucharest 2023.} *

