1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} cxd4 {Trading on d4 right away is the main line here, as played numerous times by players like Nakamura, Dominguez, or MVL. However, the many alternatives need to be covered as well.} ({Note that} 7... Be7 $6 {is inaccurate as right now, White can trade on c5 , which results in a 7.dxc5 line but with an extra tempo for White. E.g.} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bb2 {or Qxd1 Rxd1 Bxc5 Be2!?⩲ intending Ne1 - Nd3 and Bf3 .}) 8. Nxd4 Be7 {The main plan in this line for Black.} 9. Bb2 O-O (9... Bd7 {will transpose to  8...Bd7 lines sooner or later.}) 10. Nd2 ({White can also begin with} 10. Be2 {, but I like developing the knight first more.}) 10... b5 ({The main plan in this position for Black, which has proven to be equalizing. Even though I found some ideas for White, this is clearly the most solid option for Black here.} 10... Bd7 {preparing ... Nc6 , will again transpose to 8...Bd7 .}) 11. Be2 Bb7 12. Rc1 ({Now a move like Nbd7?! leaves the c6 -square weak and we can get the bishop pair.} 12. Nc6 $1 Bxc6 {Rxc6⩲ with a comfortable edge for White.}) 12... Qb6 ({An alternative to} 12... Qd7 {, but the queen on b6 is not well-placed - it runs under potential Nc4 ideas.}) 13. a4 {Fighting for the control over the c4 -square.} Nc6 14. axb5 axb5 15. Nxb5 {Black does not have sufficient compensation for the pawn. One of the nice ideas here that underline the misplaced Qb6 is the following:} Ra2 16. Nd4 ({And Rxb2 is met by the} 16. Nc4 {fork, while after any other move White is pawn up.}) *

