[Result "*"]
[ECO "D27"]
[PlyCount "37"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {This is one of the most popular lines recently against the QGA. White opts for a positional setup connected with Bb2 from where, in the future, it can exert some pressure on the kingside.} cxd4 {Trading on d4 right away is the main line here, as played numerous times by players like Nakamura, Dominguez, or MVL. However, the many alternatives need to be covered as well.} ({Note that} 7... Be7 $6 {is inaccurate as right now, White can trade on c5 , which results in a 7.dxc5 line but with an extra tempo for White. E.g.} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bb2 {or Qxd1 Rxd1 Bxc5 Be2!?⩲ intending Ne1 - Nd3 and Bf3 .}) 8. Nxd4 Be7 {The main plan in this line for Black.} 9. Bb2 O-O (9... Bd7 {will transpose to  8...Bd7 lines sooner or later.}) 10. Nd2 ({White can also begin with} 10. Be2 {, but I like developing the knight first more.}) 10... b5 ({The main plan in this position for Black, which has proven to be equalizing. Even though I found some ideas for White, this is clearly the most solid option for Black here.} 10... Bd7 {preparing ... Nc6 , will again transpose to 8...Bd7 .}) 11. Be2 Bb7 12. Rc1 ({Now a move like Nbd7?! leaves the c6 -square weak and we can get the bishop pair.} 12. Nc6 $1 Bxc6 {Rxc6⩲ with a comfortable edge for White.}) 12... Qd7 {The main move. It may seem awkward at first, but Black needs to develop the Nb8 to c6 , and this is the best square for the queen.} 13. Bf3 {I think that the best chance for White is to play this move to restrict the development of the Nb8 as the c6 -square is fully under White's control.} Ra7 {The best move (and the main one) in this position. Black ensures to recapture with the rook on b7 and potentially bring it to c7 . Considering there are issues with the development of the Nb8 , this idea bypasses moving the knight for now.} 14. g4 {This is an interesting idea I had prepared a long time ago (not sure when exactly, but it's been a while!), which I think is very challenging for Black. White launches a direct aggression on the kingside, which may not be so easy to react to, especially if caught off guard. So far, there was one game, Mamedyarov-MVL (2023) but still, this line is completely unexplored.} Bxf3 15. Qxf3 {This only helps White to bring the queen to the kingside.} Nd5 16. g5 {An interesting pawn sac.} Rc8 17. Rcd1 ({Right now, White may opt to keep rooks on the board. With more pieces, there is a higher chance of White's attack succeeding.} 17. h4 Rxc1 18. Rxc1 Rc7 19. Rd1 {with ideas like Ne4 and h5 , of course, may be played as well.}) 17... Bxg5 18. Ne4 Bd8 19. Kh1 {With a strong initiative for White on the kingside.} *

