is very challenging for Black. White launches a direct aggression on the kingside, which may not be so easy to react to, especially if caught off guard. So far, there was one game, Mamedyarov-MVL (2023) but still, this line is completely unexplored.} Bxf3 15. Qxf3 {This only helps White to bring the queen to the kingside.} Nd5 16. g5 {An interesting pawn sac.} Bxg5 {Opening the g -file looks extremely risky for Black, and White could have a strong attack here.} 17. Ne4 Be7 (17... Bf6 18. Qg3) 18. Rfd1 ({With a lot of pressure. The idea could be Qg3 with pressure on g7 and the Nb8 . I don't think that many people will accept such a pawn, so I will leave the trainable line here, but I will offer some keep clickable lines to check if you are interested in going deeper. After} 18. Rc8 {, there are two strong options for White:  A) Qg3 Rxc1 Rxc1} Rc7 19. Nc6 $3 {Bf8 Rc5!! Black survives here with only moves.} Rxc6 20. Bxg7 $3 {looks like the game is over... but Black can play} f6 {, and White is only marginally better:} 21. Bxf8 {Kxf8 Qxb8+ Kg7 , and in this endgame, Black should hold, even though it is still White that has some initiative.  B) Nxe6!? at first is legit too:} Rc1 {Rxc1 Qxe6} 22. Qg3+ $1 {or fxe6 Qg3 Bf8 Qxb8 Rc7 Rxc7 Nxc7 Ba3↑ with initiative.}) *

