is very challenging for Black. White launches a direct aggression on the kingside, which may not be so easy to react to, especially if caught off guard. So far, there was one game, Mamedyarov-MVL (2023) but still, this line is completely unexplored.} Rc8 {The best option for Black is to trade a pair of rooks to reduce White's attacking potential.} 15. Rxc8+ {I think White should trade rooks right away to worsen the position of the queen.} Qxc8 16. g5 {Putting more pressure on Black, and some choice or room to go wrong.} Bxf3 (16... Nd5 {without the bishop trade is risky for Black.} 17. h4 Nd7 18. Ne4 {with pressure. Next, we'll push the h -pawn.}) 17. Qxf3 {The most logical recapture.} Nd5 18. h4 Rc7 {In this position, White has many options. If you let the engine think, it will show 0.00 after anything. But knowing plans and ideas will make navigating through such complex positions much easier for us, despite the engine giving triple zeros everywhere!} 19. Qg4 {I like this move the most. White prepares various ideas: h5 - g6 or Ne4 - Nf6 one day.} Nb4 {This engine move is objectively best, but in my opinion, it is much more natural to bring the Nb8 into the game. There are many interesting options for White, despite all being supposedly equal...} 20. Ba3 ({I like this one the most as we are trading the dark-squared bishop, which defends Black's kingside.} 20. h5 $5 Nd3 21. Ba1 {or N4f3} Rc2 {Bf6!? Bf8 h5↑ with initiative for White in both cases, are alternatives.}) 20... Nxa2 21. Bxe7 Rxe7 22. Ne4 {It is clear that without the bishop, Black's king is weaker, and the pressure is rising.} *

