. Nd2 {This idea could be a new path in this line.} (16. a5 $5 {was played by Jeffery. I do not like it as much, and that's why I keep it as a clickable only.} Qe8 17. Qb3 Bd5 18. Bc4 Nc6 19. Nxc6 Bxc6 {Here, I would recommend a slight improvement over Jeffery's move.} 20. Bd4 $5 {and maybe White has some slight pressure here, but of course, with few accurate moves, Black should be able to neutralize it. Bxf6 gxf6= was just equal in Xiong-Dominguez, 2021.}) 16... Nc6 17. Nc4 Bc7 18. Qb3 (18. Bf3 {is suggested by Sam Shankland in his great course on 1.d4 , but after} Rac8 {, it looks like Black is just fine.} 19. Nxc6 Bxc6 20. Qxd7 Bxd7 {targeting the a4 -pawn.}) 18... Rab8 19. Rfd1 Nxd4 20. Rxd4 Bd5 21. Qa3 {Even though it is close to equal, there are still some practical problems that Black needs to resolve. The a6 -pawn may be weak one day, and the Nc4 controls many important squares, restricting Black's pieces. And if Black decides to get rid of it, White will get the bishop pair.} *

