1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Re1 {An interesting line that I tried in the 2023 US Champs against Jeffery Xiong and managed to obtain a very promising position. There are several ideas associated with this move. White prepares e4 , anticipates ... cxd4 followed by exd4 , and then Re1 would be perfectly placed on e1 , and finally, the bishop has a safe square on f1 if needed.} ({I am not going into too much detail on this line as it is an alternative to} 7. b3 {, our main move but still, I want to offer more ideas and possibilities to the repertoire to be less predictable.}) 7... b5 {This is not that great for Black. We can hide on f1 now!} 8. Bf1 {The idea is a4 . However, with Re1 on the board, we can try to employ e4 in the future!} Bb7 {The most obvious move.} 9. a4 b4 10. Nbd2 {Here, we can, of course, play via Nc4 or Nb3 , but we should not forget about the e4 idea.} Nc6 11. Nb3 cxd4 12. exd4 Be7 13. a5 O-O 14. Bf4 {White claims an advantage. The a5 pawn controls the important b6 square, and a6 is an unpleasant weakness.} *

