1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Re1 {An interesting line that I tried in the 2023 US Champs against Jeffery Xiong and managed to obtain a very promising position. There are several ideas associated with this move. White prepares e4 , anticipates ... cxd4 followed by exd4 , and then Re1 would be perfectly placed on e1 , and finally, the bishop has a safe square on f1 if needed.} ({I am not going into too much detail on this line as it is an alternative to} 7. b3 {, our main move but still, I want to offer more ideas and possibilities to the repertoire to be less predictable.}) 7... Be7 {This move is quite decent. In case of dxc5 , we now sort of transpose to the 7.dxc5 line, which I do not recommend in this course. So, the only alternative is e4 .} 8. e4 b5 9. Bb3 ({I would recommend this move here. It is more aggressive than} 9. Bf1 {, that has been played so far.}) 9... Bb7 10. e5 Nd5 11. Nc3 ({Ultimately, I would go for this. It may seem counterintuitive as Black can play c4 and get the d5 -outpost secured, along with a pawn majority on the queenside, but I like that White has center there, and there are lots of pieces on the board. Thanks to the control over the center, White can try to attack on the kingside.} 11. dxc5 {is another option, but I don't like it as much.}) 11... Nb4 {This is possible but worse than pushing the c -pawn:} 12. a3 c4 13. Bxc4 {Winning a pawn.} bxc4 14. axb4 O-O {Now, White has many options.} 15. Be3 {This seems to be the best.} Bxb4 16. Nd2 {White gives the pawn back but attacks the c4 -pawn and potentially brings the queen and other pieces to the kingside.} *

