1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Re1 {An interesting line that I tried in the 2023 US Champs against Jeffery Xiong and managed to obtain a very promising position. There are several ideas associated with this move. White prepares e4 , anticipates ... cxd4 followed by exd4 , and then Re1 would be perfectly placed on e1 , and finally, the bishop has a safe square on f1 if needed.} ({I am not going into too much detail on this line as it is an alternative to} 7. b3 {, our main move but still, I want to offer more ideas and possibilities to the repertoire to be less predictable.}) 7... Nc6 {The main move in Benjamin Gledura's Chessable course. I think that, objectively, it is the best.} 8. Nc3 Be7 {This move was played by Jeffery Xiong. It is a very solid option.} 9. dxc5 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Bxc5 {In this endgame, White has a slight edge, but eventually, Black should be able to hold. There are two ideas that White can try.} 11. Bd2 ({This is what I tried against Jeffery and got a promising position as he confused lines. But as the solution is already well known, I decided to keep it only as an alternative to my main recommendation} 11. Nd2 {.}) 11... O-O 12. Rac1 Bd7 13. Be2 {White completed development and has some pressure in the center. There are ideas of Na4 or even Nd5 !?. For this reason, it makes sense to move the bishop... which is a mistake.} Ba7 {This is what we hope for.} 14. Ng5 {Right now, we can make use of the e4 -square to bring the knight to d6 with some pressure.} Ne7 {This was played in Grischuk-Nakamura, 2022. I prepared here the following:} 15. Nce4 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Bc6 17. Nd6 Rfd8 {And here, instead of Nxb7?! which leads to a nearly instant draw due to massive simplifications...} 18. Ba5 Rd7 19. b3 {With an advantage for White as Black's position is cramped. We can try Nc4 - Nb6 .} *

