1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Re1 {An interesting line that I tried in the 2023 US Champs against Jeffery Xiong and managed to obtain a very promising position. There are several ideas associated with this move. White prepares e4 , anticipates ... cxd4 followed by exd4 , and then Re1 would be perfectly placed on e1 , and finally, the bishop has a safe square on f1 if needed.} ({I am not going into too much detail on this line as it is an alternative to} 7. b3 {, our main move but still, I want to offer more ideas and possibilities to the repertoire to be less predictable.}) 7... Nc6 {The main move in Benjamin Gledura's Chessable course. I think that, objectively, it is the best.} 8. Nc3 b5 {Gledura's recommendation again.} 9. Bd3 cxd4 10. exd4 Nb4 {This is the standard knight maneuver in IQP positions, but in this case White can win the bishop pair with a slight advantage at the end.} 11. Ne5 Be7 (11... Nxd3 12. Qxd3 Bb7 13. Qg3 Rc8 14. a3 $5 {and Black has problems with his king.}) 12. Bf1 O-O 13. a3 Nbd5 14. Nc6 {We get the bishop pair, which should give us some edge in the long run, as the following lines show.} Qb6 15. Nxe7+ Nxe7 16. Bg5 Ned5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Qg4 Ra7 (18... f5 19. Qh4 {Such weakening is usually welcome. Now Black has to worry about the e6 -pawn.}) 19. Rac1 {I believe White has better chances.} *

