1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Re1 {An interesting line that I tried in the 2023 US Champs against Jeffery Xiong and managed to obtain a very promising position. There are several ideas associated with this move. White prepares e4 , anticipates ... cxd4 followed by exd4 , and then Re1 would be perfectly placed on e1 , and finally, the bishop has a safe square on f1 if needed.} ({I am not going into too much detail on this line as it is an alternative to} 7. b3 {, our main move but still, I want to offer more ideas and possibilities to the repertoire to be less predictable.}) 7... Nc6 {The main move in Benjamin Gledura's Chessable course. I think that, objectively, it is the best.} 8. Nc3 b5 {Gledura's recommendation again.} 9. Bd3 Bb7 10. a4 {A usual idea of undermining the queenside.} b4 11. Ne4 Na5 ({Black needs to play this move. There are two options now: Nxf6 and Nxc5 , but I like the former much more.} 11... cxd4 $6 12. exd4 {is risky for Black, as we comfortably develop our pieces and will make use of the c5 -square.}) 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 (12... gxf6 $6 13. e4) 13. e4 h6 {Black must prevent Bg5 . Here, White has many options.} 14. d5 {Probably the most critical move. Here, we enter a sequence that is quite long.} c4 15. Bf1 Bc5 16. Be3 Bxe3 17. Rxe3 O-O {Here, Benjamin Gledura ends his analysis. However, I decided to go a bit deeper with some logical moves, and it appears that Black still has some problems to resolve.} 18. e5 {Now, where to go with the queen?} ({Instead,} 18. Qe1 exd5 19. Qxb4 dxe4 20. Nd2 Qe5 {is just equal.}) 18... Qd8 19. d6 {This is just terrible for Black. Compare with the almost identical position with our pawn on g3 in the alternative.} *

