1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Re1 {An interesting line that I tried in the 2023 US Champs against Jeffery Xiong and managed to obtain a very promising position. There are several ideas associated with this move. White prepares e4 , anticipates ... cxd4 followed by exd4 , and then Re1 would be perfectly placed on e1 , and finally, the bishop has a safe square on f1 if needed.} ({I am not going into too much detail on this line as it is an alternative to} 7. b3 {, our main move but still, I want to offer more ideas and possibilities to the repertoire to be less predictable.}) 7... Nc6 {The main move in Benjamin Gledura's Chessable course. I think that, objectively, it is the best.} 8. Nc3 b5 {Gledura's recommendation again.} 9. Bd3 Bb7 10. a4 {A usual idea of undermining the queenside.} b4 11. Ne4 Na5 ({Black needs to play this move. There are two options now: Nxf6 and Nxc5 , but I like the former much more.} 11... cxd4 $6 12. exd4 {is risky for Black, as we comfortably develop our pieces and will make use of the c5 -square.}) 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 (12... gxf6 $6 13. e4) 13. e4 h6 {Black must prevent Bg5 . Here, White has many options.} 14. g3 {This is quite interesting. The idea is Bf4 , but we also keep d5 for later.} (14. Bd2 $5 {is another option. Here, Black cannot play} c4 $2 15. Bc2 {as} b3 {is not possible due to the loose Na5 , and must grab the pawn instead. cxd4} 16. e5 Qd8 17. Rc1 Be7 18. h4 {offers White some compensation, but in general, it is a very unclear position.}) 14... c4 ({Now} 14... cxd4 $5 15. Bf4 {is unpleasant for Black as he is unable to play ... e5 .}) 15. Bf1 Bd6 {Here, we need to go for d5 , which results in the same position as the main line but with a pawn on g3 .} 16. d5 Bc5 17. Be3 Bxe3 18. Rxe3 O-O {Again, I would go for e5 - d6 to get a meaningful strategic trump in the form of the d6 -pawn.} 19. e5 {Again, Black has a choice now.} Qg6 ({This is what we hope for. With our pawn on g3 ,} 19... Qd8 $1 {is the way to go as the diagonal is weakened.} 20. d6 Rc8 21. Rc1 Bd5 {with an unclear game.}) 20. Nh4 Qg5 21. dxe6 fxe6 22. Qd6 ({And we are winning a pawn. Bd5 Rd1 Rad8 Qxb4} 22. Qh5 {Be2 Qf7 Qe1} Nc6 {Bg4⩲ is a sample continuation.}) *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) The Queen's Gambit Decline"]
[Black "QGD Intro"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D35"]
[PlyCount "15"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 {In the QGD, I opt for systems without or delaying Nf3 (when possible) and try to get a good version of the Carlsbad pawn structure. Of course, Black has an extremely wide range of openings to choose from: there is the Tarrasch, the Semi-Tarrasch, the Carlsbad, the Janowski, to name a few. Let us see what my recommendations are in each of these openings.} Nf6 ({•} 3... c6 {This is a Triangle Slav. I have always considered it as annoying move order and it was my issue with 3.Nc3 . The issue for White is that} 4. Nf3 {can be met with ...dxc4 , the Noteboom Variation which is double edged and I preferred to avoid it. And after e3 , Black can transpose to a Meran, or go for some hybrid Stonewall - neither of which I recommend in the course. However, I decided after thorough analysis that entering Marshall Gambit is simply the right way to tackle the Triangle Slav. e4! dxe4} ({(Black can try Bb4 but this allows White to gain space in the center.} 4. cxd5 exd5 {e5 and as I analyze, White is better here.)}) {Nxe4} 4... Bb4 5. Bd2 {The most principled approach. Even though 6.Nc3 is playable, it is not really challenging and Black has a couple of ways to equalize there. Here, however, Black is stepping on a very thin line. Qxd4 Bxb4 Qxe4+ Be2! Going for the maximum. Even though 8.Ne2 is possible too, I would go for the most ambitious line. Black must play now} Na6 {(everything else is bad) and now White has some choice. I think that the most challenging is Bd6 where the bishop is placed perfectly. The positions here are complicated but it is White that is attacking while Black must be cautious all the time.}) ({•} 3... c5 {The Tarrasch is one of the oldest openings I guess that exists and even though 10-20 years ago it was not that popular, today's engines have totally revived it and it is actually a pretty good opening choice for Black. Especially, it is worth noting that there exists the Dubov's Tarrasch that pretty much easily equalizes. But in my course, I stay clear of it and show paths for White to get good and promising positions.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 ({(After} 5... Nc6 {, White should play} 6. dxc5 $1 {We get the bishop pair in the main line:} d4 7. Na4 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Qxc5 {and here we can play 10. Rc1 , 10. e3 etc., or try a fresh approach:} 10. b4 $5 {which is promising for White.)}) 6. Bg5 $1 {Not going for 6.g3 which enables the Dubov's Tarrasch.} Be6 7. e3 {A standard setup would be my recommendation, even though 7.Bxf6 Qxf6 8.e4!? is incredibly interesting too.} c4 8. Be2 Bb4 9. O-O {and here White tries to make Ne5 - f4 ideas work. However, we can play more positionally too, like Ne5 - Bf3 . It depends on what Black does. Check out the analysis in the course to see more!}) ({cxd4 This is a Von Hennig-Schara Gambit. It is extremely sharp and tactical opening where Black sacs a pawn for activity. If White does not know it can be confusing to play but I believe that I show good paths for White there. I recommend Qa4+} 3... Bd7 {Qxd4 exd5 Qxd5 Nf6 Qd1 winning the pawn. The main line goes as follows: Bc5} 4. Nf3 {O-O e3} Nc6 {Be2 Qe7 O-O and here Black can play via ... Ne5 , ... Rfd8 or ... Rad8 . I analyze them all and I did not find equality for Black.}) ({•} 3... a6 {Janowski Variation in QGD is a sound opening that also was revived in recent years with modern engines. There is a lot of theory there actually.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 {The main line, but I cover moves like 5... h6 and 5... c6 as well.} 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e3 Nbd7 8. Bd3 {I recommend going for this most popular setup. Black has many options now and different move orders. As it is only an intro, I will just say that very often we rely on Bf4 idea (meeting ... Bd6 with Bf4 at some point), sometimes Ne5 - f4 could be really strong and if Black repels ideas on the kingside, we can always try a minority attack.} Bd6 ({(} 8... h6 9. Bf4 g5 10. Bg3 Nh5 {is a sharp line. Here I recommend} 11. Qb3 $5 {, which is relatively rare but very interesting.)}) 9. O-O c6 10. Bf4 $1 Qc7 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. h3 $1 {Restricting the bishop and turning attention to the queenside and minority attack.}) ({•} 3... h6 {This is a recent innovation. Black prevents Bg5 before playing ... Nf6 . However, we are happy to place the bishop on f4 as well, but first let's make sure we get the Carlsbad.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 Bd6 {Black trades these bishops but we continue with our usual plans.} 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. Bd3 {these positions are slightly better for White.}) ({•} 3... Be7 4. cxd5 {Here, 4.Nf3 would transpose to a standard QGD, but here we go for Carlsbad setups.} exd5 5. Bf4 {Now,} Nf6 6. e3 {results in an improved Carlsbad as we have Bf4 . After} c6 {e3 Bf5 White has huge choice here in general, but I like the recently popular} 7. Nge2 $5 {with ideas of Ng3 and h4 .}) ({•} 3... Bb4 {Black tries to transpose to the Ragozin. Here, I would recommend grabbing the bishop pair right away.} 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {we have a similar position to what I analyze in part 1 on Nimzo after d4} Nf6 {c4 e6 Nc3 Bb4} 6. e3 {d5 a3 .}) 4. cxd5 exd5 (4... Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5 {The Semi-Tarrasch is a solid opening but still it is a bit risky as White gets a nice control over the center. Here I recommend} 7. Rb1 {, which prevents quick simplifications connected with ... cxd4 and ... Bb4 . The rook also presses on the queenside.} Be7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bc4 {I analyze these classical setups.}) 5. Bg5 {Black has so many possible move orders here. However, I tried to keep it simple for White. Generally, we play e3 , Bd3 and Nge2 and then usually we prepare f3 - e4 , but we should not forget about the minority attack either.} c6 (5... Bb4 {This Ragozin-style line has become quite popular recently. It certainly can happen if you play 4.cxd5 exd5 5.Bg5 . If you hope for Carlsbad and this comes as a surprise it can be unpleasant, but following my lines should lead to good positions.} 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 9. a3 $5 {I think this is quite challenging to Black.}) 6. e3 Be7 (6... Bd6 {It is considered that the bishop is a bit misplaced here but it is actually not a bad line for Black.} 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Nge2 Re8 {Here, we need to castle at some point, but so far there are ... Bxh2 ideas that prevent us from doing so. Because of that we need to play} 9. h3 {and O-O on the next move.}) (6... Bf5 {This is an incredibly solid line for Black, however White enjoys there a rather risk-free endgame with certain edge.} 7. Qf3 Bg6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6 10. Nf3 {I would recommend this line, following the footsteps of Magnus Carlsen against Vladimir Kramnik.}) 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Nge2 {With intentions of playing in the center. Of course, Black has many move orders available and so on, but I cover it all as best as I can in the course.} *

