1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4 Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 (5... cxd5 $2 6. e5 {is a terrible French for Black.}) 6. e5 {White seizes space and comfortably controls the center. With a3 next, White will either get the pair of bishops or force the bishop to find a place for himself... which may not be easy because I can't think of any square where this bishop would be well placed. Therefore, we will likely get the pair of bishops.} Ne7 {Black can also either delay ... c5 or play without it altogether.} 7. Nf3 c5 8. a3 Ba5 {Black invites dxc5 in order to play ... Bxc3 only then and mess up White's pawn structure. White should take the bait.} ({After} 8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 {, we would sooner or later transpose to the main line.}) 9. dxc5 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qa5 {This line was tried a few times by Russian GM Sergey Yudin. Potentially, it could be strategically sound: Black will get back the pawn, has a simple plan of ... Nbc6 , ... Bg4 , and attacks White's pawns. However, we have a strong response.} 11. Be2 {This was played in a game Vakhidov-Yudin (2022), and I think this should offer White an advantage.} Qxc3+ {The most principled here.} 12. Bd2 Qxc5 13. Bb4 Qc7 14. O-O {Of course, White's compensation for the pawn is tremendous.} *

