1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4 Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 (5... cxd5 $2 6. e5 {is a terrible French for Black.}) 6. e5 {White seizes space and comfortably controls the center. With a3 next, White will either get the pair of bishops or force the bishop to find a place for himself... which may not be easy because I can't think of any square where this bishop would be well placed. Therefore, we will likely get the pair of bishops.} c5 {Playing with ... c5 is the most standard plan here for Black.} 7. a3 {This move is often played after Black plays ... c5 . Of course, White should get the pair of bishops if possible.} Ba5 8. b4 {Followed by Nb5 , this is a pretty standard idea in the French Defense.} cxd4 (8... cxb4 {is met by} 9. Nb5 bxa3+ 10. Bd2 Nc6 11. Bd3) 9. Nb5 Bc7 10. f4 {White can recapture the pawn any moment.} *

