1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 ({I would recommend going for the most principled line here. The resulting positions strike me as promising for White, and they require a lot of accuracy from Black to stay in the game. I should mention, though, that there have been many games played with} 6. Nc3 {as well, most notably a game Carlsen-Anand in the World Championship Match 2013, but the arising positions are generally speaking less promising than after Bd2 .}) 6... Qxd4 (6... Bxd2+ $6 {cannot be taken seriously - White immediately gets a fantastic position.} 7. Qxd2 Nf6 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Nf3 {Black will suffer here due to bad Bc8 and being less developed. White has clear advantage.}) 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+ 8. Be2 ({Not taking any prisoners - White goes for the maximum out of this crazy line.} 8. Ne2 {is a possible alternative; however, it is less challenging and Black should not have any issues equalizing there.}) 8... Qxg2 {This is too greedy.} ({Some people have tried here} 8... c5 $2 {, but I don't really see a point in giving away a pawn in such a way.} 9. Bxc5 Qxg2 10. Bf3 Qg5 11. Qd6 Nd7 12. Ba3 {gives White an excellent position.}) 9. Bf3 Qg5 10. Ne2 {This gives White a strong initiative. With precise dynamic play, we manage to pose serious problems.} Na6 11. Rg1 Qf6 12. Bc3 e5 13. Ng3 {Black's position is very shaky.} Qg5 {This seems the only reasonable move, stopping Ne4 , but it is only a temporary measure.} 14. h4 ({Or} 14. Qd6 Bd7 15. h4 Qe7 16. Qxe5 Qxe5+ 17. Bxe5 {with a big advantage in the endgame.}) 14... Qxh4 15. Ne4 Qe7 16. Nd6+ Kf8 17. Qe2 {With a crushing initiative. Some sample continuations:} ({Qxd6} 17. Bxe5 Qe6 {Bxg7+ Ke7 Bxh8+-}) ({f6 O-O-O Be6} 17. Bg4 $1 Bxg4 18. Qxg4 Nh6 19. Qh3) *

