1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 ({I would recommend going for the most principled line here. The resulting positions strike me as promising for White, and they require a lot of accuracy from Black to stay in the game. I should mention, though, that there have been many games played with} 6. Nc3 {as well, most notably a game Carlsen-Anand in the World Championship Match 2013, but the arising positions are generally speaking less promising than after Bd2 .}) 6... Qxd4 (6... Bxd2+ $6 {cannot be taken seriously - White immediately gets a fantastic position.} 7. Qxd2 Nf6 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Nf3 {Black will suffer here due to bad Bc8 and being less developed. White has clear advantage.}) 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+ 8. Be2 ({Not taking any prisoners - White goes for the maximum out of this crazy line.} 8. Ne2 {is a possible alternative; however, it is less challenging and Black should not have any issues equalizing there.}) 8... a5 {This is just a serious mistake as it helps White bring the bishop to d6 and at the same time Black is not developing any of his pieces.} 9. Bd6 Nh6 {Here, accuracy is required, however.} 10. Qd2 {White wants to castle queenside!} Nf5 11. Ba3 {Black will have issues completing his development.} *

