1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 ({I would recommend going for the most principled line here. The resulting positions strike me as promising for White, and they require a lot of accuracy from Black to stay in the game. I should mention, though, that there have been many games played with} 6. Nc3 {as well, most notably a game Carlsen-Anand in the World Championship Match 2013, but the arising positions are generally speaking less promising than after Bd2 .}) 6... Qxd4 (6... Bxd2+ $6 {cannot be taken seriously - White immediately gets a fantastic position.} 7. Qxd2 Nf6 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Nf3 {Black will suffer here due to bad Bc8 and being less developed. White has clear advantage.}) 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+ 8. Be2 ({Not taking any prisoners - White goes for the maximum out of this crazy line.} 8. Ne2 {is a possible alternative; however, it is less challenging and Black should not have any issues equalizing there.}) 8... Na6 {The only good move in this position. Everything else simply fails.} (8... Ne7 $2 {is not a good way to complete development.} 9. Qd2 Ng6 10. Nh3 {preventing ... Qf4 . Next, O-O-O comes.} Na6 11. O-O-O f6 12. f3 Qe5 13. Bd6 Qh5 14. f4 Qh4 15. Rhf1 {and White is winning.}) 9. Bd6 ({Along with} 9. Ba5 {, this is the strongest move, but for this course I decided to focus on Bd6 as personally it feels the most challenging. The bishop is fantastic on d6 of course, crippling Black's development and ability to castle. White has here two main ideas: Qd2 and O-O-O , or Nf3 and O-O . Depending on what Black does, White should choose either of these accordingly.}) 9... b6 {The plan of developing the bishop to b7 is common after 9.Ba5 as Black actually gains a tempo. Here, it makes no sense.} 10. Nf3 Bb7 11. O-O {Engines evaluate +2, but some accuracy is required.} Ne7 (11... O-O-O 12. Ne5 $1 Qf5 13. g4 Qf6 (13... Qf4 14. Ng6 $1) 14. f4) 12. Qd2 Nf5 13. Rfd1 O-O-O 14. Bd3 Qg4 15. Ne5 Qh5 16. g4 ({White wins material. And if Qh3 we should play} 16. Bf1 $1 {, attacking the queen again, and not gxf5?!} Rxd6 17. Nxf7 Rd4 $1 {and Black has a dangerous initiative on the kingside.}) *

