1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 ({I would recommend going for the most principled line here. The resulting positions strike me as promising for White, and they require a lot of accuracy from Black to stay in the game. I should mention, though, that there have been many games played with} 6. Nc3 {as well, most notably a game Carlsen-Anand in the World Championship Match 2013, but the arising positions are generally speaking less promising than after Bd2 .}) 6... Qxd4 (6... Bxd2+ $6 {cannot be taken seriously - White immediately gets a fantastic position.} 7. Qxd2 Nf6 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Nf3 {Black will suffer here due to bad Bc8 and being less developed. White has clear advantage.}) 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+ 8. Be2 ({Not taking any prisoners - White goes for the maximum out of this crazy line.} 8. Ne2 {is a possible alternative; however, it is less challenging and Black should not have any issues equalizing there.}) 8... Na6 {The only good move in this position. Everything else simply fails.} (8... Ne7 $2 {is not a good way to complete development.} 9. Qd2 Ng6 10. Nh3 {preventing ... Qf4 . Next, O-O-O comes.} Na6 11. O-O-O f6 12. f3 Qe5 13. Bd6 Qh5 14. f4 Qh4 15. Rhf1 {and White is winning.}) 9. Bd6 ({Along with} 9. Ba5 {, this is the strongest move, but for this course I decided to focus on Bd6 as personally it feels the most challenging. The bishop is fantastic on d6 of course, crippling Black's development and ability to castle. White has here two main ideas: Qd2 and O-O-O , or Nf3 and O-O . Depending on what Black does, White should choose either of these accordingly.}) 9... e5 ({This is the only reasonable alternative to} 9... Qxg2 {.}) 10. Nf3 Bg4 11. O-O O-O-O {This is the idea of 9...e5 - Black quickly completes queenside development.} 12. Bd3 ({The best chance for White is to enter a long, forced line that results in a complicated endgame but with objectively better chances.} 12. b4 $5 {with the idea c5 is a very interesting option as well but objectively it should not yield an advantage after} Nf6 $1 13. c5 Ne8 $1 {Black manages to put just enough pressure on the Bd6 to successfully deal with it and pretty much equalize.}) 12... Qf4 ({And if} 12... Bxf3 $4 13. Bxe4 Bxd1 14. Bf5+ $1 {and Black is forced to self-pin with} Rd7 {.}) 13. Bxe5 Qxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxd1 15. Bf5+ ({An important intermezzo, intending to take on f7 . After the immediate} 15. Nxf7 $6 Bg4 $1 16. h3 Be6 17. Nxd8 Kxd8 {, Black is not worse here.}) (15. Raxd1 Nh6 {is just equal.}) 15... Kc7 16. Nxf7 {The best try.} Nh6 17. Nxd8 Rxd8 18. Bxh7 Be2 {Now, we can basically just transpose to the 16...Be2 line by playing Rfe1 , but there is an additional option.} 19. Rfc1 Rd2 (19... Nc5 20. b3 {is also better for White.}) 20. b3 Nb4 21. f3 {White intends to play a3 to kick away the knight and to simplify the position with Rc2 ideally. The pawn majority on the kingside should be useful in the future.} ({And if Nxa2} 21. Rc2) *

