side with b4 - b5 , or play more positionally with c5 .}) 10. Bf3 {A very interesting rare line that poses a lot of practical problems to Black. The first one is right there - where should Black retreat with the queen?} Qg6 11. Ne2 {Now the game goes on in similar fashion but Black has fewer options than in the 10...Qg5 lines. As I analyzed, this is extremely dangerous to Black and even though engine is capable of holding it - on human level, I find it unlikely that people will manage to find all perfect moves...} {Bd7? Rg1!+-} e5 {This is logical but it does not equalize.} 12. Rg1 Qe6 13. Rxg7 {We can safely grab the pawn.} Qf6 14. Rg3 Ne7 15. Nc3 {Intending Ne4 . Black must, of course, prevent it.} Bf5 16. c5 {Supporting the strong Bd6 . White wants to play Qe2 and O-O-O if Black does not do anything concrete now. Also, Ne4 is an idea. Black has many options here.} Nc8 {This seems to be the most critical, as the Bd6 is really strong and it makes sense to trade it. However, now White can go for tactical solutions:} 17. Bxc6+ bxc6 18. Qa4 {Black can't protect everything.} Nxd6 {Only move.} 19. Qxc6+ Bd7 20. Qxa8+ Nc8 21. Rd1 {Black has a terrible position.} *

