1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 ({I would recommend going for the most principled line here. The resulting positions strike me as promising for White, and they require a lot of accuracy from Black to stay in the game. I should mention, though, that there have been many games played with} 6. Nc3 {as well, most notably a game Carlsen-Anand in the World Championship Match 2013, but the arising positions are generally speaking less promising than after Bd2 .}) 6... Qxd4 (6... Bxd2+ $6 {cannot be taken seriously - White immediately gets a fantastic position.} 7. Qxd2 Nf6 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Nf3 {Black will suffer here due to bad Bc8 and being less developed. White has clear advantage.}) 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+ 8. Be2 ({Not taking any prisoners - White goes for the maximum out of this crazy line.} 8. Ne2 {is a possible alternative; however, it is less challenging and Black should not have any issues equalizing there.}) 8... Na6 {The only good move in this position. Everything else simply fails.} (8... Ne7 $2 {is not a good way to complete development.} 9. Qd2 Ng6 10. Nh3 {preventing ... Qf4 . Next, O-O-O comes.} Na6 11. O-O-O f6 12. f3 Qe5 13. Bd6 Qh5 14. f4 Qh4 15. Rhf1 {and White is winning.}) 9. Bd6 ({Along with} 9. Ba5 {, this is the strongest move, but for this course I decided to focus on Bd6 as personally it feels the most challenging. The bishop is fantastic on d6 of course, crippling Black's development and ability to castle. White has here two main ideas: Qd2 and O-O-O , or Nf3 and O-O . Depending on what Black does, White should choose either of these accordingly.}) 9... Qxg2 {Black needs to accept the bait and grab the g2 -pawn to justify his risky opening choice. If White manages to play Nf3 , O-O for instance and Black is not in time to complete his development or generate counterplay, White can win in a miniature.} (9... Bd7 $2 10. Nf3 O-O-O 11. O-O {The plan of castling queenside here does not really work. White will simply crush on the queenside with b4 - b5 , or play more positionally with c5 .}) 10. Bf3 {A very interesting rare line that poses a lot of practical problems to Black. The first one is right there - where should Black retreat with the queen?} Qg6 11. Ne2 {Now the game goes on in similar fashion but Black has fewer options than in the 10...Qg5 lines. As I analyzed, this is extremely dangerous to Black and even though engine is capable of holding it - on human level, I find it unlikely that people will manage to find all perfect moves...} {Bd7? Rg1!+-} Ne7 {With ... Qg6 instead of ... Qg5 , this does not work that well but it is still the best and most solid option.} 12. Qd2 {Preparing O-O-O . Please note this is not possible against ... Qg5 !} e5 {Black must give back some material to complete his development.} 13. Bxe5 f6 {Trying to get with the queen away from Rg1 ideas.} 14. Bd6 Qf7 15. O-O-O O-O 16. b3 {This position is, however, still very unpleasant for Black. White's pair of bishops should give great chances. Potentially, we can attack on the kingside, but there is also an option of playing more positionally. Some sample continuations:} ({Rd8} 16. Qc3 Nf5 17. Ba3 {Rxd1+ Rxd1} Be6 18. Nf4) ({Or Re8} 16. h4 Be6 17. Ba3 Ng6 18. Ng3 c5 19. Ne4 Ne5 20. Bg2 {with ideas of Bb2 and Nd6 . And in the event of} Qe7 {then} 21. Qd6 $1 {is pretty strong.}) *

