side with b4 - b5 , or play more positionally with c5 .}) 10. Bf3 {A very interesting rare line that poses a lot of practical problems to Black. The first one is right there - where should Black retreat with the queen?} Qg5 {The queen is the most active here and it supports ... e5 . In some lines, Black has an idea of ... Qa5 +.} 11. Ne2 Ne7 (11... e5 {is not good due to} 12. Rg1 $1 {± with unpleasant pressure. Both e5 and g7 are weak.}) 12. Ng3 {A very rare move in this position that is recommended by the engines. The most popular move is Rg1 instead, but Black has easier task consolidating his position. And as this move is rare, people playing it with Black may be immediately out of book! The knight is headed to e4 . Here, Black has some choice but it is not an easy choice by any means. There are three decent moves that Black can play, but White is able to put Black under serious pressure everywhere, and often Black just makes it out of it alive with only moves.} (12. Rg1 $6 Qa5+ $1 {is good for Black:} 13. b4 Nxb4 14. Kf1 Na6) 12... O-O {This line is very risky for Black.} 13. Ne4 Qa5+ 14. b4 {A standard reaction to this check. Black has two options here.} Qd8 15. Rg1 {With pressure on the g -file and in the center. Black perhaps needs to give away the exchange sooner or later to avoid collapsing immediately.} Ng6 {Now, White can take on f8 , of course, but there's something even stronger.} (15... f6 $6 16. Qe2 {followed by O-O-O .}) 16. h4 f5 (16... Nxh4 $6 17. Rxg7+ $1 Kxg7 18. Be5+ f6 19. Bxf6+ {and White has the advantage.}) 17. Ng5 h6 18. Nh3 Nxh4 19. Bh5 {With an ongoing initiative.} *

