side with b4 - b5 , or play more positionally with c5 .}) 10. Bf3 {A very interesting rare line that poses a lot of practical problems to Black. The first one is right there - where should Black retreat with the queen?} Qg5 {The queen is the most active here and it supports ... e5 . In some lines, Black has an idea of ... Qa5 +.} 11. Ne2 Ne7 (11... e5 {is not good due to} 12. Rg1 $1 {± with unpleasant pressure. Both e5 and g7 are weak.}) 12. Ng3 {A very rare move in this position that is recommended by the engines. The most popular move is Rg1 instead, but Black has easier task consolidating his position. And as this move is rare, people playing it with Black may be immediately out of book! The knight is headed to e4 . Here, Black has some choice but it is not an easy choice by any means. There are three decent moves that Black can play, but White is able to put Black under serious pressure everywhere, and often Black just makes it out of it alive with only moves.} (12. Rg1 $6 Qa5+ $1 {is good for Black:} 13. b4 Nxb4 14. Kf1 Na6) 12... e5 {This is probably the strongest reply by Black. The idea is to make a path for the Bc8 to develop.} 13. Qb3 {Developing the queen and at the same time keeping an eye on the b7 -pawn. We can keep the ideas of Ne4 and h4 for the future.} Ng6 {This move is the top engine's choice. Black wants to stabilize in the center and bring the knight to h4 . So far, there are no immediate threats, so Black can afford to do it. Right now, White has a lot of options. According to the engine, everything is evaluated as 0.00, but that simply means the position is unclear and White has many options to put Black under pressure. I decided to recommend a line that appeals the most to me. However, you can see there are different moves that are possible too and incredibly dangerous for Black as well. If you are interested, I would encourage you to study them!} 14. h4 {I like this move a lot. White does not care about being two or three pawns down. What matters here are dynamic considerations, disturbing Black's coordination, and creating practical problems to our opponent.} (14. Be4 $5 f5 15. Bf3 {with ideas like h4 and Bh5 is very interesting.} ({Be2!? preparing c5 is one of the engine's choices too, and White can begin with the immediate} 15. c5 $5 {as well.})) 14... Nxh4 15. Bh5 {Activating the bishop and provoking the weakening of Black's kingside. This position looks very risky for Black. Engines manage to hold it - but I don't see anyone who would not be scared to play such a position as the margin of risk is really narrow...} g6 16. Be2 {This is far from easy for Black.} Nf5 17. Ne4 {Now, White does not have to trade the knights!} Qf4 18. Nf6+ Kd8 19. Rd1 Nd4 (19... Nxd6 $2 {It is absolutely imperative that White not capture on d6 , and instead find} 20. Qa3 $1 {with a point being} c5 21. Rxd6+ Ke7 (21... Kc7 22. Rxa6 bxa6 23. Nd5+) 22. Nd5+ $1 Kxd6 23. Nxf4) 20. Qc3 ({Keeping more pieces on the board and avoiding forced play.} 20. Rxd4 {is possible, but it leads to simplifications, and Black should be able to escape:} Qxd4 21. O-O Qxd6 22. Rd1 Qxd1+ 23. Bxd1 Ke7 24. Ne4 Rd8) 20... Be6 {This position looks deadly scary for Black, but the max I have found is a draw...} 21. Qa5+ b6 {But first check the weakest move, because that is what we are hoping for.} 22. Bxe5 bxa5 23. Bxf4 c5 24. Ne4 {And the game goes on! Nxc5 comes in soon, and the pair of bishops should give White some chances.} *

