1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 ({I would recommend going for the most principled line here. The resulting positions strike me as promising for White, and they require a lot of accuracy from Black to stay in the game. I should mention, though, that there have been many games played with} 6. Nc3 {as well, most notably a game Carlsen-Anand in the World Championship Match 2013, but the arising positions are generally speaking less promising than after Bd2 .}) 6... Qxd4 (6... Bxd2+ $6 {cannot be taken seriously - White immediately gets a fantastic position.} 7. Qxd2 Nf6 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Nf3 {Black will suffer here due to bad Bc8 and being less developed. White has clear advantage.}) 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+ 8. Be2 ({Not taking any prisoners - White goes for the maximum out of this crazy line.} 8. Ne2 {is a possible alternative; however, it is less challenging and Black should not have any issues equalizing there.}) 8... Na6 {The only good move in this position. Everything else simply fails.} (8... Ne7 $2 {is not a good way to complete development.} 9. Qd2 Ng6 10. Nh3 {preventing ... Qf4 . Next, O-O-O comes.} Na6 11. O-O-O f6 12. f3 Qe5 13. Bd6 Qh5 14. f4 Qh4 15. Rhf1 {and White is winning.}) 9. Bd6 ({Along with} 9. Ba5 {, this is the strongest move, but for this course I decided to focus on Bd6 as personally it feels the most challenging. The bishop is fantastic on d6 of course, crippling Black's development and ability to castle. White has here two main ideas: Qd2 and O-O-O , or Nf3 and O-O . Depending on what Black does, White should choose either of these accordingly.}) 9... Qxg2 {Black needs to accept the bait and grab the g2 -pawn to justify his risky opening choice. If White manages to play Nf3 , O-O for instance and Black is not in time to complete his development or generate counterplay, White can win in a miniature.} (9... Bd7 $2 10. Nf3 O-O-O 11. O-O {The plan of castling queenside here does not really work. White will simply crush on the queenside with b4 - b5 , or play more positionally with c5 .}) 10. Bf3 {A very interesting rare line that poses a lot of practical problems to Black. The first one is right there - where should Black retreat with the queen?} Qg5 {The queen is the most active here and it supports ... e5 . In some lines, Black has an idea of ... Qa5 +.} 11. Ne2 Ne7 (11... e5 {is not good due to} 12. Rg1 $1 {± with unpleasant pressure. Both e5 and g7 are weak.}) 12. Ng3 {A very rare move in this position that is recommended by the engines. The most popular move is Rg1 instead, but Black has easier task consolidating his position. And as this move is rare, people playing it with Black may be immediately out of book! The knight is headed to e4 . Here, Black has some choice but it is not an easy choice by any means. There are three decent moves that Black can play, but White is able to put Black under serious pressure everywhere, and often Black just makes it out of it alive with only moves.} (12. Rg1 $6 Qa5+ $1 {is good for Black:} 13. b4 Nxb4 14. Kf1 Na6) 12... e5 {This is probably the strongest reply by Black. The idea is to make a path for the Bc8 to develop.} 13. Qb3 {Developing the queen and at the same time keeping an eye on the b7 -pawn. We can keep the ideas of Ne4 and h4 for the future.} Ng6 {This move is the top engine's choice. Black wants to stabilize in the center and bring the knight to h4 . So far, there are no immediate threats, so Black can afford to do it. Right now, White has a lot of options. According to the engine, everything is evaluated as 0.00, but that simply means the position is unclear and White has many options to put Black under pressure. I decided to recommend a line that appeals the most to me. However, you can see there are different moves that are possible too and incredibly dangerous for Black as well. If you are interested, I would encourage you to study them!} 14. h4 {I like this move a lot. White does not care about being two or three pawns down. What matters here are dynamic considerations, disturbing Black's coordination, and creating practical problems to our opponent.} (14. Be4 $5 f5 15. Bf3 {with ideas like h4 and Bh5 is very interesting.} ({Be2!? preparing c5 is one of the engine's choices too, and White can begin with the immediate} 15. c5 $5 {as well.})) 14... Nxh4 15. Bh5 {Activating the bishop and provoking the weakening of Black's kingside. This position looks very risky for Black. Engines manage to hold it - but I don't see anyone who would not be scared to play such a position as the margin of risk is really narrow...} Nf5 {It makes sense to simplify the position a little bit from Black's perspective.} 16. Nxf5 Qxf5 (16... Bxf5 {is not possible as the b7 -pawn must remain guarded!}) 17. O-O-O {This position looks incredibly scary for Black.} g6 {Black must kick away the bishop to have an option to play ... f6 and support the e5 -pawn.} (17... Qf4+ $2 18. Rd2 {gives the white bishop a safer retreat to d1 .}) 18. Bf3 f6 19. c5 Bd7 {This is possible but it's really counterintuitive.} 20. Qxb7 Nb4 21. Qxb4 Qxf3 22. Rhe1 {Black's king is still under pressure!} *

