tters here are dynamic considerations, disturbing Black's coordination, and creating practical problems to our opponent.} (14. Be4 $5 f5 15. Bf3 {with ideas like h4 and Bh5 is very interesting.} ({Be2!? preparing c5 is one of the engine's choices too, and White can begin with the immediate} 15. c5 $5 {as well.})) 14... Nxh4 15. Bh5 {Activating the bishop and provoking the weakening of Black's kingside. This position looks very risky for Black. Engines manage to hold it - but I don't see anyone who would not be scared to play such a position as the margin of risk is really narrow...} Nf5 {It makes sense to simplify the position a little bit from Black's perspective.} 16. Nxf5 Qxf5 (16... Bxf5 {is not possible as the b7 -pawn must remain guarded!}) 17. O-O-O {This position looks incredibly scary for Black.} g6 {Black must kick away the bishop to have an option to play ... f6 and support the e5 -pawn.} (17... Qf4+ $2 18. Rd2 {gives the white bishop a safer retreat to d1 .}) 18. Bf3 f6 19. c5 Qe6 (19... Qf4+ 20. Rd2 {transposes here.}) 20. Qa4 Kf7 21. Be4 {Here, Black is under serious pressure.} Kg7 {Looks like a natural move, trying to get the king to safety. In reality though, the king is far from being safe:} 22. f4 {Opening the position!} *

