[White "12) QGD: Tarrasch 4...cxd4 (V"]
[Black "QGD Tarrasch Von Hennig-Schar"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D32"]
[PlyCount "29"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 {A very sharp line in which Black sacrifices a pawn for activity. We should be definitely familiar with it as if caught off guard, it can be really tricky to meet.} 5. Qa4+ (5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd1 exd5 7. Qxd5 {is another option that I was seriously considering here. But I found that after} Bd6 $5 {, it is not so easy to show an advantage. Still, the position is quite playable and relatively not explored so some ideas could be found there.}) 5... Bd7 (5... b5 $4 {was played in some games, but it is simply losing.} 6. Nxb5 Bd7 7. e4 $1 {and, thanks to the pin on the a-file, White does not lose a piece even if Black continues with ... a6 . Actually, White is just a pawn up, threatening d6 .}) 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6 {White has two options now: Qd1 or Qb3 . In this course, I cover 8. Qd1 , which I think is more challenging.} 8. Qd1 (8. Qb3 Na6 $1 {was played in a critical game for the line, Shankland-Carlsen (2022). I think Black should equalize quite comfortably with a few accurate moves, but as they were already played in the aforementioned game, I think many people will be familiar with what Magnus went for. Because of that, 8. Qd1 is my choice here.}) 8... Nc6 9. Nf3 {Here, I look at different plans that Black can try to go for instead of what I analyze in the main line.} Bb4 {This is an option, but the bishop is worse placed on b4 than on c5 , as we can play Bd2 , which is useful anyway, while on b4 the bishop will only run under tempo or potentially may be even traded - which helps White.} 10. Bd2 Qe7 11. e3 O-O-O {This is another plan, but I am highly skeptical about Black castling queenside here.} 12. Be2 Kb8 13. O-O g5 {Very aggressive play by Black - but we can just ignore it.} 14. Qc2 g4 15. Nh4 {And Black's attack does not really go anywhere, while the extra pawn is a tangible advantage.} *

