1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 {A very sharp line in which Black sacrifices a pawn for activity. We should be definitely familiar with it as if caught off guard, it can be really tricky to meet.} 5. Qa4+ (5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd1 exd5 7. Qxd5 {is another option that I was seriously considering here. But I found that after} Bd6 $5 {, it is not so easy to show an advantage. Still, the position is quite playable and relatively not explored so some ideas could be found there.}) 5... Bd7 (5... b5 $4 {was played in some games, but it is simply losing.} 6. Nxb5 Bd7 7. e4 $1 {and, thanks to the pin on the a-file, White does not lose a piece even if Black continues with ... a6 . Actually, White is just a pawn up, threatening d6 .}) 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6 {White has two options now: Qd1 or Qb3 . In this course, I cover 8. Qd1 , which I think is more challenging.} 8. Qd1 (8. Qb3 Na6 $1 {was played in a critical game for the line, Shankland-Carlsen (2022). I think Black should equalize quite comfortably with a few accurate moves, but as they were already played in the aforementioned game, I think many people will be familiar with what Magnus went for. Because of that, 8. Qd1 is my choice here.}) 8... Nc6 9. Nf3 {Here, I look at different plans that Black can try to go for instead of what I analyze in the main line.} Bc5 {Black has also plans involving queenside castle, but they are very risky.} 10. e3 Qe7 11. Be2 {Here, Black can transpose to the main line by castling kingside. But there are two other aggressive plans: O-O-O and g5 . Let's look at these options too.} O-O-O {There are many games like this, but recently, this line went out of fashion and for a reason. Black does not have sufficient compensation and their king will feel potentially unsafe on the queenside.} 12. O-O g5 {Black plays aggressively, but the attack simply does not work.} 13. a3 ({I like this simple move the most. Another option was} 13. b4 {, but it unnecessarily sacs a pawn.}) 13... g4 14. Nh4 {With Nh4 , Black cannot hope for ... h5 -... h4 anymore. White wants to play Qc2 , b4 , Bb2 , etc.} Kb8 15. Qc2 Rhg8 16. b4 Bb6 17. Bb2 {White is just up a pawn, and Black does not have real chances for an attack on the kingside.} *

