1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 {A very sharp line in which Black sacrifices a pawn for activity. We should be definitely familiar with it as if caught off guard, it can be really tricky to meet.} 5. Qa4+ (5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd1 exd5 7. Qxd5 {is another option that I was seriously considering here. But I found that after} Bd6 $5 {, it is not so easy to show an advantage. Still, the position is quite playable and relatively not explored so some ideas could be found there.}) 5... Bd7 (5... b5 $4 {was played in some games, but it is simply losing.} 6. Nxb5 Bd7 7. e4 $1 {and, thanks to the pin on the a-file, White does not lose a piece even if Black continues with ... a6 . Actually, White is just a pawn up, threatening d6 .}) 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6 {White has two options now: Qd1 or Qb3 . In this course, I cover 8. Qd1 , which I think is more challenging.} 8. Qd1 (8. Qb3 Na6 $1 {was played in a critical game for the line, Shankland-Carlsen (2022). I think Black should equalize quite comfortably with a few accurate moves, but as they were already played in the aforementioned game, I think many people will be familiar with what Magnus went for. Because of that, 8. Qd1 is my choice here.}) 8... Bc5 {The bishop typically belongs on the c5 -square in these positions. Black needs to quickly castle and look for active counterplay for the pawn.} 9. Nf3 O-O ({For} 9... Nc6 {, see 8... Nc6  here.}) 10. e3 Nc6 (10... Qe7 {is simply another move order.} 11. Be2 Rd8 12. O-O Nc6 {with a transposition . Nc6 O-O also transposes.}) 11. Be2 Qc7 {This is less accurate - the queen is going to run into pressure when Rc1 is played.} 12. Bd2 Rad8 (12... Ne5 13. Rc1 {is similar.}) 13. O-O Ne5 14. Rc1 {Black has insufficient compensation for the pawn.} *

