1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 {A very sharp line in which Black sacrifices a pawn for activity. We should be definitely familiar with it as if caught off guard, it can be really tricky to meet.} 5. Qa4+ (5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd1 exd5 7. Qxd5 {is another option that I was seriously considering here. But I found that after} Bd6 $5 {, it is not so easy to show an advantage. Still, the position is quite playable and relatively not explored so some ideas could be found there.}) 5... Bd7 (5... b5 $4 {was played in some games, but it is simply losing.} 6. Nxb5 Bd7 7. e4 $1 {and, thanks to the pin on the a-file, White does not lose a piece even if Black continues with ... a6 . Actually, White is just a pawn up, threatening d6 .}) 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6 {White has two options now: Qd1 or Qb3 . In this course, I cover 8. Qd1 , which I think is more challenging.} 8. Qd1 (8. Qb3 Na6 $1 {was played in a critical game for the line, Shankland-Carlsen (2022). I think Black should equalize quite comfortably with a few accurate moves, but as they were already played in the aforementioned game, I think many people will be familiar with what Magnus went for. Because of that, 8. Qd1 is my choice here.}) 8... Bc5 {The bishop typically belongs on the c5 -square in these positions. Black needs to quickly castle and look for active counterplay for the pawn.} 9. Nf3 O-O ({For} 9... Nc6 {, see 8... Nc6  here.}) 10. e3 Nc6 (10... Qe7 {is simply another move order.} 11. Be2 Rd8 12. O-O Nc6 {with a transposition . Nc6 O-O also transposes.}) 11. Be2 Qe7 12. O-O ({The main position in this line. Black has three main options now: Rfd8 , Rad8 , or quite popular lately,} 12. Ne5 {. Let's have a look.}) 12... Ne5 {This is not the most common move here, but the trend shifted towards it recently as it was played many times by Aryan Tari, and also Magnus Carlsen tried it a few times. That's why I decided to keep it as main.} 13. Qb3 {This is a new move here, but it is recommended by engines. I think it poses certain problems for Black. So far, the b7 -pawn needs attention.} b5 ({The best move here for Black. Not wasting any time for seeking counterplay, Black sacs another pawn.} 13... Rab8 $6 {looks like a waste of time. Black should not be passive, and he should look for some counterplay.} 14. e4 {is again a good move.}) 14. Rd1 {Bringing the rook into the game, preparing maybe Nd5 , or the Bd2 - Be1 idea.} ({I also analyzed} 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 15. Nxb5 {, but this seems less clear due to} Rac8 $1 {with various ideas, e.g. ... Ng4 or ... Qg5 -... Bc6 . I analyzed it quite deeply but I did not really find anything satisfactory. Ng4?! is a bit premature:} 16. Bg4 Bxg4 17. Nd4 $1 {returning a pawn with a safe and comfortable edge:} Bxd4 18. exd4 Qxd4 19. Be3) 14... Rad8 15. a3 {Stopping ... b4 . Honestly, I do not see Black having sufficient compensation here. Next, Bd2 - Be1 comes.} (15. Nd5 {is not as great here as with the rook on c8 ; the Bd7 is defended in the following line, and Black avoids the queen trade:} Nxd5 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. Qxd5 Qe7 $1 {, while after 14...Rac8 , this was not possible as the Bd7 would have been hanging.}) 15... Rfe8 {Logical, with an idea of potential ... Neg4 with pressure on f2 and e3 pawns. That's why White needs to stop it.} (15... Neg4 $2 {is way too premature - the simplest is} 16. h3 {and the knight needs to return, effectively wasting a tempo.}) 16. h3 {Taking the g4 -square under control. The position is similar as in the main line, but the rook is not particularly useful on e8 .} Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Qe5 18. Nd5 Bd6 19. Nxf6+ gxf6 20. g3 {We keep our extra pawn and have traded more pieces.} *

