1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 {Black uses this move order when he wants to avoid the Bg5 lines and navigate towards the g3 lines. Right now, the Bg5 lines are not good enough (there is no pin), while g3 is not in our repertoire. Fortunately, there is another good option.} 6. dxc5 {This line is perhaps the simplest solution to the Tarrasch.} Nf6 7. Be3 {This may look a bit awkward, but the move defends an important pawn which will become relevant later on. For now, White will fianchetto the kingside bishop.} Qa5 {Black can try to get the pawn back in this way, but it does not really work.} (7... Ng4 {is truly bad due to} 8. Bd4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 $1) 8. Nd4 {With the idea of either Nb3 , or Nxc6 followed by Qa4 , Black will be in big trouble either way.} Ne4 (8... Qxc5 {runs into} 9. Ndb5 Qe7 10. Bf4 $1) 9. Nxc6 (9. Nb3 {is fine too, but this seems to be the simplest.}) 9... bxc6 10. Qa4 {Simplifying the position and retaining the pawn.} *

