1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 {Black uses this move order when he wants to avoid the Bg5 lines and navigate towards the g3 lines. Right now, the Bg5 lines are not good enough (there is no pin), while g3 is not in our repertoire. Fortunately, there is another good option.} 6. dxc5 {This line is perhaps the simplest solution to the Tarrasch.} Nf6 7. Be3 {This may look a bit awkward, but the move defends an important pawn which will become relevant later on. For now, White will fianchetto the kingside bishop.} Be7 {Instead of recovering the pawn immediately, Black hopes to complete development and recover the c5 -pawn at a later time.} 8. g3 O-O 9. Bg2 Be6 10. O-O Ng4 {This is worse as Black does not get the pawn back anyway, despite the Be6 protecting the d5 -pawn.} 11. Bd4 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Bxc5 13. Nb3 {And White wins the pawn on d5 .} *

