1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 {Black uses this move order when he wants to avoid the Bg5 lines and navigate towards the g3 lines. Right now, the Bg5 lines are not good enough (there is no pin), while g3 is not in our repertoire. Fortunately, there is another good option.} 6. dxc5 {This line is perhaps the simplest solution to the Tarrasch.} d4 {Black pretty much must play this move - otherwise, he will be down a pawn.} ({After} 6... Bxc5 $2 7. Qxd5 {White is just a pawn up. For example:} Qb6 8. e3 Nf6 9. Qb3) 7. Na4 b5 {This is a typical resource in the Tarrasch, and one might get scared seeing it, as it looks like the Na4 can get trapped in some lines. However, there is nothing to worry about.} 8. cxb6 axb6 9. e3 {Immediately striking in the center and preventing ... b5 . There were some games here, but Black does not receive any compensation whatsoever.} Bb4+ 10. Bd2 Bd7 11. Bb5 Ra5 {The trickiest and most resilient choice.} 12. Bxb4 Nxb4 (12... Rxb5 {.}) 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7 14. b3 ({White is just winning here. The extra pawn should be enough to win. A sample continuation is dxe3 Qxd7+ Kxd7 and here} 14. O-O {!? wins, too, but stronger is Nxb6+ Kc7 Nc4 exf2+ Kxf2 Rxa2+ Rxa2} Nxa2 {Ra1 Nb4 Ra8+- .}) *

