1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 {Black uses this move order when he wants to avoid the Bg5 lines and navigate towards the g3 lines. Right now, the Bg5 lines are not good enough (there is no pin), while g3 is not in our repertoire. Fortunately, there is another good option.} 6. dxc5 {This line is perhaps the simplest solution to the Tarrasch.} d4 {Black pretty much must play this move - otherwise, he will be down a pawn.} ({After} 6... Bxc5 $2 7. Qxd5 {White is just a pawn up. For example:} Qb6 8. e3 Nf6 9. Qb3) 7. Na4 Nf6 {This is too slow:} 8. e3 {After this, Black is unable to get the pawn back.} Bxc5 9. Nxc5 Qa5+ 10. Qd2 Qxc5 11. Nxd4 {Again with an extra pawn. Sure, the conversion will perhaps take a while, but the advantage is not debatable.} *

