1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 {Black uses this move order when he wants to avoid the Bg5 lines and navigate towards the g3 lines. Right now, the Bg5 lines are not good enough (there is no pin), while g3 is not in our repertoire. Fortunately, there is another good option.} 6. dxc5 {This line is perhaps the simplest solution to the Tarrasch.} d4 {Black pretty much must play this move - otherwise, he will be down a pawn.} ({After} 6... Bxc5 $2 7. Qxd5 {White is just a pawn up. For example:} Qb6 8. e3 Nf6 9. Qb3) 7. Na4 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Qxc5 10. b4 ({A slightly less common move than} 10. Rc1 {followed by} Qb6 11. e3 {, which is relatively well-known. Many of the players that go for the Tarrasch will surely know 10.Rc1 , but 10.b4 is less explored, and there is a chance that it will cause certain practical problems.}) 10... Qb6 11. Qa4 {Here, Black needs to be very accurate in order not to become much worse. The threat is obviously b5 , so Black's next move is obvious.} a6 12. e3 dxe3 13. fxe3 {Unfortunately, White cannot recapture with the bishop, as it would have hung the b4 -pawn. But now, b5 is again a threat that Black cannot ignore.} Bd7 {This leads to a bad position for Black:} 14. b5 Nce7 15. Qa3 {Stepping away from the pin by the bishop on d7 , and pressuring the knight on e7 . The attack on the knight will make it difficult for Black to castle kingside.} Nf6 16. bxa6 bxa6 17. Bc4 Bb5 {This runs into immediate trouble.} 18. Qb3 {With a decisive double threat.} *

