1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 {Black uses this move order when he wants to avoid the Bg5 lines and navigate towards the g3 lines. Right now, the Bg5 lines are not good enough (there is no pin), while g3 is not in our repertoire. Fortunately, there is another good option.} 6. dxc5 {This line is perhaps the simplest solution to the Tarrasch.} d4 {Black pretty much must play this move - otherwise, he will be down a pawn.} ({After} 6... Bxc5 $2 7. Qxd5 {White is just a pawn up. For example:} Qb6 8. e3 Nf6 9. Qb3) 7. Na4 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Qxc5 10. b4 ({A slightly less common move than} 10. Rc1 {followed by} Qb6 11. e3 {, which is relatively well-known. Many of the players that go for the Tarrasch will surely know 10.Rc1 , but 10.b4 is less explored, and there is a chance that it will cause certain practical problems.}) 10... Qf5 {A solid response by Black. He removes the queen to safety, controls our b5 ideas (for now), and intends to complete development in standard fashion (... Nf6 , ... O-O , etc).} {White has a couple of different ways to approach this position. I feel obligated to mention that here there is another interesting idea for White: g4 is offered as an alternative.} 11. a4 {A useful move. White threatens b5 , which, of course, Black cannot allow.} (11. Rc1 $5 {with the idea of Rc5 is interesting, too - check it out yourself if you want another option here!}) 11... a6 {The inclusion of these two moves ( a4 -... a6 ) seems to favor White, at least from a practical point of view. Here, we need to complete our development.} 12. g3 {I think the fianchetto of the bishop should be the most promising. The d4 -pawn is isolated, and White will want to put pressure on it in the long term.} Nf6 13. Bg2 O-O 14. O-O {White's main idea is to play b5 at the right moment, and there are two ways of preparing it: either Qb1 or maybe Rc1 - Rc5 and then b5 . Also, sometimes Rb1 can be played too. Which one is better will depend on what Black plays.} Ne4 ({Here, White can play} 14... Qb1 {, which should transpose to the 14... Rd8 line, or use the rook.}) 15. Rb1 {This is good too.} Nc3 16. Bxc3 dxc3 17. Qc1 ({The c3 -pawn will likely fall sooner or later. Qf6} 17. b5 Nd4 18. Nxd4 {Qxd4 Rd1} Qf6 19. Rb3 {and Black has problems completing queenside development.}) *

