1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 {Black uses this move order when he wants to avoid the Bg5 lines and navigate towards the g3 lines. Right now, the Bg5 lines are not good enough (there is no pin), while g3 is not in our repertoire. Fortunately, there is another good option.} 6. dxc5 {This line is perhaps the simplest solution to the Tarrasch.} d4 {Black pretty much must play this move - otherwise, he will be down a pawn.} ({After} 6... Bxc5 $2 7. Qxd5 {White is just a pawn up. For example:} Qb6 8. e3 Nf6 9. Qb3) 7. Na4 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Qxc5 10. b4 ({A slightly less common move than} 10. Rc1 {followed by} Qb6 11. e3 {, which is relatively well-known. Many of the players that go for the Tarrasch will surely know 10.Rc1 , but 10.b4 is less explored, and there is a chance that it will cause certain practical problems.}) 10... Qf5 {A solid response by Black. He removes the queen to safety, controls our b5 ideas (for now), and intends to complete development in standard fashion (... Nf6 , ... O-O , etc).} {White has a couple of different ways to approach this position. I feel obligated to mention that here there is another interesting idea for White: g4 is offered as an alternative.} 11. a4 {A useful move. White threatens b5 , which, of course, Black cannot allow.} (11. Rc1 $5 {with the idea of Rc5 is interesting, too - check it out yourself if you want another option here!}) 11... a6 {The inclusion of these two moves ( a4 -... a6 ) seems to favor White, at least from a practical point of view. Here, we need to complete our development.} 12. g3 {I think the fianchetto of the bishop should be the most promising. The d4 -pawn is isolated, and White will want to put pressure on it in the long term.} Nf6 13. Bg2 O-O 14. O-O {White's main idea is to play b5 at the right moment, and there are two ways of preparing it: either Qb1 or maybe Rc1 - Rc5 and then b5 . Also, sometimes Rb1 can be played too. Which one is better will depend on what Black plays.} Qh5 {With the idea of ... Bh3 . This makes a lot of sense. After all, our bishop is pretty good on g2 , while Black often struggles with developing his queenside.} 15. Rc1 {Here, we can activate the rook in this fashion and prepare b5 .} Bh3 (15... Ne4 16. Qc2 Re8 17. Rfd1) 16. Rc5 Qg4 17. b5 {Once White manages to comfortably play b5 , Black's position is usually unpleasant.} axb5 18. Rxb5 {Eyeing the b7 -pawn.} Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Ra7 20. Qb3 Ne4 21. Rd1 {White enjoys a long-term edge due to Black's many weaknesses.} *

