{Bd7? meets Nb5! with 16. Qa3 or 16. Bb4 to follow, and the knight will land on d6 .} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 {Black uses this move order when he wants to avoid the Bg5 lines and navigate towards the g3 lines. Right now, the Bg5 lines are not good enough (there is no pin), while g3 is not in our repertoire. Fortunately, there is another good option.} 6. dxc5 {This line is perhaps the simplest solution to the Tarrasch.} d4 {Black pretty much must play this move - otherwise, he will be down a pawn.} ({After} 6... Bxc5 $2 7. Qxd5 {White is just a pawn up. For example:} Qb6 8. e3 Nf6 9. Qb3) 7. Na4 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Qxc5 10. b4 ({A slightly less common move than} 10. Rc1 {followed by} Qb6 11. e3 {, which is relatively well-known. Many of the players that go for the Tarrasch will surely know 10.Rc1 , but 10.b4 is less explored, and there is a chance that it will cause certain practical problems.}) 10... Nxb4 {Accepting the pawn sacrifice is probably the most critical for this line.} 11. Rc1 {Black has two options now: Qe7 or Qd6 .} Qd6 {Black tries to keep the d4 -pawn defended.} 12. e3 {A venomous move as it contains a devious trap.} Nf6 {This is not good:} 13. Qa4+ Nc6 14. Nxd4 {The pressure on the knight is definitely annoying for Black. It would have been much better for him to have played 12...Ne7 .} *

