1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 {Black uses this move order when he wants to avoid the Bg5 lines and navigate towards the g3 lines. Right now, the Bg5 lines are not good enough (there is no pin), while g3 is not in our repertoire. Fortunately, there is another good option.} 6. dxc5 {This line is perhaps the simplest solution to the Tarrasch.} d4 {Black pretty much must play this move - otherwise, he will be down a pawn.} ({After} 6... Bxc5 $2 7. Qxd5 {White is just a pawn up. For example:} Qb6 8. e3 Nf6 9. Qb3) 7. Na4 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Qxc5 10. b4 ({A slightly less common move than} 10. Rc1 {followed by} Qb6 11. e3 {, which is relatively well-known. Many of the players that go for the Tarrasch will surely know 10.Rc1 , but 10.b4 is less explored, and there is a chance that it will cause certain practical problems.}) 10... Nxb4 {Accepting the pawn sacrifice is probably the most critical for this line.} 11. Rc1 {Black has two options now: Qe7 or Qd6 .} Qd6 {Black tries to keep the d4 -pawn defended.} 12. e3 {A venomous move as it contains a devious trap.} dxe3 {It may seem that Black can just retain the extra pawn in this way. But that's not the case.} (12... d3 $6 {threatening ... Nc2 +, just loses the pawn after} 13. Qa4+ Nc6 14. Qb5) 13. Bc3 {A stunning surprise! Suddenly, Black has many things undefended, and he is in trouble!} Nd5 {Black lands on an unpleasant pin. White needs to be very precise to take advantage of it.} (13... exf2+ $2 {gives White a decisive advantage after} 14. Kxf2 {and now both} Qc5+ {and Qb6+ are countered by} 15. Bd4 {.}) 14. fxe3 (14. Bxg7 $2 Qb4+ {is annoying for White. The best is probably} 15. Nd2 {, while after Ke2} Nf4 {things get risky.}) 14... Ngf6 15. e4 Qe7 (15... Nxe4 $4 16. Qa4+ $1 {picking off the knight.}) 16. Bb5+ ({Black cannot play ...Bd7 as he would be just a piece down, Bd7 Bxd7+ Kxd7} 16. Ne5 {. The only move is} Kf8 {, but this leaves Black in an unpleasant position due to the uncastled king.}) 16... Kf8 17. O-O Nxc3 (17... Qxe4 $2 18. Re1 Qf5 19. Re5 {or Qc5+ when the simple Kh1 is enough to keep a decisive advantage.}) 18. Rxc3 {With a good compensation thanks to Black's uncastled king and lack of development.} *

