1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 {Black uses this move order when he wants to avoid the Bg5 lines and navigate towards the g3 lines. Right now, the Bg5 lines are not good enough (there is no pin), while g3 is not in our repertoire. Fortunately, there is another good option.} 6. dxc5 {This line is perhaps the simplest solution to the Tarrasch.} d4 {Black pretty much must play this move - otherwise, he will be down a pawn.} ({After} 6... Bxc5 $2 7. Qxd5 {White is just a pawn up. For example:} Qb6 8. e3 Nf6 9. Qb3) 7. Na4 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Qxc5 10. b4 ({A slightly less common move than} 10. Rc1 {followed by} Qb6 11. e3 {, which is relatively well-known. Many of the players that go for the Tarrasch will surely know 10.Rc1 , but 10.b4 is less explored, and there is a chance that it will cause certain practical problems.}) 10... Nxb4 {Accepting the pawn sacrifice is probably the most critical for this line.} 11. Rc1 {Black has two options now: Qe7 or Qd6 .} Qd6 {Black tries to keep the d4 -pawn defended.} 12. e3 {A venomous move as it contains a devious trap.} Ne7 {Black needs to ignore what White's doing and just complete his development. The knight should go to e7 , while the other knight may retreat to c6 in some lines, and this would require support.} 13. Nxd4 O-O {Here, White has some choice.} 14. Nb5 ({This is the most challenging. It forces Black to find lots of only moves just to stay in the game.} 14. Be2 {is more positional and totally acceptable as well. White enjoys the pair of bishops.}) 14... Nd3+ 15. Bxd3 Qxd3 16. Nc7 {What to do with the rook?} Rb8 {This would be a huge mistake already.} 17. Bb4 Qe4 18. Qd4 {The pin is deadly, and Black cannot hold his defense there. He can try complicating things:} Qxg2 {But with few accurate moves, White will be clearly better.} 19. Bxe7 Qxh1+ 20. Kd2 Qg2 21. Bxf8 Qxf2+ 22. Kc3 {Black is out of checks and is down material.} *

