1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 {The main move here is, of course, Be6 , but it is important to consider alternatives as well. However, they are inferior to the main line.} Be7 ({This is a worse version of} 6... cxd4 {as we will win a very useful tempo via 7. dxc5 .}) 7. dxc5 O-O {Black will have to bolster his defense of his d5 -pawn before he can even think of recovering the lost pawn on c5 .} 8. e3 Be6 ({Black could have played} 8... Be6 {first, but anyway, we would get the same position.}) 9. Bb5 {An active way to develop the bishop. It runs into a tempo loss after a potential ... a6 , but we would welcome such a turn of events! We would then gladly reposition the bishop to b3 or c2 via the a4 -square where it will stand much better than the more modest e2 -square.} Bxc5 10. O-O ({We don't want any part of} 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Nxd5 $4 Bxd5 12. Qxd5 Qxb2) 10... Be7 11. Nd4 a6 12. Ba4 Nbd7 13. Bc2 {White has a clear advantage.} *

