1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 {The main move here is, of course, Be6 , but it is important to consider alternatives as well. However, they are inferior to the main line.} c4 {This is far too premature.} 7. e4 {And White successfully breaks through in the center. Black's position collapses.} dxe4 ({Or} 7... Bb4 8. exd5 Qxd5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Be2 {followed by O-O . White has a huge advantage in development, and even if Black has ideas of ... Nc6 , ... Rg8 etc. they are all too slow. After White's castling, Black's queen will either have to move (which could drop the c4 pawn and also allow d5 ) or ... Bxc3 will have to be played (which improves White's pawn structure).  An example line could be as follows:} Rg8 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 Bh3 13. Re1 $3 {With next g3 or Bf1 . Black cannot play} Rxg2+ {due to} 14. Kh1 Kf8 15. Bf1 Rxf2 16. Bxh3 Qxf3+ 17. Qxf3 Rxf3 18. Bg2 {and White wins a whole rook.}) 8. Ne5 {White will quickly regain his pawn and possess a massive lead in development.} *

