1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 {The main move here is, of course, Be6 , but it is important to consider alternatives as well. However, they are inferior to the main line.} cxd4 {Voluntarily declaring the situation in the center is unlikely a good solution for Black. Now, White gets a comfortable position against the IQP.} 7. Nxd4 Be7 {There is probably not much difference in move orders, as Black will need to play ... Be7 , ... Nc6 and ..O-O eventually. The only potential difference that comes to mind is that Black may try ... Bb4 , but as we have already seen in previous variations, it should not be good.} 8. e3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O {We achieved a standard position with the isolated pawn. White should be comfortable here, especially since the bishop is out on g5 , which is much better than when it was on c1 ...} Be6 {In this trainable, we shall examine Black playing without ... h6 .} 11. Nxe6 {Immediately grabbing the bishop pair will be our choice against 10... h6 as well.} fxe6 12. Rc1 Rc8 {Black has not weakened his kingside with ... h6 , which could be considered as some sort of improvement over the main line... but ultimately it does not actually matter.} 13. Bd3 {The exact same idea as in the main line.} Ne5 (13... e5 $2 14. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 15. Nxd5 Qxd5 $4 16. Bxh7+ $1 {or Bc4!+-}) 14. Bb1 Qb6 15. Qe2 {With the bishop pair and a better structure.} *

