1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 {The main move here is, of course, Be6 , but it is important to consider alternatives as well. However, they are inferior to the main line.} cxd4 {Voluntarily declaring the situation in the center is unlikely a good solution for Black. Now, White gets a comfortable position against the IQP.} 7. Nxd4 Be7 {There is probably not much difference in move orders, as Black will need to play ... Be7 , ... Nc6 and ..O-O eventually. The only potential difference that comes to mind is that Black may try ... Bb4 , but as we have already seen in previous variations, it should not be good.} 8. e3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O {We achieved a standard position with the isolated pawn. White should be comfortable here, especially since the bishop is out on g5 , which is much better than when it was on c1 ...} h6 11. Bh4 {The inclusion of these moves does not change much.} Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Be6 {This was tried in a game Wojtaszek-Miton, 2018. I think that helping White get the queen out can be only good for us.} 13. Rfd1 a6 {Necessary, to free the rook from a8 .} 14. Bf3 Rc8 {Now, we should step back with the queen to avoid ... Rc4 which not only wins a tempo against our queen, but would also win the bishop on h4 .} 15. Qd2 {There are certain issues with the d5 -pawn.} g5 16. Bg3 Bb4 {Trying to resolve them, but not only does this operation weaken the kingside, but it also potentially gives away the important dark-squared bishop.} 17. h3 {This must be better for White.} *

