1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 ({An alternative approach involves playing} 6. g3 {, which is also challenging. In this course, I focus on .}) 6... Be6 {This is a recent trend in the Tarrasch Defense. Black supports the center.} 7. e3 ({I would recommend this positional approach.} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. e4 $5 {is an interesting alternative that can cause Black problems as well. Initially, I had planned on recommending this...but I encountered some obstacles, and my final conclusion was that Black should be fine with correct defense. Still - it is quite challenging, and Black needs to know his lines. At the end of the day, e3 is much simpler and has more playability. There is no way for Black to force a draw with this choice!}) 7... Nc6 {This is an option here, but in fact, it is just bad for Black. However, it has been played many times - and for this reason, it should be investigated as well.} 8. Bb5 ({The best way to put pressure on Black. Case in point: h6?} 8. Bxf6 $1 Qxf6 9. Qa4 {is completely winning for White. Now, there are many options for Black but no sight of equality anywhere.}) 8... a6 {Provoking White to take on c6 cannot be good for Black.} 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Qa4 {The problems are mounting...} Qb6 (10... Bd7 11. Ne5 {is also bad for Black.}) 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. O-O {With such horrible pawn structure, as well as the king in the center, Black is suffering.} *

