1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 ({An alternative approach involves playing} 6. g3 {, which is also challenging. In this course, I focus on .}) 6... Be6 {This is a recent trend in the Tarrasch Defense. Black supports the center.} 7. e3 ({I would recommend this positional approach.} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. e4 $5 {is an interesting alternative that can cause Black problems as well. Initially, I had planned on recommending this...but I encountered some obstacles, and my final conclusion was that Black should be fine with correct defense. Still - it is quite challenging, and Black needs to know his lines. At the end of the day, e3 is much simpler and has more playability. There is no way for Black to force a draw with this choice!}) 7... c4 ({Having supported the center, Black goes for a standard idea of gaining space on the queenside. Black wants to play ...Bb4 , which resembles the Ragozin. I would argue, though, that White has some advantage here in two ways.} 7... Nc6 $6 8. Bb5 {is good for White.}) 8. Be2 Bb4 ({Black can begin with} 8... Nbd7 9. O-O Bb4 {, move order. It avoids the e4 ideas, but it does not change much.}) 9. O-O {White has two main ideas here: 1) the e4 breakthrough, or 2)  Ne5 with some pressure in the center or an attack on the kingside with f4 , etc.} O-O ({I think we should keep it simple and play Ne5 as e4 leads to unnecessary simplifications (see next). In his course, Jorden Van Foreest recommends the} 9... Nbd7 {move order. It avoids e4 ideas, but in reality, it does not change much, as anyway} 10. Ne5 {seems to be the most promising, with a likely transposition after Black castles.}) 10. e4 Bxc3 11. bxc3 dxe4 12. Nd2 Nbd7 13. Nxe4 h6 14. Nxf6+ Nxf6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Bf3 (16. Qa4 Qg5 17. Bf3 Bd5 18. h4 Qd8 19. Bxd5 Qxd5 20. Rfe1 b5 {Black should not have any issues here.}) 16... Rab8 17. Qa4 b5 18. Qxa7 b4 {Despite our extra pawn, Black should be fine thanks to his piece activity.} *

