1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 ({An alternative approach involves playing} 6. g3 {, which is also challenging. In this course, I focus on .}) 6... Be6 {This is a recent trend in the Tarrasch Defense. Black supports the center.} 7. e3 ({I would recommend this positional approach.} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. e4 $5 {is an interesting alternative that can cause Black problems as well. Initially, I had planned on recommending this...but I encountered some obstacles, and my final conclusion was that Black should be fine with correct defense. Still - it is quite challenging, and Black needs to know his lines. At the end of the day, e3 is much simpler and has more playability. There is no way for Black to force a draw with this choice!}) 7... c4 ({Having supported the center, Black goes for a standard idea of gaining space on the queenside. Black wants to play ...Bb4 , which resembles the Ragozin. I would argue, though, that White has some advantage here in two ways.} 7... Nc6 $6 8. Bb5 {is good for White.}) 8. Be2 Bb4 ({Black can begin with} 8... Nbd7 9. O-O Bb4 {, move order. It avoids the e4 ideas, but it does not change much.}) 9. O-O {White has two main ideas here: 1) the e4 breakthrough, or 2)  Ne5 with some pressure in the center or an attack on the kingside with f4 , etc.} O-O ({I think we should keep it simple and play Ne5 as e4 leads to unnecessary simplifications (see next). In his course, Jorden Van Foreest recommends the} 9... Nbd7 {move order. It avoids e4 ideas, but in reality, it does not change much, as anyway} 10. Ne5 {seems to be the most promising, with a likely transposition after Black castles.}) 10. Ne5 ({Black needs to solve the problem of the Nb8 . Of course, they can play Nbd7 now with a transposition to the main line. h6?!} 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 {f4± with ideas of Bf3 or f5 , is just bad for Black.}) 10... Nc6 {This is not the right square for the knight. The Nf6 is not well supported now, and White can take advantage of that.} 11. Ng4 Be7 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. b3 {Undermining the queenside with some positional edge.} *

