e. It leaves a lot of room for play, where understanding of the ideas should give us the upper hand. Other options are more forcing and could fizzle out to a draw with best play.} Qa5 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. Qc2 h6 14. Bh4 Rfe8 {So far, we have been following Jorden's recommendation. Here he ends his analysis, rightfully claiming that both sides have their chances. Ideas for Black involve ... Nf8 - g6 or ... Nb6 and then around to d6 via c8 or to a4 after first inserting ... Bxc3 . All of this is correct, of course, but I would like to add a bit from White's perspective. There is pressure on the d5 -pawn, which Black needs to remember. When Black brings his knight to d6 , White may play with g4 !? to restrict the knight. Sooner or later, a3 will be on White's agenda, and a potential queen trade with Qa4 may give us a pleasant endgame. On top of that, White may also prepare a pawn breakthrough with b3 or e4 . In general, a maneuvering game will follow, and White should have the better chances.} 15. h3 {A useful waiting move, to see what Black will do with his knight. As mentioned earlier, one of the ideas for White could be g4 !? (which is mostly a prophylactic measure when Black's ... Bf5 becomes an idea). Also, we are not sure how we should place the rooks just yet, as it mostly depends on what Black does next.} Rac8 {This move is logical, of course, but now it's difficult for the knight to reach d6 (it needs the c8 -square).} 16. Rfe1 {White prepares e4 .} b5 {As we are pinned, we cannot take on d5 . But we can play...} 17. a4 {With an advantage:} Bxc3 18. bxc3 b4 19. cxb4 Qxb4 20. Reb1 Qd6 21. Bg3 Qa6 22. Rb5 {We enjoy the bishop pair, control the only open file on the board, and exert some nice pressure on Black's weak points.} *

