1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 ({An alternative approach involves playing} 6. g3 {, which is also challenging. In this course, I focus on .}) 6... Be6 {This is a recent trend in the Tarrasch Defense. Black supports the center.} 7. e3 ({I would recommend this positional approach.} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. e4 $5 {is an interesting alternative that can cause Black problems as well. Initially, I had planned on recommending this...but I encountered some obstacles, and my final conclusion was that Black should be fine with correct defense. Still - it is quite challenging, and Black needs to know his lines. At the end of the day, e3 is much simpler and has more playability. There is no way for Black to force a draw with this choice!}) 7... c4 ({Having supported the center, Black goes for a standard idea of gaining space on the queenside. Black wants to play ...Bb4 , which resembles the Ragozin. I would argue, though, that White has some advantage here in two ways.} 7... Nc6 $6 8. Bb5 {is good for White.}) 8. Be2 Bb4 ({Black can begin with} 8... Nbd7 9. O-O Bb4 {, move order. It avoids the e4 ideas, but it does not change much.}) 9. O-O {White has two main ideas here: 1) the e4 breakthrough, or 2)  Ne5 with some pressure in the center or an attack on the kingside with f4 , etc.} O-O ({I think we should keep it simple and play Ne5 as e4 leads to unnecessary simplifications (see next). In his course, Jorden Van Foreest recommends the} 9... Nbd7 {move order. It avoids e4 ideas, but in reality, it does not change much, as anyway} 10. Ne5 {seems to be the most promising, with a likely transposition after Black castles.}) 10. Ne5 ({Black needs to solve the problem of the Nb8 . Of course, they can play Nbd7 now with a transposition to the main line. h6?!} 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 {f4± with ideas of Bf3 or f5 , is just bad for Black.}) 10... Nbd7 {This move has been a trend recently. This is one of the main positions in Jorden's course.} 11. Bf3 {I like this option for White. It leaves a lot of room for play, where understanding of the ideas should give us the upper hand. Other options are more forcing and could fizzle out to a draw with best play.} Qa5 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. Qc2 h6 14. Bh4 Rfe8 {So far, we have been following Jorden's recommendation. Here he ends his analysis, rightfully claiming that both sides have their chances. Ideas for Black involve ... Nf8 - g6 or ... Nb6 and then around to d6 via c8 or to a4 after first inserting ... Bxc3 . All of this is correct, of course, but I would like to add a bit from White's perspective. There is pressure on the d5 -pawn, which Black needs to remember. When Black brings his knight to d6 , White may play with g4 !? to restrict the knight. Sooner or later, a3 will be on White's agenda, and a potential queen trade with Qa4 may give us a pleasant endgame. On top of that, White may also prepare a pawn breakthrough with b3 or e4 . In general, a maneuvering game will follow, and White should have the better chances.} 15. h3 {A useful waiting move, to see what Black will do with his knight. As mentioned earlier, one of the ideas for White could be g4 !? (which is mostly a prophylactic measure when Black's ... Bf5 becomes an idea). Also, we are not sure how we should place the rooks just yet, as it mostly depends on what Black does next.} Nb6 16. Rfb1 {Black had declared his intentions of playing on the queenside with his last move, so we keep both rooks in the area.} Nc8 ({Maneuvering the knight to d6 .} 16... g6 {with the idea of ... Bf5 is strongly met by} 17. g4 $1) 17. Ne2 Nb6 (17... Bf8 18. Nf4) (17... Bd6 18. b3 $1) 18. a3 Bd6 19. Bg3 {The trade of dark-squared bishops is something we should generally welcome. White will later want to play b3 at some point.} *

