ize on it.} 11. f4 ({Passing on the opportunity of Bxf6 for now and going for the direct attack on the kingside! I find it the most challenging from a human point of view, but in case you are not in the mood for such sharp play,} 11. Bxf6 {is calmer, and I cover it as an alternative as well.}) 11... Bxc3 {Sooner or later, Black needs to eliminate the Nc3 before occupying the e4 -square.} 12. f5 {But we are not recapturing the bishop! Black has the first of many chances to go wrong.} Bd7 {Inaccurate.} 13. bxc3 Ne4 (13... Qxc3 $2 {This is a wrong option because it allows White to take f6 (at the right time) and destroy the king's defense.} 14. Rc1 $1 Qa3 15. Bxf6 $1 Qxe3+ ({Or} 15... gxf6 16. Ng4 Qd6 17. Qe1 {is overwhelming.}) 16. Kh1 gxf6 17. Bg4 Qg5 18. Rc3 $1 {With Rg3 following and a crushing attack.}) 14. Be7 Ba4 {The only way to justify ... Bd7 .} 15. Qb1 {Again the b7 -pawn is loose, as well as the Rf8 .} Rc8 {Probably the best defense, but it is still insufficient.} 16. Bh5 {A useful intermezzo before we capture on b7 , sidestepping potential ... Nxc3 tempo hits on our bishop. With a few precise moves, White will be left in a pawn up endgame.} Be8 17. Qxb7 Nc6 18. Bb4 {Black is forced to play ... Qc7 as there is a double attack on the queen and the f7 -pawn.} Qc7 19. Qxc7 Rxc7 20. Nxc6 Bxc6 21. Bf3 {White is better here, even though Black's position is quite solid. It might not be so easy to break through, but still - a pawn is a pawn!} *

