ize on it.} 11. f4 ({Passing on the opportunity of Bxf6 for now and going for the direct attack on the kingside! I find it the most challenging from a human point of view, but in case you are not in the mood for such sharp play,} 11. Bxf6 {is calmer, and I cover it as an alternative as well.}) 11... Bxc3 {Sooner or later, Black needs to eliminate the Nc3 before occupying the e4 -square.} 12. f5 {But we are not recapturing the bishop! Black has the first of many chances to go wrong.} Bc8 {The best square for the bishop, guarding the b7 -pawn ahead of time and avoiding the dangerous knight on e5 . Potentially the Nb8 can come out to d7 as well, but we will see in a moment that Black has to be very careful about when to do this.} 13. bxc3 {We should take the time to recapture, as Bxf6 was likely too risky. Black is at a crossroads.} Ne4 {The most logical move, of course - but Black enters enormous complications that require lots of precise calculation.} 14. Be7 {Of course, we need to continue playing dynamically. Yet again, Black is at a crossroads!} Re8 {This is more human, and it would be the move I would expect the majority of people to play here.} 15. Bb4 Qc7 16. Bf3 ({Dealing with the strong Ne4 .} 16. f6 $2 {Black's lack of development proves to be too much. Bxe4 dxe4 Qh5} Rd8 17. Ng6) *

