ize on it.} 11. f4 ({Passing on the opportunity of Bxf6 for now and going for the direct attack on the kingside! I find it the most challenging from a human point of view, but in case you are not in the mood for such sharp play,} 11. Bxf6 {is calmer, and I cover it as an alternative as well.}) 11... Bxc3 {Sooner or later, Black needs to eliminate the Nc3 before occupying the e4 -square.} 12. f5 {But we are not recapturing the bishop! Black has the first of many chances to go wrong.} Bc8 {The best square for the bishop, guarding the b7 -pawn ahead of time and avoiding the dangerous knight on e5 . Potentially the Nb8 can come out to d7 as well, but we will see in a moment that Black has to be very careful about when to do this.} 13. bxc3 {We should take the time to recapture, as Bxf6 was likely too risky. Black is at a crossroads.} Ne4 {The most logical move, of course - but Black enters enormous complications that require lots of precise calculation.} 14. Be7 {Of course, we need to continue playing dynamically. Yet again, Black is at a crossroads!} Re8 {This is more human, and it would be the move I would expect the majority of people to play here.} 15. Bb4 Qc7 16. Bf3 {Dealing with the strong Ne4 .} Nf6 (16... Bxf5 $4 17. Bxe4 $1 Bxe4 18. Rxf7) 17. e4 ({Objectively the strongest move, but I must admit that} 17. g4 {looks interesting and deserves attention, too.}) 17... Nc6 (17... a5 18. Ba3 {does not change much, but it improves our bishop a bit, as there could be ideas of bringing the bishop to the attack via c1 .}) ({Bh5 didn't work, due to} 17... Rxe5 $1 18. dxe5 Qxe5 {attacking both White's weak pawns. But if Black plays dxe4 , now} 19. Bh5 $1 {is perfectly playable, e.g. Rxe5 dxe5 Qxe5 Qd8++-}) 18. Nxc6 dxe4 ({The only move - otherwise, the white pawns advance decisively with} 18... bxc6 $2 19. e5 $1) 19. Ne7+ ({The engine prefers this. White wins the exchange.} 19. Ne5 $5 {is also very challenging:} exf3 20. Qxf3 {and White's potential on the kingside is not to be underestimated. Rae1 and g4 - g5 are coming.}) 19... Rxe7 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 21. Be2 b5 {The best defense. I admit that Black has good compensation for the exchange, and White does not have any attack anymore. But we still retain better chances:} 22. a4 Bd7 23. Qb1 ({Immediately challenging the queenside pawns.} 23. d5 Qc5+ 24. Qd4 Qxd4+ 25. cxd4 a6 26. axb5 Bxb5 27. Rfc1 Rc8 28. d6 Kf8 29. Ra2 Rc6 {is less testing.}) 23... bxa4 24. Bd1 e3 25. Re1 Re8 26. Bxa4 Bxa4 27. Rxa4 {With perfect play, Black can likely equalize eventually. There is some degree of risk for White as well, as the e3 -pawn is pretty strong, and our king is a bit weak, but it requires incredibly precise play for Black to prove his compensation. I think White has good chances.} *

