1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 ({An alternative approach involves playing} 6. g3 {, which is also challenging. In this course, I focus on .}) 6... Be6 {This is a recent trend in the Tarrasch Defense. Black supports the center.} 7. e3 ({I would recommend this positional approach.} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. e4 $5 {is an interesting alternative that can cause Black problems as well. Initially, I had planned on recommending this...but I encountered some obstacles, and my final conclusion was that Black should be fine with correct defense. Still - it is quite challenging, and Black needs to know his lines. At the end of the day, e3 is much simpler and has more playability. There is no way for Black to force a draw with this choice!}) 7... c4 ({Having supported the center, Black goes for a standard idea of gaining space on the queenside. Black wants to play ...Bb4 , which resembles the Ragozin. I would argue, though, that White has some advantage here in two ways.} 7... Nc6 $6 8. Bb5 {is good for White.}) 8. Be2 Bb4 ({Black can begin with} 8... Nbd7 9. O-O Bb4 {, move order. It avoids the e4 ideas, but it does not change much.}) 9. O-O {White has two main ideas here: 1) the e4 breakthrough, or 2)  Ne5 with some pressure in the center or an attack on the kingside with f4 , etc.} O-O ({I think we should keep it simple and play Ne5 as e4 leads to unnecessary simplifications (see next). In his course, Jorden Van Foreest recommends the} 9... Nbd7 {move order. It avoids e4 ideas, but in reality, it does not change much, as anyway} 10. Ne5 {seems to be the most promising, with a likely transposition after Black castles.}) 10. Ne5 ({Black needs to solve the problem of the Nb8 . Of course, they can play Nbd7 now with a transposition to the main line. h6?!} 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 {f4± with ideas of Bf3 or f5 , is just bad for Black.}) 10... Qa5 {The most popular 10th move. It allows Bxf6 , which may seem like a good thing for White, but actually White has no way to capitalize on it.} 11. f4 ({Passing on the opportunity of Bxf6 for now and going for the direct attack on the kingside! I find it the most challenging from a human point of view, but in case you are not in the mood for such sharp play,} 11. Bxf6 {is calmer, and I cover it as an alternative as well.}) 11... Bxc3 {Sooner or later, Black needs to eliminate the Nc3 before occupying the e4 -square.} 12. f5 {But we are not recapturing the bishop! Black has the first of many chances to go wrong.} Bc8 {The best square for the bishop, guarding the b7 -pawn ahead of time and avoiding the dangerous knight on e5 . Potentially the Nb8 can come out to d7 as well, but we will see in a moment that Black has to be very careful about when to do this.} 13. bxc3 {We should take the time to recapture, as Bxf6 was likely too risky. Black is at a crossroads.} Ne4 {The most logical move, of course - but Black enters enormous complications that require lots of precise calculation.} 14. Be7 {Of course, we need to continue playing dynamically. Yet again, Black is at a crossroads!} Qxc3 {An incredibly risky capture that Black has to try. But without prior preparation, it is not easy to enter the complications.} 15. Bxf8 Qxe3+ 16. Kh1 Kxf8 {The next move by White is very easy to miss from afar.} 17. Bxc4 {A wonderful move that maintains the pressure.} Nf2+ {Forced.} 18. Rxf2 Qxf2 ({This position arises by force after nearly perfect play from both sides. Of course, it is not guaranteed that it will happen as} 18... Qc3 {could be too difficult to decide upon over the board, as the potential consequences are impossible to calculate, while Re8 is a more human alternative, after which Black struggles badly to stay alive. But even if this long line after Qxc3 occurs, White can still put a lot of practical pressure on Black. He'll be forced to find a bunch of only-moves just to keep the balance - which is a daunting task for anyone.}) 19. Qh5 ({Probably the most challenging.} 19. Bxd5 {is not as good here as in the line with 12... Bd7 , as now Black can play} Nc6 {and the bishop does not hang like in the other line!}) 19... Qxf5 20. Qh4 Qf6 {Black can try to escape to the endgame.} 21. Qxh7 Qh6 (21... dxc4 22. Qh8+ Ke7 23. Qxc8) 22. Qxh6 gxh6 23. Bxd5 {But White has great chances to win in this endgame.} *

