ize on it.} 11. f4 ({Passing on the opportunity of Bxf6 for now and going for the direct attack on the kingside! I find it the most challenging from a human point of view, but in case you are not in the mood for such sharp play,} 11. Bxf6 {is calmer, and I cover it as an alternative as well.}) 11... Bxc3 {Sooner or later, Black needs to eliminate the Nc3 before occupying the e4 -square.} 12. f5 {But we are not recapturing the bishop! Black has the first of many chances to go wrong.} Bc8 {The best square for the bishop, guarding the b7 -pawn ahead of time and avoiding the dangerous knight on e5 . Potentially the Nb8 can come out to d7 as well, but we will see in a moment that Black has to be very careful about when to do this.} 13. bxc3 {We should take the time to recapture, as Bxf6 was likely too risky. Black is at a crossroads.} Ne4 {The most logical move, of course - but Black enters enormous complications that require lots of precise calculation.} 14. Be7 {Of course, we need to continue playing dynamically. Yet again, Black is at a crossroads!} Qxc3 {An incredibly risky capture that Black has to try. But without prior preparation, it is not easy to enter the complications.} 15. Bxf8 Qxe3+ 16. Kh1 Kxf8 {The next move by White is very easy to miss from afar.} 17. Bxc4 {A wonderful move that maintains the pressure.} Nf2+ {Forced.} 18. Rxf2 Qxf2 ({This position arises by force after nearly perfect play from both sides. Of course, it is not guaranteed that it will happen as} 18... Qc3 {could be too difficult to decide upon over the board, as the potential consequences are impossible to calculate, while Re8 is a more human alternative, after which Black struggles badly to stay alive. But even if this long line after Qxc3 occurs, White can still put a lot of practical pressure on Black. He'll be forced to find a bunch of only-moves just to keep the balance - which is a daunting task for anyone.}) 19. Qh5 ({Probably the most challenging.} 19. Bxd5 {is not as good here as in the line with 12... Bd7 , as now Black can play} Nc6 {and the bishop does not hang like in the other line!}) 19... Qxf5 20. Qh4 Nc6 {The only move again!} 21. Nxc6 ({The best try. It may be tempting to play} 21. Rf1 {, but Black gives away the queen and should be able to hold it by building a fortress:} dxc4 22. Rxf5 Bxf5 23. Qh5 $1 Nxe5 24. Qxf5 Nc6 25. Qc5+ Ne7 26. Qxc4 Rc8 27. Qf1 Rd8 {I don't think Black can lose this.}) 21... Qf6 {Another stunning move.} 22. Qxh7 ({Trying to keep the queens on the board.} 22. Qxf6 gxf6 23. Bxd5 bxc6 24. Bxc6 Rb8 25. Re1 {is balanced.}) 22... Qh6 23. Qxh6 gxh6 24. Bxd5 bxc6 25. Bxc6 Rb8 26. Re1 {This is a difficult endgame for Black.} *

