ize on it.} 11. Bxf6 {The most logical move, and the one I played when facing this variation.} gxf6 12. Ng4 Nd7 ({Here, White has some choice.} 12... Kg7 $6 13. e4 $1 {And with all the black pieces away from castle, White's attack develops quickly.}) 13. e4 ({A rare move, but natural.} 13. Qc2 {is mostly played here.} Kg7 $1 {covering all the weak squares. After a complicated game, I lost to Raja Harshit. Generally, Black should be fine here.  A)} 14. h3 $6 {was my choice, and after a few natural moves, I was already much worse.} f5 15. Nh2 Nf6 16. a3 Bd6 17. Nf3 Ne4 {was Swiercz-Raja, 2020.}) ({B)} 13. e4 {is possible now as well with unclear game:} Bxc3 ({(} 13... dxe4 14. Ne3 {is the same as ...Bxc3 must be played anyway.)}) 14. bxc3 dxe4 15. Ne3 f5 16. Bxc4 {White has gotten his pawn back.} Rac8 17. d5 Ne5 18. Be2 Bd7 19. c4 {This position is simply unclear.}) ({C)  14.} 13. f3 $5 {is a bit better, but it does not necessarily give anything, either.} f5 14. Nf2 Nf6 15. a3 Be7 16. Kh1 {with ideas of e4 or g4 in the future. Also, Nh3 - Nf4 can be played as well. The position is highly complex.}) 13... Bxc3 14. bxc3 dxe4 (14... Qxc3 15. exd5 Bxd5 16. Rc1 {Black is close to defeat.}) 15. Qd2 ({Bringing the queen to the kingside in the near future.} 15. Ne3 Nb6 16. Bg4 {was played in Brunello-Ganguly, 2022, but after} Kh8 {, Black is just fine.}) 15... f5 16. Qg5+ Kh8 17. Ne3 Rg8 18. Qf4 {White has established a strong blockade on the dark squares, and ideas of d5 (which even wins a piece should Black capture on c3 ) and f3 , the last of which would undermine Black's pawns and activate our pieces further. Our play should be easier.} *

