1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} c6 6. Qc2 Nf6 {This could be played here too, but we get here some standard Carlsbad with ... a6 . It is unclear yet whether that move is useful.} 7. Bg5 ({This is also absolutely OK. In fact, I played it myself.} 7. Bf4 {is also absolutely playable.} Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. e3 O-O 10. Bd3 {with a standard Carlsbad position.}) 7... Be6 (7... h6 $4 {loses to} 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Nxd5 $1 cxd5 10. Qxc8+ {and that this is why Black must start with 7... Be6 .}) 8. e3 h6 (8... Nbd7 9. Bd3 Bd6 {would very likely transpose to the main line, e.g.} 10. Bf4 Qc7 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O O-O 13. h3 {with a transposition to the main line.}) 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Bd3 Nd7 11. O-O Bb4 {This was more accurate, intending to simplify the position.} 12. Qb3 Bxc3 13. bxc3 Rb8 14. c4 {However, White still retains some edge.} *

