1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} c6 6. Qc2 Nf6 {This could be played here too, but we get here some standard Carlsbad with ... a6 . It is unclear yet whether that move is useful.} 7. Bg5 ({This is also absolutely OK. In fact, I played it myself.} 7. Bf4 {is also absolutely playable.} Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. e3 O-O 10. Bd3 {with a standard Carlsbad position.}) 7... Be6 (7... h6 $4 {loses to} 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Nxd5 $1 cxd5 10. Qxc8+ {and that this is why Black must start with 7... Be6 .}) 8. e3 h6 (8... Nbd7 9. Bd3 Bd6 {would very likely transpose to the main line, e.g.} 10. Bf4 Qc7 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O O-O 13. h3 {with a transposition to the main line.}) 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Bd3 Nd7 11. O-O Bd6 (11... Be7 {does not look natural to me.} 12. Rae1 $5 O-O 13. e4 {is the right path for White:} dxe4 14. Nxe4 Qf4 15. Ng3 $5 {with ideas of Re3 - Rfe1 , Nh5 , maybe Bf5 . Black is under pressure.}) 12. e4 {Suddenly, Black is in serious trouble.} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Qe7 14. Rfe1 O-O 15. Bc4 {With very unpleasant pressure on the e -file.} Rfe8 ({The move played in the game.} 15... Bxc4 $2 16. Neg5 {is winning on the spot for White.}) 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. Qb3 Nf8 18. Re3 {With a big advantage for White, which, unfortunately, I did not convert in Swiercz-Vazquez, 2022.} *

