1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} c6 6. Qc2 Bd6 {Here, White has two good options: e4 and Bg5 . The first one is more complex and dynamic; the other is more positional. I decided to recommend both, but I keep one as an alternative to keep things clean and organized.} 7. e4 {Rare, but very challenging.} dxe4 8. Nxe4 Bb4+ 9. Nc3 {This would be my main recommendation here. This leads to an interesting position with the IQP, where White will seek dynamic play.} Nf6 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O {Generally, due to the pawn on a6 being rather useless, White should be able to develop some initiative.} Bg4 ({By far the best move.} 11... h6 $6 {is risky for Black. Apart from} 12. h3 {, which would just transpose, there are additional options: a3} Bd6 13. Bc4 $1 {with both bishops aiming at Black's castle.}) (11... Nbd7 $6 12. Bg5 {gives White a very good attacking position.} Be7 13. Rae1 h6 14. Bh4 Re8 15. Qe2 {is a sample line.}) 12. Ng5 {White needs to play this move to retain the initiative.} h6 13. h3 {The bishop needs to go back as ... hxg5 is way too risky.} hxg5 14. hxg4 Nxg4 (14... Qxd4 15. Bxg5 Nbd7 16. Bf5 $1 {gives White a huge advantage.}) 15. Qe2 Nh6 (15... Qxd4 $4 16. Rd1 $3 {and Black must soon sacrifice a piece for some pawns, as Bh7 + and/or Bc4 will separate the black queen from the knight on g4 .}) 16. Ne4 ({Targeting the g5 -pawn. A sample line is Qxd4} 16. Bxg5 {and Black’s position is on the brink of collapsing.}) ({Another continuation that can occur is Be7 where} 16. f4 $1 {is extremely strong, e.g.} gxf4 17. Bxf4 Qxd4+ 18. Be3 {and 20. Bxh6 next, with huge attack.}) *

