1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} c6 6. Qc2 Bd6 {Here, White has two good options: e4 and Bg5 . The first one is more complex and dynamic; the other is more positional. I decided to recommend both, but I keep one as an alternative to keep things clean and organized.} 7. e4 {Rare, but very challenging.} dxe4 8. Nxe4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 ({If you are interested, I would encourage you to study the following line as well. I intentionally did not elaborate on this too much as I find it a bit too complex, while after} 9. Nc3 {, we get the easier game.}) 9... Bxd2+ 10. Kxd2 {Thanks to a huge lead in development, this move works just fine. And the idea is Re1 !} Ne7 11. Re1 {Black never manages to get away with ... Qa5 + and ... Qxa2 , either here or in the next few moves.} Bf5 12. Bd3 ({The best move, but the alternatives} 12. Kc1 {or g4!? also deserve attention.}) 12... Bxe4 (12... O-O $2 13. Neg5 $1 {gives White a strong attack.} Bxd3 14. Qxd3 g6 15. h4) 13. Rxe4 O-O {The question is whether White has sufficient initiative here. According to the engine, White is a bit better, but the position is complicated. For example:} 14. Re2 h6 15. a3 {Deep prophylaxis - preventing potential ... Nb4 ideas.} Nd5 16. g3 {Controlling fully the Nd5 .} Nd7 17. Kc1 ({White is a bit better, most likely, but the position requires deeper analysis. Hence, this line is only an alternative due to its complexity. c5 Kb1 cxd4} 17. Qc4 N5b6 {Qxd4 Nc5} 18. Bc2 {Qxd4 Nxd4⩲ is a sample continuation.}) *

