1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} c6 6. Qc2 Bd6 {Here, White has two good options: e4 and Bg5 . The first one is more complex and dynamic; the other is more positional. I decided to recommend both, but I keep one as an alternative to keep things clean and organized.} 7. Bg5 {If you want to keep things more positional, this is the way to go.} Ne7 8. e3 f6 {A necessary move to play ... Bf5 .} 9. Bh4 Bf5 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 {Black managed to solve the issue of the light-squared bishop - but at the cost of the f6 -pawn being not ideal, as well as the Ne7 being a bit awkward.} Nd7 12. O-O O-O {Here, White has many good moves, but the main idea is to play via e4 as the f6 -pawn significantly weakens the kingside and the a2 - g8 diagonal.} 13. e4 ({We can play this move right away, or we can delay it and first play} 13. Bg3 Nb6 14. Rfe1 {where White has not yet declared whether e4 will be played, but with Rfe1 on the board, it definitely must be considered. There are also ideas of Nd2 - Nb3 .}) 13... Bb4 {This is actually quite OK for Black according to the engine, but I would expect most people to take on e4 and get the d5 -outpost.} 14. exd5 (14. Bg3 $5 {is playable too.}) 14... cxd5 15. Nd1 {Black is still under some pressure.} *

