1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} h6 {This is similar to the 3...h6 line. The idea is to prevent Bg5 and in case White plays Bf4 , then ... Bd6 will instantly offer a trade of bishops.} 6. Bf4 Nf6 7. e3 c5 {This is suspicious. It results in some Tarrasch Variation but with ... h6 , which I don't find useful.} 8. Be2 {We simply complete our development. Here, Black can play with or without ... c4 .} Nc6 (8... c4 9. Ne5 $1 {freeing the f3 -square for the bishop is better for White as well. We'll castle next.}) 9. O-O Be6 10. Ne5 Rc8 11. Nxc6 Rxc6 12. Be5 {White will take on c5 at some point and then get a comfortable position against the IQP.} *

