1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} h6 {This is similar to the 3...h6 line. The idea is to prevent Bg5 and in case White plays Bf4 , then ... Bd6 will instantly offer a trade of bishops.} 6. Bf4 Nf6 7. e3 Bd6 8. Be5 {Not the most common move, but I like it a lot. Black cannot easily trade the bishops, as then dxe5 would win a pawn in some situations, and in others Nxe5 would activate the knight.} c6 9. Bd3 Bg4 {This makes little sense here. Normally, this move is played to solve the problem of the bishop with ... Bh5 and ... Bg6 , but now, with the pawn on h6 , this would only weaken the pawn structure.} 10. h3 Bxf3 (10... Bh5 $2 11. g4 Bg6 12. Bxg6 fxg6 13. Nh4 Kf7 14. Qc2) 11. gxf3 ({With f4 next and White is much better. Bxe5 dxe5 Nfd7 f4 Qe7} 11. Qc2 {Nc5 O-O-O± is a sample continuation.}) *

