1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} h6 {This is similar to the 3...h6 line. The idea is to prevent Bg5 and in case White plays Bf4 , then ... Bd6 will instantly offer a trade of bishops.} 6. Bf4 Nf6 7. e3 Bd6 8. Be5 {Not the most common move, but I like it a lot. Black cannot easily trade the bishops, as then dxe5 would win a pawn in some situations, and in others Nxe5 would activate the knight.} c6 9. Bd3 Qe7 {The idea of this move is to play ... Nbd7 and deal with the strong Be5 . But it also wastes a tempo when White takes on d6 . Also, Black would have to play ... Nbd7 , and then Bc8 does not have an immediate way out.} (9... Bxe5 $2 10. dxe5 {is just bad for Black.}) 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Qc2 O-O {This is similar to the 9...O-O line, and normally White should go for the minority attack.} 13. Rab1 {The easiest is to go for the minority pawn attack and/or exploit weak squares on the queenside.} Qe7 14. h3 {A generally useful move.} Re8 15. Nd2 {Preventing ... Ne4 .} Nf8 16. b4 Ne6 17. Nf3 {The knight goes back to f3 , as the e5 -square has become available.} *

