1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} h6 {This is similar to the 3...h6 line. The idea is to prevent Bg5 and in case White plays Bf4 , then ... Bd6 will instantly offer a trade of bishops.} 6. Bf4 Nf6 7. e3 Bd6 8. Be5 {Not the most common move, but I like it a lot. Black cannot easily trade the bishops, as then dxe5 would win a pawn in some situations, and in others Nxe5 would activate the knight.} c6 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O Re8 (10... Bg4 $2 {is bad again:} 11. h3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 $1 {Same idea, to push f4 , as earlier!}) 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. h3 {Preventing ... Bg4 or ... Ng4 ideas in any case.} Be6 {This is possible too, leading to standard Carlsbad play.} 13. Qc2 Nbd7 14. Rac1 {In some positions, Black goes for the Be6 - Nbd7 setup; in others, it's Bc8 - Ne6 . There are other options as well. We should focus on general ideas rather than exact lines. The subtleties of move order are not so relevant. The engine will give everything within a range of 0.20-0.30 or so, and in the end it will not matter so much in which order we play Rac1 , Rab1 , and a3 , as the general idea of how we should play.} Rac8 15. Rfe1 {White's general plan is to slowly prepare some queenside play.} *

