1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} h6 {This is similar to the 3...h6 line. The idea is to prevent Bg5 and in case White plays Bf4 , then ... Bd6 will instantly offer a trade of bishops.} 6. Bf4 Nf6 7. e3 Bd6 8. Be5 {Not the most common move, but I like it a lot. Black cannot easily trade the bishops, as then dxe5 would win a pawn in some situations, and in others Nxe5 would activate the knight.} c6 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O Re8 (10... Bg4 $2 {is bad again:} 11. h3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 $1 {Same idea, to push f4 , as earlier!}) 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. h3 {Preventing ... Bg4 or ... Ng4 ideas in any case.} Nbd7 13. Qc2 Nf8 14. a3 {White slowly begins the minority attack or simply plays on the dark squares on the queenside. In general, the exact move order won't be too relevant as long as we have a clear idea of how we should play.} Ne6 15. b4 Ng5 16. Ne5 {Of course, we should not simplify the position, especially when playing Ne5 is an option. White is slightly better.} *

