1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} Nf6 ({This position can arise also from d4} 5... Nf6 {c4 e6 Nf3 d5 Nc3 a6 cxd5 exd5 , which is the standard way of reaching this position. However, in our repertoire, we do not necessarily allow any other move orders - Nc3 is my recommendation for this course. And if d5 , then cxd5 , not Nf3 . Apart from 5...Nf6 , Black can also try to play either 5...c6 or 5...h6 , as we have seen.}) 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e3 ({White should go for the most classical approach. Recently, there was some development after} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 {targeting the b7 -pawn. Black is fine here, however, after} Ra7 $1 {. For this reason, I would recommend playing 7.e3 .}) 7... Nbd7 8. Bd3 h6 9. Bf4 {Normally, I would recommend retreating to f4 in many of these positions. Especially now - when Black has not played ... Bd6 , it makes even more sense.} {If Black plays g5 (the most critical move), it is, in fact, the same as 9.Bh4 , but other moves here are worse for Black.} Be7 10. h3 {There are no ... Nh5 ideas anymore!} c5 ({Black can also begin with} 10... O-O 11. O-O {but without ... Bd6 , he should play ... c5 sooner or later - so I would expect a transposition to occur.}) 11. dxc5 Nxc5 12. O-O O-O 13. Nd4 ({White enjoys a nice positional advantage due to Black's IQP.} 13. Bc2 $5 {can be played as well.}) 13... Qb6 14. Rb1 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 Rac8 16. Rfd1 {With a comfortable position for White.} *

