1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} Nf6 ({This position can arise also from d4} 5... Nf6 {c4 e6 Nf3 d5 Nc3 a6 cxd5 exd5 , which is the standard way of reaching this position. However, in our repertoire, we do not necessarily allow any other move orders - Nc3 is my recommendation for this course. And if d5 , then cxd5 , not Nf3 . Apart from 5...Nf6 , Black can also try to play either 5...c6 or 5...h6 , as we have seen.}) 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e3 ({White should go for the most classical approach. Recently, there was some development after} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 {targeting the b7 -pawn. Black is fine here, however, after} Ra7 $1 {. For this reason, I would recommend playing 7.e3 .}) 7... Nbd7 8. Bd3 h6 9. Bf4 {Normally, I would recommend retreating to f4 in many of these positions. Especially now - when Black has not played ... Bd6 , it makes even more sense.} {If Black plays g5 (the most critical move), it is, in fact, the same as 9.Bh4 , but other moves here are worse for Black.} g5 10. Bg3 Nh5 {Black goes after the pair of bishops. White has many options here.} 11. Qb3 ({Pressuring the b7 -pawn, which is not so easy for Black to handle. It is quite similar to} 11. Qc2 {but a bit better, in my opinion. Additionally, White keeps the option of castling on either side.}) 11... Nxg3 {Black will need to trade on g3 sooner or later, but the issue with the b7 -pawn will remain.} 12. hxg3 Nb6 {This move is logical - but the Nb6 is far from being optimally placed. Normally, it should be kept on d7 to control the e5 -square and support a potential ... c5 . Another success of 11.Qb3 !} 13. O-O h5 {A reasonable option, but without developed pieces it should not be so scary.} 14. a4 {A good answer, since ... g4 is met with Ne5 , and a5 is a great threat.} g4 (14... a5 15. Rae1 {followed by Ne5 and f4 looks strong.}) 15. Ne5 a5 16. e4 {White's best option.} dxe4 17. d5 Bxd5 (17... Bd7 18. Nxe4 {is clearly better for White.}) (17... Nxd5 18. Bb5+ c6 19. Nxc6 bxc6 20. Bxc6+ {and White is winning.}) 18. Qb5+ (18. Bc4 $5 {is equally strong.}) 18... c6 19. Nxd5 {A brilliant resource that comes out of the blue. Black is under heavy attack.} Qxd5 (19... Nxd5 20. Qxb7) 20. Qxb6 Qxe5 21. Qxb7 Rd8 22. Qxc6+ Ke7 23. Rae1 ({And after Rh6} 23. Qc2 {White ends up at least with an extra pawn.}) *

