1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} Nf6 ({This position can arise also from d4} 5... Nf6 {c4 e6 Nf3 d5 Nc3 a6 cxd5 exd5 , which is the standard way of reaching this position. However, in our repertoire, we do not necessarily allow any other move orders - Nc3 is my recommendation for this course. And if d5 , then cxd5 , not Nf3 . Apart from 5...Nf6 , Black can also try to play either 5...c6 or 5...h6 , as we have seen.}) 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e3 ({White should go for the most classical approach. Recently, there was some development after} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 {targeting the b7 -pawn. Black is fine here, however, after} Ra7 $1 {. For this reason, I would recommend playing 7.e3 .}) 7... Nbd7 8. Bd3 h6 9. Bf4 {Normally, I would recommend retreating to f4 in many of these positions. Especially now - when Black has not played ... Bd6 , it makes even more sense.} {If Black plays g5 (the most critical move), it is, in fact, the same as 9.Bh4 , but other moves here are worse for Black.} g5 10. Bg3 Nh5 {Black goes after the pair of bishops. White has many options here.} 11. Qb3 ({Pressuring the b7 -pawn, which is not so easy for Black to handle. It is quite similar to} 11. Qc2 {but a bit better, in my opinion. Additionally, White keeps the option of castling on either side.}) 11... Nxg3 {Black will need to trade on g3 sooner or later, but the issue with the b7 -pawn will remain.} 12. hxg3 Nb6 {This move is logical - but the Nb6 is far from being optimally placed. Normally, it should be kept on d7 to control the e5 -square and support a potential ... c5 . Another success of 11.Qb3 !} 13. O-O Bg7 14. Rae1 {White prepares a potential e4 -break, but he keeps the other rook on f1 for potential ideas of f4 if Black should castle kingside.} Qe7 15. a4 {This is quite annoying for Black. The threat is a5 , and again - there are issues with the knight on b6 .} a5 {Black needs to play this, but there's a problem.} 16. Bb5+ {Unpleasantly, Black must move his king to avoid material loss. Black's position is clearly worse.} Kd8 (16... Kf8 17. Bd3 {followed by Qc2 and e4 .}) ({Or} 16... c6 17. Bxc6+ bxc6 18. Qxb6) 17. e4 Qb4 (17... dxe4 18. d5 Bf5 {followed by} 19. d6 {with complications favorable to White.}) 18. Qc2 ({And Black is under pressure due to his king in the center. c6} 18. exd5 Nxd5 19. Bd3 {is a sample continuation.}) *

