1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} Nf6 ({This position can arise also from d4} 5... Nf6 {c4 e6 Nf3 d5 Nc3 a6 cxd5 exd5 , which is the standard way of reaching this position. However, in our repertoire, we do not necessarily allow any other move orders - Nc3 is my recommendation for this course. And if d5 , then cxd5 , not Nf3 . Apart from 5...Nf6 , Black can also try to play either 5...c6 or 5...h6 , as we have seen.}) 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e3 ({White should go for the most classical approach. Recently, there was some development after} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 {targeting the b7 -pawn. Black is fine here, however, after} Ra7 $1 {. For this reason, I would recommend playing 7.e3 .}) 7... Nbd7 8. Bd3 h6 9. Bf4 {Normally, I would recommend retreating to f4 in many of these positions. Especially now - when Black has not played ... Bd6 , it makes even more sense.} {If Black plays g5 (the most critical move), it is, in fact, the same as 9.Bh4 , but other moves here are worse for Black.} g5 10. Bg3 Nh5 {Black goes after the pair of bishops. White has many options here.} 11. Qb3 ({Pressuring the b7 -pawn, which is not so easy for Black to handle. It is quite similar to} 11. Qc2 {but a bit better, in my opinion. Additionally, White keeps the option of castling on either side.}) 11... Nxg3 {Black will need to trade on g3 sooner or later, but the issue with the b7 -pawn will remain.} 12. hxg3 c5 {This aggressive pawn sacrifice is quite interesting from a practical point of view, but White can pretty much refute it with correct play.} 13. Qxb7 c4 14. Bb1 ({Important move. The more natural} 14. Bc2 $6 {would have run into an unnecessary tempo-loss after ... Rb8 and ... Rxb2 .}) 14... Rb8 (14... Bg7 15. O-O O-O {This developmental approach by Black makes sense, but we cannot forget that White is up a pawn.} 16. Qb4 Rb8 17. Qa3 Qb6 18. b3 $1 {and after} cxb3 19. axb3 Qxb3 20. Bd3 {the a-pawn falls, and d5 will be weak.}) 15. Qxa6 Rxb2 {Now the bishop is not hanging!} 16. O-O ({I don't see sufficient compensation for Black. White will play e4 very soon.} 16. Qb6 Qc8 17. Qd8+ Qxd8 {Kxd8} 18. e4 {is a sample continuation.}) *

