1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} Nf6 ({This position can arise also from d4} 5... Nf6 {c4 e6 Nf3 d5 Nc3 a6 cxd5 exd5 , which is the standard way of reaching this position. However, in our repertoire, we do not necessarily allow any other move orders - Nc3 is my recommendation for this course. And if d5 , then cxd5 , not Nf3 . Apart from 5...Nf6 , Black can also try to play either 5...c6 or 5...h6 , as we have seen.}) 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e3 ({White should go for the most classical approach. Recently, there was some development after} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 {targeting the b7 -pawn. Black is fine here, however, after} Ra7 $1 {. For this reason, I would recommend playing 7.e3 .}) 7... Nbd7 8. Bd3 h6 9. Bf4 {Normally, I would recommend retreating to f4 in many of these positions. Especially now - when Black has not played ... Bd6 , it makes even more sense.} {If Black plays g5 (the most critical move), it is, in fact, the same as 9.Bh4 , but other moves here are worse for Black.} g5 10. Bg3 Nh5 {Black goes after the pair of bishops. White has many options here.} 11. Qb3 ({Pressuring the b7 -pawn, which is not so easy for Black to handle. It is quite similar to} 11. Qc2 {but a bit better, in my opinion. Additionally, White keeps the option of castling on either side.}) 11... Nxg3 {Black will need to trade on g3 sooner or later, but the issue with the b7 -pawn will remain.} 12. hxg3 Rb8 {This is the best move, according to the engine. However, we can now switch to Qc2 plans. Compared to the immediate 11.Qc2 , Black cannot castle queenside now, which is their idea in many lines. At the same time, the rook on b8 does not bring much to Black's position. This is the essence of the 11.Qb3 idea!} 13. Qc2 c6 {With Black unable to castle long, White has many promising plans at his disposal. I think playing in the center makes the most sense, but there are other good options.} 14. e4 ({I like opening the center here as Black's king feels vulnerable. Playing in the center makes sense, as White has a development advantage.} 14. Nh2 $5 {or 14.Nd2!? intending to push f4 is interesting too.} Bg7 15. f4 Nf6 16. Nf3) (14. Rb1 {with the b4 - Na4 idea is a positional plan, but I like it less. Still, it is one of the things that the engine likes, so I thought it should be at least mentioned.} Bg7 15. b4 Qe7 16. Na4 b5 17. Nc5 Nxc5 18. bxc5 {or b5 a4 Nb6 axb5 axb5 Ne5} {( Qe7 a5⩲ )} Rc8 {f4⩲}) 14... dxe4 {Black should not allow White to trade on d5 , as then the f5 -square will become very weak. Instead, Black should strive to utilize the position of White's uncastled king.} 15. Nxe4 Qa5+ {The only justification for releasing the tension with Black's previous move. White can react in two ways.} 16. Ned2 {Objectively, the best try - White keeps the right to castle and hopes to bring the knight to e3 via c4 , from where it can control the f5 -square! Black can react in two main ways: with either ... Bg7 or ... Bb4 . Black can include ... g4 as well, but this will mean ... Bb4 must be played later.} g4 17. Nh4 {White's knight is headed towards the f5 -square, which is amazing, of course. Black needs to act quickly.} Bb4 {Black tries to enter an endgame - but of course, we should not allow it.} 18. Rd1 {Intending to castle next. It sacs a pawn, but it is not relevant.} Bxd2+ 19. Rxd2 Qxa2 20. O-O Qb3 21. Qc1 ({With great compensation for White. Next, Re1 and Bf5 come, and Black's king is going to suffer in the center. E.g., Nf6} 21. Re1) *

