me, the rook on b8 does not bring much to Black's position. This is the essence of the 11.Qb3 idea!} 13. Qc2 c6 {With Black unable to castle long, White has many promising plans at his disposal. I think playing in the center makes the most sense, but there are other good options.} 14. e4 ({I like opening the center here as Black's king feels vulnerable. Playing in the center makes sense, as White has a development advantage.} 14. Nh2 $5 {or 14.Nd2!? intending to push f4 is interesting too.} Bg7 15. f4 Nf6 16. Nf3) (14. Rb1 {with the b4 - Na4 idea is a positional plan, but I like it less. Still, it is one of the things that the engine likes, so I thought it should be at least mentioned.} Bg7 15. b4 Qe7 16. Na4 b5 17. Nc5 Nxc5 18. bxc5 {or b5 a4 Nb6 axb5 axb5 Ne5} {( Qe7 a5⩲ )} Rc8 {f4⩲}) 14... dxe4 {Black should not allow White to trade on d5 , as then the f5 -square will become very weak. Instead, Black should strive to utilize the position of White's uncastled king.} 15. Nxe4 Qa5+ {The only justification for releasing the tension with Black's previous move. White can react in two ways.} 16. Ned2 {Objectively, the best try - White keeps the right to castle and hopes to bring the knight to e3 via c4 , from where it can control the f5 -square! Black can react in two main ways: with either ... Bg7 or ... Bb4 . Black can include ... g4 as well, but this will mean ... Bb4 must be played later.} Bb4 {Without including ... g4 first, this move carries no threat of transposing into an endgame. We would be happy if Black gave up his bishop pair advantage.} 17. a3 (17. O-O Bxd2 18. Nxd2 O-O {doesn't pose enough problems. We should keep the rook on h1 temporarily to help prevent ... O-O .}) 17... Bxd2+ 18. Nxd2 {Black's king is still in trouble. The best way to solve this issue is to move it.} Kf8 {But White retains good chances anyway. There are two good plans:} 19. b4 ({A positional approach.} 19. O-O-O {!?} Kg7 20. f4 {is more aggressive and also good.}) 19... Qd5 20. O-O {This position is unpleasant for Black. White will trade light-squared bishops with Bc4 (whether Black takes our d4 -pawn or not) and reroute the knight to e3 with ongoing pressure.} ({For example Kg7} 20. Bc4 Qf5 21. Qb2 Bd5 {Rfe1 Rbe8} 22. Bxd5 cxd5 23. Nf1 {followed by Ne3 , with a comfortable edge.}) *

