me, the rook on b8 does not bring much to Black's position. This is the essence of the 11.Qb3 idea!} 13. Qc2 c6 {With Black unable to castle long, White has many promising plans at his disposal. I think playing in the center makes the most sense, but there are other good options.} 14. e4 ({I like opening the center here as Black's king feels vulnerable. Playing in the center makes sense, as White has a development advantage.} 14. Nh2 $5 {or 14.Nd2!? intending to push f4 is interesting too.} Bg7 15. f4 Nf6 16. Nf3) (14. Rb1 {with the b4 - Na4 idea is a positional plan, but I like it less. Still, it is one of the things that the engine likes, so I thought it should be at least mentioned.} Bg7 15. b4 Qe7 16. Na4 b5 17. Nc5 Nxc5 18. bxc5 {or b5 a4 Nb6 axb5 axb5 Ne5} {( Qe7 a5⩲ )} Rc8 {f4⩲}) 14... dxe4 {Black should not allow White to trade on d5 , as then the f5 -square will become very weak. Instead, Black should strive to utilize the position of White's uncastled king.} 15. Nxe4 Qa5+ {The only justification for releasing the tension with Black's previous move. White can react in two ways.} 16. Ned2 {Objectively, the best try - White keeps the right to castle and hopes to bring the knight to e3 via c4 , from where it can control the f5 -square! Black can react in two main ways: with either ... Bg7 or ... Bb4 . Black can include ... g4 as well, but this will mean ... Bb4 must be played later.} Bg7 {Probably the most logical way to complete development. After all, the kingside is weakened so it makes sense to keep some pieces over there.} 17. O-O O-O 18. Nc4 {White's knight is headed towards the e3 -square - from where it will be headed to f5 one day.} Qc7 19. Bh7+ {As always, it's useful to drive the king father away from the center before coming back to f5 .} Kh8 20. Ne3 Nf6 21. Bf5 {I think this looks very nice for White!} *

