1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} Nf6 ({This position can arise also from d4} 5... Nf6 {c4 e6 Nf3 d5 Nc3 a6 cxd5 exd5 , which is the standard way of reaching this position. However, in our repertoire, we do not necessarily allow any other move orders - Nc3 is my recommendation for this course. And if d5 , then cxd5 , not Nf3 . Apart from 5...Nf6 , Black can also try to play either 5...c6 or 5...h6 , as we have seen.}) 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e3 ({White should go for the most classical approach. Recently, there was some development after} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 {targeting the b7 -pawn. Black is fine here, however, after} Ra7 $1 {. For this reason, I would recommend playing 7.e3 .}) 7... Nbd7 8. Bd3 Bd6 9. O-O ({As we will see soon enough, I recommend playing for setups with Bg5 - f4 . But here, dropping back would be premature:} 9. Bf4 Bxf4 10. exf4 Bg4 $1 {With this move, Black solves the problem of his bishop with a decent position. Probably the most testing is} 11. Qe2+ Kf8 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 {, but here, with few precise moves, Black manages to equalize:} Qe7+ $1 14. Kf1 Qb4 $1 15. Nxd5 Qxd4 16. Nxf6 Nxf6 17. g4 g6 {with an unclear game.}) 9... O-O {I would argue that castling this early is a slight inaccuracy by Black. It is more important to focus on controlling the e5 -square. Also, having castled, Black can forget about ... h6 -... g5 ideas.} 10. h3 h6 11. Bf4 Qe7 {This was tried by Magnus Carlsen in a blitz game against Ding Liren. I like it when Black's queen goes to e7 , as now we can jump into the e5 -square.} 12. Ne5 {If the queen had been on c7 , this would never have been possible.} c5 ({White has a pleasant choice here. Obviously,} 12... Nxe5 $4 13. dxe5 {loses a piece.}) ({On the other hand,} 12... Bxe5 $6 13. dxe5 {is undesirable from a positional point of view.}) 13. Bg3 ({This aggressive option looks promising for White (see the arrows for how we might continue).} 13. Nxd7 Bxd7 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. dxc5 Qxc5 16. Rc1 {is also slightly better for White, aiming for a positional battle. In Petrosyan-Faizrakhmanov, 2020, White eventually won.}) *

