1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} Nf6 ({This position can arise also from d4} 5... Nf6 {c4 e6 Nf3 d5 Nc3 a6 cxd5 exd5 , which is the standard way of reaching this position. However, in our repertoire, we do not necessarily allow any other move orders - Nc3 is my recommendation for this course. And if d5 , then cxd5 , not Nf3 . Apart from 5...Nf6 , Black can also try to play either 5...c6 or 5...h6 , as we have seen.}) 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e3 ({White should go for the most classical approach. Recently, there was some development after} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 {targeting the b7 -pawn. Black is fine here, however, after} Ra7 $1 {. For this reason, I would recommend playing 7.e3 .}) 7... Nbd7 8. Bd3 Bd6 9. O-O ({As we will see soon enough, I recommend playing for setups with Bg5 - f4 . But here, dropping back would be premature:} 9. Bf4 Bxf4 10. exf4 Bg4 $1 {With this move, Black solves the problem of his bishop with a decent position. Probably the most testing is} 11. Qe2+ Kf8 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 {, but here, with few precise moves, Black manages to equalize:} Qe7+ $1 14. Kf1 Qb4 $1 15. Nxd5 Qxd4 16. Nxf6 Nxf6 17. g4 g6 {with an unclear game.}) 9... h6 {This is inaccurate.} 10. Bf4 {Black does not get his queen to c7 .} ({The point is that} 10. Bf4 $4 {loses: exf4 White threatens f5 and} Bg4 {runs into} 11. Qe1 {followed by Ne5 with a huge advantage. We'll see this motif in the main line.}) 10... Qe7 {White has many options here, but I like the following the most.} 11. Ne5 {Immediately exploiting the absence of Black's queen on c7 . White's idea is to continue with Bg3 and f4 , completing Pillsbury's favorite attacking formation. If that is achieved, the position will highly resemble the Nimzo-Indian line with an early Bd2 which I recommended and covered in part 1, but this will be a much better version for White: the Be6 will likely run into trouble due to lack of space!} c6 (11... O-O 12. Bg3) (11... g5 12. Bg3 h5 13. f4) 12. Bg3 h5 {I am not really sure what Black is hoping for with this lunge - it could easily prove to be just a further weakening of Black's position.} 13. h3 h4 14. Bh2 g5 15. Qb3 ({Hitting the b7 -pawn and intending f4 next. Rb8} 15. f4 g4 16. f5 g3 17. fxe6 gxh2+ 18. Kh1 Nxe5 19. dxe5 Bxe5 20. exf7+ Qxf7 21. Rf5 Rh5 22. Rf2 {is a sample continuation.}) *

