1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} Nf6 ({This position can arise also from d4} 5... Nf6 {c4 e6 Nf3 d5 Nc3 a6 cxd5 exd5 , which is the standard way of reaching this position. However, in our repertoire, we do not necessarily allow any other move orders - Nc3 is my recommendation for this course. And if d5 , then cxd5 , not Nf3 . Apart from 5...Nf6 , Black can also try to play either 5...c6 or 5...h6 , as we have seen.}) 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e3 ({White should go for the most classical approach. Recently, there was some development after} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 {targeting the b7 -pawn. Black is fine here, however, after} Ra7 $1 {. For this reason, I would recommend playing 7.e3 .}) 7... Nbd7 8. Bd3 Bd6 9. O-O ({As we will see soon enough, I recommend playing for setups with Bg5 - f4 . But here, dropping back would be premature:} 9. Bf4 Bxf4 10. exf4 Bg4 $1 {With this move, Black solves the problem of his bishop with a decent position. Probably the most testing is} 11. Qe2+ Kf8 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 {, but here, with few precise moves, Black manages to equalize:} Qe7+ $1 14. Kf1 Qb4 $1 15. Nxd5 Qxd4 16. Nxf6 Nxf6 17. g4 g6 {with an unclear game.}) 9... c6 {Black needs to anticipate the Bf4 idea and have ... Qc7 available in response. The c7 -square is where the queen belongs in these positions (or d6 , after the bishop trade) - however, many people put the queen on e7 instead, which is a major inaccuracy.} 10. Bf4 {In general, trading dark-squared bishops is good for White...and it would be ideal for the exchange to occur on f4 . Then we would obtain a pawn majority and firm control over the e5 -square, as well as threaten to trap the Be6 with f4 - f5 .} Bxf4 11. exf4 ({This is a nightmare scenario for Black, and avoiding the f4 - f5 threat with Bg4 does not work due to} 11. Qe1 $1 {Unpinning the knight with tempo (Black is in check), and continuing Ne5 next with a big advantage. We have seen this idea here.}) 11... g6 12. Ng5 O-O 13. Nxe6 fxe6 {This position looks promising for White, as the e6 -pawn is backward and vulnerable. Black should quickly seek counterplay with ... Qb6 and ... c5 to offset this.} 14. Bc2 {For that exact reason, Stockfish likes this prophylactic retreat the most - defending the d4 -pawn ahead of time and intending Re1 next. In case of ... Qb6 , White can always respond with Na4 .} *

