1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} Nf6 ({This position can arise also from d4} 5... Nf6 {c4 e6 Nf3 d5 Nc3 a6 cxd5 exd5 , which is the standard way of reaching this position. However, in our repertoire, we do not necessarily allow any other move orders - Nc3 is my recommendation for this course. And if d5 , then cxd5 , not Nf3 . Apart from 5...Nf6 , Black can also try to play either 5...c6 or 5...h6 , as we have seen.}) 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e3 ({White should go for the most classical approach. Recently, there was some development after} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 {targeting the b7 -pawn. Black is fine here, however, after} Ra7 $1 {. For this reason, I would recommend playing 7.e3 .}) 7... Nbd7 8. Bd3 Bd6 9. O-O ({As we will see soon enough, I recommend playing for setups with Bg5 - f4 . But here, dropping back would be premature:} 9. Bf4 Bxf4 10. exf4 Bg4 $1 {With this move, Black solves the problem of his bishop with a decent position. Probably the most testing is} 11. Qe2+ Kf8 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 {, but here, with few precise moves, Black manages to equalize:} Qe7+ $1 14. Kf1 Qb4 $1 15. Nxd5 Qxd4 16. Nxf6 Nxf6 17. g4 g6 {with an unclear game.}) 9... c6 {Black needs to anticipate the Bf4 idea and have ... Qc7 available in response. The c7 -square is where the queen belongs in these positions (or d6 , after the bishop trade) - however, many people put the queen on e7 instead, which is a major inaccuracy.} 10. Bf4 {In general, trading dark-squared bishops is good for White...and it would be ideal for the exchange to occur on f4 . Then we would obtain a pawn majority and firm control over the e5 -square, as well as threaten to trap the Be6 with f4 - f5 .} Qc7 ({After} 10... Qb8 {, again, the easiest is} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 {, which, of course, transposes to the main line.}) ({As discussed earlier, e7 is not an ideal square for the queen, and if} 10... Qe7 {, we can again trade on d6 - but we don't have to, as the queen on e7 is misplaced.} 11. h3 O-O 12. a3 {is good too.}) 11. Bxd6 ({I would keep it simple and recommend trading the bishops right away. There is also} 11. Qd2 {, but we will need to trade these bishops sooner or later, anyway.}) 11... Qxd6 12. h3 {White should prevent ... Bg4 .} h6 {Castling kingside is the main line here, but Black can also try to play without it and hope to use the h3 -pawn as a hook.} 13. Qc2 {It is not too late to play O-O , but this is roughly the same as the main line. The only reasonable alternative is going for the kingside attack.} g5 {But this is overly aggressive.} 14. Nh2 {I think this is the simplest.} Rg8 15. Ne2 {White may be preparing f4 here, but in the long term, White wants to go for a minority pawn attack on the queenside.} h5 16. f4 g4 (16... gxf4 17. Nxf4 {and White's knight on f4 protects the pawn on h3 .}) 17. h4 {We will establish a blockade.} *

