5 -square, as well as threaten to trap the Be6 with f4 - f5 .} Qc7 ({After} 10... Qb8 {, again, the easiest is} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 {, which, of course, transposes to the main line.}) ({As discussed earlier, e7 is not an ideal square for the queen, and if} 10... Qe7 {, we can again trade on d6 - but we don't have to, as the queen on e7 is misplaced.} 11. h3 O-O 12. a3 {is good too.}) 11. Bxd6 ({I would keep it simple and recommend trading the bishops right away. There is also} 11. Qd2 {, but we will need to trade these bishops sooner or later, anyway.}) 11... Qxd6 12. h3 {White should prevent ... Bg4 .} h6 {Castling kingside is the main line here, but Black can also try to play without it and hope to use the h3 -pawn as a hook.} 13. Qc2 {It is not too late to play O-O , but this is roughly the same as the main line. The only reasonable alternative is going for the kingside attack.} g5 {But this is overly aggressive.} 14. Nh2 {I think this is the simplest.} g4 15. hxg4 {This leads Black nowhere.} Nxg4 16. Nxg4 Bxg4 17. f3 Be6 18. Ne2 {With our knight soon to be firmly placed on f4 , it is impossible to imagine that Black's attack will be effective. Meanwhile, strategically, White has a great position.} *

