1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 a6 {The Janowski Variation in the QGD has gained lots of popularity recently. Initially, it was sort of a frowned-upon system as White can just get a Carlsbad pawn structure where …a6 is not really useful. But it appears that it does not matter much, and ... a6 , in many cases, can be actually useful.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {I would still recommend going for the Carlsbad. This feels the most promising.} Nf6 ({This position can arise also from d4} 5... Nf6 {c4 e6 Nf3 d5 Nc3 a6 cxd5 exd5 , which is the standard way of reaching this position. However, in our repertoire, we do not necessarily allow any other move orders - Nc3 is my recommendation for this course. And if d5 , then cxd5 , not Nf3 . Apart from 5...Nf6 , Black can also try to play either 5...c6 or 5...h6 , as we have seen.}) 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e3 ({White should go for the most classical approach. Recently, there was some development after} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 {targeting the b7 -pawn. Black is fine here, however, after} Ra7 $1 {. For this reason, I would recommend playing 7.e3 .}) 7... Nbd7 8. Bd3 Bd6 9. O-O ({As we will see soon enough, I recommend playing for setups with Bg5 - f4 . But here, dropping back would be premature:} 9. Bf4 Bxf4 10. exf4 Bg4 $1 {With this move, Black solves the problem of his bishop with a decent position. Probably the most testing is} 11. Qe2+ Kf8 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 {, but here, with few precise moves, Black manages to equalize:} Qe7+ $1 14. Kf1 Qb4 $1 15. Nxd5 Qxd4 16. Nxf6 Nxf6 17. g4 g6 {with an unclear game.}) 9... c6 {Black needs to anticipate the Bf4 idea and have ... Qc7 available in response. The c7 -square is where the queen belongs in these positions (or d6 , after the bishop trade) - however, many people put the queen on e7 instead, which is a major inaccuracy.} 10. Bf4 {In general, trading dark-squared bishops is good for White...and it would be ideal for the exchange to occur on f4 . Then we would obtain a pawn majority and firm control over the e5 -square, as well as threaten to trap the Be6 with f4 - f5 .} Qc7 ({After} 10... Qb8 {, again, the easiest is} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 {, which, of course, transposes to the main line.}) ({As discussed earlier, e7 is not an ideal square for the queen, and if} 10... Qe7 {, we can again trade on d6 - but we don't have to, as the queen on e7 is misplaced.} 11. h3 O-O 12. a3 {is good too.}) 11. Bxd6 ({I would keep it simple and recommend trading the bishops right away. There is also} 11. Qd2 {, but we will need to trade these bishops sooner or later, anyway.}) 11... Qxd6 12. h3 {White should prevent ... Bg4 .} O-O 13. Qc2 {This variation is difficult to analyze when it comes to actual move-by-move lines, as both sides can play virtually any move in any position. What matters most is understanding the usual ideas and plans - and this is what I will focus on here. White has a couple of plans. My favorite is a maneuvering one with a3 , in order to have b2 - b4 ready, placing our rooks on c1 and e1 (or c1 and d1 ). Generally, we don't have to rush with b4 - and Ne2 - f4 ideas will come in handy, as well as Na4 - c5 . Black sometimes plays ... a5 (either to dissuade our b4 -pawn push or to attack the b4 -pawn that's already there), but one of the main ideas is to play ... b5 at some point, followed by the ... Nb6 - c4 maneuver when the white pawn is on b4 . The move order of these plans does not really matter much. The idea of b4 is not necessarily about starting the minority pawn attack, but more so about gaining control over the dark squares on the queenside and preparing to anchor a knight on c5 . Black sometimes also plays ... Ne8 - d6 , where the knight would be ideally placed.} g6 {Black makes the Bd3 and Qc2 battery obsolete and prepares the ... Ne8 -... Nd6 maneuver.} 14. Rfe1 {I would start with this simple, yet deep, prophylactic move. With the rook on e1 , Black is unlikely to pull off the ... Ne8 - d6 idea successfully, as the e4 -break will become a strong option once the f6 -knight wanders away the center.} Qe7 15. a3 Ne8 {This would be an attempt to bring the knight to d6 . But here we hit in the center.} 16. e4 dxe4 17. Nxe4 {With some pressure on the dark squares again.} *

