5 -square, as well as threaten to trap the Be6 with f4 - f5 .} Qc7 ({After} 10... Qb8 {, again, the easiest is} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 {, which, of course, transposes to the main line.}) ({As discussed earlier, e7 is not an ideal square for the queen, and if} 10... Qe7 {, we can again trade on d6 - but we don't have to, as the queen on e7 is misplaced.} 11. h3 O-O 12. a3 {is good too.}) 11. Bxd6 ({I would keep it simple and recommend trading the bishops right away. There is also} 11. Qd2 {, but we will need to trade these bishops sooner or later, anyway.}) 11... Qxd6 12. h3 {White should prevent ... Bg4 .} O-O 13. Qc2 {This variation is difficult to analyze when it comes to actual move-by-move lines, as both sides can play virtually any move in any position. What matters most is understanding the usual ideas and plans - and this is what I will focus on here. White has a couple of plans. My favorite is a maneuvering one with a3 , in order to have b2 - b4 ready, placing our rooks on c1 and e1 (or c1 and d1 ). Generally, we don't have to rush with b4 - and Ne2 - f4 ideas will come in handy, as well as Na4 - c5 . Black sometimes plays ... a5 (either to dissuade our b4 -pawn push or to attack the b4 -pawn that's already there), but one of the main ideas is to play ... b5 at some point, followed by the ... Nb6 - c4 maneuver when the white pawn is on b4 . The move order of these plans does not really matter much. The idea of b4 is not necessarily about starting the minority pawn attack, but more so about gaining control over the dark squares on the queenside and preparing to anchor a knight on c5 . Black sometimes also plays ... Ne8 - d6 , where the knight would be ideally placed.} g6 {Black makes the Bd3 and Qc2 battery obsolete and prepares the ... Ne8 -... Nd6 maneuver.} 14. Rfe1 {I would start with this simple, yet deep, prophylactic move. With the rook on e1 , Black is unlikely to pull off the ... Ne8 - d6 idea successfully, as the e4 -break will become a strong option once the f6 -knight wanders away the center.} a5 15. a3 Rfe8 16. Rac1 Rac8 {Some standard moves by both sides. Finally, it is time for Na4 or Ne2 .} 17. Na4 (17. Ne2 $5 {rerouting the knight to f4 is also playable.}) 17... b6 18. Nc3 {Weakening the queenside a bit seems reasonable. Now, Ne2 - Nf4 is a possible follow-up.} *

