[PlyCount "21"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 h6 ({This line, along with its cousin (} 3... Nf6 4. Nf3 h6 {) pretty much did not exist until 2020, when the COVID pandemic hit the world. People started getting creative, and suddenly lines that had never occurred before at the top level started to become quite common!  The idea of ... h6 has also been tried in a variation of the ... a6 QGD ( a6} 5. cxd5 exd5 {Nf3 h6!? ) by Magnus Carlsen in 2018 and 2019, so it is not a completely new concept. But only in 2020 did people start throwing in ... h6 here and there! Coming back to 3... h6 . Black's main idea is to prevent all of White's Bg5 variations, and in case White plays Bf4 , Black can respond with ... Bd6 and trade dark-squared bishops (without the bishop losing a step on e7 along the way).}) 4. cxd5 ({I would recommend staying with the theme of entering the Carlsbad structure, but there are many other interesting moves as well. White can play} 4. Bf4 {without cxd5 , for example.}) 4... exd5 5. Bf4 c6 ({Before Black offers a trade of bishops, he must first fortify the d5 -pawn.} 5... Bd6 $2 6. Nxd5 $1) 6. e3 Bf5 ({This line looks like a worse version of Nc3} 6... Be7 {cxd5 exd5 Bf4 c6 e3 Bf5 as ... h6 is not that useful. Sure, in some lines, Black has the option of dropping the bishop to h7 , but White often plays Bd3 anyway, and these bishops get traded. For this reason, I think White should be pretty comfortable here. There are many good options.}) (6... Bd6 {This is also a typical move. It is similar to 3... Be7 QGD where Black 'wastes' a time on Be7 and then moves Bd6 , the difference being that here there is a pawn on h6 .} 7. Bxd6 (7. Qf3 $5 {also deserves attention}) 7... Qxd6 8. Bd3 Ne7 9. Qc2 {The idea is to stop ... Bf5 . This is very similar to the line discussed in 3... Be7 . Of course, on h7 it is not hanging in some lines, but still we play for Nge2 , f3 , prepare e4 etc.}) 7. g4 {A new move here, but I think that expanding with tempo on the kingside is pretty logical.} Bh7 (7... Bg6 {, though playable and similar, seems less logical than Bh7 when there is already the pawn on h6 .}) (7... Be6 {is also playable but inconsistent with Black's previous moves.} 8. h4 Bd6 9. Nh3) 8. h4 {White gains space on the kingside. The plan is to play Bd3 and trade the bishops, followed by Nge2 and O-O-O .} Nf6 9. g5 {If Black allows this, then we're doing really well as ... hxg5 is never really an option (due to problems along the h-file). Otherwise, 10. gxh6 will follow and leave Black with a bad pawn structure and a kingside riddled with weak squares.} Ne4 10. gxh6 gxh6 11. Bd3 {White is much better, since the damaged pawn structure on the kingside is a serious problem for Black.} *

