1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 h6 ({This line, along with its cousin (} 3... Nf6 4. Nf3 h6 {) pretty much did not exist until 2020, when the COVID pandemic hit the world. People started getting creative, and suddenly lines that had never occurred before at the top level started to become quite common!  The idea of ... h6 has also been tried in a variation of the ... a6 QGD ( a6} 5. cxd5 exd5 {Nf3 h6!? ) by Magnus Carlsen in 2018 and 2019, so it is not a completely new concept. But only in 2020 did people start throwing in ... h6 here and there! Coming back to 3... h6 . Black's main idea is to prevent all of White's Bg5 variations, and in case White plays Bf4 , Black can respond with ... Bd6 and trade dark-squared bishops (without the bishop losing a step on e7 along the way).}) 4. cxd5 ({I would recommend staying with the theme of entering the Carlsbad structure, but there are many other interesting moves as well. White can play} 4. Bf4 {without cxd5 , for example.}) 4... exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 ({Black needs to protect the d5 -pawn before developing the bishop:} 5... Bd6 $4 6. Nxd5) 6. e3 Bd6 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. Bd3 O-O {Both sides have many options! We can play with Nf3 or Nge2 , going for a minority pawn attack or preparing f3 - e4 . Black generally plays via ... c6 but may also go with ... b6 and ... c5 ideas to contest the center.} 9. Nge2 {In general, I would recommend plans with Nge2 as they are more flexible than those with Nf3 . I like preparing f3 - e4 , similar to how I analyzed in some similar positions in the Nimzo-Indian.} (9. Rc1 $5 {is also interesting, pretty much forcing plans with ... c6 .} b6 $4 {runs into} 10. Nb5 {and} c6 {is met by} 11. Ne2 {with similar plans as after 9.Nge2 . However, I am not 100% sure if Rc1 is all that useful, as there are ideas of Rae1 in the main line so it might end up being a wasted tempo.}) 9... Be6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Rc1 c6 12. f3 {White is clearly better. One of White's ideas is, of course, e4 , but we should NOT rush it. Only if our center is well supported will this work. Moves that are supportive of e4 include h3 , bringing the queen to f2 , and maybe Rcd1 .} Rfe8 13. h3 ({It is necessary to cover the g4 -square.} 13. e4 $2 {would be way too premature:} dxe4 14. fxe4 Ng4 $1 {hitting h2 and threatening a fork on e3 . If} 15. e5 {then} Ndxe5 $3 16. dxe5 Qxe5 {with too many threats for White to handle.}) 13... Rad8 14. Qe1 c5 {Black should perhaps try playing via ... c5 , but this often leads to inferior versions of an IQP.} 15. Qf2 cxd4 16. Nxd4 Ne5 17. Rfd1 {With a comfortable IQP position.} *

