chain too much.} 10. Nf4 {Useful prophylaxis.} Bb7 11. O-O c5 12. Be2 {White reroutes the bishop to f3 and begins targeting the d5 -pawn. We can see the drawback of playing with ... c5 instead of the more solid ... c6 !} Nbd7 13. Bf3 {White will want to play dxc5 sooner or later (most likely sooner!) to put pressure on the center.} Rad8 14. dxc5 ({Immediately putting pressure on the center. The preparatory} 14. Rc1 $5 {is fine, too.}) 14... bxc5 {This gives away a pawn and the compensation is nowhere to be seen from a human point of view.} 15. Bxd5 ({It is important to take with the bishop, as we don’t want to run into … Ne5 ; for instance,} 15. Nfxd5 Ne5 $1 {with counterplay.}) 15... Nxd5 16. Nfxd5 ({With a healthy extra pawn. Things are not entirely clear if Black plays the absolutely best moves - but I don't really expect it to happen, so I will just leave the rest as a clickable: Ne5} 16. e4 f5 {f4 Nc4} 17. Qe2 fxe4 18. Rad1 {Nb6 Nxe4} Qe6 {Ndc3 Rde8! Maybe here, Black can hope for compensation, but White still is up a pawn after f5 Qe5 Ng3 Qxe2 Ncxe2⩲ where Black still needs to work hard to earn equality.}) *

