chain too much.} 10. Nf4 {Useful prophylaxis.} Bb7 11. O-O c5 12. Be2 {White reroutes the bishop to f3 and begins targeting the d5 -pawn. We can see the drawback of playing with ... c5 instead of the more solid ... c6 !} Nbd7 13. Bf3 {White will want to play dxc5 sooner or later (most likely sooner!) to put pressure on the center.} Rad8 14. dxc5 ({Immediately putting pressure on the center. The preparatory} 14. Rc1 $5 {is fine, too.}) 14... Qxc5 {Black recaptures with the queen to play ... Ne5 next.} 15. Rc1 {It's too dangerous to take on d5 here.} Ne5 {Here, White has a pleasant choice. Unfortunately, Bxd5 leads only to equality (and an unnecessary mess!), but there are two other good options.} 16. Nce2 ({I like this idea.} 16. Be2 {with Nb5 - d4 next is also possible.}) 16... Nxf3+ 17. gxf3 Qd6 18. Nd4 {The Nd4 is very strong, the f3 -pawn performs an important function of restricting the Nf6 and the idea of Kh1 - Rg1 is definitely annoying for Black.} *

