1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 {Black has a choice of possible plans here. One of them is to play plans with ... c5 , another is the standard ... c6 to enter a Carlsbad structure, and finally ... Bf5 !? which is a way to improve the light-squared bishop.} Bf5 ({This is a logical move, attempting to develop the bishop actively before White plays Bd3 . It is quite similar to the line} 6... c6 {e3 Bf5 , but with one significant difference - Black's pawns on b7 and d5 are going to come under fast pressure.}) 7. Qb3 Qc8 {Black can try to sacrifice a pawn for the initiative, but White should ignore it.} 8. h3 {Preparing g4 to deal with the bishop on f5 .} ({Grabbing the pawn with} 8. Nxd5 $6 Nxd5 9. Qxd5 {is not that great for White due to} Bb4+ $1 10. Kd1 O-O {with obvious compensation for Black with the exposed white king.}) 8... c6 {Black seemingly solved his biggest issue of the Carlsbad structure, as the light-squared bishop has successfully developed out to f5 . But that is why we played h3 ! We now turn the bishop back into a problem piece...} 9. g4 {Now we can play this.} Be6 (9... Bg6 {This does not allow Bd3 , but the bishop may be badly placed, given White's aggression on the kingside.} 10. Rc1 O-O 11. Be2 $5 {Developing. Let's keep an idea of Nf3 - Ne5 or Nh4 , as well as Qd1 - h4 - h5 . What if} Nbd7 $2 {(which of course is on the horizon) Black is in trouble after} 12. h4 $1 {and the problems with the bishop are clearly visible.}) 10. Nf3 Ne4 (10... O-O {is another option, where Black will play …c5-... Nc6 , trying to exploit White’s overextended kingside. But we are solid enough in the center.} 11. Rd1 $5 (11. Ng5 {is possible too, but 11. Rd1 looks better to me. Getting ready for ... c5 .}) 11... c5 12. Bg2 $1 {Now, since Black played ... c5 , White develops the bishop in a “Catalan” way to target the d5 -pawn. With g4 on the board, we might even consider playing g5 on a good day.} Nc6 13. O-O) 11. Bd3 Nd7 12. Qc2 {Putting pressure on the knight.} Nxc3 13. bxc3 {With a comfortable position for White.} *

