1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 {Black has a choice of possible plans here. One of them is to play plans with ... c5 , another is the standard ... c6 to enter a Carlsbad structure, and finally ... Bf5 !? which is a way to improve the light-squared bishop.} Bf5 ({This is a logical move, attempting to develop the bishop actively before White plays Bd3 . It is quite similar to the line} 6... c6 {e3 Bf5 , but with one significant difference - Black's pawns on b7 and d5 are going to come under fast pressure.}) 7. Qb3 Nc6 8. g4 ({A strong move which offers an advantage to White. We cannot play} 8. Qxb7 $2 {due to} Nb4 $1 {threatening a fork on c2 . Black's initiative unfolds, and allowing all of this seems like an unnecessary risk. We should first deflect Black's bishop off the c2 - and d3 - squares, so that a future Rc1 defends c2 adequately.}) 8... Nxg4 ({After} 8... Bxg4 9. Qxb7 Nb4 10. Rc1 O-O 11. a3 $1 {Now Rc1 covers all the weak spots adequately, and it was safe to take on b7 . The c7 -pawn is a weakness, and White is better.}) (8... Bc8 9. h3 O-O 10. Nf3) 9. Qxd5 {Black has two options here: enter the endgame or keep the queens on. Probably the middlegame is the better choice, as the position will remain complicated and full of life. In my opinion, White is simply much better in the endgame.} Qxd5 10. Nxd5 Bb4+ (10... O-O-O 11. Nxe7+ Nxe7 12. h3 Nf6 13. Rc1 Ned5 14. Bh2) 11. Nxb4 Nxb4 12. Rc1 {I find this endgame to be simply unpleasant for Black. The pair of bishops and the control over the center should give White a clear advantage.} c6 13. a3 Nd5 14. h3 ({White retains the pair of bishops here as Nxf4? is just bad for Black: hxg4 Nd3+} 14. Bd3 Bxd3 15. f3 {with a difficult endgame.}) 14... Ngf6 15. Be5 Nd7 16. Bd6 {Of course, we would like to keep our bishop pair.} N7b6 17. Ne2 {The knight is headed to either f4 or c3 . Once White stabilizes and completes development, we should be clearly better.} Rd8 18. Bh2 O-O 19. Rg1 {Always a useful move in such situations.} Rfe8 20. Kd2 {We might aim to gradually expand in the center with e4 , forcing the knights backwards into passivity.} *

