1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 {Black has a choice of possible plans here. One of them is to play plans with ... c5 , another is the standard ... c6 to enter a Carlsbad structure, and finally ... Bf5 !? which is a way to improve the light-squared bishop.} Bf5 ({This is a logical move, attempting to develop the bishop actively before White plays Bd3 . It is quite similar to the line} 6... c6 {e3 Bf5 , but with one significant difference - Black's pawns on b7 and d5 are going to come under fast pressure.}) 7. Qb3 Nc6 8. g4 ({A strong move which offers an advantage to White. We cannot play} 8. Qxb7 $2 {due to} Nb4 $1 {threatening a fork on c2 . Black's initiative unfolds, and allowing all of this seems like an unnecessary risk. We should first deflect Black's bishop off the c2 - and d3 - squares, so that a future Rc1 defends c2 adequately.}) 8... Nxg4 ({After} 8... Bxg4 9. Qxb7 Nb4 10. Rc1 O-O 11. a3 $1 {Now Rc1 covers all the weak spots adequately, and it was safe to take on b7 . The c7 -pawn is a weakness, and White is better.}) (8... Bc8 9. h3 O-O 10. Nf3) 9. Qxd5 {Black has two options here: enter the endgame or keep the queens on. Probably the middlegame is the better choice, as the position will remain complicated and full of life. In my opinion, White is simply much better in the endgame.} Qc8 {This line was very often the choice of Daniel Fridman. By keeping the queens on the board, the position stays more complicated - due in large part to White's king in the center and the unorthodox pawn structure. However, White should retain the better chances due to his strong and stable f2 / e3 / d4 central pawns which control a lot of important squares.} 10. a3 {This prophylactic move is the simplest, as it restricts Black's options.} Nf6 {This is similar to the 10...O-O line as there I will also recommend retreating the queen to f3 .} 11. Qf3 ({Here, after O-O , we can play} 11. Nge2 {and transpose to the line just mentioned a couple of moves ago.}) 11... Bg4 {An awful move, driving the queen to a good square and leaving the bishop vulnerable in the long run.} 12. Qg2 {The queen is actually quite strong on this unusual square. She patrols the center and queenside, and lines herself up menacingly towards Black's kingside.} O-O 13. Nge2 {This inclusion only helps White, as the g4 -bishop and g7 -pawn will run under some heavy pressure soon with Rg1 .} *

