1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 {Black has a choice of possible plans here. One of them is to play plans with ... c5 , another is the standard ... c6 to enter a Carlsbad structure, and finally ... Bf5 !? which is a way to improve the light-squared bishop.} Bf5 ({This is a logical move, attempting to develop the bishop actively before White plays Bd3 . It is quite similar to the line} 6... c6 {e3 Bf5 , but with one significant difference - Black's pawns on b7 and d5 are going to come under fast pressure.}) 7. Qb3 Nc6 8. g4 ({A strong move which offers an advantage to White. We cannot play} 8. Qxb7 $2 {due to} Nb4 $1 {threatening a fork on c2 . Black's initiative unfolds, and allowing all of this seems like an unnecessary risk. We should first deflect Black's bishop off the c2 - and d3 - squares, so that a future Rc1 defends c2 adequately.}) 8... Nxg4 ({After} 8... Bxg4 9. Qxb7 Nb4 10. Rc1 O-O 11. a3 $1 {Now Rc1 covers all the weak spots adequately, and it was safe to take on b7 . The c7 -pawn is a weakness, and White is better.}) (8... Bc8 9. h3 O-O 10. Nf3) 9. Qxd5 {Black has two options here: enter the endgame or keep the queens on. Probably the middlegame is the better choice, as the position will remain complicated and full of life. In my opinion, White is simply much better in the endgame.} Qc8 {This line was very often the choice of Daniel Fridman. By keeping the queens on the board, the position stays more complicated - due in large part to White's king in the center and the unorthodox pawn structure. However, White should retain the better chances due to his strong and stable f2 / e3 / d4 central pawns which control a lot of important squares.} 10. a3 {This prophylactic move is the simplest, as it restricts Black's options.} O-O 11. Nge2 {The right way to develop the knight here. The queen needs a path on the diagonal to retreat in case it gets attacked. The knight may go to g3 ; it supports the Bf4 if needed, and maybe even go to c3 in the future if the 'current' Nc3 gets traded.} Re8 {This was played in Bluebaum-Fridman, 2020, but I think it's just bad for Black:} 12. Ng3 ({Stronger than} 12. h3 {, which was played in the game.}) 12... Bg6 (12... Be6 13. Qg2 {intending d5 .}) 13. Be2 {We develop the bishop here to guard against potential ... Nxd4 tricks along the e-file. The bishop may also assist us in running the h-pawn down the board.} Nf6 14. Qg2 {With good central control and better pieces.} *

