1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 {Black has a choice of possible plans here. One of them is to play plans with ... c5 , another is the standard ... c6 to enter a Carlsbad structure, and finally ... Bf5 !? which is a way to improve the light-squared bishop.} c6 7. Bd3 {It is generally considered that Carlsbad structures with Bf4 (instead of Bg5 ) are better for White. For one reason, Black's ideas of ... Ne4 are no longer available. Secondly, White may sometimes play h3 - g4 and develop a quick initiative. Finally, White maintains a firm grip over the e5 -square, which matters quite a lot as well. White will want to play h3 next, making sure that the bishop will have a retreat to h2 if needed. Additionally, just like in many similar positions, the Bc8 cannot be comfortably developed.} O-O 8. h3 Nbd7 {Black goes for a standard setup. Next, ... Re8 comes followed by ... Nf8 . With Bf4 , however, White has a pretty good version of these lines.} 9. Nf3 Nb6 {Usually the knight does not go this way in the Carlsbad...} 10. Qc2 Nc4 11. Ne5 {Our grip on the e5 -square gives us a nice advantage.} *

