1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 {Black has a choice of possible plans here. One of them is to play plans with ... c5 , another is the standard ... c6 to enter a Carlsbad structure, and finally ... Bf5 !? which is a way to improve the light-squared bishop.} c6 7. Bd3 {It is generally considered that Carlsbad structures with Bf4 (instead of Bg5 ) are better for White. For one reason, Black's ideas of ... Ne4 are no longer available. Secondly, White may sometimes play h3 - g4 and develop a quick initiative. Finally, White maintains a firm grip over the e5 -square, which matters quite a lot as well. White will want to play h3 next, making sure that the bishop will have a retreat to h2 if needed. Additionally, just like in many similar positions, the Bc8 cannot be comfortably developed.} Bg4 {Trying to solve the problem of the Bc8 before White plays h3 , as seen, after 7... O-O .  Here, however, it does not really work well.} 8. Qb3 {Exploiting the bishop's absence on the queenside.} Qb6 {Another way of protecting the pawn.} 9. h3 Bh5 {This loses a piece:} 10. Qxb6 axb6 11. Bxb8 Rxb8 12. f4 h6 13. f5 {And the Bh5 is trapped!} *

