1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 {Black has a choice of possible plans here. One of them is to play plans with ... c5 , another is the standard ... c6 to enter a Carlsbad structure, and finally ... Bf5 !? which is a way to improve the light-squared bishop.} c6 7. Bd3 {It is generally considered that Carlsbad structures with Bf4 (instead of Bg5 ) are better for White. For one reason, Black's ideas of ... Ne4 are no longer available. Secondly, White may sometimes play h3 - g4 and develop a quick initiative. Finally, White maintains a firm grip over the e5 -square, which matters quite a lot as well. White will want to play h3 next, making sure that the bishop will have a retreat to h2 if needed. Additionally, just like in many similar positions, the Bc8 cannot be comfortably developed.} Nbd7 8. h3 {With the bishop on f4 instead of g5 , it will be too difficult to both execute the f3 - e4 plan and also drop the bishop back to f2 . For this reason, I would go for the Nf3 setup.} Nf8 {Bringing the knight to the kingside first is the only reasonable alternative. In effect, Black is saving a tempo on the ... O-O , ... Re8 and ... Nf8  maneuver that we've already seen before.} 9. Nf3 Ng6 {The knight is usually misplaced here. It is not really clear what Black intends to do with it next.} 10. Bh2 O-O 11. O-O Re8 {Such strategy is risky for Black as now White gets to occupy the e5 -square.} 12. Ne5 Bd6 13. f4 c5 14. Kh1 {Preemptively stepping away from the g1 - a7 diagonal and preparing to expand on the kingside.} *

