1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 {Black has a choice of possible plans here. One of them is to play plans with ... c5 , another is the standard ... c6 to enter a Carlsbad structure, and finally ... Bf5 !? which is a way to improve the light-squared bishop.} c6 7. Bd3 {It is generally considered that Carlsbad structures with Bf4 (instead of Bg5 ) are better for White. For one reason, Black's ideas of ... Ne4 are no longer available. Secondly, White may sometimes play h3 - g4 and develop a quick initiative. Finally, White maintains a firm grip over the e5 -square, which matters quite a lot as well. White will want to play h3 next, making sure that the bishop will have a retreat to h2 if needed. Additionally, just like in many similar positions, the Bc8 cannot be comfortably developed.} Nbd7 8. h3 {With the bishop on f4 instead of g5 , it will be too difficult to both execute the f3 - e4 plan and also drop the bishop back to f2 . For this reason, I would go for the Nf3 setup.} Nf8 {Bringing the knight to the kingside first is the only reasonable alternative. In effect, Black is saving a tempo on the ... O-O , ... Re8 and ... Nf8  maneuver that we've already seen before.} 9. Nf3 Ne6 10. Bh2 {It makes no sense to play Be5 , as this square is usually intended for the knight.} O-O 11. O-O g6 {White should go for a typical minority attack or a maneuvering game on the center/queenside.} 12. a3 {Preparing b4 . I must admit it was also OK to play Rb1 , but I like the text more.} Ng7 {This is a concession - White gets to play b4 with a clear advantage.} 13. b4 a6 (13... Bf5 $6 {allows} 14. b5 $1) 14. Na4 {Improving the knight. The dark squares on the queenside are pretty weak for Black.} Bf5 15. Nc5 {If Black ever takes our knight on c5 , we'll be recapturing with the b-pawn to open up a line of attack against the very weak b7 -pawn.} Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Qc8 17. Rfc1 {White has harmony and total control of the dark squares. If Black ever challenges our knight with ... b6 , it will lead to a potentially fatal weakening of the c6 -pawn.} *

