1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 {Black has a choice of possible plans here. One of them is to play plans with ... c5 , another is the standard ... c6 to enter a Carlsbad structure, and finally ... Bf5 !? which is a way to improve the light-squared bishop.} O-O 7. Bd3 c5 8. Nge2 {The knight is much more flexible on e2 than f3 . White can bring it to f4 in the future, but the idea of f3 - e4 may be played one day - especially if Black plays ... c4 .} Nc6 (8... c4 9. Bc2 {should not change much, as it is hard to imagine Black playing without ... Nc6 .}) 9. O-O {There is no need to rush with dxc5 , as we are happy if Black changes the pawn structure with ... c4 or ... cxd4 .} cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. exd4 {These double IQP structures are quite common, and we have already seen something like this in some of the Nimzo-Indian lines covered in Part 1. Despite the symmetrical pawn structure, White retains better chances due to the more active pieces and the ability to put pressure on the d5 -pawn. One method is to make use of e5 -square (say, Be5 !?) and provoke some trade where White can play dxe5 . Moves like Re1 and Qb3 or Qf3 are also part of White's plans, along with the Bc2 - Qd3 battery.} ({Knowing ideas here is more important, so I will leave the rest here as clickable, Bd7} 11. Re1 {Bc6 Qf3} h6 12. Be5 Re8 {Qg3 Bf8 Rad1±}) ({Be6} 11. Re1 Bd6 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 {is also annoying for Black. White will set up the Bc2 - Qd3 battery.}) *

