1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 {Black has a choice of possible plans here. One of them is to play plans with ... c5 , another is the standard ... c6 to enter a Carlsbad structure, and finally ... Bf5 !? which is a way to improve the light-squared bishop.} O-O 7. Bd3 c5 8. Nge2 {The knight is much more flexible on e2 than f3 . White can bring it to f4 in the future, but the idea of f3 - e4 may be played one day - especially if Black plays ... c4 .} Nc6 (8... c4 9. Bc2 {should not change much, as it is hard to imagine Black playing without ... Nc6 .}) 9. O-O {There is no need to rush with dxc5 , as we are happy if Black changes the pawn structure with ... c4 or ... cxd4 .} Bg4 {Now it is time to go for the IQP.} 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. h3 Bxe2 ({Necessary.} 11... Bh5 $2 {loses a pawn:} 12. g4 $1 Bg6 13. Bxg6 hxg6 14. g5 {and the IQP falls.}) 12. Nxe2 {White has a nice position - a pair of bishops and an IQP to target. A brilliant illustration of how to play such a position is the game Wojtaszek-Fressinet, 2011.} d4 {This is one of the ways the side with the IQP can try to play: simply exchange the pawn before it becomes a liability.} 13. Rc1 Bb6 14. e4 {Such a position should be clearly better for White. The blockade on d3 is stable and the d4 -pawn will be targeted very soon.} Re8 15. f3 Nb4 16. Kh1 Nxd3 (16... Nxa2 17. Rc4 {With a double idea, trap the knight and add pressure to the d4 pawn.}) 17. Qxd3 {The IQP is a chronic weakness.} *

