1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 {Black has a choice of possible plans here. One of them is to play plans with ... c5 , another is the standard ... c6 to enter a Carlsbad structure, and finally ... Bf5 !? which is a way to improve the light-squared bishop.} O-O 7. Bd3 c5 8. Nge2 {The knight is much more flexible on e2 than f3 . White can bring it to f4 in the future, but the idea of f3 - e4 may be played one day - especially if Black plays ... c4 .} Nc6 (8... c4 9. Bc2 {should not change much, as it is hard to imagine Black playing without ... Nc6 .}) 9. O-O {There is no need to rush with dxc5 , as we are happy if Black changes the pawn structure with ... c4 or ... cxd4 .} c4 10. Bc2 a6 {A standard idea for Black is to expand on the queenside and make use of his pawn majority.} 11. b3 {A standard response by White - undermining the pawn chain and trying to weaken it. Surprisingly, it is a novelty!} ({cxb3?!} 11. Bb3 {is generally a favorable trade for White. The d5 -pawn is a weakness.}) 11... Nb4 12. Bb1 b5 {Here, White can play a3 followed by bxc4 and position similar to the main line. But there is the additional option of Bg5 , which I offer as an alternative.} 13. Bg5 {Black faces some issues with the d5 -pawn.} h6 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nf4 {Preparing to evict the d5 -pawn's last defender.} Bg5 16. a3 Bxf4 17. axb4 ({And White has the Nxb5 resource next. White's advantage is rather clear. Bd6} 17. Nxb5 {Bxb4 bxc4 dxc4 Na3⩲ is a sample continuation.}) *

