1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 {By far, the most popular move in this position. The idea is to quickly develop the bishop, before White plays Bd3 and stops Black from doing so. If Black does not play this move, he may face issues with the Bc8 in the long run.} ({Still, there are some alternatives:} 6... Bd6 {has been covered earlier and for Nf6} 7. Bd3 {, see the 5... Nf6  lines .}) 7. Nge2 Nf6 8. Ng3 ({No need to begin here with} 8. h4 {, and the more normal Ng3 makes perfect sense.}) 8... Be6 {Retreating this way is usually not good for Black. White can control the b1 - h7 diagonal and obtain a comfortable Carlsbad.} 9. Bd3 {It is difficult to analyze in detail this position but I think that it is enough to just know the plan: basically, White castles kingside, ideally plays Qc2 and Rad1 , at some point we should probably retreat with Nge2 ( Nf5 can be kept as an option too, of course!) and prepare the f3 - e4 idea in the long term. However, if Black messes up, there could also be ideas of f4 ! trying to take advantage of the e6 -bishop's lack of room.} Nbd7 (9... O-O 10. Qc2 {does not change much.}) 10. O-O O-O 11. Qc2 Re8 12. h3 Nf8 13. Rad1 {Such setup as Black seems reasonable. But what next? I am not so sure, while White has a clear plan - preparing f3 - e4 in the future. We should not focus on the minority pawn attack here, but ideas of Na4 - Nc5 deserve some attention as well.} Bd6 {This is an example of a typical mistake here.} ({Another inaccurate move would be} 13... Ng6 14. Bg5 $1 {and Black does not have ... h6 as in the end the knight would be loose on g6 . Here, White can again consider playing f4 !}) 14. Be5 {White can play this, and the f4 idea is very strong now.} *

