1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 {By far, the most popular move in this position. The idea is to quickly develop the bishop, before White plays Bd3 and stops Black from doing so. If Black does not play this move, he may face issues with the Bc8 in the long run.} ({Still, there are some alternatives:} 6... Bd6 {has been covered earlier and for Nf6} 7. Bd3 {, see the 5... Nf6  lines .}) 7. Nge2 Nd7 {The main move here. Generally, Black delays ... Nf6 to keep the h4 -square under control.} 8. h4 {An interesting try to seize space on the kingside, despite the e7 -bishop looking at the h4 -square. There are potential issues with the Bf5 as it will run under Ng3 . The idea of h4 is to prevent Black from playing ... Bg6 and force the bishop to e6 . Then, Bd3 can be played, followed by Nf5 . Additionally, the h4 -pawn can be used to play h5 and weaken Black's kingside.} h5 {This move is a bit risky. We get exactly what we want - targets on the kingside!} 9. Ng3 Bg4 ({This is rarer than} 9... Bg6 {, but it should not be ignored.}) 10. Be2 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 g6 12. e4 {This is similar to the 9...Bg6 line, with the difference that White's queen is on e2 . It may be a bit less active, but similar plans also occur here.} ({dxe4? is just as bad as with the queen on d3 - but White reacts differently as the queen on e2 is not attacked.} 12. O-O-O $1 Ngf6 {d5! transposes, though d5!?± is also strong.}) 12... Ngf6 13. O-O-O {Again, we should not rush e5 . Especially with the queen on e2 , when e5 - e6 loses strength as the g6 -pawn is not hanging.} Nb6 14. f3 {White supports the center.} dxe4 {The best move according to the engine, but it feels like it is not easy to play - White just supported the center. On the other hand - sooner or later, Black needs to do this. Otherwise, it is not so clear what else Black could do...} 15. Ngxe4 {A rare sight to recapture with the knight, but it seems to pose Black quite serious issues.} Nxe4 {Here, White can recapture with anything really, but taking with either knight or the queen looks the scariest for Black:} 16. Qxe4 (16. Nxe4 Nd5 17. Be5 O-O 18. g4 {launching a kingside attack is also pretty challenging.}) 16... Nd5 17. Be5 O-O 18. g4 Qa5 19. Rh2 {The rook joins the queenside via the second rank, and Black is under serious pressure. Engines manage to hold with only moves, but over the board, this looks pretty bad for Black...} ({Some sample lines: Nxc3 bxc3 and if hxg4} 19. Qc2 $1 {then h5 is coming. After} Qxc3 {Rc2 Qa3+} 20. Kb1 hxg4 21. fxg4 Qb4 {Rb2} 22. Qa4 $1 {, Black can meet Rh1 with} Rae8 {, or 25. Qd3 Rad8} 23. h5 f6 $3 {and Black holds by a miracle...}) *

