1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 {By far, the most popular move in this position. The idea is to quickly develop the bishop, before White plays Bd3 and stops Black from doing so. If Black does not play this move, he may face issues with the Bc8 in the long run.} ({Still, there are some alternatives:} 6... Bd6 {has been covered earlier and for Nf6} 7. Bd3 {, see the 5... Nf6  lines .}) 7. Nge2 Nd7 {The main move here. Generally, Black delays ... Nf6 to keep the h4 -square under control.} 8. h4 {An interesting try to seize space on the kingside, despite the e7 -bishop looking at the h4 -square. There are potential issues with the Bf5 as it will run under Ng3 . The idea of h4 is to prevent Black from playing ... Bg6 and force the bishop to e6 . Then, Bd3 can be played, followed by Nf5 . Additionally, the h4 -pawn can be used to play h5 and weaken Black's kingside.} h5 {This move is a bit risky. We get exactly what we want - targets on the kingside!} 9. Ng3 Bg6 10. Bd3 {White trades light-squared bishops in order to weaken the f5 and h5 -squares. If Black plays ... Bxd3 and ... g6 , we argue that this is a waste of time and will try to take advantage of it dynamically.} Bxh4 {The only reasonable alternative to ... Bxd3 is grabbing the pawn, which weakens the kingside.} 11. Bxg6 fxg6 12. Qc2 ({There is not much difference between} 12. Qd3 {and Qc2 , but for some reason, Stockfish likes the text move a bit more. Anyway, the ideas remain similar.}) 12... Nf8 (12... Kf7 13. e4 {is similar.}) 13. e4 Bf6 (13... Ne6 14. Be5 $1 Bxg3 15. fxg3 Ne7 16. g4 {also gives White good compensation. We'll castle long with a nice kingside initiative.}) 14. Be3 {White has a good compensation for the pawn. Black's pieces are awkward.} ({Surprisingly, the most natural move} 14. O-O-O $2 {is a big mistake.} Ne6 $1 15. Be3 Ne7 {and Black has everything covered. Be3 the same idea Ne6?? now loses after} 16. exd5 $1 {with a double attack on e6 and g6 .}) *

