1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 {By far, the most popular move in this position. The idea is to quickly develop the bishop, before White plays Bd3 and stops Black from doing so. If Black does not play this move, he may face issues with the Bc8 in the long run.} ({Still, there are some alternatives:} 6... Bd6 {has been covered earlier and for Nf6} 7. Bd3 {, see the 5... Nf6  lines .}) 7. Nge2 Nd7 {The main move here. Generally, Black delays ... Nf6 to keep the h4 -square under control.} 8. h4 {An interesting try to seize space on the kingside, despite the e7 -bishop looking at the h4 -square. There are potential issues with the Bf5 as it will run under Ng3 . The idea of h4 is to prevent Black from playing ... Bg6 and force the bishop to e6 . Then, Bd3 can be played, followed by Nf5 . Additionally, the h4 -pawn can be used to play h5 and weaken Black's kingside.} Bxh4 {This does not work.} 9. Qb3 {And Black's queen is overworked - there is no convenient way to defend the b7 -pawn.} Nb6 {This is not a solution:} 10. a4 {A thematic push against a Nb6 .} Bc8 11. a5 Nc4 12. e4 {White crushes through in the center.} Be7 13. exd5 cxd5 14. Nb5 Nd6 {This drops the d5 -pawn, but Black had to stop the fork on c7 .} 15. Qxd5 Nxb5 16. Qxb5+ Kf8 17. Be5 {Black has a terrible position.} *

