1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 {By far, the most popular move in this position. The idea is to quickly develop the bishop, before White plays Bd3 and stops Black from doing so. If Black does not play this move, he may face issues with the Bc8 in the long run.} ({Still, there are some alternatives:} 6... Bd6 {has been covered earlier and for Nf6} 7. Bd3 {, see the 5... Nf6  lines .}) 7. Nge2 Nd7 {The main move here. Generally, Black delays ... Nf6 to keep the h4 -square under control.} 8. h4 {An interesting try to seize space on the kingside, despite the e7 -bishop looking at the h4 -square. There are potential issues with the Bf5 as it will run under Ng3 . The idea of h4 is to prevent Black from playing ... Bg6 and force the bishop to e6 . Then, Bd3 can be played, followed by Nf5 . Additionally, the h4 -pawn can be used to play h5 and weaken Black's kingside.} g6 {A prophylactic move securing the f5 -square. In case of h5 , Black will reply with ... g5 . And in the future, Black may keep an eye out for the h4 -pawn.} 9. Ng3 Be6 10. Qb3 {Provoking Black's queen to go to b6 , where it will be actually misplaced.} b5 {This move is common in similar positions, but here, it is not that good. Black prepares ... a6 and ... c5 , but White can prepare for it.} (10... b6 $4 11. Ba6 $1) 11. Bd3 a6 {Getting ready for ... c5 .} 12. Qc2 Bxh4 13. e4 {And White's play in the center is likely strong. Being down a pawn does not matter much as our pieces are very active, and Black's king will have a hard time finding shelter. Of course, the position remains playable and could be explored more, but I think it is clear White has a good game here.} *

