1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 {By far, the most popular move in this position. The idea is to quickly develop the bishop, before White plays Bd3 and stops Black from doing so. If Black does not play this move, he may face issues with the Bc8 in the long run.} ({Still, there are some alternatives:} 6... Bd6 {has been covered earlier and for Nf6} 7. Bd3 {, see the 5... Nf6  lines .}) 7. Nge2 Nd7 {The main move here. Generally, Black delays ... Nf6 to keep the h4 -square under control.} 8. h4 {An interesting try to seize space on the kingside, despite the e7 -bishop looking at the h4 -square. There are potential issues with the Bf5 as it will run under Ng3 . The idea of h4 is to prevent Black from playing ... Bg6 and force the bishop to e6 . Then, Bd3 can be played, followed by Nf5 . Additionally, the h4 -pawn can be used to play h5 and weaken Black's kingside.} g6 {A prophylactic move securing the f5 -square. In case of h5 , Black will reply with ... g5 . And in the future, Black may keep an eye out for the h4 -pawn.} 9. Ng3 Be6 10. Qb3 {Provoking Black's queen to go to b6 , where it will be actually misplaced.} Qb6 ({Other moves make less sense. E.g.} 10... Nb6 11. a4 $1 a5 12. Bd3 Nf6 13. h5) 11. Qc2 {A standard idea. The queen on b6 is not well placed, and it likely should go back to d8 sooner or later.} Qd8 {Black's best bet is to retreat right away.} 12. Bd3 {White sacrifices the h4 -pawn for the activity. At the end of the day, even when the h -pawn drops, we will have an open h -file for the rook, and Black will spend some tempi to get this pawn.} Bxh4 13. Qb3 {Probably the most critical, even if the engine somehow makes it work for Black... Now, the black queen cannot defend the b7 -pawn.} (13. Nge2 $5 {is another engine's suggestion, but it does not look convincing.}) 13... b6 ({Perhaps the least evil alternative to} 13... g5 {- but now, the queenside is going to be chronically weak.}) 14. O-O-O Bg5 15. Nge2 {Despite being down a pawn, White has a good position. The lack of the h -pawn does not matter much, and one may even argue that it helps us activate the Rh1 . Black is behind in development, and it is unclear where his king will be safe. White has a simple plan of preparing e4 pawn break to open the center and maximize our active pieces.} *

