1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 {By far, the most popular move in this position. The idea is to quickly develop the bishop, before White plays Bd3 and stops Black from doing so. If Black does not play this move, he may face issues with the Bc8 in the long run.} ({Still, there are some alternatives:} 6... Bd6 {has been covered earlier and for Nf6} 7. Bd3 {, see the 5... Nf6  lines .}) 7. Nge2 Nd7 {The main move here. Generally, Black delays ... Nf6 to keep the h4 -square under control.} 8. h4 {An interesting try to seize space on the kingside, despite the e7 -bishop looking at the h4 -square. There are potential issues with the Bf5 as it will run under Ng3 . The idea of h4 is to prevent Black from playing ... Bg6 and force the bishop to e6 . Then, Bd3 can be played, followed by Nf5 . Additionally, the h4 -pawn can be used to play h5 and weaken Black's kingside.} Ngf6 {The main move here. Black completes the development, ignoring White's expansive ambitions on the kingside.} 9. Ng3 {Chasing the bishop away. Please note that the bishop cannot go to g6 now (as it would normally want), which definitely is good news for White.} Be6 (9... Bg4 $6 {only helps White as the pawn on f3 is useful in many similar positions.} 10. f3 Be6 11. Bd3) 10. Bd3 {White creates an idea of Nf5 , trying to get the pair of bishops.} O-O 11. Nf5 Bxf5 12. Bxf5 {This is good news for White. Such a pair of bishops' advantage should matter in the long run.} Re8 {Black makes space for the knight on f8 , which is a typical manouver in such positions.} 13. g4 ({We begin an expansion on the kingside, taking advantage of the pair of bishops and the still closed center. Note that if g6} 13. Bc2 $1 {the bishop should retreat here instead of the more standard Bd3 to sidestep} c5 {. White should keep the center closed to make more of his attack on the kingside.}) 13... Bb4 (13... Nf8 14. g5 N6d7 15. Qg4 {leaves Black in a passive position.}) 14. Kf1 {No need to castle to make sure the king is safe!} Nf8 15. Kg2 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Ne4 17. Qd3 {White wants f3 . The favorable pawn structure, the pressure on the kingside, and a bishop vs. knight fight should favor us here, even though Black's position is pretty solid, and there is still a long game ahead.} *

