1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {This line is sometimes employed by Ragozin players wanting to avoid the Nimzo or sometimes the Catalan. We can simply transpose here to the Nimzo e3 in a couple of ways.} 4. a3 {I would begin with this move to make sure we get the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {Black has a lot of options now. The most standard is, of course, Nf6 , but let's look at alternatives.} c5 6. e3 {Black has a choice now. Of course, Nf6 transposes to the Nimzo 4.e3 d5 , that I cover here in part 1. The main alternatives involve playing with ... Ne7 .} Qc7 {This is a standard idea in such positions, but it is now inaccurate.} 7. Qg4 {And Black probably regrets not developing the knight first.} g6 (7... f5 8. Qg3 Qxg3 9. hxg3) 8. Nf3 {Black is missing the dark-squared bishop dearly.} *

