1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {This line is sometimes employed by Ragozin players wanting to avoid the Nimzo or sometimes the Catalan. We can simply transpose here to the Nimzo e3 in a couple of ways.} 4. a3 {I would begin with this move to make sure we get the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {Black has a lot of options now. The most standard is, of course, Nf6 , but let's look at alternatives.} c5 6. e3 {Black has a choice now. Of course, Nf6 transposes to the Nimzo 4.e3 d5 , that I cover here in part 1. The main alternatives involve playing with ... Ne7 .} Ne7 7. cxd5 {I would go for this structure.} exd5 8. Bd3 {As usual, we go for the Bd3 - Ne2 setup.} O-O (8... Nbc6 {This position can also be reached when Black begins with 6...Nc6 . After} 9. Ne2 {, there is hardly anything better than playing ... Bf5 and ... O-O , so it would most likely transpose.}) 9. Ne2 Bf5 10. O-O Bxd3 11. Qxd3 {Black can play now ... Nbc6 or ... Nd7 . We play a4 followed by Ba3 first. In the future, of course, we may play f3 - e4 as well. We reached a standard position that is better for White. There are typical plans of f3 - Ng3 and preparing e4 , but there are also ideas of playing in the queenside/center with a4 - Ba3 , preparing a c4 pawn break. With the knight on e7 on the board, I would probably stick with the latter. For example:} ({Nbc6} 11. a4 $5 {intending Ba3 .} c4 12. Qc2 Qd7 13. f3 f5 14. Ba3) ({Or Nd7} 11. a4 {Rc8 Ba3⩲}) *

