1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {This line is sometimes employed by Ragozin players wanting to avoid the Nimzo or sometimes the Catalan. We can simply transpose here to the Nimzo e3 in a couple of ways.} 4. a3 {I would begin with this move to make sure we get the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {Black has a lot of options now. The most standard is, of course, Nf6 , but let's look at alternatives.} Ne7 6. e3 O-O {Delaying ... c5 is another option. Here, White can play with cxd5 or without. In any case, I would not rush with cxd5 as Black has options of ... Bf5 and play without ... c5 (or delay it at least), which, according to my analysis, is acceptable.} 7. Bd3 {This is the simplest, in my opinion. The positions here are very similar to the Nimzo 4.e3 O-O 5.Bd3 d5 6.a3 , which I analyze in Part 1 with the difference that Black's knight is on e7 instead of f6 . There is not much of a difference otherwise, I believe. I think it favors White as it will be easier to push e4 .} (7. cxd5 exd5 8. Bd3 Bf5 9. Ne2 {Again, a typical position. Plans of f3 - e4 , or c4 ( a4 - Ba3 as well) are on White's agenda.} Nd7 {intending ... Nb6 -... Nc4 or ... c5 is perhaps a quite OK version of such structures for Black.}) ({Another option is} 7. a4 $5 {as it is usually good to bring the bishop to a3 in these positions.}) 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 c5 9. Nf3 Qc7 10. Ba2 {As e4 is easier to push, I think that the bishop belongs here.} b6 (10... b5 {does not change much:} 11. O-O Bb7 12. Re1 Nd7 13. e4) 11. O-O Bb7 12. Re1 Nd7 13. e4 {White has a comfortable position.} *

