1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {This line is sometimes employed by Ragozin players wanting to avoid the Nimzo or sometimes the Catalan. We can simply transpose here to the Nimzo e3 in a couple of ways.} 4. a3 {I would begin with this move to make sure we get the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {Black has a lot of options now. The most standard is, of course, Nf6 , but let's look at alternatives.} dxc4 {This is very dubious. Black normally wants to wait with this move until the Bf1 moves.} 6. e3 {Here, we can play this, intending to recapture the pawn without losing a tempo with the bishop. If Black gives it away, White will have, of course, a comfortable position. That's why I guess Black could try to defend the c4 -pawn, but as we will see, it does not work well.} Qd5 7. Qg4 Kf8 (7... g6 {weakens the kingside dark squares, which is a major problem in the long run.} 8. Qe2 b5 9. a4 a6 10. e4 Qb7 11. g3) 8. a4 Nf6 9. Qf4 {The c4 -pawn realistically cannot be hold for long. And even if it does, White always should have more than sufficient compensation.} *

