1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {This line is sometimes employed by Ragozin players wanting to avoid the Nimzo or sometimes the Catalan. We can simply transpose here to the Nimzo e3 in a couple of ways.} 4. a3 {I would begin with this move to make sure we get the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {Black has a lot of options now. The most standard is, of course, Nf6 , but let's look at alternatives.} dxc4 {This is very dubious. Black normally wants to wait with this move until the Bf1 moves.} 6. e3 {Here, we can play this, intending to recapture the pawn without losing a tempo with the bishop. If Black gives it away, White will have, of course, a comfortable position. That's why I guess Black could try to defend the c4 -pawn, but as we will see, it does not work well.} b5 7. a4 Ba6 {This is possible, but it clearly is not what Black wants in such positions. White has so many options...} 8. Nf3 (8. axb5 Bxb5 9. Qg4 {is also strong.}) 8... Nd7 9. Nd2 Nb6 10. axb5 Bxb5 11. Qg4 {White is much better here.} *

