1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {This line is sometimes employed by Ragozin players wanting to avoid the Nimzo or sometimes the Catalan. We can simply transpose here to the Nimzo e3 in a couple of ways.} 4. a3 {I would begin with this move to make sure we get the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {Black has a lot of options now. The most standard is, of course, Nf6 , but let's look at alternatives.} c6 {This was the new trend with e3 and ... Nf6 on the board. Here, we can postpone e3 , which can be beneficial.} 6. a4 {With the idea of Ba3 , of course, especially when ... Nf6 is played.} Nf6 (6... Ne7 {is not the ideal development of the knight, but at least Black castles. Otherwise, Black's king is stuck in the center due to the Ba3 idea.} 7. e3 O-O 8. Nf3 {This is a much better version of the Nimzo 4.e3 d5 as the knight is worse on e7 than it would be on f6 . We don't need to rush with Ba3 for now (still, it is an idea, of course), but for now, it is more useful to complete the development.}) 7. Ba3 {And Black's king cannot castle! On the other hand, Black can grab the c4 -pawn, but the resulting position with the king unable to castle is definitely better for White, and Black is clearly in some trouble as he does not have time to castle.} dxc4 8. e3 b5 9. Nf3 a5 10. Qc2 Na6 11. Ne5 Qc7 12. Be2 {In order to castle, Black must give away the c4 -pawn.} b4 13. Bb2 {The c4 -pawn falls, and White is better due to the bishop pair.} *

