1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {This line is sometimes employed by Ragozin players wanting to avoid the Nimzo or sometimes the Catalan. We can simply transpose here to the Nimzo e3 in a couple of ways.} 4. a3 {I would begin with this move to make sure we get the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {Black has a lot of options now. The most standard is, of course, Nf6 , but let's look at alternatives.} b6 {This is quite rare, and I don't really see a point of this move, as generally we want to take on d5 , followed by e3 - Bd3 etc., or maybe play c4 .} 6. cxd5 exd5 7. e3 Ne7 {If Black plays ... Nf6 instead, there would likely be a transposition to the Nimzo 4.e3 .} 8. Bd3 Bf5 {Here, White has a pleasant choice.} 9. Ne2 (9. Nf3 {can also be played here, as White will play quickly c4 .} O-O 10. c4) 9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Qd7 11. O-O {With the standard plan of f3 - e4 .} *

