1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {This line is sometimes employed by Ragozin players wanting to avoid the Nimzo or sometimes the Catalan. We can simply transpose here to the Nimzo e3 in a couple of ways.} 4. a3 {I would begin with this move to make sure we get the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {Black has a lot of options now. The most standard is, of course, Nf6 , but let's look at alternatives.} Nf6 6. cxd5 ({In the d4} 6. cxd5 {c4 e6 Nc3 Bb4 move order, we have an option of capturing on d5 early, at the same time avoiding some of the lines that are in the Nimzo (like ... c6 ideas).}) ({For} 6. e3 {, see Nimzo 4.e3 d5 in Part 1. So, we can simply transpose to the Nimzo 4.e3 d5 , but I believe that the additional option of cxd5 is worth exploring.}) 6... exd5 7. e3 {Here, if Black plays either c5 or O-O , White will reply with Bd3 with a transposition to the Nimzo 4. e3  d5 , as seen in Part I .} Bf5 {Black needs to play this to prevent a carefree Bd3 . The bishop trade suits Black, and he did not spend time on... b6 -... Ba6 , as seen in the Nimzo 4.e3 d5 . For this reason, White needs to try some artificial setups, which are also very promising.} 8. f3 {White obtains a standard pawn structure. In the future, of course, e4 is an idea, but so is g4 !?, targeting the Bf5 . All in all, this is a useful move. White prepares g4 , Ne2 - Ng3 (or Nf4 ), or Bd3 for future occasions. Black can play here with ... O-O or without.} (8. Bd3 $6 {is not that good now as Black did not spend time on ... b6 to trade bishops.} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 O-O 10. Ne2 c5 11. O-O Nc6 {and Black saved up on the ... b6 move!}) 8... Nc6 {Delaying castling is also possible.} 9. Ra2 ({The rook swings via the second rank to support the kingside. Now, g4 is an idea. The immediate} 9. g4 $2 {runs into} Nxg4 $1 {and Black wins!}) (9. Ne2 h5 $1 10. Ra2 {is less accurate.}) 9... O-O 10. g4 Bg6 11. Ne2 {White is slightly better.} *

