1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {This line is sometimes employed by Ragozin players wanting to avoid the Nimzo or sometimes the Catalan. We can simply transpose here to the Nimzo e3 in a couple of ways.} 4. a3 {I would begin with this move to make sure we get the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {Black has a lot of options now. The most standard is, of course, Nf6 , but let's look at alternatives.} Nf6 6. cxd5 ({In the d4} 6. cxd5 {c4 e6 Nc3 Bb4 move order, we have an option of capturing on d5 early, at the same time avoiding some of the lines that are in the Nimzo (like ... c6 ideas).}) ({For} 6. e3 {, see Nimzo 4.e3 d5 in Part 1. So, we can simply transpose to the Nimzo 4.e3 d5 , but I believe that the additional option of cxd5 is worth exploring.}) 6... exd5 7. e3 {Here, if Black plays either c5 or O-O , White will reply with Bd3 with a transposition to the Nimzo 4. e3  d5 , as seen in Part I .} Bf5 {Black needs to play this to prevent a carefree Bd3 . The bishop trade suits Black, and he did not spend time on... b6 -... Ba6 , as seen in the Nimzo 4.e3 d5 . For this reason, White needs to try some artificial setups, which are also very promising.} 8. f3 {White obtains a standard pawn structure. In the future, of course, e4 is an idea, but so is g4 !?, targeting the Bf5 . All in all, this is a useful move. White prepares g4 , Ne2 - Ng3 (or Nf4 ), or Bd3 for future occasions. Black can play here with ... O-O or without.} (8. Bd3 $6 {is not that good now as Black did not spend time on ... b6 to trade bishops.} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 O-O 10. Ne2 c5 11. O-O Nc6 {and Black saved up on the ... b6 move!}) 8... O-O 9. Ne2 {Again, preparing g4 .} Nc6 {This is probably the best option for Black here. The idea is to go for ... Na5 and exploit the light squares, potentially later playing ... c5 , or bring the knight to e7 , which engines claim to be acceptable as well, supporting the center and kingside in some way.} 10. Ra2 {Again, this is a useful move. Now, we are ready to play g4 .} Ne7 ({Probably Black should bring the knight to the kingside/center in this fashion.} 10... Na5 {is not good here.} 11. g4 Bg6 12. Nf4 {is again very comfortable for White.}) 11. Rb2 {I would begin with this intermezzo before playing g4 . I think the rook is better placed here as sometimes there are no ... Bb5 ideas.} ({After} 11. g4 Bd7 12. Ng3 c5 13. Bd3 {, Black has a nice idea to simplify the position with} cxd4 14. cxd4 Bb5 $1 {, which would never be possible if Rb2 was played earlier!}) 11... c5 {Surprisingly, the engine simply gives away the b7 -pawn! However, it is not a human move as Black's compensation is difficult to imagine...} 12. Rxb7 {The advantage is 0.3 but it has clearly potential to go quickly higher due to the extra pawn. White continues in a standard fashion ( Ng3 - Bd3 , or g4 !?), and it is just a standard position without the b7 -pawn.} *

