1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 Nxd5 {The Semi-Tarrasch is a modern line that was highly popularized in the mid-2010s by Vladimir Kramnik, and until this day, it stays incredibly fashionable. Many top GMs followed suit and employed this opening and the current state of theory is that it holds for Black. It leads to unbalanced positions, however, in which a lot of knowledge and strong play is required by both sides, but in my feeling, if we know some ideas, it could be harder to play it with Black. Especially if we employ the 3.Nc3 move order - that way, we keep more pieces on the board, as we can see shortly. Finally, I must give a nod to other Chessable courses on this topic, especially Leinier Dominguez's and Surya Ganguly's courses, which are on the Semi-Tarrasch from Black's perspective - they are pretty amazing. Honestly, it was hard for me to improve many of the lines. Objectively, I haven't found an advantage - I want to state that clearly at the start. However, my recommendations here pose certain practical problems for Black that could be hard to resolve without prior knowledge.} 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5 7. Rb1 {With this move, we are improving the rook, putting pressure on the b7 -pawn, and most importantly, stopping the ... cxd4 and ... Bb4 operation - which is the main idea for Black. This is only possible with the 3.Nc3 move order.} ({Now Nc6? runs into} 7. d5 $1 {with huge problems. In general, Black needs to be careful with this idea of d5 .}) 7... cxd4 {Generally, taking on d4 so early is not advisable but it has been seen in some games. I must say that it would have been fine after 7.a3 (as Leinier shows in his course) but not here.} 8. cxd4 Nc6 {The only real justification behind taking on d4 . Black wants to steer the game towards ... Bb4 territory.} (8... Be7 {followed by ... O-O would result in a transposition:} 9. Nf3 O-O 10. Bc4 {transposes here.}) 9. Nf3 ({I would go for this. We get an improved version of the normal Semi-Tarrasch with} 9. Nf3 {cxd4 cxd4} Bb4+ {, as with the inclusion of Rb1 we put pressure on the queenside and the knight is not ideal on c6 either, as very often it belongs to d7 .}) 9... Bb4+ 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 O-O 12. Bb5 {An active move that prevents ... b6 for now.} Ne7 {The main move, played by Duda twice. Next, ... b6 -... Bb7 comes with a standard setup.} 13. O-O b6 14. h4 {Launching an attack on the kingside. Quite typical in such structures, as seen in the Grünfeld section in Part 1!} Bb7 15. Rfe1 Rc8 16. h5 h6 {So far we followed the game So-Duda, 2021. White has a lot of choices here.} 17. Ne5 {This was played by Wesley but here Black is fine:} f6 (17... Qd6 18. Rb3 {was So-Duda, 2021.}) 18. Nd7 Rf7 19. d5 Nxd5 20. exd5 Bxd5 {And Black will take on d7 soon. Despite then being down an exchange, an extremely well entrenched Bd5 will offer full compensation.} *

