[ECO "D35"]
[PlyCount "31"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 Nxd5 {The Semi-Tarrasch is a modern line that was highly popularized in the mid-2010s by Vladimir Kramnik, and until this day, it stays incredibly fashionable. Many top GMs followed suit and employed this opening and the current state of theory is that it holds for Black. It leads to unbalanced positions, however, in which a lot of knowledge and strong play is required by both sides, but in my feeling, if we know some ideas, it could be harder to play it with Black. Especially if we employ the 3.Nc3 move order - that way, we keep more pieces on the board, as we can see shortly. Finally, I must give a nod to other Chessable courses on this topic, especially Leinier Dominguez's and Surya Ganguly's courses, which are on the Semi-Tarrasch from Black's perspective - they are pretty amazing. Honestly, it was hard for me to improve many of the lines. Objectively, I haven't found an advantage - I want to state that clearly at the start. However, my recommendations here pose certain practical problems for Black that could be hard to resolve without prior knowledge.} 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5 7. Rb1 {With this move, we are improving the rook, putting pressure on the b7 -pawn, and most importantly, stopping the ... cxd4 and ... Bb4 operation - which is the main idea for Black. This is only possible with the 3.Nc3 move order.} ({Now Nc6? runs into} 7. d5 $1 {with huge problems. In general, Black needs to be careful with this idea of d5 .}) 7... Be7 {By far, the most popular move.} 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bc4 ({The most popular move in this position. At first, I wanted to recommend} 9. h4 $5 {here (and I spent countless hours analyzing it). However, Leinier Dominguez, in his course, found perfect solutions everywhere, and I could not really find any ideas that could potentially improve on Leinier's course. For this reason, I was forced to find another idea, and I am glad to say that I think I did!}) 9... Nc6 (9... b6 $2 {is premature - we can immediately put pressure in the center with} 10. d5 $1) 10. O-O b6 {This used to be popular a couple of years ago but then people realized that this is extremely risky for Black.} 11. d5 Na5 (11... exd5 12. Bxd5 {is, of course, better for White. We'll support the bishop with a pawn on c4 .}) 12. Bd3 c4 13. Bc2 exd5 14. exd5 {The d5 -pawn is pretty strong and with the Na5 offside, Black's kingside is a bit weak, which gives ideas of developing an attack on Black's king.} {Bf6? was tried by Duda, but after d6!± , the d -pawn is even stronger and will be supported by the Bf4 .} Bg4 {This looks logical but the idea behind this move seems to be misunderstood so far.} 15. Re1 {Creating a silent threat...} Nb7 {This falls into White's trap:} 16. Qe2 {And Black faces material losses or gets a terrible strategically position.} *

