ut pressure in the center with} 10. d5 $1) 10. O-O b6 {This used to be popular a couple of years ago but then people realized that this is extremely risky for Black.} 11. d5 Na5 (11... exd5 12. Bxd5 {is, of course, better for White. We'll support the bishop with a pawn on c4 .}) 12. Bd3 c4 13. Bc2 exd5 14. exd5 {The d5 -pawn is pretty strong and with the Na5 offside, Black's kingside is a bit weak, which gives ideas of developing an attack on Black's king.} {Bf6? was tried by Duda, but after d6!± , the d -pawn is even stronger and will be supported by the Bf4 .} Bg4 {This looks logical but the idea behind this move seems to be misunderstood so far.} 15. Re1 {Creating a silent threat...} Bd6 {This natural move was played in Svidler-Wang Hao, 2017. Surprisingly, it is very suspicious for Black.} 16. Qd4 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Re8 {More solid than Wang's choice.} 18. Bh6 ({A stunning move that gives White an advantage. For example: Bf8} 18. Bf4) (18. Qf6 {Rxe8+ Rxe8} Qxf6 {gxf6} 19. Ba4) ({gxh6? would of course give White a crushing attack after the simple} 18. Kh1 {.}) *

