1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 Nxd5 {The Semi-Tarrasch is a modern line that was highly popularized in the mid-2010s by Vladimir Kramnik, and until this day, it stays incredibly fashionable. Many top GMs followed suit and employed this opening and the current state of theory is that it holds for Black. It leads to unbalanced positions, however, in which a lot of knowledge and strong play is required by both sides, but in my feeling, if we know some ideas, it could be harder to play it with Black. Especially if we employ the 3.Nc3 move order - that way, we keep more pieces on the board, as we can see shortly. Finally, I must give a nod to other Chessable courses on this topic, especially Leinier Dominguez's and Surya Ganguly's courses, which are on the Semi-Tarrasch from Black's perspective - they are pretty amazing. Honestly, it was hard for me to improve many of the lines. Objectively, I haven't found an advantage - I want to state that clearly at the start. However, my recommendations here pose certain practical problems for Black that could be hard to resolve without prior knowledge.} 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5 7. Rb1 {With this move, we are improving the rook, putting pressure on the b7 -pawn, and most importantly, stopping the ... cxd4 and ... Bb4 operation - which is the main idea for Black. This is only possible with the 3.Nc3 move order.} ({Now Nc6? runs into} 7. d5 $1 {with huge problems. In general, Black needs to be careful with this idea of d5 .}) 7... Be7 {By far, the most popular move.} 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bc4 ({The most popular move in this position. At first, I wanted to recommend} 9. h4 $5 {here (and I spent countless hours analyzing it). However, Leinier Dominguez, in his course, found perfect solutions everywhere, and I could not really find any ideas that could potentially improve on Leinier's course. For this reason, I was forced to find another idea, and I am glad to say that I think I did!}) 9... Nc6 (9... b6 $2 {is premature - we can immediately put pressure in the center with} 10. d5 $1) 10. O-O b6 {This used to be popular a couple of years ago but then people realized that this is extremely risky for Black.} 11. d5 Na5 (11... exd5 12. Bxd5 {is, of course, better for White. We'll support the bishop with a pawn on c4 .}) 12. Bd3 c4 13. Bc2 exd5 14. exd5 {The d5 -pawn is pretty strong and with the Na5 offside, Black's kingside is a bit weak, which gives ideas of developing an attack on Black's king.} {Bf6? was tried by Duda, but after d6!± , the d -pawn is even stronger and will be supported by the Bf4 .} Bb7 15. Re1 {Black has some choice but I did not find equality.} Qd6 {Setting a blockade and preventing Bf4 . We need to play dynamically as if Black manages to play ... Rad8 , ... Bf6 etc, the d5 -pawn may simply fall leaving White without any compensation.} (15... Bf6 16. d6 $1 {again is great for White,}) 16. Ne5 ({Stronger than} 16. Bf4 Qxf4 17. Rxe7) 16... Qxd5 17. Qg4 Rad8 18. Qh3 {Weakening Black's kingside.} f5 ({The main move.} 18... h6 19. Bf4 {Black is under pressure.}) (18... g6 19. Bh6) 19. Bf4 Bc8 {Here White has some choice.} 20. g4 (20. Qg3 $5 {is an interesting alternative, intending h4 - h5 . The text is perhaps the most challenging. There was a game Petrosyan-Harutyunyan, 2017, beautifully won by Petrosyan. In the game followed:}) 20... Bf6 21. Rbd1 Qc5 22. Nd7 ({A nice tactical idea.} 22. g5 $5 {is also playable:} Bxe5 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 24. Rxe5 Qc6 25. Qe3) 22... Bxd7 23. Bd6 Qc6 24. Bxf8 Kxf8 25. Qxh7 {And White has a very strong attack. Perhaps with perfect play Black may hold, but it looks extremely scary...} *

