1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 Nxd5 {The Semi-Tarrasch is a modern line that was highly popularized in the mid-2010s by Vladimir Kramnik, and until this day, it stays incredibly fashionable. Many top GMs followed suit and employed this opening and the current state of theory is that it holds for Black. It leads to unbalanced positions, however, in which a lot of knowledge and strong play is required by both sides, but in my feeling, if we know some ideas, it could be harder to play it with Black. Especially if we employ the 3.Nc3 move order - that way, we keep more pieces on the board, as we can see shortly. Finally, I must give a nod to other Chessable courses on this topic, especially Leinier Dominguez's and Surya Ganguly's courses, which are on the Semi-Tarrasch from Black's perspective - they are pretty amazing. Honestly, it was hard for me to improve many of the lines. Objectively, I haven't found an advantage - I want to state that clearly at the start. However, my recommendations here pose certain practical problems for Black that could be hard to resolve without prior knowledge.} 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5 7. Rb1 {With this move, we are improving the rook, putting pressure on the b7 -pawn, and most importantly, stopping the ... cxd4 and ... Bb4 operation - which is the main idea for Black. This is only possible with the 3.Nc3 move order.} ({Now Nc6? runs into} 7. d5 $1 {with huge problems. In general, Black needs to be careful with this idea of d5 .}) 7... Be7 {By far, the most popular move.} 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bc4 ({The most popular move in this position. At first, I wanted to recommend} 9. h4 $5 {here (and I spent countless hours analyzing it). However, Leinier Dominguez, in his course, found perfect solutions everywhere, and I could not really find any ideas that could potentially improve on Leinier's course. For this reason, I was forced to find another idea, and I am glad to say that I think I did!}) 9... a6 10. a4 Qc7 {This is similar to the immediate 9...Qc7 , but the inclusion of a4 -... a6 seems to help White as we are able to restrict ... b5 , unlike earlier.} 11. Be2 {The best square for the bishop. Again, with Bd3 we run under ... Nc6 -... Nb4 ideas, while Bb3 with a4 is probably a bit worse.} b6 (11... cxd4 12. cxd4 {does not change much.}) 12. O-O cxd4 (12... Bb7 $2 13. d5) 13. cxd4 Bb7 14. Bd3 {Supporting the center. This looks very nice for White.} Nc6 {Black needs to put pressure on White's center and try ... Nb4 .} 15. Rb3 {This was played by Ding Liren against Wesley So and I like it a lot. White has ideas of lifting the rook to the kingside or the center.} Rfd8 16. Bb2 {This seems to help White. We guard the center and keep the rook on the 3rd rank.} Na5 (16... Nb4 $2 17. Bb1) 17. Rc3 Qd7 18. h4 {With initiative.} *

