1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 Nxd5 {The Semi-Tarrasch is a modern line that was highly popularized in the mid-2010s by Vladimir Kramnik, and until this day, it stays incredibly fashionable. Many top GMs followed suit and employed this opening and the current state of theory is that it holds for Black. It leads to unbalanced positions, however, in which a lot of knowledge and strong play is required by both sides, but in my feeling, if we know some ideas, it could be harder to play it with Black. Especially if we employ the 3.Nc3 move order - that way, we keep more pieces on the board, as we can see shortly. Finally, I must give a nod to other Chessable courses on this topic, especially Leinier Dominguez's and Surya Ganguly's courses, which are on the Semi-Tarrasch from Black's perspective - they are pretty amazing. Honestly, it was hard for me to improve many of the lines. Objectively, I haven't found an advantage - I want to state that clearly at the start. However, my recommendations here pose certain practical problems for Black that could be hard to resolve without prior knowledge.} 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5 7. Rb1 {With this move, we are improving the rook, putting pressure on the b7 -pawn, and most importantly, stopping the ... cxd4 and ... Bb4 operation - which is the main idea for Black. This is only possible with the 3.Nc3 move order.} ({Now Nc6? runs into} 7. d5 $1 {with huge problems. In general, Black needs to be careful with this idea of d5 .}) 7... Be7 {By far, the most popular move.} 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bc4 ({The most popular move in this position. At first, I wanted to recommend} 9. h4 $5 {here (and I spent countless hours analyzing it). However, Leinier Dominguez, in his course, found perfect solutions everywhere, and I could not really find any ideas that could potentially improve on Leinier's course. For this reason, I was forced to find another idea, and I am glad to say that I think I did!}) 9... Qc7 ({I think that this is the best move in this position for Black, and it is also recommended by Leinier. The idea is to meet Qe2 with} 9... a6 {and then, if White plays with a4 , the a4 -pawn would become an immediate target as it is not defended by our queen.}) 10. Bb3 {This move has not been played at all - at least, I could not find games in the regular or correspondence databases. However, Leinier briefly discusses it in his course. When looking for ideas here and comparing them with what Leinier had in his course, I had a hard time finding something that he did not cover and found a solution. But this line, as it is nearly non-existent, is pretty much not explored at all, which caught my attention. I mean, of course, Black with perfect play should equalize, but posing practical problems and being prepared until 20+ move should definitely give us some edge in our games.} ({The main move here is} 10. Qe2 {, but I honestly think that these lines are not only well known and worked out, but also Leinier's course simply shows clean paths to equality. For this reason, I would like to recommend Bb3!?}) (10. Bd3 {is not great when Black still has the knight on b8 . Now, after} Nc6 11. O-O cxd4 12. cxd4 Nb4 $1 {, hitting the bishop and the a2 -pawn, Black comfortably equalizes.}) 10... b6 {Black sooner or later needs to play this move to develop the queenside.} 11. O-O Bb7 (11... Ba6 $6 {looks strange as I am not sure what the bishop does on a6 .} 12. Re1 {is just fine.}) 12. Re1 Nd7 {Black completes the development in a standard way. Here, we can proceed in two ways.} 13. Ng5 ({This is extremely tempting, and even though Black can keep the game balanced with perfect play, I think we can put a lot of pressure. Alternatively, I can also recommend} 13. Bc2 $5 {too. Instead of engaging in immediate complications, we go for the long game where, thanks to our strong center, White should be better in the long run. I know we are spending many tempi with the bishop, but on the other hand, we bring pieces to best squares, and Black has not much counterplay as this classical setup with ... Bb7 , ... Qc7 , and ... Nd7 is a bit passive. This position does not require much analysis, and we rely on typical ideas like h4 , Qe2 , Bb2 , Rbd1 , etc.}) 13... h6 {This runs into trouble.} 14. Nxf7 {With a very strong attack.} Kxf7 (14... Rxf7 15. Bxe6) 15. Qh5+ (15. e5 $5 {with similar ideas gives good compensation, too.}) 15... g6 16. Bxe6+ Kxe6 17. Qxg6+ Bf6 18. Bxh6 {Black is under huge pressure. With perfect play he can hold but good luck finding all the best moves...} Rg8 19. d5+ Ke7 20. d6+ Qxd6 21. Qh7+ Bg7 22. Bxg7 {With an ongoing attack.} *

