ition for Black, and it is also recommended by Leinier. The idea is to meet Qe2 with} 9... a6 {and then, if White plays with a4 , the a4 -pawn would become an immediate target as it is not defended by our queen.}) 10. Bb3 {This move has not been played at all - at least, I could not find games in the regular or correspondence databases. However, Leinier briefly discusses it in his course. When looking for ideas here and comparing them with what Leinier had in his course, I had a hard time finding something that he did not cover and found a solution. But this line, as it is nearly non-existent, is pretty much not explored at all, which caught my attention. I mean, of course, Black with perfect play should equalize, but posing practical problems and being prepared until 20+ move should definitely give us some edge in our games.} ({The main move here is} 10. Qe2 {, but I honestly think that these lines are not only well known and worked out, but also Leinier's course simply shows clean paths to equality. For this reason, I would like to recommend Bb3!?}) (10. Bd3 {is not great when Black still has the knight on b8 . Now, after} Nc6 11. O-O cxd4 12. cxd4 Nb4 $1 {, hitting the bishop and the a2 -pawn, Black comfortably equalizes.}) 10... b6 {Black sooner or later needs to play this move to develop the queenside.} 11. O-O Bb7 (11... Ba6 $6 {looks strange as I am not sure what the bishop does on a6 .} 12. Re1 {is just fine.}) 12. Re1 Nd7 {Black completes the development in a standard way. Here, we can proceed in two ways.} 13. Ng5 ({This is extremely tempting, and even though Black can keep the game balanced with perfect play, I think we can put a lot of pressure. Alternatively, I can also recommend} 13. Bc2 $5 {too. Instead of engaging in immediate complications, we go for the long game where, thanks to our strong center, White should be better in the long run. I know we are spending many tempi with the bishop, but on the other hand, we bring pieces to best squares, and Black has not much counterplay as this classical setup with ... Bb7 , ... Qc7 , and ... Nd7 is a bit passive. This position does not require much analysis, and we rely on typical ideas like h4 , Qe2 , Bb2 , Rbd1 , etc.}) 13... Nf6 14. e5 {Giving room for error.} Nd5 {This allows another blow.} 15. Nxh7 Kxh7 16. c4 ({With an attack. Nb4} 16. Qh5+ Kg8 17. Re3 f6 18. Rg3 {is a sample continuation.}) *

