ition for Black, and it is also recommended by Leinier. The idea is to meet Qe2 with} 9... a6 {and then, if White plays with a4 , the a4 -pawn would become an immediate target as it is not defended by our queen.}) 10. Bb3 {This move has not been played at all - at least, I could not find games in the regular or correspondence databases. However, Leinier briefly discusses it in his course. When looking for ideas here and comparing them with what Leinier had in his course, I had a hard time finding something that he did not cover and found a solution. But this line, as it is nearly non-existent, is pretty much not explored at all, which caught my attention. I mean, of course, Black with perfect play should equalize, but posing practical problems and being prepared until 20+ move should definitely give us some edge in our games.} ({The main move here is} 10. Qe2 {, but I honestly think that these lines are not only well known and worked out, but also Leinier's course simply shows clean paths to equality. For this reason, I would like to recommend Bb3!?}) (10. Bd3 {is not great when Black still has the knight on b8 . Now, after} Nc6 11. O-O cxd4 12. cxd4 Nb4 $1 {, hitting the bishop and the a2 -pawn, Black comfortably equalizes.}) 10... b6 {Black sooner or later needs to play this move to develop the queenside.} 11. O-O Nc6 {This is recommended by Leinier.} 12. d5 {The most principled.} Na5 (12... exd5 13. Bxd5 {is typically better for White. We'll push c4 to support our strong bishop.}) 13. Bc2 Ba6 {So far we follow Leinier's recommendation in the main line. Here, he has Re1 Rad8 and Black is doing well, with which I completely agree. However, there is another option for White.} 14. e5 {I would recommend this.} exd5 {Otherwise, d6 .} 15. Re1 {And now we reached a critical position for the entire line. Black has a huge choice here, but the position looks scary for Black in my opinion. The d5 -pawn is under attack, there are ideas of e6 , Ng5 , and attack on the kingside. Without prior knowledge, I think that it is very easy for Black to go wrong.} Rae8 {Surprisingly, this is the best move for Black - but it looks so strange, doesn't it? The d5 -pawn just hangs. Even though it stops Ng5 (as the e5 -pawn hangs in the end), it is also not so clear what Black does next. From White's perspective, this position is very rich in ideas and we can try many things. I would expect some new theory to develop here. However, I would like to show some example lines and ideas that we can try to play here as White.} 16. Qxd5 {This move illustrates Black's point.} Qb7 {Black's idea to meet the capture of the d5 -pawn. It appears that Black is fine - we cannot bring our queen to the kingside comfortably as Black will play ... Rd8 and ... Bd3 .} 17. Qd2 Rd8 18. Qf4 (18. Qe3 Qd5 {intending ... Bd3 is fine for Black too.}) 18... Bd3 {And Black is doing great.} *

