ition for Black, and it is also recommended by Leinier. The idea is to meet Qe2 with} 9... a6 {and then, if White plays with a4 , the a4 -pawn would become an immediate target as it is not defended by our queen.}) 10. Bb3 {This move has not been played at all - at least, I could not find games in the regular or correspondence databases. However, Leinier briefly discusses it in his course. When looking for ideas here and comparing them with what Leinier had in his course, I had a hard time finding something that he did not cover and found a solution. But this line, as it is nearly non-existent, is pretty much not explored at all, which caught my attention. I mean, of course, Black with perfect play should equalize, but posing practical problems and being prepared until 20+ move should definitely give us some edge in our games.} ({The main move here is} 10. Qe2 {, but I honestly think that these lines are not only well known and worked out, but also Leinier's course simply shows clean paths to equality. For this reason, I would like to recommend Bb3!?}) (10. Bd3 {is not great when Black still has the knight on b8 . Now, after} Nc6 11. O-O cxd4 12. cxd4 Nb4 $1 {, hitting the bishop and the a2 -pawn, Black comfortably equalizes.}) 10... b6 {Black sooner or later needs to play this move to develop the queenside.} 11. O-O Nc6 {This is recommended by Leinier.} 12. Qe2 {A possible alternative with the intention of preparing d5 . If Black reacts dynamically, he can equalize, however.} Na5 (12... Rd8 13. d5 exd5 14. Bxd5 {and we'll support the bishop with c4 .}) 13. Ba4 Bb7 14. Re1 cxd4 15. cxd4 Rac8 16. Bb5 {This is playable too.} *

