1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 Nxd5 {The Semi-Tarrasch is a modern line that was highly popularized in the mid-2010s by Vladimir Kramnik, and until this day, it stays incredibly fashionable. Many top GMs followed suit and employed this opening and the current state of theory is that it holds for Black. It leads to unbalanced positions, however, in which a lot of knowledge and strong play is required by both sides, but in my feeling, if we know some ideas, it could be harder to play it with Black. Especially if we employ the 3.Nc3 move order - that way, we keep more pieces on the board, as we can see shortly. Finally, I must give a nod to other Chessable courses on this topic, especially Leinier Dominguez's and Surya Ganguly's courses, which are on the Semi-Tarrasch from Black's perspective - they are pretty amazing. Honestly, it was hard for me to improve many of the lines. Objectively, I haven't found an advantage - I want to state that clearly at the start. However, my recommendations here pose certain practical problems for Black that could be hard to resolve without prior knowledge.} 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5 7. Rb1 {With this move, we are improving the rook, putting pressure on the b7 -pawn, and most importantly, stopping the ... cxd4 and ... Bb4 operation - which is the main idea for Black. This is only possible with the 3.Nc3 move order.} ({Now Nc6? runs into} 7. d5 $1 {with huge problems. In general, Black needs to be careful with this idea of d5 .}) 7... Be7 {By far, the most popular move.} 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bc4 ({The most popular move in this position. At first, I wanted to recommend} 9. h4 $5 {here (and I spent countless hours analyzing it). However, Leinier Dominguez, in his course, found perfect solutions everywhere, and I could not really find any ideas that could potentially improve on Leinier's course. For this reason, I was forced to find another idea, and I am glad to say that I think I did!}) 9... Qc7 ({I think that this is the best move in this position for Black, and it is also recommended by Leinier. The idea is to meet Qe2 with} 9... a6 {and then, if White plays with a4 , the a4 -pawn would become an immediate target as it is not defended by our queen.}) 10. Bb3 {This move has not been played at all - at least, I could not find games in the regular or correspondence databases. However, Leinier briefly discusses it in his course. When looking for ideas here and comparing them with what Leinier had in his course, I had a hard time finding something that he did not cover and found a solution. But this line, as it is nearly non-existent, is pretty much not explored at all, which caught my attention. I mean, of course, Black with perfect play should equalize, but posing practical problems and being prepared until 20+ move should definitely give us some edge in our games.} ({The main move here is} 10. Qe2 {, but I honestly think that these lines are not only well known and worked out, but also Leinier's course simply shows clean paths to equality. For this reason, I would like to recommend Bb3!?}) (10. Bd3 {is not great when Black still has the knight on b8 . Now, after} Nc6 11. O-O cxd4 12. cxd4 Nb4 $1 {, hitting the bishop and the a2 -pawn, Black comfortably equalizes.}) 10... b6 {Black sooner or later needs to play this move to develop the queenside.} 11. O-O Nc6 {This is recommended by Leinier.} 12. Qe2 {A possible alternative with the intention of preparing d5 . If Black reacts dynamically, he can equalize, however.} Na5 (12... Rd8 13. d5 exd5 14. Bxd5 {and we'll support the bishop with c4 .}) 13. Ba4 cxd4 14. cxd4 Qc4 {Black should be fine. However, please note two things: one, this may not be so easy to find, and two, even here the game goes on.} 15. Qd1 {Hoping for ... Qxa2 .} ({We can also play} 15. Qxc4 Nxc4 16. Bc6 Rb8 17. Bf4 Bd6 18. Bxd6 Nxd6 19. Rfc1 {with an equal but playable endgame.}) 15... Bb7 (15... Qxa2 $6 {is too greedy.} 16. Rb2 Qc4 17. Ne5 Qc3 18. Re1 {gives us compensation.}) 16. Re1 Qxa2 17. Bf4 {With some compensation.} *

