{With potentially strong pressure on the kingside. And if Re8 then Kf2⩲ is just fine. Our king is pretty safe on f2 .} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 c6 7. Bd3 Nbd7 {In this move order, I discuss plans where Black does not castle kingside.} 8. Nge2 Nh5 {One of the plans where Black does not castle kingside (or at least delays it) is to play ... Nh5 forcing the bishop trade. After this trade, Black generally waits for White to castle, intending to mirror what White is doing with his king. The trade of bishops, on one hand, helps Black to get some room for his pieces, but it also trades the 'wrong' bishop, leaving the bad Bc8 on the board.} 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Qd2 {I like this move for White. White's queen is ideally placed on d2 to support this plan and to cover the dark squares on the kingside which might become weak after we achieve f3 and e4 . The plan is very straightforward and there is not much Black can do: O-O , f3 , Rae1 and prepare e4 .} O-O {This gives White a chance to attack on the kingside.} 11. g4 Nhf6 12. f3 *

