1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 c6 7. Bd3 Nbd7 {In this move order, I discuss plans where Black does not castle kingside.} 8. Nge2 Nh5 {One of the plans where Black does not castle kingside (or at least delays it) is to play ... Nh5 forcing the bishop trade. After this trade, Black generally waits for White to castle, intending to mirror what White is doing with his king. The trade of bishops, on one hand, helps Black to get some room for his pieces, but it also trades the 'wrong' bishop, leaving the bad Bc8 on the board.} 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Qd2 {I like this move for White. White's queen is ideally placed on d2 to support this plan and to cover the dark squares on the kingside which might become weak after we achieve f3 and e4 . The plan is very straightforward and there is not much Black can do: O-O , f3 , Rae1 and prepare e4 .} g6 ({Black should wait for White to castle.} 10... Nb6 11. O-O O-O 12. f3 $1 {with the same plan as usual.} f5 13. Rae1 Bd7 14. b3 Rae8 15. Nd1) 11. O-O O-O 12. f3 Nb6 {We could play 13. e4 , but we don't need to rush it and I think it makes a lot of sense to play b3 !? now.} 13. b3 {Restricting the knight. We can play e4 any moment - we could play Rae1 , maybe even Nd1 - Nf2 , or try even g4 at some point.} *

