1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 c6 7. Bd3 Nbd7 {In this move order, I discuss plans where Black does not castle kingside.} 8. Nge2 Nf8 {Before castling, Black brings the knight to e6 with a tempo on the bishop. I think that this is perhaps the best way to play without castling right away.} (8... h6 9. Bh4 Nh5 {can be played too, but it does not change much. We play anyway} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Qd2 {and the presence of a pawn on h6 does not really matter.}) (8... O-O {transposes to 6... O-O .}) 9. O-O Ne6 10. Bh4 {What I like about positions with Nge2 is that we can choose between playing f3 - e4 and the minority attack, or when suitable try to execute them both. It is a very flexible setup.} O-O {This can be played as well. Here I would go for a similar idea as after 10... g6 .} 11. Qb1 {Threatening Bxf6 and Bxh7 .} g6 12. b4 {We launch the minority attack, keeping an option of f3 - e4 for later.} Nh5 (12... b5 $2 13. a4 {attacking on the queenside.}) 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. b5 {White succeeded with the minority pawn attack, and the c6 -pawn will be a weakness for the rest of the game.} *

