1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 c6 7. Bd3 Nbd7 {In this move order, I discuss plans where Black does not castle kingside.} 8. Nge2 Nf8 {Before castling, Black brings the knight to e6 with a tempo on the bishop. I think that this is perhaps the best way to play without castling right away.} (8... h6 9. Bh4 Nh5 {can be played too, but it does not change much. We play anyway} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Qd2 {and the presence of a pawn on h6 does not really matter.}) (8... O-O {transposes to 6... O-O .}) 9. O-O Ne6 10. Bh4 {What I like about positions with Nge2 is that we can choose between playing f3 - e4 and the minority attack, or when suitable try to execute them both. It is a very flexible setup.} g6 {Black prepares ... Ng7 -... Nf5 (or ... Bf5 ). The most standard reaction now would be f3 with the idea of e4 , but I think that in this line we should try to put pressure on the queenside first.} 11. b4 {A tricky move, putting Black under some pressure.} a6 {There is hardly anything else as the b4 pawn is untouchable and b5 is a huge strategic threat that must be dealt with.} (11... Bxb4 $4 {loses to the brilliant} 12. Nxd5 $3 {. And} b5 13. a4 {is strategically hopeless for Black as well.}) 12. Qb1 {White continues with the minority attack, but first the b4 -pawn should be guarded. I would choose this over the more standard 12. Rb1 as in case Black plays ... b5 we respond with a4 , the a-file will open, and we will be ready to take the fight for it.} b5 13. a4 Bd7 {In this way, Black can prevent White's b5 , but the issue is that Black's knights are far away from the queenside and cannot jump quickly to the c4 outpost. White has many good plans, but I especially like the following.} 14. Rc1 O-O 15. Rc2 {White attempts to take control over the a-file and later will try to bring the knight somehow to c5 (for instance, Nc1 - Nd3 - Nc5 ).} *

