1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 c6 7. Bd3 Nbd7 {In this move order, I discuss plans where Black does not castle kingside.} 8. Nge2 Nf8 {Before castling, Black brings the knight to e6 with a tempo on the bishop. I think that this is perhaps the best way to play without castling right away.} (8... h6 9. Bh4 Nh5 {can be played too, but it does not change much. We play anyway} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Qd2 {and the presence of a pawn on h6 does not really matter.}) (8... O-O {transposes to 6... O-O .}) 9. O-O Ne6 10. Bh4 {What I like about positions with Nge2 is that we can choose between playing f3 - e4 and the minority attack, or when suitable try to execute them both. It is a very flexible setup.} g6 {Black prepares ... Ng7 -... Nf5 (or ... Bf5 ). The most standard reaction now would be f3 with the idea of e4 , but I think that in this line we should try to put pressure on the queenside first.} 11. b4 {A tricky move, putting Black under some pressure.} a6 {There is hardly anything else as the b4 pawn is untouchable and b5 is a huge strategic threat that must be dealt with.} (11... Bxb4 $4 {loses to the brilliant} 12. Nxd5 $3 {. And} b5 13. a4 {is strategically hopeless for Black as well.}) 12. Qb1 {White continues with the minority attack, but first the b4 -pawn should be guarded. I would choose this over the more standard 12. Rb1 as in case Black plays ... b5 we respond with a4 , the a-file will open, and we will be ready to take the fight for it.} O-O 13. a4 Ng7 {Continuing with the plan.} 14. f3 ({Even though} 14. b5 {was possible, I would recommend this move instead, aimed against ... Bf5 and ... Nf5 ideas. We can bring the bishop to f2 any moment, and we prepare not only b5 , but also e4 . Meanwhile, it is not clear what Black is doing.}) 14... Nf5 (14... Bf5 15. e4) 15. Bf2 {Here, not only White can play via e4 , but also b5 , or even a5 - Na4 - Nc5 , everywhere with an advantage.} *

