1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 {The most popular move here, but Black can try so many move orders that I tried to simplify what we are doing as White: our plan is Bd3 , Nge2 and O-O on nearly anything and there would be some transpositions.} ({Black can begin with} 7... h6 8. Bh4 {but we should anyway transpose as we play Nge2 on nearly anything.}) ({Beginning with} 7... Re8 8. Nge2 {should also transpose as Black needs ... c6 sooner or later.}) 8. Nge2 Re8 9. O-O a5 {Black stops the minority attack before it even started. Also, getting space on the queenside is one of the standard ideas in the Carlsbad.} 10. f3 b5 {This was tried recently in Tabatabaei-Esipenko (2023). The idea is to save a tempo on ... h6 as White likely may play Bh4 - Bf2 . However, in fact, we don't need to do it in this case.} (10... Nbd7 11. a4 {transposes to 9... Nbd7 .}) (10... Nh5 $6 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. e4) 11. Ng3 {Preparing e4 , but also keeping in mind Nf5 .} Nbd7 ({After} 11... h6 12. Bf4 {our bishop is safe as Black does not have ... Nh5 and we play via e4 soon.}) 12. Rc1 {This looks slightly better for White. I don't see any benefit of delaying ... h6 .} *

