1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 {The most popular move here, but Black can try so many move orders that I tried to simplify what we are doing as White: our plan is Bd3 , Nge2 and O-O on nearly anything and there would be some transpositions.} ({Black can begin with} 7... h6 8. Bh4 {but we should anyway transpose as we play Nge2 on nearly anything.}) ({Beginning with} 7... Re8 8. Nge2 {should also transpose as Black needs ... c6 sooner or later.}) 8. Nge2 Re8 9. O-O Nbd7 {This is the most classical setup for Black. Here, instead of the classical and well studied Qc2 , I would recommend a bit unusual plan for White, but it makes perfect sense when you understand what Black is trying to do.} 10. a4 {A purely prophylactic move. The idea is simply to stop ... b5 (which very often offers strong counterplay) and focus on playing via f3 - e4 . It appears that the b4 -square becomes weak, but in fact it is irrelevant as Black's knight has already moved to d7 .} (10. f3 b5 $5 {is sort of double-edged as Black quickly expands on the queenside, potentially playing ... c5 later.}) 10... Nh5 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. a5 {This is nearly the same position with the pawn on h6 , not much changes. Check it out here.} *

