1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 {The most popular move here, but Black can try so many move orders that I tried to simplify what we are doing as White: our plan is Bd3 , Nge2 and O-O on nearly anything and there would be some transpositions.} ({Black can begin with} 7... h6 8. Bh4 {but we should anyway transpose as we play Nge2 on nearly anything.}) ({Beginning with} 7... Re8 8. Nge2 {should also transpose as Black needs ... c6 sooner or later.}) 8. Nge2 h6 {Recently, the main theory advocates for including this move. It is debatable whether it helps Black or not, but one thing for sure - now Black cannot play with ... g6 and White's bishop has faster path towards the f2 -square ( f3 - Bf2 ).} (8... Nbd7 {can be played too but after} 9. O-O {we transpose after either} h6 {or Re8 . And if Nh5 then Bxe7 Qxe7} 10. Qd2 {with the plan of f3 - e4 ; I analyzed similar positions in the section where Black delays castling.}) 9. Bh4 {Here Black has a huge choice.} Ne8 {This idea is quite fashionable recently. Black brings the knight to d6 where it is well-placed to face a minority attack. I think that both Bg3 and Bxe7 offer some edge to White.} 10. Bg3 Nd6 11. O-O Re8 12. Qc2 Bf8 {The main position in this line. Now we have to choose our plan. Engines are not much help here, as there are countless suggested moves with more or less equal evaluations. For this reason, I tried to look for some logical human ideas. Unfortunately, it is not so easy to play f3 - e4 , but I think the minority pawn attack is the simplest approach.} 13. b4 {This was tried recently in Vitiugov-Gledura (2023) and I think it offers good practical chances.} Na6 14. a3 {We should not give away the bishop pair with Bxa6 as Black can always play ... a5 later and all light squares become weak on top of that.} b5 {This is possible (with the idea of ... Nc4 ), but it weakens the c6 -pawn and the c5 -square.} 15. Bxd6 ({A radical approach, but it works.} 15. h3 $5 {is also playable, with the idea of meeting} Nc4 {with} 16. Bxc4 bxc4 17. Qa4 {with some pressure as well.}) 15... Bxd6 16. Nc1 {Intending Nb3 next, to control the c5 -square.} Nc7 17. Nb3 Ne6 18. Ne2 {Removing the knight from the c-file and exposing Black's weakness on c6 . White is slightly better.} *

