1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 {The most popular move here, but Black can try so many move orders that I tried to simplify what we are doing as White: our plan is Bd3 , Nge2 and O-O on nearly anything and there would be some transpositions.} ({Black can begin with} 7... h6 8. Bh4 {but we should anyway transpose as we play Nge2 on nearly anything.}) ({Beginning with} 7... Re8 8. Nge2 {should also transpose as Black needs ... c6 sooner or later.}) 8. Nge2 h6 {Recently, the main theory advocates for including this move. It is debatable whether it helps Black or not, but one thing for sure - now Black cannot play with ... g6 and White's bishop has faster path towards the f2 -square ( f3 - Bf2 ).} (8... Nbd7 {can be played too but after} 9. O-O {we transpose after either} h6 {or Re8 . And if Nh5 then Bxe7 Qxe7} 10. Qd2 {with the plan of f3 - e4 ; I analyzed similar positions in the section where Black delays castling.}) 9. Bh4 {Here Black has a huge choice.} Ne8 {This idea is quite fashionable recently. Black brings the knight to d6 where it is well-placed to face a minority attack. I think that both Bg3 and Bxe7 offer some edge to White.} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O Nd6 {Here, we should not go for the f3 - e4 plan as Black is just on time with ... Bf5 trading the bishops. Instead, we need to go for the minority attack.} 12. b4 {This was played by Anish Giri and I like it too.} a6 {Ideally, Black should try to trade the a-pawns in the event of a minority attack to reduce the number of weaknesses.} (12... Bf5 13. Bxf5 Nxf5 14. b5 {seems slightly better for White as Black has not exchanged the a-pawns, which gives White additional targets and ideas.}) 13. Qc2 {I would begin with this move, preventing ... Bf5 , at least temporarily.} (13. a4 {This was played by Anish. Of course it is playable, but without the a-pawns, as in the following line, it seems like Black's position is too solid for us to hope for anything.} Bf5 14. Bxf5 Nxf5 15. b5 axb5 16. axb5 Nd7 17. bxc6 bxc6 {This is a worse version of what I recommend in the main line as Black's pieces are well-placed. Black should be able to hold quite comfortably, and this indeed happened in Giri-Tabatabaei (2023).}) 13... Qg5 ({After} 13... g6 14. Ng3 {we don't allow ... Bf5 .} h5 {doesn’t work here due to} 15. Bxg6 $1) 14. a4 ({Unfortunately,} 14. Ng3 {runs into} h5 {and Black is doing well.}) 14... Bf5 15. Bxf5 Qxf5 {The endgame is uncomfortable for Black.} 16. Qxf5 Nxf5 17. Nc1 ({We don't need to rush with b5 ; in fact, Nc1 !? with the idea of Nd3 looks good too.} 17. b5 {right away is fine too, of course.}) 17... Nd7 18. Nd3 Nd6 {And here we can play 19. b5 right away, or keep options open.} 19. b5 ({White is a bit better, typically for the Carlsbad when the minority attack succeeds. axb5 Rfc8 bxc6 bxc6 a5⩲ axb5} 19. Nb5 Nxb5 {cxb5} 20. Rab1 {Ra5 Rfc1⩲}) (19. Rfe1 Nf6 20. f3 Rfe8 21. Kf2 {with a playable endgame in which, in my opinion, White's position is preferable, although objectively it should be close to equality.}) *

