1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 {The most popular move here, but Black can try so many move orders that I tried to simplify what we are doing as White: our plan is Bd3 , Nge2 and O-O on nearly anything and there would be some transpositions.} ({Black can begin with} 7... h6 8. Bh4 {but we should anyway transpose as we play Nge2 on nearly anything.}) ({Beginning with} 7... Re8 8. Nge2 {should also transpose as Black needs ... c6 sooner or later.}) 8. Nge2 h6 {Recently, the main theory advocates for including this move. It is debatable whether it helps Black or not, but one thing for sure - now Black cannot play with ... g6 and White's bishop has faster path towards the f2 -square ( f3 - Bf2 ).} (8... Nbd7 {can be played too but after} 9. O-O {we transpose after either} h6 {or Re8 . And if Nh5 then Bxe7 Qxe7} 10. Qd2 {with the plan of f3 - e4 ; I analyzed similar positions in the section where Black delays castling.}) 9. Bh4 {Here Black has a huge choice.} Nh5 {Black forces the bishop trade.} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {This is a somewhat better version for Black with the pawn on h6 rather than the pawn on h7 , since White does not have Qb1 with tempo, with the quick b4 - b5 to follow. However, we proceed with the standard plan, preparing f3 - e4 .} 11. O-O Nd7 (11... Bg4 {was tried by Wang Hao, but after} 12. Qb3 $5 Bxe2 13. Nxe2 {White seems to be better as Black faces issues with developing his queenside due to the weakened b7 -pawn.}) 12. Qd2 Re8 {Otherwise White may play f3 .} 13. Rae1 {Here, of course we want to play e4 and that's why Rae1 was played. We need to remove the knight from e2 , however. And this is a bit tricky - generally we want Nc1 , but not always.} Nf8 {This knight move appeared in Carlsen-Kramnik (2022) and I like what Magnus did here.} 14. Nc1 Nf6 15. f3 Ne6 16. N1e2 ({Guarding the d4 -pawn and preparing e4 . But we don't even have to rush with e4 - check out the following line to see how Magnus managed to get a promising position. b5 Ng3 a5} 16. Qf2 {Ba6 Nf5} Qd8 {Ne2⩲}) *

