1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 {The most popular move here, but Black can try so many move orders that I tried to simplify what we are doing as White: our plan is Bd3 , Nge2 and O-O on nearly anything and there would be some transpositions.} ({Black can begin with} 7... h6 8. Bh4 {but we should anyway transpose as we play Nge2 on nearly anything.}) ({Beginning with} 7... Re8 8. Nge2 {should also transpose as Black needs ... c6 sooner or later.}) 8. Nge2 h6 {Recently, the main theory advocates for including this move. It is debatable whether it helps Black or not, but one thing for sure - now Black cannot play with ... g6 and White's bishop has faster path towards the f2 -square ( f3 - Bf2 ).} (8... Nbd7 {can be played too but after} 9. O-O {we transpose after either} h6 {or Re8 . And if Nh5 then Bxe7 Qxe7} 10. Qd2 {with the plan of f3 - e4 ; I analyzed similar positions in the section where Black delays castling.}) 9. Bh4 {Here Black has a huge choice.} Nh5 {Black forces the bishop trade.} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {This is a somewhat better version for Black with the pawn on h6 rather than the pawn on h7 , since White does not have Qb1 with tempo, with the quick b4 - b5 to follow. However, we proceed with the standard plan, preparing f3 - e4 .} 11. O-O Nd7 (11... Bg4 {was tried by Wang Hao, but after} 12. Qb3 $5 Bxe2 13. Nxe2 {White seems to be better as Black faces issues with developing his queenside due to the weakened b7 -pawn.}) 12. Qd2 Re8 {Otherwise White may play f3 .} 13. Rae1 {Here, of course we want to play e4 and that's why Rae1 was played. We need to remove the knight from e2 , however. And this is a bit tricky - generally we want Nc1 , but not always.} Ndf6 {Probably the best move. Now, playing Nc1 does not offer much due to ... Ne4 ! which was played many times and Black equalizes comfortably. Because of this, we need to try something else - and there are many options.} 14. Bc2 {I like this waiting move. We are not declaring yet our intentions, in the event of ... Ne4 our bishop will not fall under attack, and we actually create a devious threat of f3 ! Additionally, in some lines we may use the d3 -square for the knight.} ({I think that Black is fine after} 14. Nc1 Ne4 $1) 14... Bd7 ({Simple development is perhaps the way to go. White is generally happy after} 14... Ne4 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. b4 {and we switch to the queenside play.}) ({For illustrative purposes, I want to show what happens after} 14... a5 $6 {which is a move that is a kind of waste of time for Black. Now we play} 15. f3 $1 Qxe3+ 16. Qxe3 Rxe3 17. g4 {and White wins a piece. Now, the bishop is on c2 where it is not hit by Re3 . Black must sacrifice the piece on g4 now hoping for some compensation, but without doubt White is better and Black can only pray to survive here.}) ({Finally, after} 14... g6 15. Nc1 $1 {White is doing great.}) 15. Qd1 ({Stepping aside from ... Ne4 coming with a tempo and putting pressure on Nh5 . Unfortunately,} 15. f3 {does not work tactically:} Qxe3+ 16. Qxe3 Rxe3 17. g4 Rae8 $1 {Thanks to this move and the pressure on the e-file, Black is fine.} 18. gxh5 Bh3) 15... g6 (15... Qd6 16. h3) 16. Nc1 Ne4 17. Nd3 {The knight reached d3 -square and we prepare f3 - e4 .} *

