1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 {The most popular move here, but Black can try so many move orders that I tried to simplify what we are doing as White: our plan is Bd3 , Nge2 and O-O on nearly anything and there would be some transpositions.} ({Black can begin with} 7... h6 8. Bh4 {but we should anyway transpose as we play Nge2 on nearly anything.}) ({Beginning with} 7... Re8 8. Nge2 {should also transpose as Black needs ... c6 sooner or later.}) 8. Nge2 h6 {Recently, the main theory advocates for including this move. It is debatable whether it helps Black or not, but one thing for sure - now Black cannot play with ... g6 and White's bishop has faster path towards the f2 -square ( f3 - Bf2 ).} (8... Nbd7 {can be played too but after} 9. O-O {we transpose after either} h6 {or Re8 . And if Nh5 then Bxe7 Qxe7} 10. Qd2 {with the plan of f3 - e4 ; I analyzed similar positions in the section where Black delays castling.}) 9. Bh4 {Here Black has a huge choice.} Re8 (9... Nbd7 {can be played too but again after} 10. O-O {there should be a transposition.}) 10. O-O Nbd7 {The inclusion of ... h6 and Bh4 does not change much, and I would recommend stopping ... b5 right away.} 11. a4 {This is not the most obvious move here, as it weakens the b4 -square and normally White should go for minority attack on the queenside, not a “weird” a4 . However, the idea is somewhat deep. The point is that Black actually wants to play ... b5 , ... a5 , etc (as shown here after 10...a5 ) and with 11.a4 we are stopping it. And in case of ... a5 , Black’s knight is not getting to b4 , and the b4 -square in that case is not relevant.} Nh5 (11... Ne4 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Bc4 {looks slightly better for White too. We will put pressure on the queenside.}) 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. a5 {White gained space on the queenside which gives some strategic advantage. One of the main ideas for White here is Nc1 - Nb3 , after which we can exploit the c5 -square in many positions and also prepare f3 - e4 with Qd2 , Rae1 . Also, we may consider a6 !? to weaken Black's queenside.} a6 {This move seems kind of human, stopping a6 . But now the queenside pawn structure is really bad for Black.} 14. Nc1 {With tempo we are rerouting the knight to b3 .} Qg5 15. Nb3 Ndf6 {This looks aggressive but we can dismantle Black's ambitions!} 16. f4 Qh4 17. Qe1 ({Pretty much forcing a queen trade (as} 17. Qg4 {leads nowhere) and with a better endgame:} Qe1 18. Raxe1) *

