[Black "QGD Carlsbad - Classical setu"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D35"]
[PlyCount "35"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 {The most popular move here, but Black can try so many move orders that I tried to simplify what we are doing as White: our plan is Bd3 , Nge2 and O-O on nearly anything and there would be some transpositions.} ({Black can begin with} 7... h6 8. Bh4 {but we should anyway transpose as we play Nge2 on nearly anything.}) ({Beginning with} 7... Re8 8. Nge2 {should also transpose as Black needs ... c6 sooner or later.}) 8. Nge2 h6 {Recently, the main theory advocates for including this move. It is debatable whether it helps Black or not, but one thing for sure - now Black cannot play with ... g6 and White's bishop has faster path towards the f2 -square ( f3 - Bf2 ).} (8... Nbd7 {can be played too but after} 9. O-O {we transpose after either} h6 {or Re8 . And if Nh5 then Bxe7 Qxe7} 10. Qd2 {with the plan of f3 - e4 ; I analyzed similar positions in the section where Black delays castling.}) 9. Bh4 {Here Black has a huge choice.} Re8 (9... Nbd7 {can be played too but again after} 10. O-O {there should be a transposition.}) 10. O-O a5 {By delaying a bit the development of Nb8 Black keeps an option of ... Na6 if needed. This means that ideas of a4 are not a thing here.} 11. f3 {Getting ready for e4 and bringing the bishop to f2 . In this way, we are preventing all ideas where Black trades the bishops.} b5 (11... Nbd7 $6 12. a4 $1 {see Nbd7 line .}) 12. Bf2 Nbd7 13. Rc1 {White obtained a comfortable setup. The e4 idea is almost ready - the only thing we need is the g4 -square covered in case there are trades on e4 . White has a relatively easy plan to follow: Ng3 (or Nf4 !? sometimes), Nce2 , maybe Kh1 or h3 , Re1 could be useful too. Preventing the ... c5 pawn break should be really taken into consideration. So far, Black played 13... Nb6 , 13... Ba6 and 13... a4 . Let's explore these moves.} a4 {Gaining space on the queenside.} 14. Nf4 {Again, preparing e4 .} Nb6 {Black prevents e4 as after all trades on e4 there would follow ... Ng4 . Additionally, Nc4 is an idea, which White should stop.} 15. b3 {This position looks good for White, as it is not clear what Black is doing. However, White has many possible plans and ideas. Firstly, we intend to prepare e4 , but this is not the only idea. We can play with Nce2 - Ng3 , put pressure on the c-file, or even try the aggressive g4 !?.} Ba3 {It is useful to worsen the position of the rook, but it does not matter much.} 16. Rb1 {We need the c2 -square for the queen.} Bd6 17. Qc2 Bd7 18. Kh1 {With a playable position, but as I said earlier, it is not easy to play it with Black, while we can try many ideas. Nce2 is always on the agenda. Preparing e4 is the main idea, but there are also ideas of g4 - Rg1 !? with a potential initiative on the kingside.} *

