1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 {The most popular move here, but Black can try so many move orders that I tried to simplify what we are doing as White: our plan is Bd3 , Nge2 and O-O on nearly anything and there would be some transpositions.} ({Black can begin with} 7... h6 8. Bh4 {but we should anyway transpose as we play Nge2 on nearly anything.}) ({Beginning with} 7... Re8 8. Nge2 {should also transpose as Black needs ... c6 sooner or later.}) 8. Nge2 h6 {Recently, the main theory advocates for including this move. It is debatable whether it helps Black or not, but one thing for sure - now Black cannot play with ... g6 and White's bishop has faster path towards the f2 -square ( f3 - Bf2 ).} (8... Nbd7 {can be played too but after} 9. O-O {we transpose after either} h6 {or Re8 . And if Nh5 then Bxe7 Qxe7} 10. Qd2 {with the plan of f3 - e4 ; I analyzed similar positions in the section where Black delays castling.}) 9. Bh4 {Here Black has a huge choice.} Re8 (9... Nbd7 {can be played too but again after} 10. O-O {there should be a transposition.}) 10. O-O a5 {By delaying a bit the development of Nb8 Black keeps an option of ... Na6 if needed. This means that ideas of a4 are not a thing here.} 11. f3 {Getting ready for e4 and bringing the bishop to f2 . In this way, we are preventing all ideas where Black trades the bishops.} b5 (11... Nbd7 $6 12. a4 $1 {see Nbd7 line .}) 12. Bf2 Nbd7 13. Rc1 {White obtained a comfortable setup. The e4 idea is almost ready - the only thing we need is the g4 -square covered in case there are trades on e4 . White has a relatively easy plan to follow: Ng3 (or Nf4 !? sometimes), Nce2 , maybe Kh1 or h3 , Re1 could be useful too. Preventing the ... c5 pawn break should be really taken into consideration. So far, Black played 13... Nb6 , 13... Ba6 and 13... a4 . Let's explore these moves.} Nb6 {The most popular move. The knight heads for the c4 square, while ... b4 is kept as an option, since Na4 would no longer be so dangerous.} 14. Ng3 {Here we go to g3 . We make space for the other knight on e2 . Once this happens, the e4 -pawn break can be potentially lethal.} (14. b3 b4 $1 {is equal as we have to go back with the knight to b1 .}) (14. Nf4 {is not great now as Black can play} Nc4 $1 15. Qc2 (15. Qe2 $2 Bd6 {is even worse.}) 15... Bd6 {with pressure, not only on the e3 -pawn but also on the Nf4 .}) 14... Bd6 {This happened in a game Gumularz-Heberla (2022). I chose this game here as it serves as a perfect example of what can happen if Black does not really do much and stays passive, while White continues with his plan.} 15. b3 Bd7 16. Nce2 Rc8 17. Bb1 Qc7 ({A crucial mistake.} 17... c5 {was perhaps necessary but White is of course still better after} 18. dxc5 Rxc5 19. Qd2) 18. e4 ({And White crashed through in the center with a winning position: Ba3 e5 Bxc1 Nxc1 Nh7} 18. f4 {Gumularz-Heberla (2022).}) *

