1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Bd6 {Plans with Bd6 have always been considered inferior to classic setups with Be7 , as the old theory goes-but of course everything has changed with modern engines that make anything playable. The old logic was that the pin should be dealt with immediately. Recently, however, it has been shown not to be necessary. One of Black's ideas behind ... Bd6 is to prevent (or at least delay) White’s plan to castle kingside when playing Nge2 , because of the potential ideas of ... Bxh2 . This can give Black some time in many lines, since White often spends time on h3 . One of the leading experts in this system is Jeffery Xiong, who has played it successfully numerous times.} ({Black can also begin with} 6... h6 7. Bh4 Bd6 {which should, sooner or later, transpose as ... h6 is a move Black plays anyway.} 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2 Re8 10. h3 {and we are back at the 9... h6 main line.}) 7. Bd3 Nbd7 {With the idea Nf8 - Ne6 . White has many good ways to continue and yet again, I will try to keep things simple and recommend Nge2 plans.} 8. Nge2 Nf8 {Unfortunately, with Bd6 on the board we cannot castle due to ... Bxh2 tactics.} 9. Qc2 {A useful move.} Ne6 10. Bh4 g6 11. f3 {This is also great for White. We may play O-O , but also O-O-O comes into consideration as White's central play via e4 is extremely fast.} *

