1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Bd6 {Plans with Bd6 have always been considered inferior to classic setups with Be7 , as the old theory goes-but of course everything has changed with modern engines that make anything playable. The old logic was that the pin should be dealt with immediately. Recently, however, it has been shown not to be necessary. One of Black's ideas behind ... Bd6 is to prevent (or at least delay) White’s plan to castle kingside when playing Nge2 , because of the potential ideas of ... Bxh2 . This can give Black some time in many lines, since White often spends time on h3 . One of the leading experts in this system is Jeffery Xiong, who has played it successfully numerous times.} ({Black can also begin with} 6... h6 7. Bh4 Bd6 {which should, sooner or later, transpose as ... h6 is a move Black plays anyway.} 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2 Re8 10. h3 {and we are back at the 9... h6 main line.}) 7. Bd3 O-O {White has some choice here. In general, I think it makes sense to recommend 8. Nge2 for this course to keep it simple.} 8. Nge2 {Keeping the repertoire consistent.} Re8 9. h3 {Unfortunately, we need to spend a tempo on this move to be able to castle. This move is less popular than 9. Qc2 , and for this reason is also less explored.} ({Be careful not to fall for} 9. O-O $2 Bxh2+ $1 {and Black wins a pawn.}) ({The main move here is} 9. Qc2 h6 10. Bh4 {where the main line goes as follows:} a5 11. h3 Na6 12. a3 Nc7 13. O-O Ne6 {and there are some tries for White too. If you are interested, you can explore these lines too, but they are beyond the scope of this course, especially because I think 9. h3 is a great practical choice.}) 9... h6 10. Bh4 a5 (10... Nbd7 11. O-O {transposes to Nbd7 O-O h6 line .}) 11. O-O Na6 {This plan is quite decent for Black if White's queen is on c2 , as then White needs to spend a tempo on a3 to avoid ... Nb4 . Here, ... Nb4 is not a concern. For this reason, playing in this case ... Na6 is a bit dubious.} 12. Rc1 Nc7 13. Kh1 {A useful waiting move. By removing the king from the g1 - a7 diagonal, we prepare for opening the center with f3 - e4 . Of course, we cannot do it yet as the e3 -pawn would hang, but it is not clear what Black does now, while we, if given another move, can try Qd2 , f3 and e4 . Please note that the pin from Bh4 is quite annoying, and that is an issue with Bd6 plans.} ({Some samples lines. Ne6} 13. f3 $1 {now Ne6 stands in the way of the Re8 .} Be7 14. Bg3 $1 Nh5 15. Be5 {Apart from e4 , we may try to develop an attack on the kingside with f4 !?, g4 etc.}) ({After Bd7 we can play positionally with} 13. Qd2 {, or tactically with e4! where Black is immediately in trouble. dxe4} Ne4 14. Be7 {Bxf6 Bxf6 Nd6±}) *

