1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Bd6 {Plans with Bd6 have always been considered inferior to classic setups with Be7 , as the old theory goes-but of course everything has changed with modern engines that make anything playable. The old logic was that the pin should be dealt with immediately. Recently, however, it has been shown not to be necessary. One of Black's ideas behind ... Bd6 is to prevent (or at least delay) White’s plan to castle kingside when playing Nge2 , because of the potential ideas of ... Bxh2 . This can give Black some time in many lines, since White often spends time on h3 . One of the leading experts in this system is Jeffery Xiong, who has played it successfully numerous times.} ({Black can also begin with} 6... h6 7. Bh4 Bd6 {which should, sooner or later, transpose as ... h6 is a move Black plays anyway.} 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2 Re8 10. h3 {and we are back at the 9... h6 main line.}) 7. Bd3 O-O {White has some choice here. In general, I think it makes sense to recommend 8. Nge2 for this course to keep it simple.} 8. Nge2 {Keeping the repertoire consistent.} Re8 9. h3 {Unfortunately, we need to spend a tempo on this move to be able to castle. This move is less popular than 9. Qc2 , and for this reason is also less explored.} ({Be careful not to fall for} 9. O-O $2 Bxh2+ $1 {and Black wins a pawn.}) ({The main move here is} 9. Qc2 h6 10. Bh4 {where the main line goes as follows:} a5 11. h3 Na6 12. a3 Nc7 13. O-O Ne6 {and there are some tries for White too. If you are interested, you can explore these lines too, but they are beyond the scope of this course, especially because I think 9. h3 is a great practical choice.}) 9... Nbd7 {The main move. Black is in time to play ... Nf8 when White plays Qc2 , so there is no need for ... h6 .} 10. O-O h6 {Black can also include this move in order to push the bishop back and prevent (at least temporarily) f3 - e4 ideas.} 11. Bh4 Nf8 {The idea is ... Ng6 , as there is no need to worry about Bxg6 . As there is pressure on the e3 -pawn, White cannot play f3 .} 12. Qc2 {A simple prophylaxis against ... Ng6 . Anytime Black plays ... Ne6 we can play f3 , which is our main idea.} Bd7 {Black may somehow try to delay putting anything on the e-file, that would block the Re8 , which prevents f3 . But it is also not really clear what is Black actually doing, while we can improve our position step by step with simple development moves that also do slowly prepare f3 - e4 .} 13. Rad1 ({We can play either} 13. Rad1 {, Rae1 or even Kh1 with similar plans. We intend to meet ... Ne6 with f3 . I think White is slightly better.}) *

