1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Bd6 {Plans with Bd6 have always been considered inferior to classic setups with Be7 , as the old theory goes-but of course everything has changed with modern engines that make anything playable. The old logic was that the pin should be dealt with immediately. Recently, however, it has been shown not to be necessary. One of Black's ideas behind ... Bd6 is to prevent (or at least delay) White’s plan to castle kingside when playing Nge2 , because of the potential ideas of ... Bxh2 . This can give Black some time in many lines, since White often spends time on h3 . One of the leading experts in this system is Jeffery Xiong, who has played it successfully numerous times.} ({Black can also begin with} 6... h6 7. Bh4 Bd6 {which should, sooner or later, transpose as ... h6 is a move Black plays anyway.} 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2 Re8 10. h3 {and we are back at the 9... h6 main line.}) 7. Bd3 O-O {White has some choice here. In general, I think it makes sense to recommend 8. Nge2 for this course to keep it simple.} 8. Nge2 {Keeping the repertoire consistent.} Re8 9. h3 {Unfortunately, we need to spend a tempo on this move to be able to castle. This move is less popular than 9. Qc2 , and for this reason is also less explored.} ({Be careful not to fall for} 9. O-O $2 Bxh2+ $1 {and Black wins a pawn.}) ({The main move here is} 9. Qc2 h6 10. Bh4 {where the main line goes as follows:} a5 11. h3 Na6 12. a3 Nc7 13. O-O Ne6 {and there are some tries for White too. If you are interested, you can explore these lines too, but they are beyond the scope of this course, especially because I think 9. h3 is a great practical choice.}) 9... Nbd7 {The main move. Black is in time to play ... Nf8 when White plays Qc2 , so there is no need for ... h6 .} 10. O-O Nf8 {Black does not spend time on ... h6 and intends to play first ... Ng6 and then ... h6 , getting the bishop pair. However, in this case, our e3 -pawn remains defended by the Bg5 , and we can play f3 - e4 right away!} 11. f3 {The most principled approach, taking advantage of the opportunity.} h6 {The most critical. Black gets the bishop pair but White gets to play e4 .} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. e4 {This looks promising for White and the best thing is that it is completely unexplored territory so very likely our opponent won't be prepared.} Ng6 {Black can sacrifice a piece.} 14. e5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Rxe5 {With some compensation, but I don't think it's enough if we quickly bring our pieces into play on good squares, as I show in the following line.} 16. f4 Re3 17. Qc2 Bd7 18. Rf2 {Doubling the rooks on the f-file.} Rae8 19. Raf1 ({And even though Black's pieces are nicely placed and the bishop pair can be annoying, we have an extra piece after all and I do not really see any particular danger to White. Slowly, we should be able to consolidate and retain our advantage. b5} 19. Nd1 R3e7 20. Kh1 (20. Rf3 $5) {b4 b3} 20... a5 21. Ng3) *

