we can play f3 - e4 right away!} 11. f3 {The most principled approach, taking advantage of the opportunity.} h6 {The most critical. Black gets the bishop pair but White gets to play e4 .} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. e4 {This looks promising for White and the best thing is that it is completely unexplored territory so very likely our opponent won't be prepared.} dxe4 {The most natural response.} 14. fxe4 Qg5 {This is a risky alternative to ... Qe7 .} 15. e5 ({The most critical. With only moves Black can avoid immediate defeat, but his position remains worse.} 15. Kh1 $5 {is also tricky for Black.}) 15... Bxh3 16. Rf2 Rxe5 ({The only move.} 16... Bc7 $2 17. Ne4) 17. dxe5 Bc5 {This is Black's idea.} 18. Qf1 {But with this simple move we hold our kingside together and retain extra material.} Bxf2+ 19. Qxf2 Bxg2 20. Qf4 Bh3+ 21. Qxg5 hxg5 22. Kh2 {Perhaps Black can hold here, but still it is White that has winning chances.} *

