1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Bd6 {Plans with Bd6 have always been considered inferior to classic setups with Be7 , as the old theory goes-but of course everything has changed with modern engines that make anything playable. The old logic was that the pin should be dealt with immediately. Recently, however, it has been shown not to be necessary. One of Black's ideas behind ... Bd6 is to prevent (or at least delay) White’s plan to castle kingside when playing Nge2 , because of the potential ideas of ... Bxh2 . This can give Black some time in many lines, since White often spends time on h3 . One of the leading experts in this system is Jeffery Xiong, who has played it successfully numerous times.} ({Black can also begin with} 6... h6 7. Bh4 Bd6 {which should, sooner or later, transpose as ... h6 is a move Black plays anyway.} 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2 Re8 10. h3 {and we are back at the 9... h6 main line.}) 7. Bd3 O-O {White has some choice here. In general, I think it makes sense to recommend 8. Nge2 for this course to keep it simple.} 8. Nge2 {Keeping the repertoire consistent.} Re8 9. h3 {Unfortunately, we need to spend a tempo on this move to be able to castle. This move is less popular than 9. Qc2 , and for this reason is also less explored.} ({Be careful not to fall for} 9. O-O $2 Bxh2+ $1 {and Black wins a pawn.}) ({The main move here is} 9. Qc2 h6 10. Bh4 {where the main line goes as follows:} a5 11. h3 Na6 12. a3 Nc7 13. O-O Ne6 {and there are some tries for White too. If you are interested, you can explore these lines too, but they are beyond the scope of this course, especially because I think 9. h3 is a great practical choice.}) 9... Nbd7 {The main move. Black is in time to play ... Nf8 when White plays Qc2 , so there is no need for ... h6 .} 10. O-O Nf8 {Black does not spend time on ... h6 and intends to play first ... Ng6 and then ... h6 , getting the bishop pair. However, in this case, our e3 -pawn remains defended by the Bg5 , and we can play f3 - e4 right away!} 11. f3 {The most principled approach, taking advantage of the opportunity.} h6 {The most critical. Black gets the bishop pair but White gets to play e4 .} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. e4 {This looks promising for White and the best thing is that it is completely unexplored territory so very likely our opponent won't be prepared.} dxe4 {The most natural response.} 14. fxe4 Qe7 15. e5 Bc7 {This position looks promising for White. We have a strong center and potential ideas of an attack on the kingside.} 16. Kh1 {Stepping aside as Black intended ... Bb6 with pressure on the g1 - a7 diagonal.} Rd8 17. Qc2 Bb6 18. Ne4 Be6 {This is perhaps the critical position as White can choose between a couple of ideas. I keep the one I think is the strongest as the main one, but I will mention alternatives that you can explore as well on your own.} (18... Ne6 $2 19. Bc4) (18... Bxd4 $2 19. Nd6 $1 {with Nxf7 next.}) 19. Nd6 {The simplest. Nd6 is very strong and Black has to pretty much sacrifice an exchange, but this gives us a material advantage.} (19. Rf4 $5 {is an interesting option too:} Ng6 20. Nf6+ gxf6 21. Rxf6) (19. Nf6+ gxf6 20. exf6 Qd6 21. Rf3 {looks very testing as well.}) 19... Rxd6 20. exd6 Qxd6 21. Nf4 ({Surely Black has some compensation here, but given the position is quite open, and we can easily solve issues with the dark squares on the kingside, White is better. What we need to remember now is to meet Bc7 with} 21. Qc5 $1 {with the advantage.}) *

