1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 {When Black tries to play without ... c6 , there are two ideas for him to choose from: playing via ... c5 (say, ... Be7 , ... O-O , ... b6 and eventually ... c5 ) or ... Bb4 in the style of the Ragozin. The latter has become some sort of trend recently.} Bb4 {Black goes for a Ragozin-style position, looking for more unbalanced positions compared to the established QGD exchange lines. However, the lack of Nf3 makes White's options wider.  This line was chosen by Ian Nepomniachtchi in the game Caruana-Nepomniachtchi (2024), from the last round of the Candidates Tournament.} 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 Bf5 {This move was tried a few times by Alexandr Predke. It is a standard idea in the Ragozin of course, but here the position is a bit different due to the knight still being on g1 .} 8. Qf3 {Similar to the line Bf5 , White uses this advantage to attack the bishop and put pressure on the Nf6 .} Be4 {After other retreats, Bxf6 should give White a favorable endgame.} 9. Bxf6 Qd6 10. Qf4 ({Forcing the endgame with a better pawn structure. In the game Suleymanli-Predke (2022) followed} 10. Be5 {, protecting the bishop, which makes a lot of sense, of course. But Black can force a draw now.} Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qa3 12. Qd1 Qxc3+ 13. Ke2 Qc4+ 14. Ke1 Qc3+ {with a perpetual.}) 10... Qxf4 11. exf4 gxf6 {Here, a3 would give White a better endgame. But I think it is better to keep this idea for later and first play f3 .} 12. f3 {Asking the bishop where it wants to go!} Bf5 {Trying to keep the bishop away from g6 .} 13. g4 Bc8 {But this endgame seems unpleasant for Black due to the bad pawn structure on the kingside.} 14. Nge2 {This move is played with two ideas: a3 and/or Ng3 . The first idea is about trading the dark squared bishop and the second one is about stopping ... f5 .} f5 {Black can play this move now, but we simply turn to the a3 idea.} 15. a3 Bxc3+ (15... Bd6 $5 {is an insane suggestion by the engine.} 16. Nxd5 Nc6 {According to the engine Black's position is not bad despite being down a pawn... but I don't expect many people to give away a pawn just like that! And anyway, White retains some chances.} 17. Ne3 Ne7 18. Kf2) 16. Nxc3 c6 17. Rg1 {White will put pressure on the queenside. Apart from obvious moves like Bd3 or Kf2 , White will try to bring the knight with Nd1 - Ne3 or Ne2 - Ng3 .} *

