1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 {When Black tries to play without ... c6 , there are two ideas for him to choose from: playing via ... c5 (say, ... Be7 , ... O-O , ... b6 and eventually ... c5 ) or ... Bb4 in the style of the Ragozin. The latter has become some sort of trend recently.} Bb4 {Black goes for a Ragozin-style position, looking for more unbalanced positions compared to the established QGD exchange lines. However, the lack of Nf3 makes White's options wider.  This line was chosen by Ian Nepomniachtchi in the game Caruana-Nepomniachtchi (2024), from the last round of the Candidates Tournament.} 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 h5 {Black can begin with this move too.} 9. Be5 {This move was played by Fabiano Caruana in an online blitz game. Even though it was 'only' a blitz game, I would expect Fabiano to really know what he's doing. I looked at this line and in fact it is pretty challenging for Black.} (9. Qb3 $5 {is another option which deserves attention, but I focused on Be5 in this course.}) 9... Nbd7 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Qb3 {This position is pretty much just like a Ragozin, but with pawns on g5 and h5 - which probably is rather weakening than improving Black's position. Now, both the Bb4 and the d5 -pawn are attacked.} Qb6 {This is another typical idea in the Ragozin.} 12. Bd3 {I would recommend this move, intending to take control over the f5 -square.} ({If you turn on the engine, I am sure you would see that the 'best' move here is} 12. h4 $5 {but if you analyze it a bit deeper you will see that it leads to an absolutely crazy position in which anything can happen. Additionally, once you make few moves, you would notice that the eval drops...} gxh4 13. Qxd5 Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 Qb2 15. Rd1 Qxc3+ 16. Rd2 Qc1+ 17. Ke2 {The eval here is at 0.3-0.4 at first, but then it drops. But even without much analysis, we can probably sense that White takes up here a lot of risk as well...} Rh6 $5 {Logical, but not the only move.} (17... Nb6 $5 {appears to work as well.} 18. Qe5+ Be6 19. Qxh8+ Kd7 20. Qh7 Bc4+ 21. Kf3 Bd5+ 22. e4 Be6) 18. Rxh4 Nb6 19. Qb5+ Bd7 20. Qb2 Qc6 21. Ke1 O-O-O {With a messy position.}) 12... c6 13. Bf5 {White wants to make sure Black will not have the bishop pair.} Nf6 ({After} 13... Be7 14. Qc2 $1 {White needs to keep the queens on the board!}) 14. Bxc8 Rxc8 15. h4 {With a slight positional edge. White will try to exploit Black's pawn structure on the queenside. Next comes Nge2 , along with Qc2 . The f5 -square is an issue for Black.} *

