1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 {When Black tries to play without ... c6 , there are two ideas for him to choose from: playing via ... c5 (say, ... Be7 , ... O-O , ... b6 and eventually ... c5 ) or ... Bb4 in the style of the Ragozin. The latter has become some sort of trend recently.} Bb4 {Black goes for a Ragozin-style position, looking for more unbalanced positions compared to the established QGD exchange lines. However, the lack of Nf3 makes White's options wider.  This line was chosen by Ian Nepomniachtchi in the game Caruana-Nepomniachtchi (2024), from the last round of the Candidates Tournament.} 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 h5 {Black can begin with this move too.} 9. Be5 {This move was played by Fabiano Caruana in an online blitz game. Even though it was 'only' a blitz game, I would expect Fabiano to really know what he's doing. I looked at this line and in fact it is pretty challenging for Black.} (9. Qb3 $5 {is another option which deserves attention, but I focused on Be5 in this course.}) 9... Nbd7 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Qb3 {This position is pretty much just like a Ragozin, but with pawns on g5 and h5 - which probably is rather weakening than improving Black's position. Now, both the Bb4 and the d5 -pawn are attacked.} Qd6 {This looks like the most human move: keeping everything defended. Now, White glances at the kingside to weaken it.} (11... Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 {makes little sense for Black - it is better to wait for a3 to capture on c3 to make White lose a tempo.}) 12. h4 gxh4 (12... g4 13. Nge2 {is of course bad for Black.}) 13. a3 Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 {With a nice positional edge. The h4 -pawn will fall, the f4 -square is a strong outpost for White's knight and ideas of c4 in the future will likely cause some problems too.} *

