1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 {When Black tries to play without ... c6 , there are two ideas for him to choose from: playing via ... c5 (say, ... Be7 , ... O-O , ... b6 and eventually ... c5 ) or ... Bb4 in the style of the Ragozin. The latter has become some sort of trend recently.} Bb4 {Black goes for a Ragozin-style position, looking for more unbalanced positions compared to the established QGD exchange lines. However, the lack of Nf3 makes White's options wider.  This line was chosen by Ian Nepomniachtchi in the game Caruana-Nepomniachtchi (2024), from the last round of the Candidates Tournament.} 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 9. a3 {A somewhat rarer move than the more popular 9. Nge2 , but since it is less explored, I think more playable positions can be obtained here. This move is by far GM Salem's favorite choice.} Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 {If Nxc3 then Qc1 or Qc2 winning back the pawn on c7 with a favorable structure.} Nc6 {This move is interesting. Before playing ... h5 etc. Black completes his development with the intention of castling on the queenside.} 11. Bd3 Bf5 12. Ne2 Qe7 {Black intends to castle queenside and push his kingside pawns.} 13. O-O {We should not worry about Black's attack as we know how to tackle it.} O-O-O {Black can forget about any attack on the kingside due to Re1 !.} 14. Re1 {Followed by f3 . A few exchanges follow, and White gains a strategically superior position.} h5 (14... Rhe8 15. Bb5 $1 {This is even stronger than the immediate f3 .} Qe6 16. f3 Nxg3 17. Nxg3 Bg6 18. e4) 15. f3 {Black has many options here, but nothing equalizes.} Nxg3 (15... Nd6 16. Nc1 $1 Bxd3 17. Nxd3 h4 18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. e4 {The center gives White a certain edge.}) (15... h4 16. fxe4 dxe4 17. Bb5 $5 hxg3 18. Bxc6 gxh2+ 19. Kh1 bxc6 20. Qa4) 16. Nxg3 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 {Of course White is better here.} h4 18. Nf5 Qd7 19. e4 h3 20. g4 {Closing the kingside and supporting the knight on f5 . White is in control.} *

