1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 {When Black tries to play without ... c6 , there are two ideas for him to choose from: playing via ... c5 (say, ... Be7 , ... O-O , ... b6 and eventually ... c5 ) or ... Bb4 in the style of the Ragozin. The latter has become some sort of trend recently.} Bb4 {Black goes for a Ragozin-style position, looking for more unbalanced positions compared to the established QGD exchange lines. However, the lack of Nf3 makes White's options wider.  This line was chosen by Ian Nepomniachtchi in the game Caruana-Nepomniachtchi (2024), from the last round of the Candidates Tournament.} 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 9. a3 {A somewhat rarer move than the more popular 9. Nge2 , but since it is less explored, I think more playable positions can be obtained here. This move is by far GM Salem's favorite choice.} Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 {If Nxc3 then Qc1 or Qc2 winning back the pawn on c7 with a favorable structure.} Nc6 {This move is interesting. Before playing ... h5 etc. Black completes his development with the intention of castling on the queenside.} 11. Bd3 Bf5 12. Ne2 Qe7 {Black intends to castle queenside and push his kingside pawns.} 13. O-O {We should not worry about Black's attack as we know how to tackle it.} h5 14. h3 {This move however slows down Black's attack. We intend to preserve the dark squared bishop with Bh2 when suitable.} O-O-O (14... Nxg3 $6 15. Nxg3 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 {results in favorable trades for White as White controls the f5 square and e4 is a strong idea.}) 15. Rb1 {Launching our own initiative on the queenside. Right now, Black has some practical problems to solve.} h4 16. Bh2 g4 (16... Qe6 {transposes to Qe6 Bh2 h4 line .}) 17. Qb3 b6 18. Qa4 Rh6 19. Bf4 ({And Black cannot avoid material losses. Still, the position is complex, and a huge mess follows, but we should really know the lines until here. It would really take a lot of space to cover all the lines in detail, but I cover the main lines in the following clickables, so check them out! Rg6} 19. hxg4 Bxg4 20. f3) ({gxh3 Bxh6 Qd6} 19. Bf4 {Qg6} g3 {h2+ Kg2 hxg3} 20. fxg3 {Rh8 Qb5!} Kb7 21. Rbd1 $1 {The game goes on, but we are up a rook and there is no mate. If ... Bh3 we can play Kh1 and we are safe.}) *

