1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 {When Black tries to play without ... c6 , there are two ideas for him to choose from: playing via ... c5 (say, ... Be7 , ... O-O , ... b6 and eventually ... c5 ) or ... Bb4 in the style of the Ragozin. The latter has become some sort of trend recently.} Bb4 {Black goes for a Ragozin-style position, looking for more unbalanced positions compared to the established QGD exchange lines. However, the lack of Nf3 makes White's options wider.  This line was chosen by Ian Nepomniachtchi in the game Caruana-Nepomniachtchi (2024), from the last round of the Candidates Tournament.} 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 9. a3 {A somewhat rarer move than the more popular 9. Nge2 , but since it is less explored, I think more playable positions can be obtained here. This move is by far GM Salem's favorite choice.} Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 {If Nxc3 then Qc1 or Qc2 winning back the pawn on c7 with a favorable structure.} h5 ({Black goes after the Bg3 . After} 10... c5 $6 11. Bd3 Nxg3 12. hxg3 {White gets a great version of the Ragozin.}) 11. f3 {Solving the problem immediately.} Nxg3 (11... h4 12. Be5 $1 {Looks unpleasant for Black.} Nf6 13. Bd3 Nc6 14. Ne2 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd7 16. f4) 12. hxg3 {The resulting pawn structure looks promising for White, especially with the Ng1 not developed yet. There are ideas of g4 followed by Nh3 . The king will feel very safe on f2 .} Nc6 {Most likely the most flexible option. Black does not declare yet where his bishop and queen will go.} 13. g4 {Not wasting time and beginning the usual plan - after provoking ... h4 , there follows Nh3 and Bd3 .} h4 14. Nh3 Qe7 (14... f5 $6 {is logical but premature.} 15. Bd3 $1 fxg4 16. fxg4 Rf8 17. Rf1 Rxf1+ 18. Kxf1 Be6 19. e4) 15. Bd3 {Sacrificing the e3 -pawn for a quick development.} Qxe3+ ({Black should accept the sacrifice.} 15... Be6 16. O-O O-O-O 17. Re1 {with e4 next.}) 16. Kf1 {But this position looks scary for Black. The king is in the middle, pieces are undeveloped and there are many weaknesses. The main line is perhaps the following.} Rg8 ({A difficult move!} 16... Qe7 $2 {looks more human, but it runs into} 17. Qb3 {with big problems for Black.}) 17. g3 {Getting the king to g2 and connecting the rooks!} Qe7 18. Rb1 hxg3 19. Kg2 Qxa3 20. Qd2 {With so many weaknesses Black is definitely under pressure, despite being up material at the moment.} *

