1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 {Here I analyze what happens when Black decides to go for the endgame with ... Bf5 . There are two ways Black can do this: either ... Bf5 immediately, or first ... h6 and then ... Bf5 . Although both are possible, I find it hard to believe that having the pawn on h6 improves Black's position. In fact, when the bishop retreats to g6 , it would be somewhat more vulnerable, as we shall see in the analysis.} h6 7. Bh4 Bf5 {Another way of reaching the endgame.} 8. Qf3 {Preventing Black's ideal setup while damaging Black's pawn structure.} Bh7 {The bishop here has even less support than on g6 .} 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Qxf6 gxf6 11. Nf3 {I would go for the exactly same setup as after immediate 6... Bf5 . Even though with Nh4 White's knight will not hit the bishop, potential idea of occupying the f5 outpost and trade of bishops with Bd3 , should give White good chances.} Nd7 12. Nh4 {Actually, there is not much difference between the main line and this one. If anything, it is a somewhat better version for White, since Bh7 is less stable. On the other hand, the ideas of f4 - f5 are not so great anymore since they are not coming with tempo, but the preparation of Bd3 , as well as Ne2 - Ng3 are definitely good ideas.} Be7 13. Ne2 {Same stuff!} f5 (13... Bb4+ 14. Kd1 Nb6 15. Ng3 a5 16. Ngf5 {This basically mirrors the game Carlsen-Kramnik (2016).}) 14. Nf3 Bb4+ 15. Kd1 Nf6 16. Ne1 {The same idea as in Aronian-Dominguez (2023).} Ne4 17. Nd3 {White will play f3 next, taking control of the e4 -square, and Nef4 .} *

