1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 {Here I analyze what happens when Black decides to go for the endgame with ... Bf5 . There are two ways Black can do this: either ... Bf5 immediately, or first ... h6 and then ... Bf5 . Although both are possible, I find it hard to believe that having the pawn on h6 improves Black's position. In fact, when the bishop retreats to g6 , it would be somewhat more vulnerable, as we shall see in the analysis.} h6 7. Bh4 Bf5 {Another way of reaching the endgame.} 8. Qf3 {Preventing Black's ideal setup while damaging Black's pawn structure.} Bg6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Qxf6 gxf6 11. Nf3 {Same plan as usual. Here, with h6 on the board, I would argue it is a simply better version, as similarly as with 8... Bh7 , the bishop is not as stable.} Nd7 12. Nh4 Nb6 13. f4 {Threatening f5 .} f5 (13... h5 {transposes to the main line.}) 14. Bd3 Nc4 15. Bxc4 dxc4 16. Kf2 {We got a simply better version of what we had in Carlsen's game as the pawn on h6 weakens Black's position.} *

