1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 {Here I analyze what happens when Black decides to go for the endgame with ... Bf5 . There are two ways Black can do this: either ... Bf5 immediately, or first ... h6 and then ... Bf5 . Although both are possible, I find it hard to believe that having the pawn on h6 improves Black's position. In fact, when the bishop retreats to g6 , it would be somewhat more vulnerable, as we shall see in the analysis.} h6 7. Bh4 Bf5 {Another way of reaching the endgame.} 8. Qf3 {Preventing Black's ideal setup while damaging Black's pawn structure.} Bg6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Qxf6 gxf6 11. Nf3 {Same plan as usual. Here, with h6 on the board, I would argue it is a simply better version, as similarly as with 8... Bh7 , the bishop is not as stable.} Nd7 12. Nh4 Be7 13. Ne2 f5 14. Nf3 {I am not sure if there is any point in analyzing it - it is more or less the same position as the main line, since the presence of the pawn in h6 instead of h7 makes no difference.} *

