1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 {Here I analyze what happens when Black decides to go for the endgame with ... Bf5 . There are two ways Black can do this: either ... Bf5 immediately, or first ... h6 and then ... Bf5 . Although both are possible, I find it hard to believe that having the pawn on h6 improves Black's position. In fact, when the bishop retreats to g6 , it would be somewhat more vulnerable, as we shall see in the analysis.} h6 7. Bh4 Bf5 {Another way of reaching the endgame.} 8. Qf3 {Preventing Black's ideal setup while damaging Black's pawn structure.} Be6 {I think that when Black plays with h6 , the bishop should not retreat to g6 or h7 but instead go to e6 - the bishop feels quite stable there and will certainly not be trapped with f4 - f5 . Some of the most famous players who have opted for this solution are GMs Bluebaum and Shimanov.} 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Qxf6 gxf6 11. Bd3 {White should immediately take control over the b1 - h7 diagonal and ideally install the knight on the f5 -outpost.} a5 ({The main move according to the database. Black immediately seeks counterplay on the queenside.} 11... Nd7 12. Nge2 Bd6 13. Ng3 {is simply better for White.}) 12. Nge2 a4 {The most obvious move is a3 , but the engine does not approve of it. This is a bit surprising to me, but after inspection I understood why. White needs to control the c4 square, whereas as long as Black's knight does not reach b4 , White should clearly be better.} 13. Ng3 a3 14. b3 Na6 (14... Bd6 15. Nce2) 15. Bxa6 Rxa6 16. Nh5 {Due to closed nature of the position and number of outposts for White's knights, I like White's position here.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
