1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 {Here I analyze what happens when Black decides to go for the endgame with ... Bf5 . There are two ways Black can do this: either ... Bf5 immediately, or first ... h6 and then ... Bf5 . Although both are possible, I find it hard to believe that having the pawn on h6 improves Black's position. In fact, when the bishop retreats to g6 , it would be somewhat more vulnerable, as we shall see in the analysis.} Bf5 {In many Carlsbad positions it is believed that when Black takes his bishop to f5 , he should equalize. Here, however, White has the idea of Qf3 ! which damages Black's pawn structure.} 7. Qf3 Bg6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6 {So, it all starts here. The debate about whether Black's poor pawn structure gives White sufficient chances to win is still ongoing, and I do not expect it to be resolved soon. In my opinion, I think Black should objectively have enough resources to mitigate the problems associated with bad pawn structure, but we cannot forget that chess is still a game and people are prone to make mistakes. If we can get an easier game with some advantage, and we know what our plans and ideas are, we should be okay. And I think my viewpoint can give an idea of how to deal with these positions. White has many plans at his disposal. I am particularly fond of a plan played by Magnus Carlsen against Vladimir Kramnik in 2015.} 10. Nf3 {This is what Magnus played; more recently it was played by Ian Nepomniachtchi against Ding Liren in the GCT Superbet Romania. Ian, having played two World Championship matches, is one of the best prepared players in the world and the fact that he chose Nf3 - Nh4 idea says it all.} a5 {This was Ding's response. It is quite rare but not a bad move.} 11. Nh4 {As we see in many similar positions, White has two ideas here: Ne2 - Ng3 , followed by occupation of f5 square, or f4 - f5 , trying to trap or exclude the Bg6 from the game. Depending on what Black does, White generally chooses between the two.} Bb4 {This is another option for Black. Black intends to trade on c3 and ideally force bxc3 which would give Black a decent counterplay on the queenside due to possible pawn breaks and accessibility of outposts. Therefore, we need to remember to have an option to recapture with the rook on c3 .} 12. Rc1 {We need to be able to recapture Rxc3 . Of course, we intend a3 on the next move.} (12. a3 {This is not great as it has huge drawish tendencies.} Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 b5 $1 {With the idea of ... Nd7 -... Nb6 .} 14. a4 {The most natural reaction, but things simply work out here well for Black.} bxa4 $1 15. Rxa4 Nd7 16. Kd2 Ke7 {With ... Rhb8 and ... Nb6 next. The a5 -pawn may become quite strong one day if White gets careless. I analyzed it a bit further but I did not find anything great for White.} 17. Be2 (17. Bd3 Bxd3 18. Kxd3 Nb6 19. Ra2 Rhb8 20. Rha1 Nc4 ({Nf3} 20... a4 {Rha1 Ra5 Nd2 Rb5} 21. g4 c5)) 17... Rhb8 18. Nxg6+ fxg6 19. Rha1 (19. Ra2 Nb6 20. Rha1 a4 21. Bd3 Ra5 22. g4 Kd6) 19... Rb2+ 20. Ke1 Rb3) 12... Nd7 13. a3 Bxc3+ ({The most consistent with previous ... Bb4 .} 13... Bd6 $2 14. f4 $1 {is a standard idea in this line.}) 14. Rxc3 a4 {Fixing the pawn structure on the queenside. Now, it is important to know the plan for White, as again direct lines are useless. The knight should operate among squares f4 , b4 and c5 , which makes d3 an ideal square for this reason. White should play f3 to restrict Black's play. Doubling on c-file makes sense, Kd2 , Be2 , potentially h4 . At the right moment White should look for the pawn break: either b3 , g4 or e4 , depending on what Black does. Generally, despite Black being super solid, White is better.} 15. g3 Ke7 {Black generally should reroute the knight to e6 to deal with White’s knight getting to f4 . Stacking rooks on the a-file looks silly but it prevents any b3 pawn break. The optimal setup is Ne6 , Kd6 and keep the rooks connected. It is hard to prepare ... b6 -... c5 for Black and generally he needs to wait in place. I think this is unpleasant to play for Black.} 16. Be2 Nf8 {Bringing the knight to the right square.} 17. Kd2 Ne6 18. Rhc1 Ng5 {Provoking f3 , but it does not really weaken White’s position.} 19. f3 h5 20. Ng2 Ne6 21. Ke1 ({The king may be well-placed on f2 as well. Kd6 Kf2 Ra5} 21. h4 {Now the knight will come back into play via e1 - d3 . Rha8 Bf1 Rb8 Ne1 Rba8 Nd3 At some point, some pawn break will occur, and it is Black that must be careful here from which side we will try to bite.}) *

