ooses between the two.} a4 12. a3 {Not allowing ... a3 .} Be7 {As Black faced a threat of f4 - f5 , Black must be ready to meet f4 with ... f5 himself. That is only possible when Be7 hits Nh4 .} 13. Ne2 {As f4 is met with .... f5 and Nh4 is under attack, we should go for Ne2 - Ng3 idea.} Ra5 14. Ng3 Nd7 {This setup was chosen in an online game by Etienne Bacrot. I think it is pretty solid for Black. It was also OK to begin with ... Nd7 and then ... Ra5 . The idea is to play ... Nb6 -... Nc4 . The rook on a5 is perfectly positioned against ideas with Ngf5 , as then when ... Nc4 is played, after potential trades the rook would pressure the knight on f5 .} 15. f4 {I like this idea again. Black faces some practical problems.} Be4 ({Not an easy move to play. Voluntarily allowing Nxe4 looks difficult from practical point of view. Getting the bishop to b3 fails again:} 15... Bc2 $6 16. Rc1 Bb3 17. Nf3 $1 {with a clear edge.} c5 18. dxc5 Rxc5 19. Rxc5 Bxc5 20. Kf2 {Where f5 could be a nice outpost for the knight.}) 16. Rc1 {We don't need to rush with Nxe4 as it simply does not run away.} Nb6 {Black tries to bring the knight to d6 .} 17. Nhf5 Nc8 {This is a bit premature.} 18. Nxe4 dxe4 19. g4 {And White brings his knight to g3 , as ... h5 is met by Ng7 +!} Nd6 20. Ng3 {Attacking Black's weakness, the e4 -pawn.} *

