1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 {Here I analyze what happens when Black decides to go for the endgame with ... Bf5 . There are two ways Black can do this: either ... Bf5 immediately, or first ... h6 and then ... Bf5 . Although both are possible, I find it hard to believe that having the pawn on h6 improves Black's position. In fact, when the bishop retreats to g6 , it would be somewhat more vulnerable, as we shall see in the analysis.} Bf5 {In many Carlsbad positions it is believed that when Black takes his bishop to f5 , he should equalize. Here, however, White has the idea of Qf3 ! which damages Black's pawn structure.} 7. Qf3 Bg6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6 {So, it all starts here. The debate about whether Black's poor pawn structure gives White sufficient chances to win is still ongoing, and I do not expect it to be resolved soon. In my opinion, I think Black should objectively have enough resources to mitigate the problems associated with bad pawn structure, but we cannot forget that chess is still a game and people are prone to make mistakes. If we can get an easier game with some advantage, and we know what our plans and ideas are, we should be okay. And I think my viewpoint can give an idea of how to deal with these positions. White has many plans at his disposal. I am particularly fond of a plan played by Magnus Carlsen against Vladimir Kramnik in 2015.} 10. Nf3 {This is what Magnus played; more recently it was played by Ian Nepomniachtchi against Ding Liren in the GCT Superbet Romania. Ian, having played two World Championship matches, is one of the best prepared players in the world and the fact that he chose Nf3 - Nh4 idea says it all.} Nd7 {This is by far the most popular continuation.} 11. Nh4 Nb6 {This move is inaccurate as it does not act against the f4 idea.} 12. f4 h5 ({Carries a risk of Bg6 being completely shut off due to f5 . White has two very good options: either} 12... f5 {right away, or} 13. Kf2 {first.}) 13. f5 (13. Kf2 $5 {at first is playable too. The best move by the engine is actually to sac a pawn with 13... f5 and avoid getting terrible bishop...} f5 14. Bd3 {But here the f5 -pawn falls and Black hardly has sufficient compensation.}) 13... Bh7 14. Bd3 {Black is left with a terrible bishop on h7 . He needs to act quickly to try to solve this problem, but with few accurate moves White can retain his advantage.} Bh6 15. Kf2 Bg5 {Activating the bishop.} 16. Nf3 Nc8 {And after Nh4 moved, now going after the f5 -pawn. It is not sufficient, however - White can defend it!} 17. h3 h4 18. Ne2 Nd6 19. g4 hxg3+ 20. Nxg3 Bh6 21. h4 {White is clearly better thanks to better pieces and Bh7 being shut off.} *

