1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 {Here I analyze what happens when Black decides to go for the endgame with ... Bf5 . There are two ways Black can do this: either ... Bf5 immediately, or first ... h6 and then ... Bf5 . Although both are possible, I find it hard to believe that having the pawn on h6 improves Black's position. In fact, when the bishop retreats to g6 , it would be somewhat more vulnerable, as we shall see in the analysis.} Bf5 {In many Carlsbad positions it is believed that when Black takes his bishop to f5 , he should equalize. Here, however, White has the idea of Qf3 ! which damages Black's pawn structure.} 7. Qf3 Bg6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6 {So, it all starts here. The debate about whether Black's poor pawn structure gives White sufficient chances to win is still ongoing, and I do not expect it to be resolved soon. In my opinion, I think Black should objectively have enough resources to mitigate the problems associated with bad pawn structure, but we cannot forget that chess is still a game and people are prone to make mistakes. If we can get an easier game with some advantage, and we know what our plans and ideas are, we should be okay. And I think my viewpoint can give an idea of how to deal with these positions. White has many plans at his disposal. I am particularly fond of a plan played by Magnus Carlsen against Vladimir Kramnik in 2015.} 10. Nf3 {This is what Magnus played; more recently it was played by Ian Nepomniachtchi against Ding Liren in the GCT Superbet Romania. Ian, having played two World Championship matches, is one of the best prepared players in the world and the fact that he chose Nf3 - Nh4 idea says it all.} Nd7 {This is by far the most popular continuation.} 11. Nh4 Nb6 {This move is inaccurate as it does not act against the f4 idea.} 12. f4 f5 13. Bd3 {Black must play now ... Nc4 to keep the pawn.} Nc4 (13... Bb4 14. Kf2 Bxc3 15. bxc3 {and the f5 -pawn falls.}) 14. Bxc4 dxc4 {But here, we have a strategically better endgame for White. The Bg6 is out of play and bad pawn structure will matter in the long run.} 15. Kf2 {Probably, the critical game for the line here is Praggnanandhaa-Niemann (2022) in which both players played good logical moves, until I would recommend an improvement over Pragg's choice at some point.} O-O-O 16. a4 {Preventing ... b5 and isolating the c4 -pawn.} Be7 17. Nf3 f6 {Trying to revive Bg6 , but White simply comes back with the knight.} 18. Nh4 Bb4 19. Rhc1 Rhe8 20. Nxg6 ({An important move to include before playing Nd1 . Pragg played} 20. Nd1 $2 Bf7 21. Nxf5 c5 $1 {and here Niemann obtained counterplay.}) 20... hxg6 21. Nd1 {White wins the c4 -pawn and Black does not have the bishop pair to compensate for it.} *

