1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 {Here I analyze what happens when Black decides to go for the endgame with ... Bf5 . There are two ways Black can do this: either ... Bf5 immediately, or first ... h6 and then ... Bf5 . Although both are possible, I find it hard to believe that having the pawn on h6 improves Black's position. In fact, when the bishop retreats to g6 , it would be somewhat more vulnerable, as we shall see in the analysis.} Bf5 {In many Carlsbad positions it is believed that when Black takes his bishop to f5 , he should equalize. Here, however, White has the idea of Qf3 ! which damages Black's pawn structure.} 7. Qf3 Bg6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6 {So, it all starts here. The debate about whether Black's poor pawn structure gives White sufficient chances to win is still ongoing, and I do not expect it to be resolved soon. In my opinion, I think Black should objectively have enough resources to mitigate the problems associated with bad pawn structure, but we cannot forget that chess is still a game and people are prone to make mistakes. If we can get an easier game with some advantage, and we know what our plans and ideas are, we should be okay. And I think my viewpoint can give an idea of how to deal with these positions. White has many plans at his disposal. I am particularly fond of a plan played by Magnus Carlsen against Vladimir Kramnik in 2015.} 10. Nf3 {This is what Magnus played; more recently it was played by Ian Nepomniachtchi against Ding Liren in the GCT Superbet Romania. Ian, having played two World Championship matches, is one of the best prepared players in the world and the fact that he chose Nf3 - Nh4 idea says it all.} Nd7 {This is by far the most popular continuation.} 11. Nh4 Be7 12. Ne2 {Now, that f4 is met by ... f5 , White transfers the knight to g3 to occupy the f5 -square.} Nb6 13. Ng3 {No need to fear ... Bb4 , as I also discuss after 12... Bb4 . This was played by Magnus Carlsen and it most likely must have been a huge surprise for Kramnik.} Bb4+ ({Black is not on time to bring the knight to d6 :} 13... Nc8 $6 14. f4 $1) 14. Kd1 Na4 ({Looking for active play.} 14... Nc4 15. Ngf5 Nd6 {was probably a better defense, trying to tackle the Nf5 . But after} 16. Bd3 $1 Nxf5 17. Bxf5 {White retains a positional edge.}) 15. Ngf5 {White installs the knight on f5 -outpost as ... Nxb2 simply does not work.} Kd7 ({After} 15... Nxb2+ 16. Kc2 Nc4 17. Bxc4 dxc4 18. Rhb1 $1 {Black's position pretty much collapses.}) 16. Rb1 {This move looks a bit passive, but there is no rush. Soon, Black's pieces will drop back, while the grip on the kingside should offer us great winning chances.} a5 17. Bd3 Nb6 {This was probably called for, dropping the knight back, but of course White's advantage is clear.} 18. Ke2 a4 19. g4 {With similar plans as in the Carlsen's game, i.e. Ng2 - f4 followed by h4 - h5 .} *

