ave been a huge surprise for Kramnik.} Bb4+ ({Black is not on time to bring the knight to d6 :} 13... Nc8 $6 14. f4 $1) 14. Kd1 Na4 ({Looking for active play.} 14... Nc4 15. Ngf5 Nd6 {was probably a better defense, trying to tackle the Nf5 . But after} 16. Bd3 $1 Nxf5 17. Bxf5 {White retains a positional edge.}) 15. Ngf5 {White installs the knight on f5 -outpost as ... Nxb2 simply does not work.} Kd7 ({After} 15... Nxb2+ 16. Kc2 Nc4 17. Bxc4 dxc4 18. Rhb1 $1 {Black's position pretty much collapses.}) 16. Rb1 {This move looks a bit passive, but there is no rush. Soon, Black's pieces will drop back, while the grip on the kingside should offer us great winning chances.} Ke6 17. Bd3 Rhc8 {Black seeks some counterplay with ... c5 , but it simply does not work.} 18. Ke2 Bf8 19. g4 c5 20. Ng2 {And Black's position is pretty much lost.} *

