[White "27) Slav: Introduction"]
[Black "Slav Intro"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D12"]
[PlyCount "19"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 {The Slav is a popular and solid opening that has existed since the dawn of chess. White has many ways to deal with this opening. I would recommend playing 4. e3 , which generally leads to playable positions offering White a slight edge.} 3. Nf3 Nf6 (3... e6 {Using the Slav's move order, Black can also go for a Stonewall setup. In the section on the Dutch Stonewall we play via g3 , but here it is not possible because Black waits with ... f5 until we play e3 .} 4. e3 Bd6 5. Bd3 f5 {And we reached the Stonewall. It is solid for Black, but the issues with the e5 -square can last for a long time.} 6. O-O Nf6 7. b3 {We should try to trade dark squared bishops. And if Black plays} Qe7 {then the simple} 8. Bb2 {with the intention of occupying the e5 -square, is good and should give White a nice edge.}) 4. e3 {This is what I recommend for White here. Black has a huge choice of possible setups. Let's have a look what Black can do and how we react.} Bf5 {I think this line is the most popular recently, and I have tried it myself as Black.} ({•} 4... Bg4 {is another solid option for Black. Here I recommend a modern approach.} 5. Qb3 $5 Qb6 6. Ne5 {This line is not the most common here, but recently it received some recognition and I believe that it leads to somewhat uncomfortable positions for Black. The main line goes as follows:} Bf5 7. cxd5 Qxb3 8. axb3 Nxd5 9. Bd3 {where White has a nice control over the center, and thanks to that we can play on either side of the board. Even though it is move 8 and we traded queens, this endgame can be uncomfortable for Black, as I show in my analysis.}) ({•} 4... e6 {With this move, Black tries to get a Meran. Of course, the Meran is a great opening choice for Black but here we don't have the Nc3 , which reduces the strength of ... dxc4 -... b5 for Black. Because of this detail, I think we can be better here.} 5. Bd3 Nbd7 (5... dxc4 6. Bxc4 {is possible too, but the transpositions are inevitable, as I show in the course.}) 6. O-O Bd6 ({After} 6... dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Bd3 {please note that Black cannot use ... b4 to push away our knight, which often is an idea in Merans. And we intend to play via e4 !}) 7. Nc3 {We cannot delay Nc3 any longer, as ... e5 could have been an idea.} dxc4 (7... O-O {allows White to quickly play} 8. e4 {which can be an issue for Black; for this reason 7... dxc4 is preferable.} dxc4 (8... dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 {is considered as better for White, and I also show it in the course.}) 9. Bxc4 e5 10. Be3 {This is my recommendation here.}) 8. Bxc4 b5 {Here, I would recommend} 9. Bb3 $5 {which is more challenging than 9. Bd3 which I tried against Illya Nyzhnyk in 2022.}) ({•} 4... a6 {The Chebanenko is a solid sytem for Black as well. The thing about this move order is that apart from ... b5 , Black can switch to Semi-Slav with ... e6 next, or develop the bishop with either ... Bf5 or ... Bg4 . Therefore, it is a flexible move order.} 5. Bd3 {To keep things simple, I would recommend this move. Again, playing with ... e6 is rather dubious having played ... a6 (it would have made sense with our knight on c3 though) and ... Bf5 is not available.} Bg4 6. Nbd2 e6 7. O-O Nbd7 8. h3 Bh5 9. b3 {I think that following the Bb2 - Qc2 setup is good for White. We intend to prepare e4 .}) ({•} 4... g6 {The Schlechter Variation is another version of Slav, but it also bears some resemblance to Grünfeld, thanks to the fianchetto bishop and the pawn on d5 . White has many options, but I would choose} 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O {which is the most classical plan. Black has a lot of moves here. I cover them all in the course.}) 5. Nc3 e6 (5... a6 {This is some hybrid between 4... Bf5 and the Chebanenko. The idea is to have options of both ... b5 or ... Ra7 to guard the b7 -pawn and also to not give away the bishop pair due to Nh4 .} 6. Qb3 {One of the most challenging moves against this line. We put immediate pressure on b7 -pawn.} b5 ({After} 6... Ra7 7. Bd2 {Black has hardly anything better than} e6 {but then} 8. Nh4 {gets the bishop pair.}) 7. c5 $1 {I have always been fond of such pawn structures for White. We intend to play a4 and challenge the queenside pawns. And if} a5 {then} 8. Nh4 $5 Bc8 9. f4 $1 {gives us a space advantage.}) 6. Nh4 {We are going after the bishop pair. Black can play either 6... Be4 or 6... Bg6 , as 6... Bg4 is worse and has gone completely out of fashion.} Be4 {Black provokes f3 by trying to argue that it weakens White's position. This is a double-edged line, in which f3 may in fact be weakening, or it may improve White's position because of the suddenly possible g4 ideas, for example. There is a lot of theory here.} ({•} 6... Bg6 {a very solid line. White has a countless number of lines available here. I decided to recommend something that I personally like, and it leads to playable positions.} 7. Be2 Nbd7 8. O-O {Generally, we wait with Nxg6 until Black castles. That way Black does not have any ideas to make use of the h-file.} Bd6 {The most popular move.} (8... Be7 {is recently popular. Here, I would go for the rare} 9. Bd2 $5 {again waiting with Nxg6 .}) 9. g3 O-O 10. Nxg6 {Only now we take on g6 , after Black castled.} hxg6 11. Qc2 $5 {This move is better than 11. Qb3 that used to be played in the past.}) ({•} 6... Bg4 7. Qb3 {followed by quick h3 - g4 allows White to gain space on the kingside, which improves all standard lines.}) 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {I would recommend this line against the ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. It is quite popular recently, and I think it puts Black to test. Another approach is Qb3 , but with the Bd2 we keep both Qc2 and Qb3 available. However (spoiler) I recommend playing via Qc2 (after of course taking on g6 ).} Be7 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {Here, White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is the recent fashion here and I think it gives White pretty good chances. This idea was played first in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, however only in 2020 it got larger recognition as Anish Giri played it in 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory developed significantly.} *

