1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Bd3 f5 ({The Stonewall is a solid pawn structure for Black, but not without drawbacks: of course the e5 square is of interest to White and that is what White tries to target. With} 5... Nf6 {Black can transpose into Meran setups, which I discuss separately.}) 6. O-O Nh6 {An unusual way to develop the knight, but in modern chess this move is not so surprising because it has already been tried in similar positions. The idea is to take the knight to f7 and free the f6 square for the second knight.} 7. Ne5 {I think this is the best reaction. White immediately occupies the e5 -square and will support it with f4 , which is especially effective with Black's knight on h6 (instead of the normal f6 ) as it cannot get to the e4 -square!} O-O 8. f4 Nd7 9. Nd2 {A flexible way to develop the knight, essentially directing it to f3 . It was played in Vidit-Ponkratov (2022) and I would call it a slight improvement over 9. Nc3 , played in Meier-Aronian (2013).} Nf6 (9... Nxe5 $6 {is not good due to} 10. dxe5 $1 Be7 11. cxd5 $1 cxd5 (11... exd5 12. Nf3) 12. Nf3 {and the knight can occupy the d4 -outpost.}) 10. Ndf3 c5 11. b4 dxc4 (11... cxb4 {is strongly met by} 12. a3 $1 bxa3 13. c5 Be7 14. Bxa3) 12. Bxc4 cxb4 13. a3 {White is clearly better. Black's good bishop will be exchanged, and the e6 square will be a permanent weakness.} *

