1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Bd3 f5 ({The Stonewall is a solid pawn structure for Black, but not without drawbacks: of course the e5 square is of interest to White and that is what White tries to target. With} 5... Nf6 {Black can transpose into Meran setups, which I discuss separately.}) 6. O-O Qf6 {An unorthodox way to develop pieces here. Black wants to play ... Nh6 , ... Nf7 , ... g5 etc. However, committing the queen to f6 this early has its drawbacks too.} 7. Nc3 Nh6 8. Bd2 {White opts for a different plan, as the queen has left the queenside weakened. Now, b4 - b5 is a very strong idea!} Nd7 9. b4 g5 ({Black can try to launch an attack, but White's initiative is faster.} 9... Nf7 10. b5) 10. b5 g4 11. Ne1 {White is already crushing on the queenside, and Black’s attack can be easily neutralized with f4 if needed. Next, Rc1 can be played, applying more pressure on the c-file.} *

