1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Bd3 f5 ({The Stonewall is a solid pawn structure for Black, but not without drawbacks: of course the e5 square is of interest to White and that is what White tries to target. With} 5... Nf6 {Black can transpose into Meran setups, which I discuss separately.}) 6. O-O Nd7 {This move is possible of course but it is a bit inaccurate as the f5 -pawn is now not supported temporarily by Bc8 and White can take advantage of that.} 7. cxd5 {Forcing Black to recapture with the c-pawn, which normally is not ideal since ... exd5 is preferable. Here, however the f5 -pawn is loose!} cxd5 8. b3 {White continues in a standard fashion. The opening of the c-file helps White as he should be able to put some pressure on the queenside before Black gets started with the kingside attack.} Qe7 9. a4 Ngf6 10. Ba3 {Without c-pawns we obtain a better version of the normal Stonewall; White should be first here to take control of the c-file.} *

