1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Bd3 f5 ({The Stonewall is a solid pawn structure for Black, but not without drawbacks: of course the e5 square is of interest to White and that is what White tries to target. With} 5... Nf6 {Black can transpose into Meran setups, which I discuss separately.}) 6. O-O Nf6 7. b3 {White's standard idea here is Ba3 (if possible), but Bb2 is reasonable too.} O-O 8. Ba3 {This is of course great for White - the trade of the dark squared bishops will help seize control over the e5 -square.} Bxa3 ({Black should trade right away, as then White's knight will not be great on a3 .} 8... Qe7 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. Qc2 {Black simply wasted a tempo here by having to move the queen twice.}) 9. Nxa3 Qe7 10. Qc1 Ne4 11. Nb1 {I think that the knight should head back to the e2 square!} Nd7 12. Nc3 Rf6 13. Ne2 {Black does not have anything on the kingside. White may play Qb2 next with the potential idea b4 - b5 , and Ne5 is always an idea too when needed. The Bc8 is dead and it is not easy to bring it into the game without further weakening the position.} ({If . then} 13. cxd5 {forces} exd5 {, which leaves the queenside more weakened than it would be with the pawn still on b7 . Now, White should play} 14. Qb2 {Bb7 Nf4} c5 15. h4 $5 {stopping ... g5 in any case. Next, Rac1 , Rfd1 , g3 , etc. are on the agenda. White is better.}) *

