1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Bd3 f5 ({The Stonewall is a solid pawn structure for Black, but not without drawbacks: of course the e5 square is of interest to White and that is what White tries to target. With} 5... Nf6 {Black can transpose into Meran setups, which I discuss separately.}) 6. O-O Nf6 7. b3 {White's standard idea here is Ba3 (if possible), but Bb2 is reasonable too.} Qe7 {Black should not allow Ba3 so easily.} 8. Bb2 {I would recommend going for Bb2 plans here as I don't think that a4 is that great in general.} O-O 9. Nc3 {The knight goes to e2 in many of the lines, while the other one jumps to e5 .} b6 {Developing this way makes sense in many similar positions if Black is in time to play ... c5 . This is not the case here, however. As b6 is played, the queenside got a bit weaker and it makes sense for White to play cxd5 at some point.} 10. Rc1 Ne4 11. cxd5 {A well-timed move.} Nxc3 ({After} 11... exd5 {we continue with} 12. Ne2 {, intending Nf4 and Ne5 next.}) 12. Rxc3 exd5 13. Rc2 {White is better as Black has many weaknesses, especially the c6 -pawn and the e5 -square.} *

