1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Bd3 f5 ({The Stonewall is a solid pawn structure for Black, but not without drawbacks: of course the e5 square is of interest to White and that is what White tries to target. With} 5... Nf6 {Black can transpose into Meran setups, which I discuss separately.}) 6. O-O Nf6 7. b3 {White's standard idea here is Ba3 (if possible), but Bb2 is reasonable too.} Qe7 {Black should not allow Ba3 so easily.} 8. Bb2 {I would recommend going for Bb2 plans here as I don't think that a4 is that great in general.} O-O 9. Nc3 {The knight goes to e2 in many of the lines, while the other one jumps to e5 .} Nbd7 {This move leaves the f-pawn not supported by the Bc8 which immediately opens a possibility of cxd5 ... but we should not fall for it as Black can obtain there a very strong initiative (see the notes following 10. cxd5 ).} 10. cxd5 {White should not go for this and let me illustrate why.} exd5 {Black sacrifices the f5 -pawn for activity.} ({•} 10... Nxd5 $6 {is generally great news for White.} 11. e4 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 fxe4 13. Bxe4 Nf6 14. Bc2 {gives White a clear advantage.} Bd7 15. Qd3 Be8 16. Ne5 Rd8 17. Qh3) ({•} 10... cxd5 $2 11. Nb5 $1 {is the standard idea.}) 11. Bxf5 Ne4 12. Bh3 {It looks like Black has no compensation at all, but that's simply not true.} Rf6 {It appears that it is not easy to play as White.} 13. g3 {This for some time is suggested by the engine with idea of Bg2 and solidifying the kingside. But then the engine realizes that the complications after 13... Rxf3 !! work well for Black.} ({White can bail out with} 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Ne5 {but after all the trades the position simplifies and it is equal.} Nxe5 15. dxe5 Bxe5 16. Bxe5 Qxe5 17. Bxc8 Rxc8) 13... Rxf3 14. Qxf3 Ng5 15. Qg2 Ne5 16. Bxc8 Nef3+ 17. Kh1 Rxc8 18. e4 Bb4 {With extremely doubled edged play. There is no need to enter any of that.} *

