1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Bd3 f5 ({The Stonewall is a solid pawn structure for Black, but not without drawbacks: of course the e5 square is of interest to White and that is what White tries to target. With} 5... Nf6 {Black can transpose into Meran setups, which I discuss separately.}) 6. O-O Nf6 7. b3 {White's standard idea here is Ba3 (if possible), but Bb2 is reasonable too.} Qe7 {Black should not allow Ba3 so easily.} 8. Bb2 {I would recommend going for Bb2 plans here as I don't think that a4 is that great in general.} O-O 9. Nc3 {The knight goes to e2 in many of the lines, while the other one jumps to e5 .} Bd7 {I think this move is objectively the best here. Black needs to solve the problem of the light squared bishop and bringing it via e8 to h5 makes a lot of sense.} (9... Ne4 10. Ne2 $1 {Of course, we bring the knight to e2 to follow with Nf4 . There are likely transpositions to other move orders, say 9... Nbd7 10. Rc1 etc.} b6 ({(} 10... Nd7 11. Rc1 {simply transposes to Nbd7 Rc1 Ne4 Ne2! , though} Ne5 $5 {is great for White too. Nec5!?} 12. Bc2 {Bxe5 dxe5} dxc4 13. bxc4 b5 {f4⩲ )}) 11. Rc1 Bb7 12. Ne5 Nd7 13. Nf4 {with a transposition.}) 10. Ne2 {I would recommend transferring the knight to f4 , at least for now.} Be8 11. Nf4 Bh5 ({This, as an alternative to} 11... Nbd7 {, makes sense but with Nf4 we can simply get the bishop pair.}) 12. Nxh5 Nxh5 {Here, White has many good moves.} 13. a3 {One of the good options here but I like the concrete idea of immediately launching play on the queenside.} *

