[Result "*"]
[ECO "D30"]
[PlyCount "19"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 {With this move, Black aims for a Meran pawn structure, with a small but significant difference that plays in White's favor: the Nb1 is still undeveloped, which gives White additional possibilities. For example, the knight can go to d2 . Or Nc3 can be played at an opportune time. The ideas of b3 - Bb2 help control the e5 square, and Black may find it difficult to successfully execute the pawn break ... e5 .} 5. Bd3 ({I would recommend delaying the development of Nb1 . If White plays} 5. b3 $5 {then Black has really huge choice. But one of the most critical lines follows} c5 $5 {immediately hitting the center. Although in the end White is perhaps a little better (and I am not sure that he is!) there is absolutely no reason to play 5. b3 immediately, because we simply have to learn many more lines than necessary.}) 5... Nbd7 {The most flexible move. Black retains the option of ... Bd6  (or perhaps another way to develop the bishop) along with the ideas ... b6 -... Bb7 or ... dxc4 .} ({Black can play} 5... dxc4 {immediately, with a chance of transposing to QGA if Black plays ... c5 on the next move, or 6... Nbd7 7. O-O , which is covered when Black starts with 5... Nbd7 6. O-O  dxc4 .} 6. Bxc4 {The only independent line now seems to be the quick ... b5 , but as we'll see, we transpose anyway.} b5 ({For} 6... c5 {see the QGA lines .}) ({While} 6... Nbd7 7. O-O {transposes to dxc4 Bxc4 Nbd7 O-O}) 7. Bd3 a6 8. a4 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 {transposes to the line we're studying.}) 6. O-O {Another option is 6. b3 , followed by Bb2 . Of course, these plans are also totally playable. These lines are beyond the scope of this course where I focus on the more classic Meran lines, but I encourage you to study them on your own if interested!} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 ({After} 7... Bd6 {White has two options:} 8. Nc3 {, which simply transposes to the main line, or Qc2!? which is an additional option we get only in this move order. For this reason, to simplify the learning process, I decided to keep only 8. Nc3 . 8. Qc2 objectively does not offer that much anyway, but if you are interested to explore it, I encourage you to do so!}) 8. Bd3 {This helps White to achieve e4 .} Bd6 {This move, with inclusion of ... b5 and without Nc3 , is simply bad for Black.} 9. e4 e5 10. a4 ({there are immediate issues with Black's queenside. And} 10. b4 {doesn't come with tempo, since our knight is not on c3 , and we can continue with Nbd2± , intending Nc4 next.}) *

