 learning process, I decided to keep only 8. Nc3 . 8. Qc2 objectively does not offer that much anyway, but if you are interested to explore it, I encourage you to do so!}) 8. Bd3 {This helps White to achieve e4 .} a6 ({Preparing ... c5 . Black can start with} 8... Bb7 9. e4 a6 {which transposes as White anyway plays} 10. a4 {to prevent ... c5 .}) 9. a4 {Preventing ... c5 !} Bb7 10. e4 {To prevent ... c5 anyway.} Be7 {Black needs to complete the development. White has many options here but I would recommend the following one.} (10... c5 $2 {is premature. It does not work due to} 11. axb5 axb5 12. Rxa8 Qxa8 13. Bxb5) 11. axb5 {We immediately initiate play on the queenside and give Black room for error} axb5 ({Black must keep the idea of ... c5 .} 11... cxb5 {is worse, as White will simply keep a stronger center.} 12. Qe2 O-O 13. Nc3) 12. Rxa8 {Again, we offer Black an opportunity to make a mistake.} Bxa8 13. Qc2 {Prophylaxis. Black cannot castle now.} h6 (13... O-O $2 14. e5 {and White wins a pawn.}) (13... c5 $2 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. e5 {also wins a pawn for White.}) 14. Be3 O-O 15. Nbd2 {White's position is preferable. Whenever Black plays ... c5 it is linked to the loss of a pawn. Thereafter, Rc1 and Nb3 are on White's agenda, while ... Ng4 clashes with Bf4 and is therefore useless.} *

