1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 {With this move, Black aims for a Meran pawn structure, with a small but significant difference that plays in White's favor: the Nb1 is still undeveloped, which gives White additional possibilities. For example, the knight can go to d2 . Or Nc3 can be played at an opportune time. The ideas of b3 - Bb2 help control the e5 square, and Black may find it difficult to successfully execute the pawn break ... e5 .} 5. Bd3 ({I would recommend delaying the development of Nb1 . If White plays} 5. b3 $5 {then Black has really huge choice. But one of the most critical lines follows} c5 $5 {immediately hitting the center. Although in the end White is perhaps a little better (and I am not sure that he is!) there is absolutely no reason to play 5. b3 immediately, because we simply have to learn many more lines than necessary.}) 5... Nbd7 {The most flexible move. Black retains the option of ... Bd6  (or perhaps another way to develop the bishop) along with the ideas ... b6 -... Bb7 or ... dxc4 .} ({Black can play} 5... dxc4 {immediately, with a chance of transposing to QGA if Black plays ... c5 on the next move, or 6... Nbd7 7. O-O , which is covered when Black starts with 5... Nbd7 6. O-O  dxc4 .} 6. Bxc4 {The only independent line now seems to be the quick ... b5 , but as we'll see, we transpose anyway.} b5 ({For} 6... c5 {see the QGA lines .}) ({While} 6... Nbd7 7. O-O {transposes to dxc4 Bxc4 Nbd7 O-O}) 7. Bd3 a6 8. a4 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 {transposes to the line we're studying.}) 6. O-O {Another option is 6. b3 , followed by Bb2 . Of course, these plans are also totally playable. These lines are beyond the scope of this course where I focus on the more classic Meran lines, but I encourage you to study them on your own if interested!} Bd6 7. Nc3 {White should go for the Meran here. Black has three possible plans: 1) the standard ... dxc4 and ... b5 ; 2) ... dxc4 followed by meeting e4 with ... e5 ; and 3) meeting e4 with ... dxe4 . They all lead to different positions. Let's take a look.} ({Please note that} 7. b3 $2 {is a serious error due to} e5 $1 {and Black begins to take over.}) 7... O-O 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 {This position has been very popular years ago, but modern engines simply don't see equality here. White's space advantage is substantial.} c5 11. Bc2 Qc7 (11... cxd4 $2 12. Qxd4 {helps White developing the pieces quickly, with a strong initiative.}) 12. Qd3 f5 13. b4 ({A nice idea of expanding on the queenside.} 13. Rd1 $5 {is playable too.}) 13... b6 ({The pawn cannot be captured.} 13... cxb4 $2 14. c5 {And White is almost winning.}) 14. dxc5 {Another strong move - the idea is to play Rd1 next, forcing the bishop back.} bxc5 15. Rd1 Be7 16. b5 {3 vs. 2 on the queenside is a good strategic setup for White. It will be potentially easier to create a passed pawn. Black needs to seek counterplay connected with ... e5 , and that's why it is necessary to play ... Bf6 .} Bf6 17. Rb1 Nb6 {With the bishop on c8 Black defends the f5 pawn and will play ... e5 next. But the last move, Nb6 , weakened the c5 -pawn and White can take advantage of it.} 18. Be3 {With the idea of meeting ... e5 with Qd6 .} e5 19. Qd6 Qxd6 20. Rxd6 e4 21. Nd2 Be7 22. Bxc5 {A standard exchange sacrifice for the huge pawn mass on the queenside.} Bxd6 23. Bxd6 Rd8 24. c5 Be6 25. a4 {Of course, Black is struggling here.} *

