1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 {With this move, Black aims for a Meran pawn structure, with a small but significant difference that plays in White's favor: the Nb1 is still undeveloped, which gives White additional possibilities. For example, the knight can go to d2 . Or Nc3 can be played at an opportune time. The ideas of b3 - Bb2 help control the e5 square, and Black may find it difficult to successfully execute the pawn break ... e5 .} 5. Bd3 ({I would recommend delaying the development of Nb1 . If White plays} 5. b3 $5 {then Black has really huge choice. But one of the most critical lines follows} c5 $5 {immediately hitting the center. Although in the end White is perhaps a little better (and I am not sure that he is!) there is absolutely no reason to play 5. b3 immediately, because we simply have to learn many more lines than necessary.}) 5... Nbd7 {The most flexible move. Black retains the option of ... Bd6  (or perhaps another way to develop the bishop) along with the ideas ... b6 -... Bb7 or ... dxc4 .} ({Black can play} 5... dxc4 {immediately, with a chance of transposing to QGA if Black plays ... c5 on the next move, or 6... Nbd7 7. O-O , which is covered when Black starts with 5... Nbd7 6. O-O  dxc4 .} 6. Bxc4 {The only independent line now seems to be the quick ... b5 , but as we'll see, we transpose anyway.} b5 ({For} 6... c5 {see the QGA lines .}) ({While} 6... Nbd7 7. O-O {transposes to dxc4 Bxc4 Nbd7 O-O}) 7. Bd3 a6 8. a4 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 {transposes to the line we're studying.}) 6. O-O {Another option is 6. b3 , followed by Bb2 . Of course, these plans are also totally playable. These lines are beyond the scope of this course where I focus on the more classic Meran lines, but I encourage you to study them on your own if interested!} Bd6 7. Nc3 {White should go for the Meran here. Black has three possible plans: 1) the standard ... dxc4 and ... b5 ; 2) ... dxc4 followed by meeting e4 with ... e5 ; and 3) meeting e4 with ... dxe4 . They all lead to different positions. Let's take a look.} ({Please note that} 7. b3 $2 {is a serious error due to} e5 $1 {and Black begins to take over.}) 7... O-O 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 {This position has been very popular years ago, but modern engines simply don't see equality here. White's space advantage is substantial.} h6 {I think this is the most solid for Black. It prevents Bg5 and some Bxh7 ideas (as in immediate 10... e5 ) and prepares ... e5 now.} 11. Bc2 {With idea Qd3 of course. So, Black needs to react in the center right away.} e5 12. Re1 (12. Qd3 f5 {is playable but is probably not that clear.} 13. c5 Bc7 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Qc4+ Kh8 17. Bf4 (17. Re1 $2 Re8) 17... Qd4 {with only a minimal edge, but close to equality.}) 12... exd4 13. Qxd4 Bc5 {Here, White has two options: Qc3 or . The majority of people goes for Qc3 and I like it too - it is a very good square for the queen. However, Qf4 can be played as well.} 14. Qc3 Qb6 {Worse than 14... a5 .} 15. Re2 (15. Bxh6 $5 gxh6 16. Re4 {is an interesting option too!}) 15... Rd8 16. a3 a5 17. Bf4 ({Both the text move, intending Rae1 next, and} 17. b3 {followed by Bb2 are great for White.}) *

