 to different positions. Let's take a look.} ({Please note that} 7. b3 $2 {is a serious error due to} e5 $1 {and Black begins to take over.}) 7... O-O 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 {This position has been very popular years ago, but modern engines simply don't see equality here. White's space advantage is substantial.} h6 {I think this is the most solid for Black. It prevents Bg5 and some Bxh7 ideas (as in immediate 10... e5 ) and prepares ... e5 now.} 11. Bc2 {With idea Qd3 of course. So, Black needs to react in the center right away.} e5 12. Re1 (12. Qd3 f5 {is playable but is probably not that clear.} 13. c5 Bc7 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Qc4+ Kh8 17. Bf4 (17. Re1 $2 Re8) 17... Qd4 {with only a minimal edge, but close to equality.}) 12... exd4 13. Qxd4 Bc5 {Here, White has two options: Qc3 or . The majority of people goes for Qc3 and I like it too - it is a very good square for the queen. However, Qf4 can be played as well.} 14. Qc3 a5 ({Black must prevent b4 . Also, ... Bb4 is a threat too.} 14... Nf6 15. b4) 15. a3 Nf6 (15... Re8 16. Bf4) (15... Qb6 16. Bxh6 gxh6 17. Re4) 16. Bxh6 {A sudden tactical strike!} gxh6 {Accepting the sacrifice loses for Black.} 17. Rad1 Bd7 {White has many good moves. But the strongest move according to the engine is h3 !.} 18. h3 ({It pretty much leaves Black without useful moves as everything tactically falls apart for him (eval is +2!). For instance,} 18. Re8 Rxe8 {Nxe8} 19. Ne5 {Qh4 Nxd7} Bxf2+ 20. Kh1 {Qg3 Rd3+-}) *

