1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 {With this move, Black aims for a Meran pawn structure, with a small but significant difference that plays in White's favor: the Nb1 is still undeveloped, which gives White additional possibilities. For example, the knight can go to d2 . Or Nc3 can be played at an opportune time. The ideas of b3 - Bb2 help control the e5 square, and Black may find it difficult to successfully execute the pawn break ... e5 .} 5. Bd3 ({I would recommend delaying the development of Nb1 . If White plays} 5. b3 $5 {then Black has really huge choice. But one of the most critical lines follows} c5 $5 {immediately hitting the center. Although in the end White is perhaps a little better (and I am not sure that he is!) there is absolutely no reason to play 5. b3 immediately, because we simply have to learn many more lines than necessary.}) 5... Nbd7 {The most flexible move. Black retains the option of ... Bd6  (or perhaps another way to develop the bishop) along with the ideas ... b6 -... Bb7 or ... dxc4 .} ({Black can play} 5... dxc4 {immediately, with a chance of transposing to QGA if Black plays ... c5 on the next move, or 6... Nbd7 7. O-O , which is covered when Black starts with 5... Nbd7 6. O-O  dxc4 .} 6. Bxc4 {The only independent line now seems to be the quick ... b5 , but as we'll see, we transpose anyway.} b5 ({For} 6... c5 {see the QGA lines .}) ({While} 6... Nbd7 7. O-O {transposes to dxc4 Bxc4 Nbd7 O-O}) 7. Bd3 a6 8. a4 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 {transposes to the line we're studying.}) 6. O-O {Another option is 6. b3 , followed by Bb2 . Of course, these plans are also totally playable. These lines are beyond the scope of this course where I focus on the more classic Meran lines, but I encourage you to study them on your own if interested!} Bd6 7. Nc3 {White should go for the Meran here. Black has three possible plans: 1) the standard ... dxc4 and ... b5 ; 2) ... dxc4 followed by meeting e4 with ... e5 ; and 3) meeting e4 with ... dxe4 . They all lead to different positions. Let's take a look.} ({Please note that} 7. b3 $2 {is a serious error due to} e5 $1 {and Black begins to take over.}) 7... O-O 8. e4 dxc4 9. Bxc4 e5 {One of the classical ways to play the Meran as Black, which lost its popularity recently to ... b5 -... Bb7 lines. However, thanks to the 4. e3 move order, Black does not get to enter the main Meran lines, which makes 4. e3 an effective method to avoid certain variations.} 10. Be3 {I think this move is the most promising. The idea is to have an option to recapture on d4 with the bishop. Sam Shankland does not cover this line much, but it actually deserves some attention, so I decided to look into it.} Qe7 {Black prepares ... exd4 and then will want to play ... Ne5 . But now Black does not control the f4 -square so well, as with Qc7 . Here, we don't need Kh1 for now.} 11. h3 {Covering the g4 -square.} exd4 {Here, White has two decent options.} 12. Nxd4 {Less explored than Bxd4 , but pretty challenging too. We are provoking Black to take the e4 -pawn which, although acceptable, is very risky for him.} Nc5 13. f3 ({White secures the center and even though the dark squares on the kingside are weakened, Black has no way to exploit them. We can always rely on Nce2 idea to cover them. Nh5} 13. Qd2 Rd8 14. Rad1 Qc7 15. Nce2 b5 16. e5 $1 {and things get tactical but White should be ahead, e.g.} Bf8 17. Nxb5 $1 Qxe5 18. Qc3 Qxc3 19. Nbxc3) *

