1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 {With this move, Black aims for a Meran pawn structure, with a small but significant difference that plays in White's favor: the Nb1 is still undeveloped, which gives White additional possibilities. For example, the knight can go to d2 . Or Nc3 can be played at an opportune time. The ideas of b3 - Bb2 help control the e5 square, and Black may find it difficult to successfully execute the pawn break ... e5 .} 5. Bd3 ({I would recommend delaying the development of Nb1 . If White plays} 5. b3 $5 {then Black has really huge choice. But one of the most critical lines follows} c5 $5 {immediately hitting the center. Although in the end White is perhaps a little better (and I am not sure that he is!) there is absolutely no reason to play 5. b3 immediately, because we simply have to learn many more lines than necessary.}) 5... Nbd7 {The most flexible move. Black retains the option of ... Bd6  (or perhaps another way to develop the bishop) along with the ideas ... b6 -... Bb7 or ... dxc4 .} ({Black can play} 5... dxc4 {immediately, with a chance of transposing to QGA if Black plays ... c5 on the next move, or 6... Nbd7 7. O-O , which is covered when Black starts with 5... Nbd7 6. O-O  dxc4 .} 6. Bxc4 {The only independent line now seems to be the quick ... b5 , but as we'll see, we transpose anyway.} b5 ({For} 6... c5 {see the QGA lines .}) ({While} 6... Nbd7 7. O-O {transposes to dxc4 Bxc4 Nbd7 O-O}) 7. Bd3 a6 8. a4 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 {transposes to the line we're studying.}) 6. O-O {Another option is 6. b3 , followed by Bb2 . Of course, these plans are also totally playable. These lines are beyond the scope of this course where I focus on the more classic Meran lines, but I encourage you to study them on your own if interested!} Bd6 7. Nc3 {White should go for the Meran here. Black has three possible plans: 1) the standard ... dxc4 and ... b5 ; 2) ... dxc4 followed by meeting e4 with ... e5 ; and 3) meeting e4 with ... dxe4 . They all lead to different positions. Let's take a look.} ({Please note that} 7. b3 $2 {is a serious error due to} e5 $1 {and Black begins to take over.}) 7... O-O 8. e4 dxc4 9. Bxc4 e5 {One of the classical ways to play the Meran as Black, which lost its popularity recently to ... b5 -... Bb7 lines. However, thanks to the 4. e3 move order, Black does not get to enter the main Meran lines, which makes 4. e3 an effective method to avoid certain variations.} 10. Be3 {I think this move is the most promising. The idea is to have an option to recapture on d4 with the bishop. Sam Shankland does not cover this line much, but it actually deserves some attention, so I decided to look into it.} Qe7 {Black prepares ... exd4 and then will want to play ... Ne5 . But now Black does not control the f4 -square so well, as with Qc7 . Here, we don't need Kh1 for now.} 11. h3 {Covering the g4 -square.} exd4 {Here, White has two decent options.} 12. Nxd4 {Less explored than Bxd4 , but pretty challenging too. We are provoking Black to take the e4 -pawn which, although acceptable, is very risky for him.} Ne5 {The most standard move here.} 13. Bb3 {Usually a good square for the bishop from where it can exert pressure on the f7 -pawn. Also, f4 is a threat now, so Black should be careful.} Rd8 (13... Ng6 $6 14. Qc2 {is less good for Black as White gets the same position as in the main line but with Rf8 instead of Rd8 on the board.}) 14. Qe2 {White must prevent ... c5 -... c4 , therefore 14. Qc2 was not good and 14. Qe2 is required.} (14. Qc2 $6 {allows} c5 $1 15. Ndb5 c4 $1 16. Nxd6 Rxd6 {with a double-edged game.}) 14... Ng6 {The best reaction by Black, everything else is clearly better for White. But still, White's position is preferable.} 15. Qc2 {Wasting a tempo, but as I checked the pawn e4 must be protected and this is the best way to do it, especially since Nf5 !? is an idea, so removing the queen from e2 is necessary. Also, ... c5 -... c4 is not a thing anymore!} Nh5 ({The idea of installing either of the knights on f4 is logical, but not that scary.} 15... Bf4 16. Nf5 Qc7 17. Rae1 $1 Bxe3 18. Rxe3 {White looks better due to the strong Nf5 .}) 16. Rad1 {Now, Black has a dilemma - which knight should go to f4 ?} Bxh3 {This is an option too, but it does not fully work.} 17. gxh3 Ngf4 {Or the other knight.} 18. Bxf4 Nxf4 19. Nce2 {White must get rid of the f4 -knight.} Nxh3+ (19... Qg5+ {is worse due to} 20. Ng3 Nxh3+ 21. Kh1 $1 Nf4 22. Nf3 {and White’s king is safe as we always have Nh2 if needed.}) 20. Kg2 Nf4+ 21. Kf3 ({The best move, but not} 21. Nxf4 $2 {as} Qg5+ $1 {keeps the balance.}) 21... Qg5 {The only try.} 22. Rh1 ({White should be better here, even though the position remains complicated. The best line for both sides goes as follows: Ng6} 22. Ng3 $1 {Nh4 Ke2} Qg4+ {Ke1 Bxg3 fxg3 Rxd4 Rxh4! Qxg3 Qf2± with inevitable simplifications, and the extra piece should eventually decide the game.}) *

