1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 {With this move, Black aims for a Meran pawn structure, with a small but significant difference that plays in White's favor: the Nb1 is still undeveloped, which gives White additional possibilities. For example, the knight can go to d2 . Or Nc3 can be played at an opportune time. The ideas of b3 - Bb2 help control the e5 square, and Black may find it difficult to successfully execute the pawn break ... e5 .} 5. Bd3 ({I would recommend delaying the development of Nb1 . If White plays} 5. b3 $5 {then Black has really huge choice. But one of the most critical lines follows} c5 $5 {immediately hitting the center. Although in the end White is perhaps a little better (and I am not sure that he is!) there is absolutely no reason to play 5. b3 immediately, because we simply have to learn many more lines than necessary.}) 5... Nbd7 {The most flexible move. Black retains the option of ... Bd6  (or perhaps another way to develop the bishop) along with the ideas ... b6 -... Bb7 or ... dxc4 .} ({Black can play} 5... dxc4 {immediately, with a chance of transposing to QGA if Black plays ... c5 on the next move, or 6... Nbd7 7. O-O , which is covered when Black starts with 5... Nbd7 6. O-O  dxc4 .} 6. Bxc4 {The only independent line now seems to be the quick ... b5 , but as we'll see, we transpose anyway.} b5 ({For} 6... c5 {see the QGA lines .}) ({While} 6... Nbd7 7. O-O {transposes to dxc4 Bxc4 Nbd7 O-O}) 7. Bd3 a6 8. a4 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 {transposes to the line we're studying.}) 6. O-O {Another option is 6. b3 , followed by Bb2 . Of course, these plans are also totally playable. These lines are beyond the scope of this course where I focus on the more classic Meran lines, but I encourage you to study them on your own if interested!} Bd6 7. Nc3 {White should go for the Meran here. Black has three possible plans: 1) the standard ... dxc4 and ... b5 ; 2) ... dxc4 followed by meeting e4 with ... e5 ; and 3) meeting e4 with ... dxe4 . They all lead to different positions. Let's take a look.} ({Please note that} 7. b3 $2 {is a serious error due to} e5 $1 {and Black begins to take over.}) 7... O-O 8. e4 dxc4 9. Bxc4 e5 {One of the classical ways to play the Meran as Black, which lost its popularity recently to ... b5 -... Bb7 lines. However, thanks to the 4. e3 move order, Black does not get to enter the main Meran lines, which makes 4. e3 an effective method to avoid certain variations.} 10. Be3 {I think this move is the most promising. The idea is to have an option to recapture on d4 with the bishop. Sam Shankland does not cover this line much, but it actually deserves some attention, so I decided to look into it.} b5 11. Bb3 Bb7 {A typical Meran development by Black. But it seems like Black is worse here.} 12. Re1 a6 (12... Qc7 $6 13. Rc1 {is again unpleasant for Black.}) (12... Qe7 13. h3 Rad8 14. Qc1 $5) 13. h3 Qc7 14. Rc1 Rad8 15. d5 (15. Nd5 $5 Qb8 $2 16. dxe5 $1 {is winning for White, whereas after} Nxd5 $1 17. exd5 {exd4! Nxd4} c5 $1 {Nf5 g6! Black has to find four only moves in a row but ends up only very slightly worse.}) 15... c5 16. Bc2 {White is much better due to the space advantage. There are typical ideas of Ne2 - Ng3 , but I would begin by playing on the queenside with a4 to weaken the queenside pawns.} *

