hite can play 16. Be2 or 16. Bd3 , instead of the 'standard' 16. Bb3 and avoid the bishop trade right away.} 16. Be2 ({I like this the most. White keeps majority of pieces on the board.} 16. Bd3 $5 {was tried by Giri and it is also interesting. I like it a bit less than 16. Be2 due to} Rd8 17. Qf3 Be6 18. h3 Rxd3 $1 {and Ding managed to simplify the position.} 19. Qxd3 Bc4 20. Qd2 Bxf1 21. Rxf1 {In this case, White is still slightly better, since e5 is coming and White controls the d-file. However, many pieces have been exchanged, and I expect that Black can defend himself with some accurate moves.}) (16. Bb3 {is what we should avoid now, due to} Be6 {and Black gets to trade the light squared bishops in a comfortable manner, followed by ... Rad8 .}) 16... Be6 17. Qe1 {Bringing the queen to the kingside. This position looks promising for White as my analysis shows.} Bc4 {Black 'forces' the bishop trade - but the setup of Qc5 and Bc4 is a bit shaky and White can try to take advantage of it.} (17... Rad8 18. Qg3 {White simply prepares the attack on the kingside.}) 18. b4 {Putting pressure on Black tactically. Black manages to stay in the game with only moves, but the final position is clearly better for White.} Qxb4 19. Rb1 Qc5 20. Na4 Qa3 (20... Qd4 $2 21. Rd1) 21. Bxc4 Qxa4 22. Rb4 Qa3 23. Rxb7 {White got the pawn back and is left with a superior bishop over the knight and a better pawn structure. After all, 17... Bc4 did not 'force' the bishop trade!} *

