lowing a spectacular blow.} 16. Bxe6 {This position looks terrible for Black, if not for one calm move...} O-O ({Cold-blooded, but works and keeps Black in the game.} 16... fxe6 $4 17. Rxe6+ {just wins for White.}) 17. Bxd7 Qxd7 {White is up a pawn but Black has some compensation. Still, it is Black that must be very careful here.} 18. Bf4 Qg4 19. Bg3 Bxf3 20. gxf3 Qxf3 {Black has recovered the pawn and weakened White's king. Unfortunately, Black is objectively okay here, but from a practical point of view it still looks rather scary, since the c5 pawn is quite strong, and any endgame will clearly be difficult for Black.} 21. Qc4 (21. Qb3 $5 Qxb3 22. axb3 Rxc5 23. Rxa7 {is close to equal too, but I might argue that we are playing for two results as the b4 -pawn will likely fall and the passed b-pawn will cause some practical problems for Black in this endgame.}) 21... a5 22. a3 {Causing some problems on the queenside!} Qc6 (22... bxa3 23. Rxa3 {holds too but is really hard to imagine to be played OTB as it loses the pawn...}) 23. axb4 axb4 24. Qxb4 Qxc5 25. Qxc5 Rxc5 26. b4 Rb5 27. Bd6 {Black is on the defensive side!} *

