1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 {With this move, Black aims for a Meran pawn structure, with a small but significant difference that plays in White's favor: the Nb1 is still undeveloped, which gives White additional possibilities. For example, the knight can go to d2 . Or Nc3 can be played at an opportune time. The ideas of b3 - Bb2 help control the e5 square, and Black may find it difficult to successfully execute the pawn break ... e5 .} 5. Bd3 ({I would recommend delaying the development of Nb1 . If White plays} 5. b3 $5 {then Black has really huge choice. But one of the most critical lines follows} c5 $5 {immediately hitting the center. Although in the end White is perhaps a little better (and I am not sure that he is!) there is absolutely no reason to play 5. b3 immediately, because we simply have to learn many more lines than necessary.}) 5... Nbd7 {The most flexible move. Black retains the option of ... Bd6  (or perhaps another way to develop the bishop) along with the ideas ... b6 -... Bb7 or ... dxc4 .} ({Black can play} 5... dxc4 {immediately, with a chance of transposing to QGA if Black plays ... c5 on the next move, or 6... Nbd7 7. O-O , which is covered when Black starts with 5... Nbd7 6. O-O  dxc4 .} 6. Bxc4 {The only independent line now seems to be the quick ... b5 , but as we'll see, we transpose anyway.} b5 ({For} 6... c5 {see the QGA lines .}) ({While} 6... Nbd7 7. O-O {transposes to dxc4 Bxc4 Nbd7 O-O}) 7. Bd3 a6 8. a4 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 {transposes to the line we're studying.}) 6. O-O {Another option is 6. b3 , followed by Bb2 . Of course, these plans are also totally playable. These lines are beyond the scope of this course where I focus on the more classic Meran lines, but I encourage you to study them on your own if interested!} Bd6 7. Nc3 {White should go for the Meran here. Black has three possible plans: 1) the standard ... dxc4 and ... b5 ; 2) ... dxc4 followed by meeting e4 with ... e5 ; and 3) meeting e4 with ... dxe4 . They all lead to different positions. Let's take a look.} ({Please note that} 7. b3 $2 {is a serious error due to} e5 $1 {and Black begins to take over.}) 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 b5 {Plan 1) . Usually, when Black plays ... dxc4 , it is followed immediately by ... b5 . I played it as White against Illya Nyzhnyk who surprised me with the move orders and I did not expect this particular line. In my game, I reacted with 9. Bd3 which is the most popular move. I did not get much out of the opening, and although I had some chances later in the game, it ended in a draw. But I completely forgot the option of playing 9. Bb3 ! which is by far the most challenging.} 9. Bb3 {This would be my recommendation. The idea of this move is to play e4 as soon as possible and in case Black replies with ... e5 , the bishop will be very well-placed on b3 .} b4 {The main and the best move. Black needs to deal with the e4 threat. There are few alternatives; however, they are clearly worse.} 10. Na4 Bb7 {The best move. Black prepares ... c5 .} 11. e4 ({An interesting pawn sacrifice that puts a lot of pressure on Black.} 11. Qe2 {is the main line which I don't think promises much. The problem is that Black can play} Qa5 12. Rd1 {and now either} Ba6 $1 {or Qh5!?} 13. h3 g5 {with a good game for Black. I believe 11. e4 !? offers much better chances.}) 11... Nxe4 12. Re1 Nef6 ({The knight needs to go back. Now, White has some choice.} 12... c5 $2 13. d5 $1 {is an important little detail.}) 13. Qc2 {I like this positional idea here. The idea is to obtain a long term compensation for the pawn and play in a positional fashion, unlike after 13. Ng5 !?, an alternative that we will examine later .} O-O {The most natural move.} 14. Nc5 Qb8 {Similar to ... Qc7 - but I find it hard to believe that someone chooses this over more natural ... Qc7 .} 15. Bd2 (15. Bg5 $5 a5 16. a4 {is another option.}) 15... a5 16. a3 {White has good compensation for the pawn.} *

