[White "30) Slav: 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 a6 C"]
[Black "Chebanenko - 5...g6 6.O-O Bg7"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D11"]
[PlyCount "19"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 a6 5. Bd3 {I would recommend this move, trying to play without Nc3 and keep the flexibility of developing the knight to d2 .} (5. Be2 $5 {This could be another good option for White which is rarely played, but deserves attention as well.}) (5. Nc3 {is the main move of course, but the point is that after} e6 {we enter the classic Semi-Slav with ... a6 which is very well studied and objectively not necessarily better than 5. Bd3 . And 5. Bd3 is way simpler to learn! Moreover, Black can play the classical Chebanenko with 5... b5 , which only increases the lines to be learned. Therefore, I would choose 5. Bd3 !}) 5... g6 {In this way Black can try to direct the game to the Schlechter Variation. Since against the Schlechter I recommend Be2 setting, it seems that Black can use this move order to deceive us. However, the presence of a6 (which is sometimes useful, but can sometimes be a waste of time) opens up other options for White that seek to exploit the a-pawn move.} 6. O-O Bg7 7. Nbd2 {Not developing the knight to c3 but to d2 , with a completely different plan than in the standard Schlechter.} O-O 8. b4 {A very rare idea in this particular position but it makes a lot of sense in my opinion. Since a6 is not so useful when implementing central play (e.g., ... Bg4 and preparing for the breakup ... e5 as sometimes happens in the Schlechter) White gets 'extra' time to develop some play on the queen side, since a6 is not so useful.} Bf5 (8... Bg4 {A normal development move; Black intends to give away the bishop pair - and White is happy about it.} 9. Qc2 Nbd7 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 e6 12. Bb2) 9. Bxf5 gxf5 10. a4 {White has a great position. One of the main ideas is c5 !? to gain space on the queenside and then prepare b5 .} *

