1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 a6 5. Bd3 {I would recommend this move, trying to play without Nc3 and keep the flexibility of developing the knight to d2 .} (5. Be2 $5 {This could be another good option for White which is rarely played, but deserves attention as well.}) (5. Nc3 {is the main move of course, but the point is that after} e6 {we enter the classic Semi-Slav with ... a6 which is very well studied and objectively not necessarily better than 5. Bd3 . And 5. Bd3 is way simpler to learn! Moreover, Black can play the classical Chebanenko with 5... b5 , which only increases the lines to be learned. Therefore, I would choose 5. Bd3 !}) 5... e6 {Not a great continuation for Black.} 6. b3 {Black gets a position that is a worse version of the Meran (or the Semi-Slav with a6 ), since the a6 pawn is not of much help to Black's position. Again, we can develop our knight on d2 instead of c3 .} *

