1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 a6 5. Bd3 {I would recommend this move, trying to play without Nc3 and keep the flexibility of developing the knight to d2 .} (5. Be2 $5 {This could be another good option for White which is rarely played, but deserves attention as well.}) (5. Nc3 {is the main move of course, but the point is that after} e6 {we enter the classic Semi-Slav with ... a6 which is very well studied and objectively not necessarily better than 5. Bd3 . And 5. Bd3 is way simpler to learn! Moreover, Black can play the classical Chebanenko with 5... b5 , which only increases the lines to be learned. Therefore, I would choose 5. Bd3 !}) 5... Bg4 ({The main move here. By including a6 , Black deals with Qb3 ideas. If Black plays} 5... dxc4 {we will have sooner or later a transposition to QGA (similarly as after e6 Bd3 dxc4 ) .} 6. Bxc4 e6 7. O-O b5 {(7... c5 see QGA.)} 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. a4 Nbd7 10. e4 {see the Slav 4... e6  Meran .}) (5... b5 $6 {without Nc3 , this move is not good for Black.} 6. b3 {White supports the c4 -pawn and will develop the knight to d2 .}) 6. Nbd2 {Reinforcing the Nf3 , so that we can recapture with the knight any moment.} e6 7. O-O {I would use this move to avoid Black's ideas related to ... c5 , which surprisingly work quite well with the inclusion of h3 and ... Bh5 .} c5 {This idea has been played here too. Now, however, it is not great as Bg4 in some lines is vulnerable.} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. dxc5 {Now, this move comes with a threat!} Nd7 (9... Bxc5 $4 10. Qa4+ {with a double attack.}) (9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Bxc5 11. Ne4) 10. c6 {A typical way to give back the pawn.} bxc6 11. e4 Nf4 12. Nc4 {Obviously White is better.} *

