1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 a6 5. Bd3 {I would recommend this move, trying to play without Nc3 and keep the flexibility of developing the knight to d2 .} (5. Be2 $5 {This could be another good option for White which is rarely played, but deserves attention as well.}) (5. Nc3 {is the main move of course, but the point is that after} e6 {we enter the classic Semi-Slav with ... a6 which is very well studied and objectively not necessarily better than 5. Bd3 . And 5. Bd3 is way simpler to learn! Moreover, Black can play the classical Chebanenko with 5... b5 , which only increases the lines to be learned. Therefore, I would choose 5. Bd3 !}) 5... Bg4 ({The main move here. By including a6 , Black deals with Qb3 ideas. If Black plays} 5... dxc4 {we will have sooner or later a transposition to QGA (similarly as after e6 Bd3 dxc4 ) .} 6. Bxc4 e6 7. O-O b5 {(7... c5 see QGA.)} 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. a4 Nbd7 10. e4 {see the Slav 4... e6  Meran .}) (5... b5 $6 {without Nc3 , this move is not good for Black.} 6. b3 {White supports the c4 -pawn and will develop the knight to d2 .}) 6. Nbd2 {Reinforcing the Nf3 , so that we can recapture with the knight any moment.} e6 7. O-O {I would use this move to avoid Black's ideas related to ... c5 , which surprisingly work quite well with the inclusion of h3 and ... Bh5 .} Nbd7 {The most standard move.} 8. h3 ({I think we should make Black declare the intentions of the Bg4 . The most normal retreat is Bh5 , but} 8. Bf5 {seems possible too, while} Bxf3 {gives away voluntarily the bishop pair so I don't take it serously.}) 8... Bh5 ({After} 8... Bxf3 {I would recapture with the knight,} 9. Nxf3 {but Qxf3 is also better for White.}) 9. b3 {The bishop gets developed to b2 , the queen goes to c2 and White prepares e4 .} Bd6 (9... Be7 10. Bb2 O-O 11. Qc2 {is very similar to 9... Bd6 as Black needs to play} Bg6 {which results in a very similar position to what I analyze in the main line.}) 10. Bb2 O-O 11. Qc2 {White's ideas are the following: e4 , Ne5 or Ng5 , depending on what Black does.} Bg6 {Black needs to trade these bishops.} 12. Bxg6 {I would not wait with this move, but trade the bishops right away to worsen Black's pawn structure.} hxg6 {Right now White has many good moves, but sooner or later he will have to play e4 . I would not sugarcoat it and play it right away.} 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 ({Black needs to simplify the position.} 14... Be7 $6 15. Neg5 {is clearly better for White.}) 15. Qxe4 {This position is a classic type of middlegame that we can find in many Slavs or Caro-Kanns. Of course Black is super solid and has no obvious weaknesses. Since some minor pieces have already been exchanged, Black should have no problems with the lack of space. However, all this does not mean that Black's position is easy, in my opinion. I like that White has good control of the center with the c4 and d4 pawns. Such control offers a little more space and potential for improvement to White's pieces. In addition, the pawns on g6 and g7 weaken Black's position in my eyes because of the potential h4 - h5 ideas in the future, or the Ng5 move one day. White also has a rather simple plan: place the rooks in the center, ideally on d1 and d3 , control Black's counterplay, and one day launch an attack on the queen side. In the case of ... a5 by Black, generally a4 is favorable since the b4 outpost is irrelevant and it is more important to keep Black in some kind of constraint. Overall, I prefer White and Black has yet to prove parity.} Nf6 (15... Qa5 16. Rfd1 Qf5 {Such a plan can be played by some. Of course, White does not exchange queens.} 17. Qe2 Rfe8 18. Rd3) 16. Qe2 {Usually, the queen is well placed here.} c5 17. Rad1 Qc7 18. Rd3 Rad8 19. Rfd1 {Despite Black being very solid, I believe that White is slightly better and has an easier-to-play position. The d-file is more likely to be under White’s control. We can play Ne5 at some point, and in the future, our 3 vs 2 on the queenside may be easier to push forward as well.  Overall, the Chebanenko Slav is a very solid option for Black, but I believe that the lines I recommend offer playable positions with small but durable advantages and, most importantly, the positions are easy to play for White.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Slav: 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 g6 S"]
[Black "Schlechter - 7...Bg4 8.cxd5 c"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D94"]
[PlyCount "29"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} Bg4 {As the bishop leaves the b7 pawn unattended, we can go for a standard Slav idea.} 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Qb3 {Targeting both the b7 and d5 pawns. It seems like we are voluntarily going for an Exchange Slav, but it is a much better version compared to the normal lines, as the Bg7 is misplaced.} Bc8 {This is an option, but it is somewhat passive.} 10. Ne5 ({I think it makes a lot of sense to install this knight on e5 and further support it with f4 . A more positional} 10. Bd2 Nc6 11. Rfc1 {makes a lot of sense as well.}) 10... Nc6 (10... e6 11. Bd2 Nfd7 12. f4 {and Black has hardly anything better than} Nc6 {, which transposes.}) 11. f4 ({White needs to support the knight. The most common move is} 11. Nxc6 $2 bxc6 {but it spoils all White's advantage.}) 11... e6 (11... Qb6 {This was played in Caruana-Ortega (2011). Fabiano chose} 12. Bd2 {which is fine, but Stockfish likes more Qxb6 axb6 b3!± the b-pawns are a weakness, and Na4 is an idea.}) 12. Bd2 Nd7 {Black wants to trade the Ne5 and then play ... f6 , opening the center.} 13. Be1 {Prophylaxis!} f6 (13... Ndxe5 14. fxe5 f6 15. Bh4 $1) 14. Nxc6 {Now this move makes much more sense than on move 11.} bxc6 15. Rc1 {White has pressure against the weak c6 -pawn.} *

