1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} Bg4 {As the bishop leaves the b7 pawn unattended, we can go for a standard Slav idea.} 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Qb3 {Targeting both the b7 and d5 pawns. It seems like we are voluntarily going for an Exchange Slav, but it is a much better version compared to the normal lines, as the Bg7 is misplaced.} Bc8 {This is an option, but it is somewhat passive.} 10. Ne5 ({I think it makes a lot of sense to install this knight on e5 and further support it with f4 . A more positional} 10. Bd2 Nc6 11. Rfc1 {makes a lot of sense as well.}) 10... Nc6 (10... e6 11. Bd2 Nfd7 12. f4 {and Black has hardly anything better than} Nc6 {, which transposes.}) 11. f4 ({White needs to support the knight. The most common move is} 11. Nxc6 $2 bxc6 {but it spoils all White's advantage.}) 11... e6 (11... Qb6 {This was played in Caruana-Ortega (2011). Fabiano chose} 12. Bd2 {which is fine, but Stockfish likes more Qxb6 axb6 b3!± the b-pawns are a weakness, and Na4 is an idea.}) 12. Bd2 Ne7 {Black intends to fight the Ne5 by reorganizing his own knights and eventually playing ... f6 .} 13. Qa3 {I like this idea the most. The queen remains flexible and puts pressure on the queenside, as well as the a3 - f8 diagonal where we can keep an eye on important d6 -square, trying to prevent Black's regrouping.} ({An important point is that Ne8? leads to immediate trouble after} 13. Nb5 $1 {with the Bb4 idea.}) 13... Bd7 14. Bd3 Be8 {This is what Black sometimes does in such positions. Now, however, the b7 -pawn is a bit weak.} 15. Qb3 {The queen comes back as the Be8 is not great now. We can play via a4 - a5 .} Rb8 16. a4 {We intend a5 , and if Black plays ... a5 , that will weaken quite significantly his queenside. White is better.} *

