1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} Bg4 {As the bishop leaves the b7 pawn unattended, we can go for a standard Slav idea.} 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Qb3 {Targeting both the b7 and d5 pawns. It seems like we are voluntarily going for an Exchange Slav, but it is a much better version compared to the normal lines, as the Bg7 is misplaced.} Bc8 {This is an option, but it is somewhat passive.} 10. Ne5 ({I think it makes a lot of sense to install this knight on e5 and further support it with f4 . A more positional} 10. Bd2 Nc6 11. Rfc1 {makes a lot of sense as well.}) 10... Nc6 (10... e6 11. Bd2 Nfd7 12. f4 {and Black has hardly anything better than} Nc6 {, which transposes.}) 11. f4 ({White needs to support the knight. The most common move is} 11. Nxc6 $2 bxc6 {but it spoils all White's advantage.}) 11... e6 (11... Qb6 {This was played in Caruana-Ortega (2011). Fabiano chose} 12. Bd2 {which is fine, but Stockfish likes more Qxb6 axb6 b3!± the b-pawns are a weakness, and Na4 is an idea.}) 12. Bd2 Ne7 {Black intends to fight the Ne5 by reorganizing his own knights and eventually playing ... f6 .} 13. Qa3 {I like this idea the most. The queen remains flexible and puts pressure on the queenside, as well as the a3 - f8 diagonal where we can keep an eye on important d6 -square, trying to prevent Black's regrouping.} ({An important point is that Ne8? leads to immediate trouble after} 13. Nb5 $1 {with the Bb4 idea.}) 13... Nf5 14. Rfc1 {There is not much of a difference between Rfc1 and Rac1 . In some lines, the Ra1 may be more useful when the queenside opens (like after 14... a5 15.b4! ), and for this reason, I decided to keep Rfc1 as the best move. Generally, Black does not have easy play here. The knight cannot easily get to d6 due to certain tactical reasons (thanks to Qa3 !). Some example lines:} Ne8 {The best attempt to regroup.} (14... Bd7 $2 15. g4 $1) (14... a5 15. b4 $1) (14... Nd6 $2 15. Nb5 $1 {and White actually just wins as Black is not able to complete his development!}) 15. g4 Nfd6 16. Nb5 {Putting pressure on the crucial d6 -square.} Nxb5 17. Bxb5 Nd6 18. Be2 {White is clearly pressing. One last thing we should know:} Bxe5 {We meet this with a brilliant reply!} 19. Bb4 {Retaining our initiative.} *

