1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} Bg4 {As the bishop leaves the b7 pawn unattended, we can go for a standard Slav idea.} 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Qb3 {Targeting both the b7 and d5 pawns. It seems like we are voluntarily going for an Exchange Slav, but it is a much better version compared to the normal lines, as the Bg7 is misplaced.} b6 10. h3 {I like this move for White more than 10. Bd2 , which has been a bit more popular recently. Here, White is able to keep more pieces on the board, making the position much more playable.} (10. Bd2 {As mentioned, I don't like this move due to} Ne4 11. Be1 Nc6 12. h3 Nxc3 $1 13. Bxc3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 e6 {and it seems that due to the traded minor pieces Black should be able to hold rather comfortably.}) 10... Bc8 {This move was played a couple of times by Vladislav Artemiev, arguing that inclusion of h3 and b6 moves helps Black. The bishop may go to b7 now for instance. However, I believe it is only weakening Black's queenside!} 11. Bd2 Nc6 12. Ne5 ({It makes sense to install the knight on e5 .} 12. Rfc1 Bb7 13. Rc2 $5 {is a decent alternative.}) 12... Bb7 13. f4 {White is slightly better thanks to the strong knight on e5 . Next, Rfc1 and Be1 - h4 could follow.} *

