1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} Bg4 {As the bishop leaves the b7 pawn unattended, we can go for a standard Slav idea.} 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Qb3 {Targeting both the b7 and d5 pawns. It seems like we are voluntarily going for an Exchange Slav, but it is a much better version compared to the normal lines, as the Bg7 is misplaced.} b6 10. h3 {I like this move for White more than 10. Bd2 , which has been a bit more popular recently. Here, White is able to keep more pieces on the board, making the position much more playable.} (10. Bd2 {As mentioned, I don't like this move due to} Ne4 11. Be1 Nc6 12. h3 Nxc3 $1 13. Bxc3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 e6 {and it seems that due to the traded minor pieces Black should be able to hold rather comfortably.}) 10... Bxf3 11. Bxf3 e6 {Black gave up the pair of bishops to stabilize the position and try to claim that the Exchange Slav pawn structure is sufficient to equalize. It is not so easy though - White's bishop pair will matter in the long run, especially because of the weakened light squares on the queenside.} 12. Qa4 {Not making it easy for Black to complete his development. It is actually nearly impossible now to develop the knight from b8 to c6 .} Qd7 (12... a6 {This move does not threaten ... b5 due to the pin. White can just play} 13. Bd2 {and Black needs to perhaps try ... Nbd7 , but of course it is not optimal. For example} Nbd7 14. Rfc1 b5 15. Qd1 Nb6 16. Be1) 13. Qxd7 {This endgame is chronically worse for Black.} Nfxd7 {This leaves Black in a bad endgame.} 14. Nxd5 {Taking advantage of the rook's position, still locked in a8 .} exd5 15. Bxd5 Na6 16. Bxa8 Rxa8 17. Bd2 {Black's knights have no outposts and White's pawn mass does great job with restricting Black's pieces. Sooner or later these pawns may go forward, but at the meantime White will take over the c-file!} *

