1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} Nbd7 {This move declares too early where the knight is going. If White goes for the Exchange Slav structure, then the Nbd7 will be definitely misplaced.} 8. cxd5 cxd5 {The knight would love to be placed on c6 now!} 9. Qb3 e6 (9... Nb6 10. a4 $1 {is also great for White. Black is forced to play} a5 {which severely weakens the b5 -square and the Nb6 will be also misplaced.}) 10. Rd1 ({White prepares Bd2 . After} 10. Bd2 Ne4 {White should play} 11. Be1 {to maintain some edge, but now the rook will be misplaced on f1 . Because of this, I like 10. Rd1 more.}) 10... a6 (10... Nb8 {is a logical move as well, fixing the position of the knight.} 11. Bd2 Nc6 12. Rac1) 11. Bd2 b6 12. Rac1 Bb7 13. Na4 {Black is under pressure. The ideas of Bb4 and Nc5 are unpleasant to meet.} *

