1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} a6 {Black tries a hybrid Chebanenko and Schlechter setups.} 8. a4 {I would prevent ... b5 and at the same time expand on the queenside. So far Black tried many moves but I will cover the ones that I feel like make the most sense.} Bg4 {In comparison with 7... Bg4 , right now Qb3 ideas can be met with ... Ra7 guarding the b7 pawn. It is a standard idea, but it does not equalize.} 9. Qb3 Ra7 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 e6 12. a5 {Fixing the queenside pawn structure.} Nbd7 13. Rd1 {White has two possible approaches here: play e4 quickly (hence Rd1 ) or play more "slowly" with g3 , Bd2 , Bg2 , not rushing things. Either way, White is clearly better.} *

