1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} a6 {Black tries a hybrid Chebanenko and Schlechter setups.} 8. a4 {I would prevent ... b5 and at the same time expand on the queenside. So far Black tried many moves but I will cover the ones that I feel like make the most sense.} dxc4 9. Bxc4 c5 {This idea was tried by Kamsky a couple of times. White has two good options here.} (9... Bg4 {is simply a worse version of dxc4 Bxc4 Bg4 as I recommend playing with a4 anyway.}) 10. dxc5 ({I like this approach the most.} 10. d5 {is also good, of course.}) 10... Qxd1 (10... Qa5 11. h3 $1 Qxc5 12. Qe2 {followed by e4 and Be3 .}) 11. Rxd1 Nbd7 {Black will recapture the pawn but his position will be unpleasant in the endgame.} 12. c6 bxc6 13. a5 {White has a clear edge in this endgame due to a better pawn structure.} *

