1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} a6 {Black tries a hybrid Chebanenko and Schlechter setups.} 8. a4 {I would prevent ... b5 and at the same time expand on the queenside. So far Black tried many moves but I will cover the ones that I feel like make the most sense.} a5 {With this move Black seizes control over the b4 -square but he also concedes the b5 -square.} 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. e4 Nb4 11. Be3 ({With a considerable advantage due to the strong center. A nice illustration of how the game can unfold is Giri-Andreikin from 2022 World Blitz Championship. Bg4} 11. h3 {Bxf3 Bxf3} Nd7 {Be2 Qc7} 12. Qb3 {Rad8 Rfd1} Nf6 {Rac1 e6} 13. e5 Nfd5 14. Bg5 f6 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Bxf6 Rxf6 17. Ne4 Rf4 18. Nc5 {Qf7} Bg4) *

