1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} a6 {Black tries a hybrid Chebanenko and Schlechter setups.} 8. a4 {I would prevent ... b5 and at the same time expand on the queenside. So far Black tried many moves but I will cover the ones that I feel like make the most sense.} a5 {With this move Black seizes control over the b4 -square but he also concedes the b5 -square.} 9. cxd5 cxd5 {Necessary, as taking with the knight allows White to control the center; the b4 -square will not be relevant.} 10. b3 {A very logical and healthy way to complete development.} Nc6 (10... Ne4 $6 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Nd2) 11. Ba3 Bg4 (11... Bf5 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. h3) 12. Ne1 {With this move White avoids ... Bxf3 and wants to keep the knight to eventually install it on d3 .} Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Ne4 14. Nb5 {I think this is a very pleasant position for White.} *

