1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} b6 {This line leads to quite a passive setups for Black. White has many options, but I like in particular what happened in the game Carlsen-Mamedyarov (2015).} 8. a4 {White gains space and potentially intends a5 , but there are also ideas related to b4 and further expansion on the queenside.} Bb7 {Probably the most solid move. After strengthing the control over the d5 -square, Black intends ... c5 .} 9. b4 {I would expand on the queenside first to prevent (or discourage) ... c5 ideas.} dxc4 (9... Nbd7 10. a5 {is really unpleasant.}) 10. Bxc4 Nd5 ({Trying to simplify the position.} 10... Nbd7 11. Qb3 e6 12. Ba3 {favors White as well.}) 11. Nxd5 cxd5 12. Be2 {White is better as we get a good version of the Exchange Slav with a bad bishop on g7 .} *

