1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} b6 {This line leads to quite a passive setups for Black. White has many options, but I like in particular what happened in the game Carlsen-Mamedyarov (2015).} 8. a4 {White gains space and potentially intends a5 , but there are also ideas related to b4 and further expansion on the queenside.} Ba6 9. b3 {Supporting the c4 -pawn. White intends Ba3 with a nice positional advantage.} c5 {Black can try to fight for the center in the following way, but it is not enough for equality.} 10. Ba3 dxc4 11. bxc4 Nc6 12. Rc1 cxd4 13. exd4 ({One may argue that White's c4 and d4 pawns could be weak, but indeed they are strong central pawns that control many important squares and give White a space advantage. Na5} 13. Ne5 Nd7 14. Nd5 $1 Re8 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Nb4 Bb7 17. c5 $1 bxc5 18. Rxc5 {with ideas of Bb5 and d5 .}) *

