1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} b6 {This line leads to quite a passive setups for Black. White has many options, but I like in particular what happened in the game Carlsen-Mamedyarov (2015).} 8. a4 {White gains space and potentially intends a5 , but there are also ideas related to b4 and further expansion on the queenside.} a5 {A logical move but it appears to be already an inaccuracy.} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. b3 {Just like after a6 a4 a5 , Black suffers from the weak b5 -square. The b6 -pawn on one hand helps Black to complete development with Bb7 and Nc6 , but it also weakens the light squares on the queenside.} Bb7 11. Ba3 Nc6 {This was more solid, compared to 10... Ne4 ?!, but White has a big positional advantage anyway. The b4 square is not as great of an outpost as the b5 square.} 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. h3 ({A waiting move, as Black does not have many useful moves.} 13. Ne5 $5 {is interesting too.} Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. f4 Nc5 16. Nb5) 13... Re8 {Black tries to bring his bishop to the game.} 14. Bb5 e6 15. Ne5 {The pin is really annoying. Black needs to play ... Nd7 .} Nd7 {And White now obtains a very promising position with the following sequence.} 16. Bxc6 Bxc6 17. Nxc6 Rxc6 18. Nb5 {It is White that will control the c-file.} *

