1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} b6 {This line leads to quite a passive setups for Black. White has many options, but I like in particular what happened in the game Carlsen-Mamedyarov (2015).} 8. a4 {White gains space and potentially intends a5 , but there are also ideas related to b4 and further expansion on the queenside.} a5 {A logical move but it appears to be already an inaccuracy.} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. b3 {Just like after a6 a4 a5 , Black suffers from the weak b5 -square. The b6 -pawn on one hand helps Black to complete development with Bb7 and Nc6 , but it also weakens the light squares on the queenside.} Ne4 {Mamedyarov chooses a wrong plan.} 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Nd2 Bb7 13. Ba3 {White has a very nice position and a simple plan: Rc1 , Nc4 . Maybe Bb5 is worth including as well, and b4 !? is an idea too.} f5 14. Rc1 Kh8 (14... Nd7 15. b4 $5 Nf6 16. bxa5 bxa5 17. Nc4 {White is strategically dominant. Vachier Lagrave - Li Chao (2015).}) 15. Nc4 Nd7 16. d5 {With a big advantage, as seen in Carlsen-Mamedyarov (2015).} *

