1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} e6 {This line somewhat resembles a Meran but with ... g6 . I think it is an odd configuration for Black. The bishop on g7 is not well placed and White can exploit it immediately.} 8. b3 {The bishop goes to a3 , taking control over the a3 - f8 diagonal. Of course, if Black's bishop was normally placed on d6 , this would not have been possible} b6 ({•} 8... Nbd7 {This move likely results in a transposition, as ... b6 -... Bb7 is rather inevitable. Playing without it leaves the c8 -bishop really badly placed.} 9. Ba3 Re8 10. Rc1 Ne4 (10... b6 11. Ne5 {would transpose after 11... Bb7 12. f4 , while other moves are just bad.} Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. f4 Bb7 14. cxd5 exd5 15. e4 $1) 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Nd2 f5 13. b4) ({•} 8... Re8 {This move was tried by players such as Van Foreest and Kamsky. However, after} 9. Ba3 {the transposition to either 8... b6 or 8... Nbd7 is inevitable.}) 9. Ba3 Re8 10. Ne5 {A useful move - the knight immediately exerts some pressure on the c6 -pawn.} Bb7 11. Rc1 Nbd7 12. f4 {I remember this position happening live in game Bok-Ipatov (2019) and Benjamin was blitzing out his preparation. And indeed, this is a good line for White. White's idea is to fully support the Ne5 and play next Bf3 to discourage potential ... c5 ideas.} c5 {Alex Ipatov tried this move and it seems like a good practical decision.} 13. Bf3 Bf8 14. Qe2 ({A strong novelty. White should first complete his development. In the Bok-Ipatov game followed} 14. Nxd7 $2 Qxd7 15. dxc5 Bxc5 16. Bxc5 bxc5 17. Na4 {which is approximately equal; the players agreed (perhaps prematurely) to a draw.}) 14... Rc8 (14... cxd4 15. Bxf8 Nxf8 16. exd4 {is also better for White, of course.}) 15. Rfd1 Qc7 {Black's position seems solid here. But with a few accurate move White can dismantle this illusion.} 16. Nxd7 {Unlike in Bok's game, this move works now as there is Rfd1 already on the board.} Qxd7 17. dxc5 Bxc5 (17... bxc5 18. Bb2 {followed by Na4 , with pressure against the d5 -pawn.}) 18. Bxc5 bxc5 19. e4 {This is the point.} d4 20. e5 Nh5 21. Bxb7 Qxb7 22. Ne4 {White has a huge advantage.} *

