1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} Be6 8. b3 {I think this is the simplest.} c5 {The most popular move - but I am not sure if Black is fully ready to engage in such dynamic play.} 9. Ba3 {I like this developmental move.} Ne4 ({The only move that does not lead to an awful position. It is quite rare though.} 9... cxd4 $6 {is the most common move, but after} 10. Nxd4 {there are issues with the Be6 . Positions like this arise in some lines of the Grünfeld, but here it is simply bad.} Nc6 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Rc1) 10. Nxd5 ({This is the simplest and that's why I recommend it. But} 10. Na4 {is an interesting option too, with the idea of} dxc4 11. Qc2 {which you are welcome to explore yourself.}) 10... Bxd5 11. cxd5 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nc3 13. Qd3 Nxe2+ 14. Qxe2 Qxd5 {We obtain this position nearly by force. Due to the lead in development, White has the advantage.} 15. Rad1 Qe4 16. f3 Qe5 17. f4 Qe4 (17... Qc7 $2 18. Nb5 {and Black does not hold the e7 -pawn.}) 18. Qd3 Qxd3 19. Rxd3 {With a clearly better endgame.} *

