1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} Be6 8. b3 {I think this is the simplest.} Ne4 {A standard idea in these positions - trading one pair of knights helps Black deal with less space.} 9. Bb2 ({I think this is the simplest and leads to a slight advantage for White. A couple of years ago I analyzed} 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Ng5 $5 {which is fascinating, following Ding's game, but seems unnecessarily complicated and objectively no better than 9. Bb2 .}) 9... Nd7 10. Rc1 Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Nf6 {Black can also play this way, still trying to install Ne4 . In this case, 12. Nd2 is possible but a bit passive and I would prefer something more active.} 12. Ne5 Ne4 13. Bb2 ({With f3 next and a pleasant position for White. The trades on e5 are in White's favor, as the dark squares in the long run would be pretty weak. Bxe5 dxe5 dxc4 Bxc4!} 13. Qd2 $5 {White can now go for the forcing 16. Qxd2 or the more positional 16. Rc2 . Qxd2! Rc2!? Qxd1 Rxd1 Rfd8 Rxd8+ Rxd8 Be2!⩲} Nxd2 {Bxe6 Nxf1 Bd7! Nd2} 14. f3 {Rfd8 e6 fxe6 Bxe6+ Kf8} Bxe5 {followed by Kf2 - e2 .}) *

