1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} Be6 8. b3 {I think this is the simplest.} Ne4 {A standard idea in these positions - trading one pair of knights helps Black deal with less space.} 9. Bb2 ({I think this is the simplest and leads to a slight advantage for White. A couple of years ago I analyzed} 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Ng5 $5 {which is fascinating, following Ding's game, but seems unnecessarily complicated and objectively no better than 9. Bb2 .}) 9... Nxc3 {Sooner or later Black needs to trade anyway.} 10. Bxc3 Bg4 {Black wants to simplify the position, but in doing so he concedes the bishop pair and gets a worse middlegame. However, Black's position is quite solid after the exchanges, so it is a decent option to play.} ({In 2017, Peter Prohashka played against me} 10... Bf5 {White has many good options, I opted for} 11. b4 $1 {with the plan of expanding on the queenside. You can see the annotated game in the model games section.}) 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 e6 {In these positions, it is important not to rush and to find a good plan and set-up for the pieces. In my opinion, such a plan includes g3 - Kg2 , expansion on the queenside, placement of rooks in c1 and d1 or in b1 and c1 and, above all, control of Black's counterplay, which is mainly related to the pawn breaks ... e5 and ... c5 . Then we should have a nice edge.} 13. a4 {White can begin with this move, as a5 could be a bit annoying potentially.} Nd7 14. Qc2 {We should not rush with a5 , as after ... a6 it could be difficult to open the queenside.} Re8 15. Rfd1 Qe7 16. Rac1 Rac8 17. g3 h5 18. Kg2 {An optimal position for both sides - but it is White that leads the play. We can prepare b4 - b5 , and we can double the rooks on the c-file. We should not worry about ... h4 as g4 is good for White.} (18. h4 {g4⩲}) ({a6} 18. Be1 Nf6 19. Qd3) *

