1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} Bf5 {One of the possible ways to develop the bishop.} 8. h3 {Kind of aiming against Bf5 - now, there are ideas of g4 !, especially when Black plays ... Nbd7 or ... e6 .} ({I would have loved to recommend} 8. cxd5 {, and a move like 8. b3 is also completely OK.} cxd5 (8... Nxd5 $6 {is worse due to} 9. Ng5 $1) 9. Qb3 {In the case of 9... Bc8 we simply transpose, while ... b6 is rarely good for Black. This would make it very easy to counter 7... Bf5 - but I encountered problems after} Qb6 $1 {which is a strong pawn sacrifice.} 10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Nc6 {And here, I did not find anything great for White. It feels like Black has a good compensation as ... e5 is coming soon and White will have issues completing the development of his queenside.}) 8... Ne4 ({•} 8... Nbd7 $2 {runs into} 9. g4 $1 {and White is better after} Be6 10. Ng5 {or Be4 Nd2±}) ({•} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 {is of course comfortable for White.}) 9. Qb3 {A standard way of meeting ... Ne4 , as the d5 -pawn is weakened.} b6 10. Rd1 {I am not sure if it is necessary to analyze it further: White has a good position. The pressure on d5 is troublesome for Black. If ... dxc4 , White is happy because Black gives up the center. There is no good way to develop Nb8 , and .... e6 can be dealt with either with g4 !?, or with a simple Nd2 and keep g4 for the future.} *

