1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} Ne4 {This was played in Duda-Yu Yangyi (2019). It seems like this move is a bit premature as we can take on e4 and play Nd2 , attacking the e4 -pawn, but it is actually not so clear. I think that White should keep the tension and not go for concrete play just yet.} 8. Qb3 ({I like this move the most.} 8. Nxe4 {was what Duda played but it seems like Black gets good counterplay after} dxe4 9. Nd2 c5 $1 10. dxc5 f5 {with an unclear game.}) 8... dxc4 ({The best response. Everything else is fairly easy for White.} 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 {gives White a comfortable pawn structure.} b6 10. Ba3 Ba6 11. Rfe1) 9. Qxc4 {It is important to recapture with the queen as after Nd6 it is good to have the Qd3 retreat, followed by e4 !} Bf5 {This can be played too, as an alternative to ... Nd6 .} 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Ng5 {Chasing the bishop.} Bd5 12. Qc2 f5 13. Nh3 {A nice regrouping. White has a clear edge.} *

