1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} Ne4 {This was played in Duda-Yu Yangyi (2019). It seems like this move is a bit premature as we can take on e4 and play Nd2 , attacking the e4 -pawn, but it is actually not so clear. I think that White should keep the tension and not go for concrete play just yet.} 8. Qb3 ({I like this move the most.} 8. Nxe4 {was what Duda played but it seems like Black gets good counterplay after} dxe4 9. Nd2 c5 $1 10. dxc5 f5 {with an unclear game.}) 8... dxc4 ({The best response. Everything else is fairly easy for White.} 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 {gives White a comfortable pawn structure.} b6 10. Ba3 Ba6 11. Rfe1) 9. Qxc4 {It is important to recapture with the queen as after Nd6 it is good to have the Qd3 retreat, followed by e4 !} Nd6 10. Qd3 {The point of 9. Qxc4 ! Now, White can play e4 and build a strong center with an advantage.} Bg4 (10... Na6 11. e4) 11. e4 ({The most principled.} 11. h3 $5 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 {is also completely playable, with the bishop pair and a slight edge.}) 11... Nd7 12. Be3 Rc8 {This position resembles the Russian Variation in the Grünfeld but as a good version for White as we have a good grip over the center. Also, so far we have been following the game Keymer-Nihal (2021), but here I would recommend an improvement over Keymer's 13. Rad1 .} 13. Ng5 Bxe2 14. Qxe2 {A good trade for White. White's idea could be to play 15. f4 or sometimes even 15. e5 with a nice space advantage. Because of that, Black should try ... e5 .} e5 {But White retains the advantage.} 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. f4 Nec4 17. e5 {Things get a little bit forced or tactical here.} Nxe3 18. Qxe3 Nf5 19. Qh3 h6 20. Nge4 ({White's position looks promising. The Bg7 is out of play, White has strong center and active pieces. Now, g4 is an idea, so Black can try h5 but after} 20. Kh1 {White has ideas of Ng5 and Ng3 , dealing with Nf5 .}) *

