1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} Re8 {A rare move that was tried by Jorden Van Foreest. The main idea seems to be to provoke the standard b3 that no longer allows Qb3 ideas in case of ... Bg4 . Therefore, this is a sneaky move order. However, we have some interesting ideas.} 8. a4 {I would recommend this move, expanding on the queenside. The idea is a5 or b4 . Therefore, Black's response is standard.} a5 (8... Bg4 9. Qb3 $1 {is unpleasant for Black.}) 9. cxd5 {Only now we enter the Exchange Slav pawn structure as now White will control the b5 square.} cxd5 10. Ne5 {This is the engine's recommendation. White's Ne5 will be supported with f4 and will be very strong. Next, Bb5 will be likely played, and the idea of Bd2 - Be1 - Bh4 is coming as well.} Nc6 11. f4 Be6 ({Preparing ... Ne4 .} 11... Bf5 $6 {the bishop may run into g4 ideas, either right away or after} 12. Bb5 Rc8 13. g4 $1) (11... Ne4 $2 {is premature due to} 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Bc4 $1) 12. Bf3 {Stopping ... Ne4 .} Rc8 13. Bd2 {I like White in this position but of course there is a lot of play ahead.} *

