1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} Qb6 {This move has been played quite frequently by Gata Kamsky. I think it is played mainly to anticipate the ideas of Qb3 and/or Bd2 , as well as to maintain the flexibility of Nb8 to develop into c6 in case of exchanges on d5 . For example, one of the points of Qb6 is to play ... Bg4 and avoid reaction with cxd5 and Qb3 .} 8. h3 {That's why I like this move for White - Black does not have ... Bg4 now.} Bf5 9. b3 {The simplest. Completing the development.} Ne4 10. Bb2 Rd8 {Played in Di Berardino-Kamsky (2011). I think this move is unnecessary, as there was no threat of cxd5 anyway. I think White is simply better here in a number of ways. In the game followed the very reasonable 11. Rc1 .} (10... Nd7 {was perhaps a bit more accurate, but White enjoys a pleasant position in many ways. For example} 11. Rc1 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Nf6 13. a4 a5 14. Bb2) 11. Rc1 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 a5 13. Qd2 ({With a comfortable position for White. Kamsky played Nd7 which allows} 13. g4 $1 {which is stronger than 14. Qb2 played by Di Berardino. Right now, White gets the bishop pair and gains space.} Be4 14. Ng5 ({Be6} 14. Ng5)) *

