1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} c5 {This move results in a Grünfeld, but with one less tempo because Black played ... c6 and then ... c5 . Of course, it is possible, but having one more move as White should be at least promising.} 8. dxc5 {This one seems the most critical. After all, White gets a pawn here!} Na6 ({The best reaction.} 8... dxc4 $6 9. Bxc4 {has been mostly played so far but it does not offer compensation. In fact, we transpose to a line that I cover in QGA with 4... g6 .}) 9. cxd5 Nxc5 10. Bc4 {Best move. White supports the d5 pawn, preventing the liberating ... e6 -ideas and will soon complete the development.} a6 11. a4 Bd7 {Preparing the potential ... b5 makes a lot of sense.} 12. b3 {As we will see in a moment, there is no tactic associated with the long diagonal, and this move is good because we want to develop the bishop in a3 . At the same time, ... b5 does not solve Black's problems.} b5 (12... Nfe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Nd4 $1 {simply neutralizes Black's counterplay.}) 13. axb5 axb5 14. Rxa8 Qxa8 15. Nxb5 Bxb5 16. Bxb5 Nxd5 17. Qc2 Rc8 18. Bd2 {White enjoys an extra pawn and the road to equality for Black is still very long.} *

