1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} dxc4 {Black gives up control of the center, but intends to play ... Bg4 later and prepare for the pawn break ... e5 as soon as possible.} 8. Bxc4 Bg4 {This is considered as the most solid approach for Black. The idea is to play ... Nbd7 and ... e5 as quickly as possible, even at a cost of the bishop pair, to generate counterplay in the center.} 9. h3 {At least as an informational line, I need to bring up 9. h3 as well.} Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nbd7 {Black plays ... e5 next. The main line goes as follows.} 11. Rd1 e5 12. d5 e4 13. Nxe4 ({And here Black can play either} 13. Nxe4 {(which I think it is not so accurate), or} Ne5 $1 {, which in my opinion should equalize.}) 13... Ne5 {Black makes sure that he rids White from the bishop pair.} (13... Nxe4 {I don't like it much for Black, due to} 14. Qxe4 Nb6 15. Be2 $1 {and White gives the pawn back but retains the bishop pair with some advantage.} cxd5 (15... Nxd5 16. Rb1 Re8 17. Qc2) 16. Qd3 {Followed by Bf3 , Bd2 and Rb1 .}) 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Qe4 Nxc4 16. Qxc4 cxd5 17. Rxd5 Qb6 {I think that Black has sufficient compensation. I analyzed it quite a bit but Black's activity always seemed sufficient to equalize. Of course, it can be played too, but it just seems that 9. Be2 offers more playable and fresh positions.} *

