1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} dxc4 {Black gives up control of the center, but intends to play ... Bg4 later and prepare for the pawn break ... e5 as soon as possible.} 8. Bxc4 Bg4 {This is considered as the most solid approach for Black. The idea is to play ... Nbd7 and ... e5 as quickly as possible, even at a cost of the bishop pair, to generate counterplay in the center.} 9. Be2 ({I like this move as it is rarer than} 9. h3 {and it is aimed precisely against Black's ideas of ... e5 .}) 9... Nbd7 10. e4 Bxf3 11. gxf3 {A very rare and interesting idea against Black's pawn break with ... e5 . At the time this course was created, there are only 3 games in the database - but the engine is definitely appreciating White's chances, and all three of these games were won by White. Right now, ... e5 is simply as bad as I have analyzed. White controls the center, has the bishop pair, and with a simple development is able to put pressure on Black. The biggest challenge for Black is the dramatic change in the nature of the position: normally Black plays via ... e5 and here he cannot do so. Therefore, from a practical point of view, this position looks very promising for White.} e6 {Black needs to play with ... e6 here. The idea is to meet e5 with ... Nd5 .} 12. Be3 {Here Black has a couple of plans available.} Ne8 {An interesting and logical maneuver that improves the bishop and knight. Black wants to pressure the d4 pawn, as well as bring the knight to d6 or c7 . Also, ... Qh4 is an idea!} 13. Qb3 {We should put pressure on the queenside right away.} c5 {Black can try to hit the center right away, taking advantage of a little tactic.} 14. d5 ({A standard push in these positions.} 14. dxc5 $6 {spoils the advantage.} Nxc5 {and White cannot win the piece with} 15. Bxc5 $2 {due to} Qg5+ {, with a double attack.}) 14... exd5 15. Nxd5 {This position looks promising for White - Black 's light squares are pretty weak we want to play Rad1 , f4 , e5 etc. On top of that, the b7 -pawn is under attack.} *

