1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {I definitely recommend this line against the Schlechter, as I think it is the most challenging option. One of the main points is that if Black plays ... Bg4 , we are not pinned, and very often, there are Qb3 ideas. Another point is that in some positions after ... dxc4 , we are not forced to recapture right away, unlike after 6.Bd3 , let's say. And finally, I tried this line in my games and have been getting great positions!} O-O 7. O-O {Black has many moves, among which Bg4 , dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.} dxc4 ({Black has many moves, among which} 7... Bg4 {, dxc4 and perhaps a6 would be the most challenging. The rest, although there are many moves played in the database, I can address with short lines.}) 8. Bxc4 b5 {This move was tried in some rare games by Dubov and Van Foreest. It is not great, but White should know how to react to it.} 9. Bd3 {White prepares e4 with this move.} a5 {This is also an option. White has countless ways to an advantage.} 10. e4 {The most straightforward.} e5 {Black shouldn't play this:} 11. dxe5 Ng4 12. Bg5 ({Followed by a thematic maneuver: Qe8} 12. h3 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 {Qxe5 f4± with an excellent position for White.}) *

