1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A solid line for Black against the 4. e3 Slav. White has many interesting options here.} 5. Qb3 {Recently this move has been scoring well for White. White immediately puts pressure on the b7 -pawn and gets out of the pin, allowing Nf3 to move.} Bxf3 {Black is not in time to mess up White's pawn structure.} 6. Qxb7 Be4 {The most resilient move, according to the engine. But it’s still not enough.} 7. Qxa8 Qc7 {Black tries to trap White's queen or at least keep it away from the game. One of Black's ideas is to play ... e6 , ... Be7 , and ... O-O , followed by ... Nbd7 . Another idea involves dxc4 , followed by rerouting the Nf6 to b6 .} 8. f3 {I think this is the most direct approach that forces matters. Sure, there are some things to memorize here, but everything is pretty straightforward.} Bxb1 9. Rxb1 dxc4 {The only move. Black tries to trap the queen with ... Nd5 /... Nfd7 -... Nb6 idea. Here, we need to play a very important move.} ({After} 9... e6 10. b4) 10. b3 {White tries to open the b-file, or at least create a path for the Bf1 so it can rescue the queen with the Ba6 idea.} c3 {Black cannot let the b-file open.} 11. Ba6 {Now White's queen escapes to b7 . It looks like Black is lost, but with precise play (good luck finding all these moves!) Black can sort of survive the initial phase of the game and reach a difficult endgame.} e5 12. dxe5 Nd5 (12... Qxe5 13. b4 $1 {and White should win.} c2 14. Rb3 Bxb4+ 15. Kf2 O-O 16. Qxa7) 13. Qb7 Qxb7 14. Bxb7 {It looks totally winning for White, but the Bb7 is actually trapped.} Kd8 15. e4 Nb6 {Again with precise play White retains a substantial advantage.} 16. e6 Kc7 17. Ba8 {Double exclam for how unusual this move looks!} Nxa8 18. exf7 ({White is much better here. The idea is to surround the c3 pawn, and the resulting position with a rook and two pawns versus two knights should be much better for White. Bb4} 18. Ke2 {Rf8 a3} Bd6 19. Be3 Nb6 20. Bd4 {Rxf7 Bxc3±}) *

