1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A solid line for Black against the 4. e3 Slav. White has many interesting options here.} 5. Qb3 {Recently this move has been scoring well for White. White immediately puts pressure on the b7 -pawn and gets out of the pin, allowing Nf3 to move.} Qb6 {The most solid response by Black.} 6. Ne5 Bf5 {Black should preserve his bishop. There are alternatives but they are worse.} 7. cxd5 {An important move. White picks the right moment to take on d5 and avoid the Exchange Slav pawn structure, as Black cannot recapture with the pawn. And if the knight recaptures on d5 , White has a superior pawn structure in the center.} cxd5 8. Qxb6 axb6 9. Nc3 {This is a very difficult endgame (or queenless middlegame) for Black due to many weaknesses. Some sample continuations:} ({e6?} 9. Bb5+ {is just crushing:} Nfd7 10. Bd2 f6 11. Nxd7 Nxd7 {Rc1+- and Na4 is coming.}) (9. Nc6 {f3!? restricting the Nf6 and potentially planning g4 .} Bd7 {Black should bring the bishop back, as otherwise, the Bb5 pin may be crushing. Nb5 Rc8} 10. g4 e6 11. Bd2 {White is clearly better.}) *

