1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A solid line for Black against the 4. e3 Slav. White has many interesting options here.} 5. Qb3 {Recently this move has been scoring well for White. White immediately puts pressure on the b7 -pawn and gets out of the pin, allowing Nf3 to move.} Qb6 {The most solid response by Black.} 6. Ne5 Bf5 {Black should preserve his bishop. There are alternatives but they are worse.} 7. cxd5 {An important move. White picks the right moment to take on d5 and avoid the Exchange Slav pawn structure, as Black cannot recapture with the pawn. And if the knight recaptures on d5 , White has a superior pawn structure in the center.} Nxd5 {This is a reasonable option but this can easily transpose to the main line.} 8. Qd1 {This is another option that may be good to explore as well but given that in 7... Qxb3 move order we don't have it, to keep things simple I stick with 8. Bd3 in the course. To show how the game may proceed here, I will just show a few moves.} g6 (8... e6 9. a3 $1) 9. Nc4 Qc7 10. Nbd2 ({This deserves further studies. Nf6} 10. b4 Bg7 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Be2) ({b5!} 10. Ne5 {e4!? Bxe4 Nxe4 bxc4 Bxc4∞} Nd7 11. Nxd7 Bxd7 {Nf3∞}) *

