1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A solid line for Black against the 4. e3 Slav. White has many interesting options here.} 5. Qb3 {Recently this move has been scoring well for White. White immediately puts pressure on the b7 -pawn and gets out of the pin, allowing Nf3 to move.} Qb6 {The most solid response by Black.} 6. Ne5 Bf5 {Black should preserve his bishop. There are alternatives but they are worse.} 7. cxd5 {An important move. White picks the right moment to take on d5 and avoid the Exchange Slav pawn structure, as Black cannot recapture with the pawn. And if the knight recaptures on d5 , White has a superior pawn structure in the center.} Qxb3 {The main move.} 8. axb3 Nxd5 9. Bd3 {White offers further trades as the Bf5 is kind of annoying and White's knight on d3 would be placed very well.} Be6 {Black can try this move. But I hardly see any improvement to Black's position here compared to 9... Bxd3 .} 10. Bd2 Nd7 11. Nxd7 Bxd7 12. Ke2 {Black's bishop is not well-placed on d7 . Probably the best option is to exchange it. White wants Na3 , Nc4 with some pressure on the queenside and the center.} *

