1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A solid line for Black against the 4. e3 Slav. White has many interesting options here.} 5. Qb3 {Recently this move has been scoring well for White. White immediately puts pressure on the b7 -pawn and gets out of the pin, allowing Nf3 to move.} Qb6 {The most solid response by Black.} 6. Ne5 Bf5 {Black should preserve his bishop. There are alternatives but they are worse.} 7. cxd5 {An important move. White picks the right moment to take on d5 and avoid the Exchange Slav pawn structure, as Black cannot recapture with the pawn. And if the knight recaptures on d5 , White has a superior pawn structure in the center.} Qxb3 {The main move.} 8. axb3 Nxd5 9. Bd3 {White offers further trades as the Bf5 is kind of annoying and White's knight on d3 would be placed very well.} Bxd3 {Nearly everyone trades the bishops. If Black does not do that, his bishop is not going to be well placed.} 10. Nxd3 e6 11. Bd2 {This is what White wants in this line - the edge in the center, the opened a-file and a bit more active pieces. One might say that this is not the most exciting line, and perhaps that is true. On the other hand, however, White has a rather simple game and a comfortable, almost risk-free position in which Black has to be careful... Recently several games have been played in this line, and White has had good results.} Nd7 {has been tried in some games - but it is clearly inferior to Na6 . The knight on d7 is passive and White easily gets to play anything he wants.} 12. Ke2 {This move is a novelty. White's idea is Na3 - Nc4 and so far the immediate 12. Na3 has been chosen by many people, but the engine likes Ke2 first. Perhaps the reason is that Black needs to develop the bishop somehow and if Na3 is played then, ... Bxa3 would be just a waste of a tempo.} ({Here, however,} 12. Na3 {might be met with} Bxa3 {. It should not fully equalize either, but if the engine prefers the 12. Ke2 move order more, we should stick with it!}) 12... Be7 (12... c5 $2 13. Rc1 $1 cxd4 ({Black is close to lost after} 13... b6 14. Na3 {or e4}) 14. e4 $1 Ne7 {Best but still not sufficient.} 15. Rc7 $1 {Regaining the pawn with big advantage.}) 13. Na3 ({Here, we are back at a game Bronstein-Postny (2022) that arose from} 13. Na3 {Be7 Ke2 move order.} a6 14. Rac1 O-O 15. b4 Nc7 16. Nc4 Nb5 17. g4 Nf6 18. f3 Rad8 19. Nc5 Bxc5 20. bxc5 Nd7 21. Be1 f5 22. gxf5 exf5 23. Rd1) *

