1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A solid line for Black against the 4. e3 Slav. White has many interesting options here.} 5. Qb3 {Recently this move has been scoring well for White. White immediately puts pressure on the b7 -pawn and gets out of the pin, allowing Nf3 to move.} Qb6 {The most solid response by Black.} 6. Ne5 Bf5 {Black should preserve his bishop. There are alternatives but they are worse.} 7. cxd5 {An important move. White picks the right moment to take on d5 and avoid the Exchange Slav pawn structure, as Black cannot recapture with the pawn. And if the knight recaptures on d5 , White has a superior pawn structure in the center.} Qxb3 {The main move.} 8. axb3 Nxd5 9. Bd3 {White offers further trades as the Bf5 is kind of annoying and White's knight on d3 would be placed very well.} Bxd3 {Nearly everyone trades the bishops. If Black does not do that, his bishop is not going to be well placed.} 10. Nxd3 e6 11. Bd2 {This is what White wants in this line - the edge in the center, the opened a-file and a bit more active pieces. One might say that this is not the most exciting line, and perhaps that is true. On the other hand, however, White has a rather simple game and a comfortable, almost risk-free position in which Black has to be careful... Recently several games have been played in this line, and White has had good results.} Na6 {Black needs to fight for the control over the b4 square. Right now, White has two interesting ideas.} 12. Ke2 Be7 {In the majority of games followed ... Be7 , which gives White an easy edge in many ways.} 13. Rc1 (13. Ra4 {is also interesting.}) 13... O-O ({After} 13... Nab4 {White can always play} 14. Ne1 $1 {which is an improved version of the main line as White's rook is already on c1 !}) 14. Na3 Nab4 {The most natural move in this position is already a serious mistake.} 15. Nc5 {Right now, White does not have to play Ne1 anymore (which happened in the game Keymer-Kamsky, 2022) and this active move is stronger.} b6 (15... Bxc5 $6 16. dxc5 {is even worse for Black as not only Black's knights are loose but also the d6 -outpost will be a problem soon.} Na6 17. e4 Ndc7 18. b4) 16. Nd7 {A very concrete approach.} Rfd8 {Worse than ... Rfc8 . White can obtain very large advantage with a precise move sequence.} 17. Ne5 c5 18. e4 Nf6 19. Nac4 Rxd4 20. f3 {Black's position has too many weaknesses to hold.} *

