n d5 which does not allow for Rxa6 .}) 13... c5 {Probably the most logical move here. After all, if Black does not play this move at some point, his position will be cramped.} (13... f5 {stops e4 , but weakens Black's position.} 14. Nf3 {followed by Rhc1 , Na3 - c4 .}) 14. e4 Nc7 15. Bxb4 cxb4 16. Nd2 {I like White's position. The center is quite strong, and White can expand to the queenside as well. Again, because of some space advantage, there should be possibilities. One of White's main ideas is to play f4 . But moves such as Nc2 , Nc4 , Rhd1 , etc. also come to mind.} ({For example, Nb5} 16. Nc2 Rc8 {Nc4 Be7} 17. Rd1 {O-O f4} f5 18. e5) ({Or Be7} 16. f4 O-O-O 17. Nf3 Nb5 18. Ke3 {with Nc4 next.}) *

