1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {A solid line for Black against the 4. e3 Slav. White has many interesting options here.} 5. Qb3 {Recently this move has been scoring well for White. White immediately puts pressure on the b7 -pawn and gets out of the pin, allowing Nf3 to move.} Qb6 {The most solid response by Black.} 6. Ne5 Bf5 {Black should preserve his bishop. There are alternatives but they are worse.} 7. cxd5 {An important move. White picks the right moment to take on d5 and avoid the Exchange Slav pawn structure, as Black cannot recapture with the pawn. And if the knight recaptures on d5 , White has a superior pawn structure in the center.} Qxb3 {The main move.} 8. axb3 Nxd5 9. Bd3 {White offers further trades as the Bf5 is kind of annoying and White's knight on d3 would be placed very well.} Bxd3 {Nearly everyone trades the bishops. If Black does not do that, his bishop is not going to be well placed.} 10. Nxd3 e6 11. Bd2 {This is what White wants in this line - the edge in the center, the opened a-file and a bit more active pieces. One might say that this is not the most exciting line, and perhaps that is true. On the other hand, however, White has a rather simple game and a comfortable, almost risk-free position in which Black has to be careful... Recently several games have been played in this line, and White has had good results.} Na6 {Black needs to fight for the control over the b4 square. Right now, White has two interesting ideas.} 12. Ra4 {White fights for the control over the b4 -square, attempting to prevent ... Na(d)b4 and some trades. If Black does not get to play this idea, White will be surely better thanks to the space advantage.} Nb6 {For the reasons above, Black should kick out the rook and go back to d5 and eventually get to play ... Nb4 .} 13. Ra5 {Keeping the rook active.} Nd5 14. Ke2 Nab4 (14... Ndb4 15. Nxb4 {is the same as 14... Nab4 . Black cannot recapture with the bishop due to Rxa6 !} Bxb4 $4 16. Rxa6 Bxd2 17. Ra4 $1 b5 18. Ra6 $1) ({After} 14... Be7 {we can play} 15. Rc1) 15. Nxb4 {Unlike after 12. Ke2 , Black does not get to trade the bishops now for tactical reasons.} Nxb4 16. g4 {White's position is a little more pleasant, despite being objectively close to equal. I am sure Black can somehow draw here, but on the board it may not be so easy. White has a simple plan: advance the kingside pawns, bring the knight to c4 , and slowly exploit the space advantage in search of break.} ({There has been one game so far, Jacobson-Salinas (2022), and Salinas played some normal moves here and immediately got into trouble: Be7} 16. Na3 Nd5 17. Nc4 a6 {g5!? an unnecessary, yet interesting decision, even if the engine likes 19. h4 more. Nc7?!} ({Salinas had to find the difficult} 17... h6 $1 {gxh6 g6!} 18. e4 Nc7 {with equality.}) 18. h4 {Right now, White is back on track. Nb5 Raa1} f6 {Rag1⩲ with some pressure. No doubt, White's position is easier to play and he retains some edge.}) *

