1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 a6 ({One of the modern approaches to Chebanenko that gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The main idea is to improve on the standard Bf5 Nc3} 5... e6 {where White plays} 6. Nh4 {and gets the pair of bishops.}) {Here, Nh4 makes less sense, while Black's a6 is helpful to secure the b7 -pawn with either ... b5 or ... Ra7 if needed. White has many options, but I would like to recommend a line that I personally find very attractive.} 6. Qb3 {White targets the b7 -pawn, forcing Black to do something about it right away.} Ra7 {The most popular but not necessarily the best move.} 7. Bd2 {White plays this developmental move with intention of meeting ... e6 with Nh4 .} h6 {Preserving the Bf5 is way too slow.} 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Rc1 {Suddenly, the pressure on the queenside is unbearable for Black.} e6 10. Qa4+ Nc6 (10... Nbd7 $2 11. Nb5) 11. Ne5 {White wins a pawn.} Qa8 12. Nd1 ({The key idea; there is no way to defend the pawn. And if b5? then} 12. Bb5 axb5 13. Qxb5) *

