1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 a6 ({One of the modern approaches to Chebanenko that gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The main idea is to improve on the standard Bf5 Nc3} 5... e6 {where White plays} 6. Nh4 {and gets the pair of bishops.}) {Here, Nh4 makes less sense, while Black's a6 is helpful to secure the b7 -pawn with either ... b5 or ... Ra7 if needed. White has many options, but I would like to recommend a line that I personally find very attractive.} 6. Qb3 {White targets the b7 -pawn, forcing Black to do something about it right away.} Ra7 {The most popular but not necessarily the best move.} 7. Bd2 {White plays this developmental move with intention of meeting ... e6 with Nh4 .} e6 8. Nh4 ({Getting the bishop pair. This is in some way similar to e3 Bf5 Nc3 e6} 8. Nh4 {line - with the difference that Qb3 and Bd2 moves are useful for White, while a6 and Ra7 do not necessarily help Black. Still, Black is pretty solid, so let's see what can happen.}) 8... dxc4 {This is generally good news for White since Black somehow gives up control of the center. But in this case, the idea is simply not to give up the bishop pair.} 9. Bxc4 Be4 {In this way Black preserves the bishop pair because in case of trade on e4 , our Bd2 will also be traded. But after ... dxc4 we control the center, so we are okay anyway.} 10. O-O Be7 11. Be2 O-O (11... Bd5 12. Qc2 $1) 12. Rfd1 ({Alternatively, White can also play} 12. Be1 $5 Bd5 13. Qc2 {getting the bishop pair. However, we should not trade on d5 with Black's pawn still on c6 , to avoid a symmetric position. That's why after} Nbd7 14. Nf3 {is a good move, nearly forcing ... Bxf3 as otherwise e4 will be played.}) 12... h6 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 {White has two good options, Ng6 and Nf3 .} 14. Ng6 ({A flashy move; the simple} 14. Nf3 {is also good.} Nxd2 15. Rxd2 {White is better due to control over the center.}) 14... Nxd2 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Qb6 {A touch of finesse, even though we could have taken the knight right away too.} Ra8 17. Rxd2 {White is better.} *

