1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 a6 ({One of the modern approaches to Chebanenko that gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The main idea is to improve on the standard Bf5 Nc3} 5... e6 {where White plays} 6. Nh4 {and gets the pair of bishops.}) {Here, Nh4 makes less sense, while Black's a6 is helpful to secure the b7 -pawn with either ... b5 or ... Ra7 if needed. White has many options, but I would like to recommend a line that I personally find very attractive.} 6. Qb3 {White targets the b7 -pawn, forcing Black to do something about it right away.} Ra7 {The most popular but not necessarily the best move.} 7. Bd2 {White plays this developmental move with intention of meeting ... e6 with Nh4 .} e6 8. Nh4 ({Getting the bishop pair. This is in some way similar to e3 Bf5 Nc3 e6} 8. Nh4 {line - with the difference that Qb3 and Bd2 moves are useful for White, while a6 and Ra7 do not necessarily help Black. Still, Black is pretty solid, so let's see what can happen.}) 8... Bg6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 {This is an improved version of a 'normal” line: Bf5 Nc3 e6 Nh4 Bg6 . In these lines, Black almost never plays ... a6 and ... Ra7 , while Qb3 and Bd2 are standard moves for White.} 10. O-O-O {The most aggressive option, played in 2023 by Vincent Keymer. However, plans involving g3 - Bg2 - O-O instead were fine too.} Nbd7 11. Kb1 Be7 ({After} 11... b5 {White needs to close the queenside and gain space:} 12. c5 $1) (11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 c5 14. g4) 12. Be2 {White prepares expansion on the kingside with g4 - g5 .} dxc4 13. Qxc4 c5 {Black goes for the usual pawn break. White has huge choice, but I would continue with the plan that began with Be2 .} 14. g4 (14. dxc5 $5 Nxc5 15. Qd4 {was Keymer's choice, and it is also slightly better for White, but 14. g4 looks stronger.}) 14... b5 15. Qd3 {Black has two main options here - ... c4 or ... cxd4 . Neither equalizes, as my analysis shows.} c4 {This looks tempting, hoping for some attack on the queenside. But it does not work.} 16. Qc2 Nb6 17. h4 {White's initiative is simply faster, while ... b4 only weakens the pawns and Black does not have enough pieces on the queenside to compensate for the pawn.} *

