1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 a6 ({One of the modern approaches to Chebanenko that gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The main idea is to improve on the standard Bf5 Nc3} 5... e6 {where White plays} 6. Nh4 {and gets the pair of bishops.}) {Here, Nh4 makes less sense, while Black's a6 is helpful to secure the b7 -pawn with either ... b5 or ... Ra7 if needed. White has many options, but I would like to recommend a line that I personally find very attractive.} 6. Qb3 {White targets the b7 -pawn, forcing Black to do something about it right away.} Ra7 {The most popular but not necessarily the best move.} 7. Bd2 {White plays this developmental move with intention of meeting ... e6 with Nh4 .} e6 8. Nh4 ({Getting the bishop pair. This is in some way similar to e3 Bf5 Nc3 e6} 8. Nh4 {line - with the difference that Qb3 and Bd2 moves are useful for White, while a6 and Ra7 do not necessarily help Black. Still, Black is pretty solid, so let's see what can happen.}) 8... Be4 {By far the main move here.} 9. cxd5 ({A well-timed move. It is important NOT to play} 9. f3 $2 {due to} dxc4 $1 10. Bxc4 Bd5 {and Black is absolutely fine.}) 9... Bxd5 10. Qc2 {White will get the bishop pair sooner or later and the position should open. White wants Be2 , O-O and prepare for the central play.} c5 {Perhaps the most critical line, trying to open the center before White completes his development. But Black also plays with undeveloped pieces so it's a double-edged sword...} 11. Nxd5 ({The most forcing.} 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Bc4 {is good as well. White enjoys a bishop pair advantage.}) 11... Nxd5 12. e4 Nb6 ({Not an obvious move. If} 12... Nb4 13. Bxb4 cxb4 14. Nf3 {White is much better due to our strong center.}) 13. dxc5 N6d7 14. Nf3 Bxc5 {White has many ways to play here. I would recommend the following:} 15. b4 Bd6 16. Be2 {With a nice edge due to the bishop pair and better pieces.} *

