1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 a6 ({One of the modern approaches to Chebanenko that gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The main idea is to improve on the standard Bf5 Nc3} 5... e6 {where White plays} 6. Nh4 {and gets the pair of bishops.}) {Here, Nh4 makes less sense, while Black's a6 is helpful to secure the b7 -pawn with either ... b5 or ... Ra7 if needed. White has many options, but I would like to recommend a line that I personally find very attractive.} 6. Qb3 {White targets the b7 -pawn, forcing Black to do something about it right away.} b5 {This is a human move - what could be more logical than gaining space on the queenside and defending the pawn at the same time?} 7. cxd5 {It may be a tempting move to play.} cxd5 8. a4 {Immediately challenging the queenside. However, Black can do quite well here if he plays ... b4 .} b4 9. Qxb4 Nc6 {With a strong pawn sacrifice that gives Black plenty of compensation. The line goes as follows.} 10. Qc5 Bd7 ({A new trend that I believe gives Black a good game. Things get somewhat forced now.} 10... Na5 $6 {used to be played in the past, but due to} 11. Bxa6 $1 Rxa6 12. Qb5+ Rc6 13. Ne5 Bd7 14. Nxd7 $1 Nxd7 ({Or} 14... Kxd7 15. e4 $1 e6 16. Bg5) 15. Bd2 $1 Rc8 16. Nxd5 Nc4 17. Rc1 Nd6 18. Rxc8 Qxc8 19. Qa6 $1 {White is better in this endgame. The three pawns should be stronger than the knight, particularly since the a-pawn and b-pawn will be well-supported.}) 11. Ne5 e6 12. Nxc6 Qc7 13. Ne7 Qxc5 14. dxc5 Bxe7 15. b4 a5 {And Black should regain the pawn soon with an approximately equal endgame.} *

