1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 a6 ({One of the modern approaches to Chebanenko that gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The main idea is to improve on the standard Bf5 Nc3} 5... e6 {where White plays} 6. Nh4 {and gets the pair of bishops.}) {Here, Nh4 makes less sense, while Black's a6 is helpful to secure the b7 -pawn with either ... b5 or ... Ra7 if needed. White has many options, but I would like to recommend a line that I personally find very attractive.} 6. Qb3 {White targets the b7 -pawn, forcing Black to do something about it right away.} b5 {This is a human move - what could be more logical than gaining space on the queenside and defending the pawn at the same time?} 7. c5 {In general, I like the approach of gaining space on the queenside in these positions. If we can play a4 and undermine the queenside, White will gain additional options to sacrifice the piece on b5 and create a pawn majority. I used this line in 2015.} Nbd7 {I would not play a4 right away.} 8. Nh4 ({This is stronger! In my game, I played} 8. a4 {which is another option, but it appears that after} e5 $1 {things are probably not so clear.}) 8... Bg6 (8... e6 $6 9. Nxf5 exf5 10. a4 {is just a dream position for White.}) 9. f4 {White prevents ... e5 for good.} e6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 {Here, the h-file opened which opens door for potential ... Nh5 !? ideas.} 11. g3 {Before playing a4 , we should make sure to neutralize Black's counterplay. The idea is to meet ... Nh5 with Bg2 and there is no tactic on the h-file.} Nh5 (11... a5 12. Bg2) 12. Bg2 f5 {Black must play in this way to fight for control of the e4 square and avoid being cramped. Here, White has two options.} 13. a4 {I think this is the simplest. White goes for standard positional play.} Nhf6 14. O-O Be7 15. Bd2 Kf7 {Here, White employs a classical maneuver.} 16. Na2 ({With clear advantage. And after} 16. Ne4 {Be1⩲ makes Black's position unpleasant.}) *

