1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 a6 ({One of the modern approaches to Chebanenko that gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The main idea is to improve on the standard Bf5 Nc3} 5... e6 {where White plays} 6. Nh4 {and gets the pair of bishops.}) {Here, Nh4 makes less sense, while Black's a6 is helpful to secure the b7 -pawn with either ... b5 or ... Ra7 if needed. White has many options, but I would like to recommend a line that I personally find very attractive.} 6. Qb3 {White targets the b7 -pawn, forcing Black to do something about it right away.} b5 {This is a human move - what could be more logical than gaining space on the queenside and defending the pawn at the same time?} 7. c5 {In general, I like the approach of gaining space on the queenside in these positions. If we can play a4 and undermine the queenside, White will gain additional options to sacrifice the piece on b5 and create a pawn majority. I used this line in 2015.} Nbd7 {I would not play a4 right away.} 8. Nh4 ({This is stronger! In my game, I played} 8. a4 {which is another option, but it appears that after} e5 $1 {things are probably not so clear.}) 8... Bg6 (8... e6 $6 9. Nxf5 exf5 10. a4 {is just a dream position for White.}) 9. f4 {White prevents ... e5 for good.} e6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 {Here, the h-file opened which opens door for potential ... Nh5 !? ideas.} 11. g3 {Before playing a4 , we should make sure to neutralize Black's counterplay. The idea is to meet ... Nh5 with Bg2 and there is no tactic on the h-file.} Nh5 (11... a5 12. Bg2) 12. Bg2 f5 {Black must play in this way to fight for control of the e4 square and avoid being cramped. Here, White has two options.} 13. e4 {Objectively, this move should be the strongest, as Black cannot take on e4 due to pressure on the e6 -pawn. And if White can, e5 would be great to play. However, Black has stunning counterplay.} Bxc5 {Out of the blue, this seems to work quite well!} 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Qc2 (15. Qd1 $5 dxe4 16. Qxd8+ Rxd8 17. O-O) 15... dxe4 16. O-O Nf6 {Black has compensation for the piece. With the best play White manages to retain some advantage.} 17. Nd1 {The best move, transferring the knight to f2 , allowing Be3 to be played in the future.} (17. Be3 $6 Nd3 18. Rad1 Kf7 {is suddenly equal, according to the engine!}) 17... Nd3 18. Qxc6+ Kf7 {The position looks far from clear. With further accurate play, White manages to retain an advantage.} 19. Qb7+ Nd7 20. Nf2 Rb8 21. Qc6 Rc8 22. Qd6 N7c5 23. Qxd8 Rhxd8 24. Rd1 {And slowly Black's counterplay dissipates.} *

