1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 a6 ({One of the modern approaches to Chebanenko that gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The main idea is to improve on the standard Bf5 Nc3} 5... e6 {where White plays} 6. Nh4 {and gets the pair of bishops.}) {Here, Nh4 makes less sense, while Black's a6 is helpful to secure the b7 -pawn with either ... b5 or ... Ra7 if needed. White has many options, but I would like to recommend a line that I personally find very attractive.} 6. Qb3 {White targets the b7 -pawn, forcing Black to do something about it right away.} b5 {This is a human move - what could be more logical than gaining space on the queenside and defending the pawn at the same time?} 7. c5 {In general, I like the approach of gaining space on the queenside in these positions. If we can play a4 and undermine the queenside, White will gain additional options to sacrifice the piece on b5 and create a pawn majority. I used this line in 2015.} a5 {Black absolutely must play this move in order to meet a4 with ... b4 .} 8. Nh4 Bc8 {Other moves make little sense since White would get the bishop pair or the bishop would be caught between other Black pieces.} 9. f4 {White seizes more space and prevents any attempts of ... e5 .} Ne4 {This move is possible too, but it looks a bit premature. After all, playing with only one knight is unlikely to bring positive effects. However, there is a threat: ... e5 . Therefore, we must move the knight.} 10. Nf3 f5 {This move supports the Ne4 , but also weakens the e5 square.} 11. Ne5 a4 12. Qc2 {With a similar position as in the main line, but I would argue it is a bit better version as Black needs to spend some time to develop the Nb8 , due to strong Ne5 .} *

