1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 a6 ({One of the modern approaches to Chebanenko that gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The main idea is to improve on the standard Bf5 Nc3} 5... e6 {where White plays} 6. Nh4 {and gets the pair of bishops.}) {Here, Nh4 makes less sense, while Black's a6 is helpful to secure the b7 -pawn with either ... b5 or ... Ra7 if needed. White has many options, but I would like to recommend a line that I personally find very attractive.} 6. Qb3 {White targets the b7 -pawn, forcing Black to do something about it right away.} b5 {This is a human move - what could be more logical than gaining space on the queenside and defending the pawn at the same time?} 7. c5 {In general, I like the approach of gaining space on the queenside in these positions. If we can play a4 and undermine the queenside, White will gain additional options to sacrifice the piece on b5 and create a pawn majority. I used this line in 2015.} a5 {Black absolutely must play this move in order to meet a4 with ... b4 .} 8. Nh4 Bc8 {Other moves make little sense since White would get the bishop pair or the bishop would be caught between other Black pieces.} 9. f4 {White seizes more space and prevents any attempts of ... e5 .} Ne4 {This move is possible too, but it looks a bit premature. After all, playing with only one knight is unlikely to bring positive effects. However, there is a threat: ... e5 . Therefore, we must move the knight.} 10. Nf3 Bf5 {This looks the most logical, as there is no Nh4 now.} 11. a4 ({It is important to include this move!} 11. Nxe4 $2 a4 $1 {and Black equalizes.}) 11... b4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Nd2 {The e4 -pawn is weak and needs constant attention. On top of that, Nc4 comes in soon.} Nd7 14. Qc2 Nf6 15. h3 h5 16. g3 {White enjoys space advantage. The e4 -pawn is weak, and the d5 -outpost is not a sufficient compensation for it.} *

