1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 a6 ({One of the modern approaches to Chebanenko that gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The main idea is to improve on the standard Bf5 Nc3} 5... e6 {where White plays} 6. Nh4 {and gets the pair of bishops.}) {Here, Nh4 makes less sense, while Black's a6 is helpful to secure the b7 -pawn with either ... b5 or ... Ra7 if needed. White has many options, but I would like to recommend a line that I personally find very attractive.} 6. Qb3 {White targets the b7 -pawn, forcing Black to do something about it right away.} b5 {This is a human move - what could be more logical than gaining space on the queenside and defending the pawn at the same time?} 7. c5 {In general, I like the approach of gaining space on the queenside in these positions. If we can play a4 and undermine the queenside, White will gain additional options to sacrifice the piece on b5 and create a pawn majority. I used this line in 2015.} a5 {Black absolutely must play this move in order to meet a4 with ... b4 .} 8. Nh4 Bc8 {Other moves make little sense since White would get the bishop pair or the bishop would be caught between other Black pieces.} 9. f4 {White seizes more space and prevents any attempts of ... e5 .} g6 {Black must somehow complete his development. Here is an important moment as White should recognize what Black is trying to do: either ... Ne4 or ... Nh5 with idea of ... e5 . And if Nh4 leaves then ... Bf5 can be played too.} 10. Qc2 {For the reasons above, I would recommend playing this move. Now ... Ne4 is not an option anymore, while ... Nh5 can be neutralized with Qf2 !} ({After} 10. Bd3 Nh5 $1 {the threat of ... e5 is annoying.} 11. Nf3 Bf5 {Here, Black gets to trade light-squared bishops without committing to ... b4 . Of course, it is playable too - but I find 10. Qc2 a more precise way to play here.}) 10... Bg7 {This is the most logical move, and I expect many people to go for it. But now Black does not get to play ... Bf5 which is a success for White.} (10... b4 {is premature due to} 11. Na4 $1 {with ideas of a3 and Nb6 .}) 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Nf3 {It is not so easy to play for Black due to lack of space. Sooner or later, ... b4 should be played - but this weakens the pawns, and they can easily become targets, as we will see shortly.} b4 13. Ne2 (13. Na4 {is possible too.}) 13... Ba6 14. Ng3 {The e4 -square is under full control and White will play a3 now.} *

