ad of Qc2 is that right now we have this additional option of swinging the queen to f2 ! Generally, White wants to keep the majority of pieces on the board to make the most out of his space advantage.} Bg7 (11... b4 $6 12. Na4 {is generally welcome by White - we can challenge the queenside with a3 in the future.}) 12. Bd3 {As a matter of fact, I would not fear ... b4 as even though it leads to a trade of light-squared bishops, it weakens Black's queenside and creates targets for White.} b4 ({This is the top engine's move, so I thought I would keep it as the main one.} 12... f5 {is similar to 11... f5 .} 13. h3 Nf6 14. Qc2 O-O 15. Nf3) (12... O-O 13. O-O {does not change much, as sooner or later Black should play with ... b4 or ... f5 anyway.}) 13. Na4 Ba6 {Black goes for a favorable trade of light-squared bishops, but at the cost of severely weakening the queenside.} 14. Bxa6 Rxa6 (14... Nxa6 {is less good as Na6 is a bit misplaced.} 15. Nf3 Nf6 16. a3 Ne4 17. Qe2) 15. Nf3 Nf6 16. Qc2 O-O 17. O-O ({White has a comfortable position. The idea is to exploit the weakened queenside in the following way: a3 , b3 , Bd2 and then Nb2 - Nd3 . In the end, we will want to double the rooks on the a-file. The e4 -square is not that relevant. Ne4} 17. a3 {Nd7 Bd2 Qb8} b3 {Qb5 Nb2!⩲ Applying pressure on the b4 -pawn. Rfa8 Nd3 bxa3 Rxa3⩲}) *

