1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg6 {A very solid line for Black. Without provoking f3 (as after 6... Be4 ) this line navigates toward more positional play. White has a wide choice.} 7. Be2 Nbd7 8. O-O {I like this line for White. I have been waiting quite a while to play it, but unfortunately so far I have not been given the chance to do so. White is in no hurry with Nxg6 and completes his development first. Black's main moves are 8... Bd6 or 8... Be7 , but other moves have also been tried.} Be7 {This move was tried recently by Daniil Dubov.} 9. Bd2 {I would wait with capturing the bishop on g6 for now. Also, playing 9. g3 (see illustrative line ) slightly weakens the kingside as well (even though it may seem imperceptible), so this developmental move would be my recommendation.} dxc4 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Bxc4 {We have an improved version of the 9. g3 line as White's kingside remains solid, thus ideas of ... Qa5 -... Qh5 or (... Qf5 ) causing danger with the pawn on g3 are not an issue now.} Qc7 {We can play either h3 or g3 and then Rc1 would make Qc7 rather vulnerable.} 12. g3 ({And now, if Black tries the ... Qa5 -... Qf5 idea, it simply fails: Qa5?} 12. e4) *

