1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg6 {A very solid line for Black. Without provoking f3 (as after 6... Be4 ) this line navigates toward more positional play. White has a wide choice.} 7. Be2 Nbd7 8. O-O {I like this line for White. I have been waiting quite a while to play it, but unfortunately so far I have not been given the chance to do so. White is in no hurry with Nxg6 and completes his development first. Black's main moves are 8... Bd6 or 8... Be7 , but other moves have also been tried.} Be7 {This move was tried recently by Daniil Dubov.} 9. g3 {This move is the main move here, but I like it less due to the following line.} dxc4 10. Nxg6 (10. Bxc4 Bh5 $1 ({Unlike after dxc4 Bxc4} 10... Bh5 {, here this is fine for Black as the inclusion of moves g3 and Be7 definitely helps Black.}) 11. Be2 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 b5 $1 {and, according to my analysis, Black is fine.} 13. f3 O-O 14. g4 {Bg6 is not so clear as with the king on g1 the kingside is weakened.}) 10... hxg6 11. Bxc4 Qa5 {Black makes use of the open h-file. Ideas of ... Qf5 -... Qh3 or ... Qh5 could be annoying. I analyzed it quite extensively and I concluded that despite the position being playable, Black has an easy game, which I cannot say after 9.Bd2.} 12. Bd3 {This seems like the best try. White prevents ... Qf5 and ... Qh5 leads to a better endgame.} Rd8 (12... Qh5 $6 13. Qxh5 gxh5 {is simply better for White because of the pair of bishops. There are numerous ways to continue, but the one I like the most is} 14. Be2 $5 {as we intend to meet ... h4 with g4 !.}) 13. Bd2 Qc7 {And here I simply think that Black should be OK. And what’s worse, ... e5 comes soon with an easy game for Black.} *

