1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg6 {A very solid line for Black. Without provoking f3 (as after 6... Be4 ) this line navigates toward more positional play. White has a wide choice.} 7. Be2 Nbd7 8. O-O {I like this line for White. I have been waiting quite a while to play it, but unfortunately so far I have not been given the chance to do so. White is in no hurry with Nxg6 and completes his development first. Black's main moves are 8... Bd6 or 8... Be7 , but other moves have also been tried.} Be7 {This move was tried recently by Daniil Dubov.} 9. Bd2 {I would wait with capturing the bishop on g6 for now. Also, playing 9. g3 (see illustrative line ) slightly weakens the kingside as well (even though it may seem imperceptible), so this developmental move would be my recommendation.} O-O 10. Nxg6 {We capture the bishop now that Black has castled - since there is no more danger on the h-file.} hxg6 11. Qb3 {One of the few moments where I would recommend Qb3 over Qc2 .} Qb6 {This is worse than ... Qc7 , as nearly all endgames are slightly better for White. We can try any move like 12. Rfd1 or 12. Rfc1 , but there is another option too.} 12. Qxb6 {A rather surprising exchange, which helps Black open the a-file and potentially play ... b5 in the future with a great pawn formation. But things are not so easy.} axb6 (12... Nxb6 13. c5 Nbd7 14. b4 {with b5 next is of course unpleasant for Black.}) 13. a4 {This move is important, as it fixes the pawn structure on the queenside. Now, Black is virtually stuck, as the standard move ... c5 is never an option, as it leaves Black with many weaknesses.} *

