1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg6 {A very solid line for Black. Without provoking f3 (as after 6... Be4 ) this line navigates toward more positional play. White has a wide choice.} 7. Be2 Nbd7 8. O-O {I like this line for White. I have been waiting quite a while to play it, but unfortunately so far I have not been given the chance to do so. White is in no hurry with Nxg6 and completes his development first. Black's main moves are 8... Bd6 or 8... Be7 , but other moves have also been tried.} Ne4 {A relatively rare move and somewhat risky.} 9. g3 Nd6 {This is an aggressive and speculative approach by Black. Moving the knight so many times in the opening is a risky strategy, especially since White can expand on the queenside with tempo.} 10. c5 Nf5 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. b4 {There are positions or lines where White voluntarily plays c5 to expand on the queenside. In this case, Black wasted many moves with his knight and White took advantage of it. I would expect a very nice position for White, but I admit that Black might have some counterplay, so we should be careful.} Qf6 (12... Be7 {is the main move here, but it is passive.} 13. Rb1 Qc7 14. f4 $5) 13. Rb1 g5 {Black can play for the immediate attack on the h-file. Fortunately for us, it does not lead anywhere.} 14. Kg2 Qh6 {We can play Rh1 , which is sufficient, but there is also h4 !?.} 15. h4 ({And Black cannot really take on h4 : gxh4} 15. e4 {and both the knight and the queen are hanging.}) *

