1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg6 {A very solid line for Black. Without provoking f3 (as after 6... Be4 ) this line navigates toward more positional play. White has a wide choice.} 7. Be2 Nbd7 8. O-O {I like this line for White. I have been waiting quite a while to play it, but unfortunately so far I have not been given the chance to do so. White is in no hurry with Nxg6 and completes his development first. Black's main moves are 8... Bd6 or 8... Be7 , but other moves have also been tried.} Bd6 {The idea behind this move is to play ... Qe7 at some point and most likely prepare ... e5 . However, ... c5 is still quite often an idea.} 9. g3 {White is not rushing with Nxg6 as with the rook on h8 a potential opening of the h-file could be problematic in some lines. Of course, many times White does it anyway - but here at least there is no rush, because the bishop has no 'safe' squares to go to without being taken.} Qe7 {The second most popular move. Black delays castling, awaiting Nxg6 , hoping to get some activity on the kingside. One of Black's ideas is ... Ne4 .} 10. c5 {This would be my recommendation. We are gaining space on the queenside. It is quite rare here, but the engine likes it the most, and so do I.} Bc7 11. b4 {It is quite typical for many Slav positions - White gains a lot of space on the queenside.} a6 12. a4 {White will manage to break through on the queenside sooner or later.} Ne4 (12... e5 13. f4 $1 {is a typical idea to play here.}) 13. Bb2 {There is no need to take on g6 just yet as we are not in time to play b5 right away with the inclusion of a4 and ... a6 . But with 13. Bb2 we keep the tension and an advantage.} *

