1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg6 {A very solid line for Black. Without provoking f3 (as after 6... Be4 ) this line navigates toward more positional play. White has a wide choice.} 7. Be2 Nbd7 8. O-O {I like this line for White. I have been waiting quite a while to play it, but unfortunately so far I have not been given the chance to do so. White is in no hurry with Nxg6 and completes his development first. Black's main moves are 8... Bd6 or 8... Be7 , but other moves have also been tried.} Bd6 {The idea behind this move is to play ... Qe7 at some point and most likely prepare ... e5 . However, ... c5 is still quite often an idea.} 9. g3 {White is not rushing with Nxg6 as with the rook on h8 a potential opening of the h-file could be problematic in some lines. Of course, many times White does it anyway - but here at least there is no rush, because the bishop has no 'safe' squares to go to without being taken.} dxc4 {This feels premature. The main rationale for this move is to try to escape from Nh4 with ... Bg6 , or in the event of Nxg6 , keep the rook on h8 for potential pressure on the kingside.} 10. Bxc4 {We should not worry about ... Bh5 .} Bh5 {The point of Black's previous move.} 11. f3 ({Keeping the Bh5 at bay. The idea is e4 . However,} 11. Be2 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 {is also better for White.}) 11... O-O 12. e4 e5 {Black must stop the white pawn.} 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Be2 {The black bishop is misplaced and will probably have to retreat to g6 , where it can be traded. White has a powerful idea of pushing the central pawns.} *

