1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg6 {A very solid line for Black. Without provoking f3 (as after 6... Be4 ) this line navigates toward more positional play. White has a wide choice.} 7. Be2 Nbd7 8. O-O {I like this line for White. I have been waiting quite a while to play it, but unfortunately so far I have not been given the chance to do so. White is in no hurry with Nxg6 and completes his development first. Black's main moves are 8... Bd6 or 8... Be7 , but other moves have also been tried.} Bd6 {The idea behind this move is to play ... Qe7 at some point and most likely prepare ... e5 . However, ... c5 is still quite often an idea.} 9. g3 {White is not rushing with Nxg6 as with the rook on h8 a potential opening of the h-file could be problematic in some lines. Of course, many times White does it anyway - but here at least there is no rush, because the bishop has no 'safe' squares to go to without being taken.} O-O 10. Nxg6 {After castling we can safely take the bishop pair.} hxg6 11. Qc2 {Recently, this move got some recognition in favor of the old 11. Qb3 . White makes room for the rook on d1 , which is often useful.} ({I am not convinced by} 11. Qb3 Rb8 {due to the queen being under some pressure from ... Rb8 , as Black intends ... b5 !} 12. Bd2 b5 13. cxb5 cxb5 14. Rfc1 a6 15. a4 b4 16. Nb1 a5 17. Be1 e5 {or} 18. Rd1 {b5! cxb5 cxb5 a4 Qa5 Bd2 b4 Nb5} Be7 19. Rc1 {Rfc8= and Black comfortably equalizes.}) 11... Qe7 {A standard developmental move (after all, following ... Bd6 with the purpose of keeping the e7 -square for the queen, right?), but I think it is simply an inaccuracy.} 12. Rd1 {I am not sure what is the right continuation for Black but everything looks unpleasant.} a6 {I decided to keep this as the main move, as it was played by GMs Bu and Gledura.} 13. Bd2 b5 {A 'Chebanenko' style move. White has two interesting options here.} 14. e4 ({This central pawn advance could be played right away as well. Black faces so many hurdles...} 14. c5 Bc7 15. f4 $5 {is playable too, aiming for the space advantage.}) 14... c5 {Only this move keeps the balance! However, figuring out all the details is very difficult.} ({•} 14... b4 $6 15. e5 bxc3 16. exd6 Qxd6 17. c5 Qe7 18. bxc3) ({•} 14... e5 15. dxe5 Bxe5 16. exd5 cxd5 17. cxb5) 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. exd5 exd5 17. b4 d4 {Black survives with only moves.} 18. bxc5 Bxc5 19. Bf3 dxc3 20. Bxc3 Rac8 21. Rab1 bxc4 22. Kg2 {But even if Black gets there, White has fantastic compensation thanks to the bishop pair.} *

