1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg6 {A very solid line for Black. Without provoking f3 (as after 6... Be4 ) this line navigates toward more positional play. White has a wide choice.} 7. Be2 Nbd7 8. O-O {I like this line for White. I have been waiting quite a while to play it, but unfortunately so far I have not been given the chance to do so. White is in no hurry with Nxg6 and completes his development first. Black's main moves are 8... Bd6 or 8... Be7 , but other moves have also been tried.} Bd6 {The idea behind this move is to play ... Qe7 at some point and most likely prepare ... e5 . However, ... c5 is still quite often an idea.} 9. g3 {White is not rushing with Nxg6 as with the rook on h8 a potential opening of the h-file could be problematic in some lines. Of course, many times White does it anyway - but here at least there is no rush, because the bishop has no 'safe' squares to go to without being taken.} O-O 10. Nxg6 {After castling we can safely take the bishop pair.} hxg6 11. Qc2 {Recently, this move got some recognition in favor of the old 11. Qb3 . White makes room for the rook on d1 , which is often useful.} ({I am not convinced by} 11. Qb3 Rb8 {due to the queen being under some pressure from ... Rb8 , as Black intends ... b5 !} 12. Bd2 b5 13. cxb5 cxb5 14. Rfc1 a6 15. a4 b4 16. Nb1 a5 17. Be1 e5 {or} 18. Rd1 {b5! cxb5 cxb5 a4 Qa5 Bd2 b4 Nb5} Be7 19. Rc1 {Rfc8= and Black comfortably equalizes.}) 11... dxc4 {I think Black should quickly opt for the ... c5 idea. This is an old move; today most people try 11... Qe7 , but I think it is not that good.} (11... Rc8 {can be played, but it likely results in a transposition.} 12. Rd1 dxc4 13. Bxc4 c5 14. Bf1 cxd4 15. exd4 {and we are back at the main line.}) 12. Bxc4 c5 13. Rd1 {Keeping the tension in the center. I think that going for the position with the IQP is the way to go for White.} ({In some older games by top players (e.g. Kramnik, Gelfand) this move was played. However, the engine claims it is just nothing serious.} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Rd1 Rc8 15. Bf1 Bb4 16. Bd2 Nd5 {with equality. Ivanchuk-Gelfand (2007).}) 13... cxd4 14. exd4 {In this position, White needs to transfer the bishop to the long diagonal. The preferable square would be f3 , as from there it also supports h4 - h5 ideas and makes space for the king on g2 , if needed. However, it is not always possible to do so.} Nb6 {Possible too, intending to immediately set a blockade.} 15. Be2 {The bishop here is a bit more active than on f1 - it supports potential h4 - h5 ideas, and our king may go to g2 if needed.} Nfd5 {This is less logical than ... Nbd5 - the knight leaves the kingside, allows Ne4 and makes Nb6 a bit awkward.} 16. Qb3 Be7 17. Ne4 {With multiple ideas, as shown with the arrows.} *

