e claims it is just nothing serious.} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Rd1 Rc8 15. Bf1 Bb4 16. Bd2 Nd5 {with equality. Ivanchuk-Gelfand (2007).}) 13... cxd4 14. exd4 {In this position, White needs to transfer the bishop to the long diagonal. The preferable square would be f3 , as from there it also supports h4 - h5 ideas and makes space for the king on g2 , if needed. However, it is not always possible to do so.} Nb6 {Possible too, intending to immediately set a blockade.} 15. Be2 {The bishop here is a bit more active than on f1 - it supports potential h4 - h5 ideas, and our king may go to g2 if needed.} Nbd5 16. Bf3 Qb6 17. Bg5 Rac8 18. Rac1 {With some pressure. The Nd5 is obviously nice, but the bishop pair in an open position is also strong. And in this case, we keep the pressure on the d5 square, as well as maybe one day h4 - h5 , Kg2 and we could open the h-file.} ({Qa5} 18. Bd2 Nb4 19. Qb3 {Qf5 Kg2} Nd3 {Ra1⩲ The Nd3 may get trapped at some point!}) ({Nxc3 bxc3 Qa5} 18. Bd2) *

