e claims it is just nothing serious.} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Rd1 Rc8 15. Bf1 Bb4 16. Bd2 Nd5 {with equality. Ivanchuk-Gelfand (2007).}) 13... cxd4 14. exd4 {In this position, White needs to transfer the bishop to the long diagonal. The preferable square would be f3 , as from there it also supports h4 - h5 ideas and makes space for the king on g2 , if needed. However, it is not always possible to do so.} Rc8 {A logical continuation. Unfortunately, going for Be2 - Bf3 does not work well for White.} 15. Be2 {Let's examine a possible continuation.} Bb4 16. Qb3 Qa5 17. Bd2 Bxc3 {Here, unfortunately, White needs to recapture with the bishop, which is far from ideal - Black simply gets full control over the d5 -outpost.} 18. bxc3 Ne4 19. Be1 Nxc3 {Now the Be2 is hanging! White needs to bail out with Bf3 .} 20. Bf3 Qb6 21. Bxc3 Qxb3 22. axb3 Rxc3 23. Bxb7 {But of course, this is not something White intends to get out of the opening.} *

