1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg4 {Another move that has gone almost completely out of fashion. The g4 -bishop will soon face h3 - g4 giving White a few more moves than the normal lines.} 7. Qb3 dxc4 {This is an incredibly risky pawn sacrifice, but I decided to keep it as the main line as it leads to sharp play, while both 7... Qc7 and 7... Qb6 lead to chronically worse and more passive positions for Black.} 8. Qxb7 Nbd7 9. h3 Bh5 10. Qxc6 {I don't think Black has sufficient compensation.} Rc8 11. Qa4 (11. Qb5 $5 {is equally good.}) 11... Nd5 12. Nf3 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Bb4 14. Bd2 O-O 15. Bg2 {All this happened in Niemann-Aravindh (2022) and I think that White is just up a pawn for nothing in return.} e5 {An extremely speculative choice on Aravindh's part that Hans was able to refute convincingly.} 16. Nxd5 Bxd2+ 17. Kxd2 exd4 18. Ke2 ({I don't think Black has enough compensation, as in Niemann-Aravindh (2022). d3+ Kd2} 18. Nb6 Nxb6 {Qxb6} 19. Qa3 Rc5 20. Qc3 Rg5 21. Bf1 {and Black's compensation begins to disappear.}) *

