1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Nbd7 {Developing the knight on d7 early is generally inadvisable for Black, since in the event of cxd5 and ... cxd5 , Black can no longer put the knight on c6 . And the recapture of ... exd5 generally allows e4 -ideas, while ... Nxd5 allows White to build a strong center. Still, it has been played by some top players.} 9. Nxg6 ({If} 9. Qb3 $6 {Black has the extraordinary resource of giving up the b7 pawn:} dxc4 $1 10. Qxb7 (10. Bxc4 b5) 10... Bd3 $1 11. Bxd3 cxd3 12. f4 c5 {with an unclear game. For this reason, it is logical to take on g6 first and then play Qb3 .}) 9... hxg6 10. Qb3 {This is another good option. However, here we simply transpose to another big line, which is unnecessary to learn, especially since we try to avoid Qb3 lines in this course.} (10. Qc2 {is not that great now, as Black can save on ... Be7 .} dxc4 11. Bxc4 a6 {and after c5 and subsequent exchanges, Black can try to recapture with the bishop in one move without losing a tempo.}) 10... Qb6 {After both 10... Qb6 and 10... Qc7 there have been hundreds of games played and diving into this theory makes little sense when we have an easy solution in 9. cxd5 .} *

