1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Nbd7 {Developing the knight on d7 early is generally inadvisable for Black, since in the event of cxd5 and ... cxd5 , Black can no longer put the knight on c6 . And the recapture of ... exd5 generally allows e4 -ideas, while ... Nxd5 allows White to build a strong center. Still, it has been played by some top players.} 9. cxd5 {I would recommend taking on d5 immediately to clarify the situation and take advantage of the fact that ... Nbd7 was played so early, as explained above.} exd5 {This take is hardly ideal because White will soon play e4 .} 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Bd3 {I would recommend a simple development. White should be better thanks to the bishop pair.} Bd6 12. Qe2 ({And we keep the idea of castling queenside. We should not worry about losing the h2 -pawn as the bishop would be (nearly) trapped. And if} 12. O-O {then O-O-O⩲ and we will attack on the kingside.}) *

