{The queen is of course untouchable: fxe6?? Bxg6#} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} dxc4 {A rare move in this position. It seems to me that Black prematurely declares the situation in the center, but there are some concrete ideas with a quick ... b5 that absolutely must be checked.} 9. Bxc4 b5 10. Nxg6 {A well-timed capture. The point is that White wants his bishop on d3 !} hxg6 11. Bd3 Nbd7 (11... a6 {Playing without ... Nbd7 can be considered too, but it's unlikely any good.} 12. Qe2 c5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. O-O-O) 12. Qe2 {For some reason, the engine likes to place the queen on e2 at this point! Then, White wants to castle on the queenside and hide his king on b1 . As far as I know, e2 is a safer square than c2 , in case the c-file opens. There is also an idea of g4 - g5 that is very good.} a6 {Black prepares ... c5 . Now, it's time for active play, so we should delay castling a little bit.} 13. g4 c5 14. g5 {Black is under pressure.} cxd4 15. exd4 ({Opening the e-file only helps White. One of the most illustrative lines is the following:} 15. b4 {gxf6 bxc3 Qxe6+!! A beautiful tactical idea!} Be7 {Qxe7+ Qxe7+ fxe7 cxd2+ Kxd2± with an extra pawn (as the e7 -pawn will fall).}) *

