{Black has pawn weaknesses and an exposed king. The main line (and perhaps one that shows the main ideas here) is the following: Nb6 Bb5+ Kf8 Rh1 Kg8 f4!± and Black faces big problems.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} Qc7 {Hitting the h2 -pawn seems logical, but in reality, White can just ignore it.} 11. O-O-O {Perhaps Black should ignore the h2 -pawn...} Rxh2 {This is incredibly risky as White manages to immediately hit in the center. And the h2 -pawn is not that relevant.} 12. Rxh2 Qxh2 13. cxd5 Nxd5 (13... exd5 14. e4 {is quite similar.}) 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Qb3 {I find it useful to put pressure on both b7 and d5 pawns before playing e4 .} Qc7 16. e4 Nd7 17. exd5 cxd5+ 18. Kb1 *

