[Black "Slav - 5...e6/6...Be4 with 8."]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D12"]
[PlyCount "33"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} Qc7 {Hitting the h2 -pawn seems logical, but in reality, White can just ignore it.} 11. O-O-O {Perhaps Black should ignore the h2 -pawn...} Nbd7 {But now Black has no option of playing ... Nc6 after the trades on d5 . For this reason, I would recommend cxd5 !} 12. cxd5 cxd5 (12... exd5 $2 13. g3 {is terrible for Black.}) 13. Kb1 {Once again ignoring the h2 pawn and preparing e4 . It was also possible to play e4 right away, but we don't need to rush, and it makes sense to first move the king to safety. Moreover, Rc1 also fits into White's plans.} Rc8 ({After} 13... Rxh2 14. Bd3 {the h-file opens, and it is White that will control it.}) 14. e4 {The pressure in the center can be annoying for Black.} Nb6 {Supporting the center and going for ... Nc4 maybe in the future.} 15. Bb5+ {An unpleasant check.} Nfd7 {This is worse than ... Kf8 .} 16. Qb3 {Adding pressure on the d5 -pawn.} dxe4 17. Rc1 ({And Black is in big trouble. exf3} 17. Nd5 Nxd5 {Rxc7 Rxc7 Qxf3±}) *

