1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} dxc4 {Black may begin with dxc4 , but the most likely result here is just a transposition to the main line.} 11. Bxc4 c5 {This is the only independent line as far as I can see, but it is very risky for Black to open the center right away as he is not developed.} ({•} 11... b5 12. Be2 a6 13. O-O-O Nbd7 {or}) ({•} 11... a6 12. O-O-O b5 13. Be2 Nbd7 {transpose here.}) 12. dxc5 {Opening the position for the bishops.} Bxc5 13. O-O-O Nc6 14. g4 {White is clearly better.} *

