1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} a5 {This is a fresh and interesting approach, played so far mainly in the Sorokin-Gledura game (2022). Because of its rarity, it can be an interesting line for Black to play. The idea is to expand on the queenside with ... a4 and ... a3 if given the chance. Also, there are ideas of ... Bb4 when it is appropriate to exchange the dark-squared bishop.} 11. h4 {I like this idea for White. For now, ... a4 is useless because there is still no king on the queenside, while we keep the tension in the center and start expanding on the kingside, making Black's castling on the kingside very risky. So far there has been only one Lazavik-Firouzja game (2023), and Alireza has not reacted to the best.} (11. O-O-O {is another option that deserves attention, but I am not so sure about castling before playing Nb8 , due to a potential ... Na6 -... Nb4 idea, as in the following line:} a4 12. Kb1 a3 13. b3 Na6 {with a double-edged game. After} 14. cxd5 Nxd5 {a3 b5!⇆ , the c6 -pawn is guarded, giving Black an option to quickly open the queenside.}) 11... dxc4 {Played by Alireza, but it is a bit premature.} 12. Bxc4 Nd5 ({Consequent with the previous move, but incorrect.} 12... Nbd7 {was necessary, with a possible transposition after} 13. O-O-O {, or the somewhat mysterious Ne2!? which is recommended by the engine.}) 13. g3 {The way to go. We should not castle yet and give Black counterplay.} (13. O-O-O {was played by Lazavik, but now Black's position is perhaps quite OK due to} Nb4 $1 (13... a4 $2 14. a3 {was in the game and White is much better thanks to} b5 15. Bxd5 $1 exd5 16. Na2) 14. Qb1 b5 15. Be2 a4 16. a3 N4a6 $6 {with counterplay.}) 13... Nb4 14. Qb1 Nd7 15. a3 Nd5 16. Kf2 {The king is now perfectly safe on the kingside, and thanks to the bishop pair White has a nice advantage.} *

