1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} a5 {This is a fresh and interesting approach, played so far mainly in the Sorokin-Gledura game (2022). Because of its rarity, it can be an interesting line for Black to play. The idea is to expand on the queenside with ... a4 and ... a3 if given the chance. Also, there are ideas of ... Bb4 when it is appropriate to exchange the dark-squared bishop.} 11. h4 {I like this idea for White. For now, ... a4 is useless because there is still no king on the queenside, while we keep the tension in the center and start expanding on the kingside, making Black's castling on the kingside very risky. So far there has been only one Lazavik-Firouzja game (2023), and Alireza has not reacted to the best.} (11. O-O-O {is another option that deserves attention, but I am not so sure about castling before playing Nb8 , due to a potential ... Na6 -... Nb4 idea, as in the following line:} a4 12. Kb1 a3 13. b3 Na6 {with a double-edged game. After} 14. cxd5 Nxd5 {a3 b5!⇆ , the c6 -pawn is guarded, giving Black an option to quickly open the queenside.}) 11... Nbd7 {The best reaction.} 12. O-O-O {Now, White can castle more securely because the knight is already on d7 and this means that the c6 pawn in some lines is not defended, which makes the idea of ... b5 -... b4 not great.} dxc4 (12... a4 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. a3 {is slightly better for White, as ... b5 is not that strong anymore. And we should not worry about losing the h4 -pawn either.} Rxh4 (14... b5 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Kb1) 15. Rxh4 Bxh4 16. Bd3) 13. Bxc4 a4 {The best chance for counterplay.} 14. Kb1 {We should ignore ... a3 as we can play b3 and with Nd7 on the board, Black cannot comfortably install a knight on b4 (... Na6 -... Nb4 ).} (14. a3 $2 {runs into} b5 $1) 14... Nb6 15. Be2 a3 16. b3 {This position seems better for White because of the bishop pair, and the outpost on the b4 square is not that important. We should remember now to try to keep the knights on the chessboard.} Bb4 {This is the engine's suggestion but it's not as logical as ... Nbd5 or ... Nfd5 .} ({•} 16... Nbd5 17. Na4 $1) ({•} 16... Nfd5 17. Ne4) 17. g4 {With some pressure.} *

