1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} Nbd7 ({The main move.} 10... a6 11. O-O-O (11. c5 $5 {is another option, followed by} Nbd7 12. Na4 $5 {with playing for the squeeze. However - there is no need to enter it, as 11. O-O-O will simply transpose to the main line. 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 with an inevitable transposition.})) 11. O-O-O Nb6 {Being surprised (I guess so at least!), Fabiano Caruana played this move, which is an inaccuracy. Provoking c5 here is not right.} 12. c5 {Gaining space, and an important tempo.} Nbd7 {Black's idea is to play ... b6 , but we can easily guard our queenside with Na4 .} 13. Kb1 ({A logical move, but it is possible to play without it, as you can see:} 13. g4 b6 14. Na4 {looks good for White, e.g.} bxc5 15. dxc5 g5 16. Be1 $1) 13... b6 14. Na4 {I would recommend this move, keeping the bind on the queenside.} bxc5 15. dxc5 {In such position Black can pretty much never castle as h4 - h5 would destroy the kingside. Any time Black plays ... e5 , it would be subject to e4 and a serious weakening of the light squares, which is a problem given that Black does not have the light-squared bishop. Finally, White can prepare an expansion on the kingside, since on the queenside he is safe and Black does not have much counterplay.} Qc7 {This is less good than ... Qb8 .} 16. g4 {And Black cannot take the h2 -pawn.} Rxh2 17. Ba5 Rxc2 18. Bxc7 Rf2 19. Ba6 ({With a big advantage. Rxf3 Bb7 Rb8} 19. Rh8+ Bf8 {Bxc6 Rc8} 20. Rxf8+ $1 Kxf8 21. Bd6+ $1 Kg8 {Bb7±}) *

