1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} Nbd7 ({The main move.} 10... a6 11. O-O-O (11. c5 $5 {is another option, followed by} Nbd7 12. Na4 $5 {with playing for the squeeze. However - there is no need to enter it, as 11. O-O-O will simply transpose to the main line. 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 with an inevitable transposition.})) 11. O-O-O a6 {An interesting move order. Black prepares ... dxc4 followed by ... b5 . And with a6 on the board, it is useful to play ... c5 immediately. Also, Black can try to delay ... b5 altogether. But not playing ... dxc4 opens the door for White to play c5 , and we should do so.} ({Trying to transpose to} 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 a6 13. e4 {by playing e4!? does not work that well as Black can play dxe4 and White does not have here anything: fxe4?!} Ng4 $1 {or Nxe4 Nxe4 when both Qxe4 Nf6= and fxe4} 14. Bg5 {lead to equality.}) 12. Kb1 {Trying to transpose to the main line with Kb1 does not offer good chances for advantage as well.} dxc4 13. Bxc4 {Here, with 13... b5 we would just transpose to the main line, but Black can play ... c5 .} c5 {Which I believe equalizes quite easily. The point is that now Black has an additional idea of ... Nb6 , hitting both the Bc4 and the d4 -pawn.} 14. g4 ({The main move.} 14. dxc5 Nxc5 {White cannot hope for much here.}) (14. d5 {is met by} Nb6 $1 {and Black wins a pawn.}) 14... Nb6 {I did not find here anything that could be attractive for White.} 15. dxc5 ({The main move.} 15. Bxe6 $5 {could be tried, but White is also taking a lot of risks.} cxd4 $1 16. Bc1 fxe6 17. Rxd4 Qc8 18. g5 Nfd5 19. Qxg6+ Kf8 {We are down by a piece and the compensation does not look convincing to me. The engine evaluates 0.00, but all it takes is one inaccurate move and our initiative could evaporate.... Perhaps the main line is} 20. Nxd5 Nxd5 21. h4 Bc5 22. Rc4 b5 23. Rc2 Nb4 24. Rc3 Nd5 {with a repetition.}) 15... Nxc4 16. Qa4+ Nd7 17. Qxc4 Nxc5 18. Ne4 ({This might look somewhat promising for White due to the lead in development and open position, but Black is just fine. Alternatively,} 18. Be1 Qb6 19. Na4 Qc6 20. Nxc5 Qxc5) 18... Nxe4 19. Qxe4 Qd5 {By forcing the queen trade Black solves his development problems.} 20. Qxd5 exd5 {And the resulting endgame is roughly equal. There was a game Mishra-Gledura (2023) which quickly ended with a draw.} 21. h3 Rd8 22. Ba5 Rd7 23. Rc1 O-O 24. Bb6 f5 25. Rhf1 Kf7 26. f4 Bd8 27. Bd4 Bf6 28. Bc5 Be7 29. Bd4 Bf6 30. Bc5 Be7 31. Bd4 Bf6 {A draw was agreed in the game Mishra,A (2550)-Gledura,B (2644), Saint Louis USA 2023.} *

