1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} Nbd7 ({The main move.} 10... a6 11. O-O-O (11. c5 $5 {is another option, followed by} Nbd7 12. Na4 $5 {with playing for the squeeze. However - there is no need to enter it, as 11. O-O-O will simply transpose to the main line. 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 with an inevitable transposition.})) 11. O-O-O a6 {An interesting move order. Black prepares ... dxc4 followed by ... b5 . And with a6 on the board, it is useful to play ... c5 immediately. Also, Black can try to delay ... b5 altogether. But not playing ... dxc4 opens the door for White to play c5 , and we should do so.} 12. c5 {This looks like the best try for White. As Black played ... a6 , Black cannot recapture with the pawn in the event of ... b6 and trades on b6 .} b6 13. cxb6 {As Black cannot recapture with the pawn, I would recommend taking on b6 , however, 13. Na4 is playable too.} Qxb6 14. Kb1 {A useful move, putting the king to safety, waiting to see whether Black plays ... c5 right away.} c5 {If Black plays ... c5 right away, White focuses on the queenside play.} 15. Na4 Qa7 16. dxc5 ({Opening the position for the bishops and preventing ... c4 .} 16. Bc3 $5 {is possible too, but one must reckon with} c4 {which is double-edged.}) 16... Nxc5 17. Bc3 {Maintaining the tension. The bishop is very well-placed on c3 , and it can go to d4 .} O-O {Sooner or later Black must castle.} 18. Bd4 Rfc8 (18... Nfd7 {is worse as it leaves the kingside without much protection and White can play} 19. h4 $1 {with an immediate attack.}) 19. Be2 {Simply completing development. The focus right now is on the queenside and the c-file.} Nfd7 (19... Rc7 20. Rc1 Rac8 21. Qd2) 20. Rd3 {With some pressure.} *

