1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} Nbd7 ({The main move.} 10... a6 11. O-O-O (11. c5 $5 {is another option, followed by} Nbd7 12. Na4 $5 {with playing for the squeeze. However - there is no need to enter it, as 11. O-O-O will simply transpose to the main line. 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 with an inevitable transposition.})) 11. O-O-O Rc8 {Played in some games with an idea of ... c5 and intending to recapture with the rook.} 12. Kb1 c5 ({But surprisingly, this move has not been played yet!} 12... O-O {? happened in Keymer-Lazavik (2022) where White can immediately launch an attack on the kingside.} 13. h4 $1 dxc4 14. h5) 13. dxc5 ({The simplest. The alternative is unnecessarily complicated:} 13. cxd5 cxd4 14. dxe6 dxc3 15. exd7+ Qxd7 16. Bxc3 Nd5 {or} 17. Be1 Qe6 $1 {with a messy position.}) 13... dxc4 (13... Rxc5 $6 {is way worse:} 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Qb3) 14. Bxc4 {The position opened but White is ready for that. Next, e4 and f4 come.} Rxc5 15. Qd3 O-O 16. e4 Ne5 17. Qxd8 Rxd8 18. Be2 ({With a better endgame for White, e.g. Nc4 Bxc4 Rxc4} 18. Be3 a6 19. Rxd8+ Bxd8 {e5 Nd7} 20. Rd1 Rc7 21. Bb6 {Nxb6 Rxd8+} Kh7 {Ne4 g5 Nxg5+ Kg6} 22. f4) *

