1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} Nbd7 ({The main move.} 10... a6 11. O-O-O (11. c5 $5 {is another option, followed by} Nbd7 12. Na4 $5 {with playing for the squeeze. However - there is no need to enter it, as 11. O-O-O will simply transpose to the main line. 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 with an inevitable transposition.})) 11. O-O-O dxc4 {The main move, but there are numerous alternatives.} 12. Bxc4 a6 {Trying to transpose to the informational line when White plays Kb1 . But we are not obliged to do that.} 13. e4 {This is much stronger.} b5 ({Critical, as now we need to temporarily sacrifice a piece. After} 13... Nb6 14. Ne2 {White gives up the bishop pair but retains a strong center.}) 14. Bxe6 {A little bit unexpected, but very strong.} fxe6 15. e5 {Black is under pressure and perhaps he needs to return the piece right away and secure his king.} Nd5 {This is extremely risky for Black.} 16. Qxg6+ Kf8 17. Nxd5 cxd5 18. h4 {And Black's king is in big danger.} *

