1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} Nbd7 ({The main move.} 10... a6 11. O-O-O (11. c5 $5 {is another option, followed by} Nbd7 12. Na4 $5 {with playing for the squeeze. However - there is no need to enter it, as 11. O-O-O will simply transpose to the main line. 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 with an inevitable transposition.})) 11. O-O-O dxc4 {The main move, but there are numerous alternatives.} 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 a6 {This position can arise from various move orders. Black prepares ... c5 , which is a standard pawn break.} 14. Kb1 {I like this the most for White.} c5 15. d5 {This is the point. White sacrifices a pawn to open the d-file and put a lot of pressure on the center. Black has two moves: 15... exd5 or 15... Nxd5 .} exd5 {Recently, there were some more games here as well. The positions can get a bit confusing, as we will see shortly. I will make sure to clarify everything!} 16. Bc1 {Targetting the d5 -pawn.} Qb6 {Black ignores the d5 -pawn and tries to get some activity. We can't play g4 , as ... d4 could be a threat of some sort.} 17. f4 {This move is pretty strong. The idea is to strengthen the pressure in the center by playing Bf3 .} Qe6 {In this way Black tries to guard the d5 -pawn.} 18. Bf3 Nb6 {Black created a threat of ... b4 , therefore White needs to play a very important move that must be memorized.} 19. e4 {Opening the center up. Black is not in time to generate his initiative.} d4 20. f5 Qe5 21. Ne2 {Removing the blockade.} Nfd7 {Here, White should enter a forced sequence.} 22. Bf4 Qf6 23. e5 Qxf5 24. Be4 Qe6 25. Bxa8 Nxa8 {It seems like Black is doing great, with two pawns for the exchange and a nice blockade. But White has tactical resources.} 26. Nxd4 cxd4 27. Qc8+ Bd8 28. Qxa8 {White is up an exchange, so if Black does not do anything, White will just retain extra material. Therefore, Black does not have time to castle and must play ... Qf5 and get the Bf4 .} ({Qf5+} 28. Ka1 {Qxf4 But now, Black's king does not get to castle without material losses after} Qc6 $1 {with many threats. Black's position is incredibly shaky.}) *

