1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} Nbd7 ({The main move.} 10... a6 11. O-O-O (11. c5 $5 {is another option, followed by} Nbd7 12. Na4 $5 {with playing for the squeeze. However - there is no need to enter it, as 11. O-O-O will simply transpose to the main line. 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 with an inevitable transposition.})) 11. O-O-O dxc4 {The main move, but there are numerous alternatives.} 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 a6 {This position can arise from various move orders. Black prepares ... c5 , which is a standard pawn break.} 14. Kb1 {I like this the most for White.} c5 15. d5 {This is the point. White sacrifices a pawn to open the d-file and put a lot of pressure on the center. Black has two moves: 15... exd5 or 15... Nxd5 .} Nxd5 {This game was played in So-Vachier Lagrave, where I recall that MVL blitzed his preparation (and the entire game) and ended in a draw. However, I did find some improvements.} 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. Bc3 {Black has two options here.} b4 {Entering a forced sequence, like in the game So-MVL (2020). If Black does not do it, White will simply recapture the pawn and enjoy an advantage based mostly on the pair of bishops.} 18. Bxg7 Rh7 {Oops - the bishop is trapped... but no worries: we get plenty of active play here with White!} 19. Rxd5 Rxg7 20. Rhd1 Ra7 21. Qa4 Qc8 {So far, we have been following So-Vachier Lagrave. Here, however, White has a strong improvement.} 22. f4 {The pin is incredibly troublesome for Black, and we should not release the tension. The idea is to improve the bishop by taking it to f3 , or sometimes to g4 . Unfortunately, with absolutely perfect play the engines can draw in the end. But I would not worry about that: finding unique moves in such an absurd position, where Black is under pressure, is very difficult.} ({Wesley played} 22. Bb5 axb5 23. Qxa7 Nf6 24. Re5 Nd7 25. Red5 Nf6 {and the game ended with a repetition.}) 22... f5 {This is a human move - Black blocks Bg4 ideas and connects the Rg7 to the defense on the d7 -square. But this is already a serious inaccuracy.} 23. Bc4 {I like the idea of stopping ... c4 counterplay for good.} (23. Bf3 $5 {is possible too.}) 23... Bf8 24. g4 {Black is under huge pressure. The pin is close to being unbearable.} Kd8 {This is the best defense, trying to get away to safety on c7 .} 25. gxf5 Kc7 26. f6 (26. Qc2 $5 {is also good.}) 26... Rf7 27. Qc2 Kb6 28. Qxg6 Rxf6 29. Qg4 Kc6 {With such weird only moves Black manages to avoid immediate collapse. But it looks simply bad and White can make a draw any moment.} 30. Qg5 ({With multiple threats. Be7} 30. Be2 Nb8 31. Rxc5+ Bxc5 {Qxf6+ Kc7} 32. Bf3+) *

