1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} Nbd7 ({The main move.} 10... a6 11. O-O-O (11. c5 $5 {is another option, followed by} Nbd7 12. Na4 $5 {with playing for the squeeze. However - there is no need to enter it, as 11. O-O-O will simply transpose to the main line. 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 with an inevitable transposition.})) 11. O-O-O dxc4 {The main move, but there are numerous alternatives.} 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 a6 {This position can arise from various move orders. Black prepares ... c5 , which is a standard pawn break.} 14. Kb1 {I like this the most for White.} c5 15. d5 {This is the point. White sacrifices a pawn to open the d-file and put a lot of pressure on the center. Black has two moves: 15... exd5 or 15... Nxd5 .} Nxd5 {This game was played in So-Vachier Lagrave, where I recall that MVL blitzed his preparation (and the entire game) and ended in a draw. However, I did find some improvements.} 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. Bc3 {Black has two options here.} b4 {Entering a forced sequence, like in the game So-MVL (2020). If Black does not do it, White will simply recapture the pawn and enjoy an advantage based mostly on the pair of bishops.} 18. Bxg7 Rh7 {Oops - the bishop is trapped... but no worries: we get plenty of active play here with White!} 19. Rxd5 Rxg7 20. Rhd1 Ra7 21. Qa4 Qc8 {So far, we have been following So-Vachier Lagrave. Here, however, White has a strong improvement.} 22. f4 {The pin is incredibly troublesome for Black, and we should not release the tension. The idea is to improve the bishop by taking it to f3 , or sometimes to g4 . Unfortunately, with absolutely perfect play the engines can draw in the end. But I would not worry about that: finding unique moves in such an absurd position, where Black is under pressure, is very difficult.} ({Wesley played} 22. Bb5 axb5 23. Qxa7 Nf6 24. Re5 Nd7 25. Red5 Nf6 {and the game ended with a repetition.}) 22... c4 {Black needs to look for some counterplay... even if at first sight it is not clear what this move brings. But by playing ... c3 in the future, Black can try to weaken White's king.} 23. Bf3 {Creating a threat of Rxd7 !} Kd8 24. e4 {Now, Bg4 is another threat!} c3 {And Black must seek counterplay!} 25. Bg4 ({The best try. If you are interested, however, moves like} 25. e5 {or bxc3 bxc3 Kc2 are also interesting - but still, I like text the most.}) 25... f5 (25... c2+ {is also a move, but it results in a transposition.} 26. Qxc2 Qxc2+ 27. Kxc2 f5 28. exf5 {see the 26...c2 line.}) 26. exf5 {Here, Black faces a critical moment.} c2+ {This is the most humane move, but it is an inaccuracy. Under such a siege, who would not be attracted to simplify the position and take the queens off the board! On purpose, I left it as the main move because it is the most likely from the human point of view. Defense after 26... Rc7 !!  is almost unlikely to be found...} 27. Qxc2 Qxc2+ 28. Kxc2 Ke8 {Gives an additional option of fxg6 , which I think we should take advantage of. But Rxd7 is possible too, with a roughly similar endgame as the main line.} 29. fxg6 (29. Rxd7 Rxd7 30. Rxd7 gxf5 31. Bxf5 Rxg2+ 32. Kb3 {is a pawn up endgame, similar (or in case of} Bf6 {identical!) endgame as in the main line.}) 29... Nf6 30. Rg5 ({4 pawns for the piece is a lot of pawns! After Rc7} 30. Kb1 Nxg4 {Rxg4} 31. Rc5 {Black must prevent White's pawns from advancing. Rc1 Rd5 h4 There is no way to attack White's pawns. Kd7 f5 Rxf5 Rd4+ Ke6 g4 Rc5 h5 Rxc1+ Kxc1 And Black needs to fight hard to earn a draw.}) *

