1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} Nbd7 ({The main move.} 10... a6 11. O-O-O (11. c5 $5 {is another option, followed by} Nbd7 12. Na4 $5 {with playing for the squeeze. However - there is no need to enter it, as 11. O-O-O will simply transpose to the main line. 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 with an inevitable transposition.})) 11. O-O-O dxc4 {The main move, but there are numerous alternatives.} 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 a6 {This position can arise from various move orders. Black prepares ... c5 , which is a standard pawn break.} 14. e4 {Another testing option, which was tried in 2022 by Ding Liren. This leads to extremely double-edged positions, so it may not suit everyone's style and requires in-depth analysis. For this reason I show it only as an alternative and discuss it briefly.} c5 15. d5 exd5 {Here, White has two options.} 16. Nxd5 (16. exd5 $5 {is the other one. White tries to play g4 - g5 quickly, but there are also ideas of sacrificing the d6 pawn.} c4 ({•} 16... Bd6 17. g4) ({•} 16... Nb6 17. Kb1 Qc7 18. d6 Qxd6 19. g4) 17. g4 Nb6 18. Kb1 {with an unclear game.}) 16... Nxd5 17. exd5 {In this case, White's main idea is f4 - Bf3 , and it is usually played either in the center, or via f5 or the h4 - h5 pawn break on the kingside. In addition, g4 is often useful. Black sooner or later needs to castle on the kingside, which will open up some practical possibilities.} Nf6 ({•} 17... Qc7 18. f4 Rd8 19. Kb1 Nf6 20. Bf3 Nxd5 21. f5) ({•} 17... Nb6 18. Ba5 O-O 19. h4 Qd6 20. h5) 18. Kb1 {A useful move, stronger than 18. Bg5 played by Ding.} O-O 19. g4 Nxd5 20. h4 Qb6 21. f4 {I am not arguing that White is better, but it is certainly a playable position in which White's plan is rather simple.} *

