1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 {This is a recent trend in ... Be4 -... Bg6 line. This idea attempts to improve over the standard 8. Qb3 : considering that Bd2 must still be played, we start with it and later try to see if Qb3 is useful, or perhaps Qc2 is more appropriate.} Be7 {The main move. Just like with the inclusion of Qb3 - Qc7 , Black delays the development of Nb8 to meet cxd5 with ... cxd5 and have an option to play ... Nc6 in the future.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 {White simply does not go for Qb3 at all. This is recent fashion and I think it gives White a good chance. This idea was first played in 2017 by Ahmed Adly, but it was not until 2020 that it gained wider recognition, as Anish Giri played it at the 2020 Candidates against Fabiano Caruana. Since then, the theory has developed significantly.} Nbd7 ({The main move.} 10... a6 11. O-O-O (11. c5 $5 {is another option, followed by} Nbd7 12. Na4 $5 {with playing for the squeeze. However - there is no need to enter it, as 11. O-O-O will simply transpose to the main line. 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 with an inevitable transposition.})) 11. O-O-O dxc4 {The main move, but there are numerous alternatives.} 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 a6 {This position can arise from various move orders. Black prepares ... c5 , which is a standard pawn break.} 14. Ne4 {A new move in this position, but the idea is very common in these 4. e3 Slav lines. Ideally, White would like to build a strong center after the exchanges on e4 . It can be tried, especially as a surprise weapon.} Nxe4 (14... c5 {could be played right away too, but without particular success.} 15. Nxc5 Rc8 16. Kb1 Nxc5 17. dxc5 Rxc5 18. Qb3) 15. fxe4 {This is generally good news for White. Next, e5 is an idea to open diagonals for the light squared bishop. But Black can hold with perfect play.} c5 16. Kb1 {Necessary prophylaxis-since the c-file is about to open, White's king must reach the safe b1 -square, and Rc1 must follow.} Rc8 17. Rc1 {Here, Black has a couple of options.} O-O {The best move.} ({•} 17... e5 18. Bg4 $1 {and the light squares are very weak for Black.}) ({•} 17... c4 18. h4 $1 {is dangerous for Black too.}) 18. e5 cxd4 19. Qxc8 Qxc8 20. Rxc8 Rxc8 21. exd4 ({White is slightly better in this endgame, and probably Black should be able to hold it. Still, the position remains somewhat playable. Nb6} 21. Rc1 {Rook trade seems inevitable.} Rxc1+ 22. Kxc1 Kf8 23. Kc2 Ke8 24. Kd3 {Kd7 Bd1 Kc6= with a possible fortress. Well, what to do if someone plays perfect chess...}) *

