1. d4 d5 2. c4 {Here I discuss openings that are more uncommon than traditional options such as Slav, QGA or QGD.} c5 {A rare line today, but Shakhriyar Mamedyarov has played it many times. It became very popular in the mid-2010s.} ({•} 2... e5 {The Albin Countergambit is a risky opening choice. White has many paths to advantage. I recommend the following:} 3. dxe5 d4 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 {This is by far the simplest. We intend Nb3 and target the d4 -pawn, but we also keep in mind the idea of g3 - Bg2 .}) ({•} 2... Nc6 {The Chigorin Defense is not much played nowadays at the highest level, but it does happen from time to time. In the 2000s it was taken up by Morozevich and later by Rapport, and both achieved good results with it, but in general it is a rather suspect opening for Black.} 3. Nf3 {The following line is the most challenging option:} Bg4 4. cxd5 Bxf3 5. gxf3 Qxd5 6. e3 e5 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Bd2 Bxc3 9. bxc3 {where White builds a strong center and has the bishop pair.}) ({•} 2... Nf6 $6 {This is certainly a dubious move that many novice chess players tend to play. The problem is that Black gives up the fight for the center.} 3. cxd5 Nxd5 (3... Qxd5 4. Nc3 Qd8 5. Nf3 $1 {followed by e4 is the most precise.}) 4. Nf3 $1 {I would not rush with e4 as Black cannot really stop it anyway. The only attempt could be} Bf5 {but it has other drawbacks.} 5. Nbd2 Nf6 6. Qb3 $1 {and White is much better.}) ({•} 2... Bf5 {This also is a suspicious opening choice by Black.} 3. cxd5 Bxb1 {(otherwise, Nc3 next)} 4. Rxb1 Qxd5 {and here, I would recommend} 5. Nf3 $1 Qxa2 6. Bd2 $1 {which is a powerful pawn sacrifice, as Black plays only with his queen while we develop all our pieces, have the bishop pair, and finally control the center.}) 3. cxd5 Qxd5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nc3 Qa5 6. Nxd4 Nf6 {Here, White has a lot of possibilities. I decided to stick with a3 .} (6... e5 {is premature due to} 7. Nb3 Qc7 8. Nb5 $1 {and Black's queen is chased around, and it is a problem.}) 7. a3 {With the idea of preventing ... Bb4 , when Black plays ... e5 . Additionally, sometimes we may play b4 as well.} e5 {The main line.} 8. Nb3 Qc7 9. Nb5 ({White is better after both this move, which is my main recommendation, and} 9. Bg5 {, which I offer as an alternative.}) *

