1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nf6 {This opening is often played by novice chess players who do not understand the concept of controlling the center. The d5 -pawn is not sufficiently supported now (as it is after 2... c6 or 2... e6 ), and White can play cxd5 and e4 , since Black cannot recapture the pawn. However, there are some hidden rocks that White needs to watch out for.} 3. cxd5 Qxd5 4. Nc3 {This is a bad version of the Scandinavian, as White soon manages to control the center with e4 .} Qd8 {Perhaps the most resilient and safest square for the queen.} 5. Nf3 ({White should prepare e4 with a clear advantage. And not play} 5. e4 {right away because of} e5 $1 {and Black gets some counterplay here. I faced this once with White (I did not know the idea of ... e5 in this position) and did not get much from the opening.}) *

