1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nf6 {This opening is often played by novice chess players who do not understand the concept of controlling the center. The d5 -pawn is not sufficiently supported now (as it is after 2... c6 or 2... e6 ), and White can play cxd5 and e4 , since Black cannot recapture the pawn. However, there are some hidden rocks that White needs to watch out for.} 3. cxd5 Nxd5 4. Nf3 {White should not rush with e4 as Black has no successful way of stopping it.} ({It is also OK to start with} 4. e4 {, but it runs into slight issues:} Nf6 {Perhaps White needs to play} 5. Bd3 {but Black can anyway play ... e5 .} ({•} 5. e5 Nd5 {is not ideal too - Black gets the outpost on d5 .}) ({•} 5. Nc3 e5 $1 {is the same as Qxd5 Nc3 Qd8 e4?!} 6. dxe5 $1) 5... e5 $1 6. dxe5 Ng4 7. Bb5+ c6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Be2 Nxe5 {and despite a clear advantage for White, I think it may not be so easy to prove.}) 4... g6 5. e4 Nb6 {We got to some Grünfeld-style position, but without a couple of tempi for Black.} 6. h3 {In any case, preventing ... Bg4 .} Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be3 {This position normally appears with White not having played h3 . Here, White simply has an extra tempo and this h3 pawn makes a huge difference - there is no ... Bg4 , which is the main Black's idea in similar positions.} Nc6 9. Bb5 {With the intention of playing Bxc6 to mess up Black's pawn structure. I don't think it requires further analysis as it is clearly bad for Black.} *

