1. d4 d5 2. c4 Bf5 {This move is acceptable when White plays 2. Nf3 , but not in this case. The pressure in the center is already there and Black should have already done something.} 3. cxd5 Bxb1 ({A logical continuation of Black's last move.} 3... Qxd5 $2 4. Nc3) 4. Rxb1 (4. Qa4+ {is much better for White as well, but I decided to stick with 4. Rxb1 and 5. Nf3 as it feels more principled to go for an advantage in development.}) 4... Qxd5 5. Nf3 {Stockfish is just ruthless and evaluates +1. I mean, it makes sense - Black gave away the pair of bishops and the center and roams around with the queen. It cannot be good for Black.} Nc6 {This is safer than 5... Qxa2 , but it is still ineffective.} 6. e3 O-O-O {White has two excellent options for you to choose from.} ({•} 6... Qxa2 7. Bd2 {is similar to the main line.}) ({•} 6... e5 7. dxe5 Qxa2 8. Bd2 {not much changes!}) 7. Qc2 e5 8. Bc4 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Bb4 10. dxe5 Bxd2+ 11. Nxd2 {White will win a pawn with great chances of victory. Some caution is needed, however, because White's king is in the center.} Qxe5 {Otherwise, e6 could have saved the pawn.} (11... Nxe5 12. Qf5+ Kb8 13. b4) 12. O-O {Black's position is strategically very shaky. His king is weak on the queenside and will be quickly attacked with b4 - b5} (12. Bxf7 Nh6 13. Bc4 {wins the pawn and should also win the game, but from a practical point of view it is more complicated because White's king remains in the center and there are the ideas of ... Ng4 and ... Nxe3 . They do not work, but there is no need to allow them in any case.}) *

