{Offering another pawn for a huge initiative. Black is just lost (+3!). e6 O-O Nf6 Re1 Bd6 Bc4 Qf5 Ng5+-} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 Bf5 {This move is acceptable when White plays 2. Nf3 , but not in this case. The pressure in the center is already there and Black should have already done something.} 3. cxd5 Bxb1 ({A logical continuation of Black's last move.} 3... Qxd5 $2 4. Nc3) 4. Rxb1 (4. Qa4+ {is much better for White as well, but I decided to stick with 4. Rxb1 and 5. Nf3 as it feels more principled to go for an advantage in development.}) 4... Qxd5 5. Nf3 {Stockfish is just ruthless and evaluates +1. I mean, it makes sense - Black gave away the pair of bishops and the center and roams around with the queen. It cannot be good for Black.} Qxa2 {Black can try to be greedy, but it simply does not work. The a2 -pawn is pretty much irrelevant here.} 6. Bd2 {It is important to cover the b4 -square, so that Black cannot play ... e5 and ... Bb4 .} Qd5 7. Rc1 c6 {Black returns with the queen and protects the pawn, but is significantly behind in development.} 8. e4 (8. e3 $5 {is very strong too.}) 8... Qxe4+ 9. Be2 *

