1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6 {The Chigorin Defense is not much played nowadays at the highest level, but it does happen from time to time. In the 2000s it was taken up by Morozevich and later by Rapport, and both achieved good results, but in general it is a rather suspect opening for Black.} 3. Nf3 e5 {This is kind of a delayed Albin Countergambit. I think that White should grab the pawn as Black will not have any significant compensation.} 4. Nxe5 ({Trading more pieces helps White as Black counterplay resources will be depleted. However,} 4. dxe5 {with potential transposition to the Albin Countergambit also works.}) 4... Nxe5 5. dxe5 d4 {White has many options here, but I like the fianchetto of the Bf1 the most.} 6. g3 Ne7 7. Bg2 Nc6 8. f4 {Just defending the pawn. I must admit though that 8. O-O was giving White a nice edge too.} Bf5 9. a3 {Stopping any ... Nb4 or ... Bb4 ideas. Next, White will play via Nd2 and O-O , potentially b4 as well.} *

