1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6 {The Chigorin Defense is not much played nowadays at the highest level, but it does happen from time to time. In the 2000s it was taken up by Morozevich and later by Rapport, and both achieved good results, but in general it is a rather suspect opening for Black.} 3. Nf3 Bf5 ({This is similar to} 3... Nf6 {- Black does not manage to hold in the center.}) (3... dxc4 $2 4. d5 $1 {This is definitely not what Black wants...} Nb8 {A sad necessity.} (4... Na5 {simply loses.} 5. Qa4+ c6 6. Bd2 $1 b6 7. Bxa5 bxa5 8. Nc3) 5. e4 {With a significant advantage thanks to the strong center.}) 4. cxd5 Qxd5 (4... Bxb1 5. dxc6) 5. Nc3 Qa5 6. Bd2 {White just crushes in the center.} *

