1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6 {The Chigorin Defense is not much played nowadays at the highest level, but it does happen from time to time. In the 2000s it was taken up by Morozevich and later by Rapport, and both achieved good results, but in general it is a rather suspect opening for Black.} 3. Nf3 Bg4 ({If Black plays} 3... e6 {we get a Queen's Gambit Declined with an awkward ... Nc6 . I discuss this in section on Tango, in Part 1. I would recommend} 4. Nc3 Nf6 {and now either} 5. Bg5 {or a3 (see Part )}) 4. cxd5 Bxf3 5. gxf3 Qxd5 6. e3 {Intending Nc3 next, building a strong center. Black absolutely must fight for the center.} e5 (6... e6 $6 {is clearly worse:} 7. Nc3 Qd7 8. Qb3 O-O-O 9. Bd2 {with O-O-O next.}) 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Bd2 Bxc3 9. bxc3 {I like this line against the Chigorin Defense. The idea is to build a strong center and get the bishop pair. A slight drawback is that the pawn structure is a bit damaged and White's king may feel a bit insecure at times, but knowing the ideas can definitely solve these problems. White's ideas include the possibility of playing c4 - d5 . Assuming Black defends, White opts for the ideas Rb1 , Qb3 . Very often the idea of f4 and Bg2 (or f4 - exf4 - e4 !), even if it involves the sacrifice of a pawn, is a strong option. And of course, if White manages to exchange queens, his advantage will be indisputable.} Qd7 {Played in the game Nakamura-Rapport (2017) with similar idea as ... Qd6 , but keeping defended the f7 -pawn.} 10. Rb1 O-O-O ({Defending the b7 -pawn and completing the development.} 10... b6 {is worse due to} 11. Rg1 g6 12. f4 $1 exf4 13. e4) 11. Bg2 (11. f4 $5 exf4 12. e4 Nf6 13. f3 {This is another interesting idea suggested by the engine. The center and the pair of bishops are very strong.}) 11... Nge7 {Here, I would recommend an improvement over Nakamura's move.} 12. f4 ({Hikaru grabbed a pawn with} 12. Qb3 $6 b6 13. Qxf7 {, but this gave Rapport a compensation on the f-file:} Rhf8 14. Qc4 Kb8 {and even though White is still ahead, things may be here pretty complicated.}) 12... exf4 13. O-O {A very strong pawn sacrifice. The Bg2 and Rb1 are putting a lot of pressure on the queenside and given that White still controls the center, the missing pawn is irrelevant.} ({• h5 Kh1} 13. h4 {h3 Rh6 Re1± or} fxe3 14. Bxe3) ({• fxe3 fxe3 f5} 13. Qa4 Kb8 14. c4) *

