1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6 {The Chigorin Defense is not much played nowadays at the highest level, but it does happen from time to time. In the 2000s it was taken up by Morozevich and later by Rapport, and both achieved good results, but in general it is a rather suspect opening for Black.} 3. Nf3 Bg4 ({If Black plays} 3... e6 {we get a Queen's Gambit Declined with an awkward ... Nc6 . I discuss this in section on Tango, in Part 1. I would recommend} 4. Nc3 Nf6 {and now either} 5. Bg5 {or a3 (see Part )}) 4. cxd5 Bxf3 5. gxf3 Qxd5 6. e3 {Intending Nc3 next, building a strong center. Black absolutely must fight for the center.} e5 (6... e6 $6 {is clearly worse:} 7. Nc3 Qd7 8. Qb3 O-O-O 9. Bd2 {with O-O-O next.}) 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Bd2 Bxc3 9. bxc3 {I like this line against the Chigorin Defense. The idea is to build a strong center and get the bishop pair. A slight drawback is that the pawn structure is a bit damaged and White's king may feel a bit insecure at times, but knowing the ideas can definitely solve these problems. White's ideas include the possibility of playing c4 - d5 . Assuming Black defends, White opts for the ideas Rb1 , Qb3 . Very often the idea of f4 and Bg2 (or f4 - exf4 - e4 !), even if it involves the sacrifice of a pawn, is a strong option. And of course, if White manages to exchange queens, his advantage will be indisputable.} Qd6 {The main move - Black prevents c4 and d5 .} 10. Qb3 {There are many options, but this is the one I like best. White immediately puts pressure on both pawns b7 and f7 .} O-O-O {A standard pawn sacrifice in this variation. Black does not mind giving up the f-pawn, as long as he gets some dynamic and compensating play. The engine, however, is ruthless.} 11. Rb1 b6 12. Qxf7 Kb8 {Probably the most resilient - avoiding any checks and keeping queens on the board. Black normally wants to play ... Nge7 , but if played immediately then White can trade queens.} 13. Qc4 Qf6 (13... Nge7 14. Bd3 $1) (13... Nf6 14. Bg2) 14. Be2 (14. Bg2 {is also possible but more complicated.} Nge7 15. O-O Ng6 16. f4 $1 Na5 17. Qb5 Nh4 $1 {and things get messy. With precise play, White should win, but it seems like that none of that is necessary.} 18. Qxa5 Qg6 19. Rxb6+ $3 cxb6 20. Qxe5+ Rd6 21. Qe4 Nxg2 22. f5 $3 {and White should win eventually as the knight falls and White's central pawns will roll forward.}) 14... Nge7 15. h4 Rhf8 16. Rb5 {The extra pawn, the strong center, the pair of bishops - all tell the same story: White is much better.} *

