Rb8 , he generally wants to control the b-file with ... Rb6 and ... Rfb8 .} 13. Rd1 {Centralizing the rook and anticipating the doubling on the b-file that would have potentially created a threat of ... Rb1 . Now, with Rd1 , this is no longer a problem.} Rb6 14. Qc4 Rfb8 15. Be2 {White intends to eventually castle kingside.} Nd5 16. f4 {A standard pawn breakthrough, critical I must say in this position.} e4 ({The best chance for Black is to keep the position closed. After} 16... exf4 17. e4 {White gets a powerful pawn center.} Nde7 18. Qd3) ({After} 16... exd4 {, instead of immediately recapturing, a good intermezzo is} 17. Bf3 $1 {with big advantage:} Rb5 18. cxd4 {or} Nce7 {Qxd4!±}) 17. Qc5 {White retains great chances due to the extra pawn and the pair of bishops which in the future will very likely matter. White intends c4 in the future.} Qxc5 18. dxc5 Rb2 {Looks decent for Black but thanks to Bc4 !, White mantains his advantage.} 19. Bc4 Nde7 20. Bc1 Rc2 21. Bb3 {White gives away both pawns on the c-file in order to activate his bishops.} Rxc3 22. Bb2 Rxc5 23. Rd7 {White's pair of bishops is dominant.} *

