Rb8 , he generally wants to control the b-file with ... Rb6 and ... Rfb8 .} 13. Rd1 {Centralizing the rook and anticipating the doubling on the b-file that would have potentially created a threat of ... Rb1 . Now, with Rd1 , this is no longer a problem.} Rb6 14. Qc4 Rfb8 15. Be2 {White intends to eventually castle kingside.} Nd5 16. f4 {A standard pawn breakthrough, critical I must say in this position.} e4 ({The best chance for Black is to keep the position closed. After} 16... exf4 17. e4 {White gets a powerful pawn center.} Nde7 18. Qd3) ({After} 16... exd4 {, instead of immediately recapturing, a good intermezzo is} 17. Bf3 $1 {with big advantage:} Rb5 18. cxd4 {or} Nce7 {Qxd4!±}) 17. Qc5 {White retains great chances due to the extra pawn and the pair of bishops which in the future will very likely matter. White intends c4 in the future.} Qd7 {Generally, it feels to me that Black should try to keep queens on the board.} 18. Rg1 {As c4 does not run away (and also does not work now due to 18.... Nxf4 !), White improves his rook.} (18. c4 $2 {is bad due to} Nxf4 $1 {and the tables turned!}) 18... Nce7 (18... g6 19. Rg5) 19. c4 Nb4 20. Qe5 {The most concrete move, attacking both e4 and g7 pawns. Everything checks out tactically for White.} Nc2+ 21. Kf1 Qh3+ 22. Rg2 Ng6 (22... Rg6 23. Qxe4 {and White's material advantage is too large.}) 23. Qg5 {Final prophylaxis, preventing ... Nh4 . Black is running out of ideas to create chaos and White should win.} *

