{With b4 - Bb2 next. Black is unable to get the pawn back, as after Re8 Bc4+- is a serious problem for Black.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 {Albin's Countergambit is certainly a speculative opening choice for Black, but it can lead to very interesting and unbalanced positions. In a way, it reminds me of the Budapest Gambit (which I discuss in part 1 ).} 3. dxe5 Ne7 {This has been tried in some online games by Dubov and Carlsen. Seeking to get out of the book is a common strategy nowadays, but I am not sure if this is the right way to do it.} 4. Nf3 Nbc6 5. cxd5 {I think this is one of the simplest paths, even though there are surely many other possibilities.} Qxd5 6. Qxd5 Nxd5 7. a3 {It is important to cover the b4 -square in any case, preventing ... Ndb4 . White simply has an extra pawn and Black's compensation (if there is any) is really dubious.} Bg4 (7... h6 {with idea of ... g5 and ... Bg7 can be met by simple} 8. h4 {and Black should probably play ... g6 anyway, but in my opinion the inclusion of h4 and ... h6 moves helps White due to a slight space expansion on the kingside.}) 8. Nbd2 O-O-O 9. e3 *

