1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 {Albin's Countergambit is certainly a speculative opening choice for Black, but it can lead to very interesting and unbalanced positions. In a way, it reminds me of the Budapest Gambit (which I discuss in part 1 ).} 3. dxe5 Ne7 {This has been tried in some online games by Dubov and Carlsen. Seeking to get out of the book is a common strategy nowadays, but I am not sure if this is the right way to do it.} 4. Nf3 Nbc6 5. cxd5 {I think this is one of the simplest paths, even though there are surely many other possibilities.} Qxd5 6. Qxd5 Nxd5 7. a3 {It is important to cover the b4 -square in any case, preventing ... Ndb4 . White simply has an extra pawn and Black's compensation (if there is any) is really dubious.} g6 {Black should surround the e5 -pawn, hoping to regain it.} 8. e4 Nb6 {Here, White has some choice.} 9. Nc3 Bg7 10. Nb5 {Going after another pawn!} O-O 11. Nxc7 Rb8 {White is better in number of ways, but Black has some compensation. With accurate play, White should be better.} 12. e6 fxe6 (12... Bxe6 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Rb1 {is even worse for Black.}) 13. Be2 Nd4 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 15. O-O Bd7 16. Bg4 {And Black is struggling.} *

