1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 {Albin's Countergambit is certainly a speculative opening choice for Black, but it can lead to very interesting and unbalanced positions. In a way, it reminds me of the Budapest Gambit (which I discuss in part 1 ).} 3. dxe5 d4 {The main move, of course, but there are others as well.} ({After} 3... dxc4 $2 4. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {the resulting endgame is simply bad for Black. By just developing the pieces, White will not only defend his e5 pawn, but also try to capture the c4 pawn. With Black's king in the center, his task of survival is difficult.} 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3) 4. Nf3 Nc6 {I must decide whether a3 or . Both should give White a clear edge, but I need to make up my mind.} 5. Nbd2 {I think this is by far the simplest line we can play against the Albin to gain a clear and comfortable advantage without having to learn too much. The idea is to play Nb3 and attack the d4 pawn. However, we retain the idea of also developing via g3 - Bg2 .} (5. a3 {is another line that offers an advantage, but I find it a bit more complex. There have been thousands of games played and White is better, so if you are interested, feel free to explore it! However, I will stick to 5. Nbd2 which is simpler and at least as good.}) 5... Bg4 {This is the most common move according to my database, but the engine simply hates it. With Nbd2 on the board, the Nf3 is well-supported. White has many good moves, but I mostly like completing the development.} 6. g3 Qd7 {Making use of the pawn on g3 , Black anticipates White castling kingside and gets ready for ... Bh3 and ... h5 , hoping for an attack on the kingside.} (6... f6 7. exf6 Nxf6 8. Bg2 {such gambit play is not good for Black either.}) 7. Bg2 O-O-O (7... Bh3 {see here.}) 8. O-O Bh3 {White has a neat resource.} 9. e6 Bxe6 10. Ng5 {We return the pawn immediately, but gain the bishop pair after capturing Black's light-squared bishop. On top of that, our own bishop on g2 becomes incredibly strong. In this way, White will have his king safe and Black's king on the queenside will not be safe at all.} ({And if Bf5 then Bxc6! and Black must recapture with the pawn, leaving his king very insecure. bxc6} 10. Qa4) *

