1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 {Albin's Countergambit is certainly a speculative opening choice for Black, but it can lead to very interesting and unbalanced positions. In a way, it reminds me of the Budapest Gambit (which I discuss in part 1 ).} 3. dxe5 d4 {The main move, of course, but there are others as well.} ({After} 3... dxc4 $2 4. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {the resulting endgame is simply bad for Black. By just developing the pieces, White will not only defend his e5 pawn, but also try to capture the c4 pawn. With Black's king in the center, his task of survival is difficult.} 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3) 4. Nf3 Nc6 {I must decide whether a3 or . Both should give White a clear edge, but I need to make up my mind.} 5. Nbd2 {I think this is by far the simplest line we can play against the Albin to gain a clear and comfortable advantage without having to learn too much. The idea is to play Nb3 and attack the d4 pawn. However, we retain the idea of also developing via g3 - Bg2 .} (5. a3 {is another line that offers an advantage, but I find it a bit more complex. There have been thousands of games played and White is better, so if you are interested, feel free to explore it! However, I will stick to 5. Nbd2 which is simpler and at least as good.}) 5... Nge7 {Black should try to get the e5 -pawn back.} 6. Nb3 Nf5 {If Black defends the pawn, White can play with g3 , but I find it even stronger to play e4 !} 7. e4 {A very strong move, transitioning to a much better endgame with an extra pawn.} dxe3 8. Qxd8+ Nxd8 9. fxe3 ({White is just up a pawn and Black does not have sufficient compensation. The double pawns are actually pretty strong as they restrict Black's pieces. Be7} 9. Bd2 Nh4 10. Nbd4) ({Or g6} 9. Bd2 {Bg7 Nbd4 O-O Bd3} Ne7 {Be4 Bg4} 10. Bc3 Nec6 {Nxc6 Nxc6 Bxc6 bxc6} 11. h3 Be6 {b3±}) *

