1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 {Albin's Countergambit is certainly a speculative opening choice for Black, but it can lead to very interesting and unbalanced positions. In a way, it reminds me of the Budapest Gambit (which I discuss in part 1 ).} 3. dxe5 d4 {The main move, of course, but there are others as well.} ({After} 3... dxc4 $2 4. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {the resulting endgame is simply bad for Black. By just developing the pieces, White will not only defend his e5 pawn, but also try to capture the c4 pawn. With Black's king in the center, his task of survival is difficult.} 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3) 4. Nf3 Nc6 {I must decide whether a3 or . Both should give White a clear edge, but I need to make up my mind.} 5. Nbd2 {I think this is by far the simplest line we can play against the Albin to gain a clear and comfortable advantage without having to learn too much. The idea is to play Nb3 and attack the d4 pawn. However, we retain the idea of also developing via g3 - Bg2 .} (5. a3 {is another line that offers an advantage, but I find it a bit more complex. There have been thousands of games played and White is better, so if you are interested, feel free to explore it! However, I will stick to 5. Nbd2 which is simpler and at least as good.}) 5... Nge7 {Black should try to get the e5 -pawn back.} 6. Nb3 Ng6 7. Nbxd4 ({This is by far the simplest solution. Next, it would be best to return the extra pawn and thus gain a large positional advantage. If one prefers to keep the extra pawn,} 7. a3 $5 {(which is an alternative ) would be an interesting option.}) 7... Ngxe5 (7... Ncxe5 {is less accurate as on top of} 8. Nxe5 {which is the same as the main line, White can also play e3± with a big advantage as Ng6 is misplaced.}) 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 (8... Nxd4 $2 9. e3) 9. e3 Bc5 ({Black must develop his pieces and put pressure on White's center.} 9... Bb4+ $6 {leads only to favorable trades for White:} 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 O-O 12. Be2 {with a healthy extra pawn.}) 10. Bd2 ({I think that White should return the pawn and simplify the position. I find that} 10. Be2 {is less accurate due to} Qg5 $1 {and Black obtains some counterplay. The best move according to the engine is} 11. Kf1 {, but honestly I am not convinced if this is what White should be happy about here, despite the extra pawn.   The engine evaluates this position at approximately +0.5, but with the king in the center and a lot of pieces on the board, it looks a bit risky from a practical point of view. Meanwhile, 10. Bd2 returns the pawn and simplifies the position, transferring to a clearly better endgame.}) 10... Bxd4 {Black must take the pawn as otherwise Bc3 will be played with a big advantage.} (10... O-O 11. Bc3) 11. exd4 Qxd4 12. Bc3 Qe4+ (12... Qf4 13. Qd2 {is roughly the same as the main line as} Qe4+ {needs to be played anyway. Here, we can transpose with} 14. Qe2 {but also Be2!? is interesting.}) (12... Qxd1+ 13. Rxd1 f6 14. Bxe5 fxe5 15. Rd5 {and the e5 -pawn falls.}) 13. Qe2 Nd3+ 14. Kd2 Qxe2+ 15. Kxe2 Nf4+ 16. Kf3 Ne6 17. Rd1 {White is clearly better. The position is open and the bishop pair will give White great winning chances.} *

