1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 {Albin's Countergambit is certainly a speculative opening choice for Black, but it can lead to very interesting and unbalanced positions. In a way, it reminds me of the Budapest Gambit (which I discuss in part 1 ).} 3. dxe5 d4 {The main move, of course, but there are others as well.} ({After} 3... dxc4 $2 4. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {the resulting endgame is simply bad for Black. By just developing the pieces, White will not only defend his e5 pawn, but also try to capture the c4 pawn. With Black's king in the center, his task of survival is difficult.} 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3) 4. Nf3 Nc6 {I must decide whether a3 or . Both should give White a clear edge, but I need to make up my mind.} 5. Nbd2 {I think this is by far the simplest line we can play against the Albin to gain a clear and comfortable advantage without having to learn too much. The idea is to play Nb3 and attack the d4 pawn. However, we retain the idea of also developing via g3 - Bg2 .} (5. a3 {is another line that offers an advantage, but I find it a bit more complex. There have been thousands of games played and White is better, so if you are interested, feel free to explore it! However, I will stick to 5. Nbd2 which is simpler and at least as good.}) 5... Nge7 {Black should try to get the e5 -pawn back.} 6. Nb3 Ng6 7. a3 {Another option, which delays the inevitable capture on d4 , but also waits for Black to capture the e5 -pawn first - which enables a favorable queen trade!} Ngxe5 {Presumably, the most obvious move, but White's position is clearly better.} 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. Qxd4 {That is the reason to delay taking on d4 on move 7 - now, we get to trade queens which helps!} Qxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxc4 {Black gets the pawn back, but Black's position is difficult here.} 11. e4 Ne5 (11... Nb6 12. Nb5 $1) 12. Nb5 Kd8 {Here, White has a lot of good options.} 13. Bf4 (13. Be3 c6 14. Rd1+ Bd7 15. Nc3 {with f4 coming next.}) 13... f6 14. O-O-O+ Bd7 15. Bg3 {White will play f4 next, with a nice advantage.} *

