1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 {Albin's Countergambit is certainly a speculative opening choice for Black, but it can lead to very interesting and unbalanced positions. In a way, it reminds me of the Budapest Gambit (which I discuss in part 1 ).} 3. dxe5 d4 {The main move, of course, but there are others as well.} ({After} 3... dxc4 $2 4. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {the resulting endgame is simply bad for Black. By just developing the pieces, White will not only defend his e5 pawn, but also try to capture the c4 pawn. With Black's king in the center, his task of survival is difficult.} 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3) 4. Nf3 Nc6 {I must decide whether a3 or . Both should give White a clear edge, but I need to make up my mind.} 5. Nbd2 {I think this is by far the simplest line we can play against the Albin to gain a clear and comfortable advantage without having to learn too much. The idea is to play Nb3 and attack the d4 pawn. However, we retain the idea of also developing via g3 - Bg2 .} (5. a3 {is another line that offers an advantage, but I find it a bit more complex. There have been thousands of games played and White is better, so if you are interested, feel free to explore it! However, I will stick to 5. Nbd2 which is simpler and at least as good.}) 5... Nge7 {Black should try to get the e5 -pawn back.} 6. Nb3 Ng6 7. a3 {Another option, which delays the inevitable capture on d4 , but also waits for Black to capture the e5 -pawn first - which enables a favorable queen trade!} Be7 {Black also needs to delay capturing the pawn.} 8. Nbxd4 {It is time to capture the pawn.} Ngxe5 {This move enables Bf4 , which is a useful option.} 9. Bf4 Nxf3+ 10. Nxf3 Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 Bf6 12. Rd2 Na5 {Black must look for some counterplay.} 13. e4 ({Stronger than} 13. e3 {, as then there could be ... Bf5 ideas.}) 13... Nb3 14. Rc2 c5 15. Be2 Bg4 16. O-O {Again, Black clearly has some compensation as the d4 -square is weak, but it is not sufficient.} *

