1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 {Albin's Countergambit is certainly a speculative opening choice for Black, but it can lead to very interesting and unbalanced positions. In a way, it reminds me of the Budapest Gambit (which I discuss in part 1 ).} 3. dxe5 d4 {The main move, of course, but there are others as well.} ({After} 3... dxc4 $2 4. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {the resulting endgame is simply bad for Black. By just developing the pieces, White will not only defend his e5 pawn, but also try to capture the c4 pawn. With Black's king in the center, his task of survival is difficult.} 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3) 4. Nf3 Nc6 {I must decide whether a3 or . Both should give White a clear edge, but I need to make up my mind.} 5. Nbd2 {I think this is by far the simplest line we can play against the Albin to gain a clear and comfortable advantage without having to learn too much. The idea is to play Nb3 and attack the d4 pawn. However, we retain the idea of also developing via g3 - Bg2 .} (5. a3 {is another line that offers an advantage, but I find it a bit more complex. There have been thousands of games played and White is better, so if you are interested, feel free to explore it! However, I will stick to 5. Nbd2 which is simpler and at least as good.}) 5... Nge7 {Black should try to get the e5 -pawn back.} 6. Nb3 Ng6 7. a3 {Another option, which delays the inevitable capture on d4 , but also waits for Black to capture the e5 -pawn first - which enables a favorable queen trade!} Be7 {Black also needs to delay capturing the pawn.} 8. Nbxd4 {It is time to capture the pawn.} Ncxe5 {Black recaptures with the c6 -knight to have ... c5 as an idea.} 9. Qc2 {The best move according to the engine, simply moving away from the d-file so that in case of exchanges White does not have the king in the center. In addition, sometimes White may also consider Nf5 .} O-O 10. e3 Bf6 (10... c5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Nf5 $1 {and the Qc2 appeared useful! Next, Be2 , Bd2 etc. will be played.}) 11. Be2 {White is better for sure, but I would not write off Black completely just yet.} c5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Nf3 Nh4 14. O-O Bf5 15. e4 Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 Be6 17. Rb1 {White is better due to the extra pawn of course, but Black has some compensation.} *

