1. d4 d5 2. c4 c5 {This is a rare line. It became quite popular in mid 2010s, and Shakhriyar Mamedyarov played it many times.} 3. cxd5 {I think this is the most challenging.} Nf6 {This slightly delaying recapture is a very risky approach.} 4. e4 {This is a direct attempt at refutation.} Nxe4 5. dxc5 Qa5+ (5... Nxc5 6. Nc3) 6. Bd2 Nxd2 7. Qxd2 Qxd2+ ({Black must accept that he is down a pawn.} 7... Qxc5 8. Na3 $5 {followed by Rc1 is even worse.}) 8. Nxd2 g6 {Black's best chance, but insufficient. With the pieces undeveloped and without even attempting to regain the pawn, it is hard to think that Black can be okay here.} 9. Rc1 Bh6 10. Bb5+ Nd7 (10... Kf8 11. Ne2 $5 {Heading to c3 .} Kg7 12. Rd1) 11. c6 bxc6 12. dxc6 Nb6 13. Ngf3 O-O 14. O-O a6 15. Be2 {White is clearly better. Black's pair of bishops offer some compensation, but it cannot be ever sufficient - the c6 -pawn is really strong.} *

