1. d4 d5 2. c4 c5 {This is a rare line. It became quite popular in mid 2010s, and Shakhriyar Mamedyarov played it many times.} 3. cxd5 {I think this is the most challenging.} Qxd5 ({Black should recapture the pawn right away.} 3... cxd4 $2 4. Qxd4 {White is just up a pawn. Next, Nc3 and e4 follow with a winning position.}) 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nc3 Qa5 ({Other moves are just bad.} 5... Qd8 $2 6. Qxd4 $1 {is just terrible for Black due to the lag in development.}) 6. Nxd4 Nf6 7. a3 {This is not the most common move, and at first I thought it was simply unnecessary - why should White play a3 when there is no need? However, after taking a closer look, I realized what is going on: it is simply prophylactic, since Black's main idea here is ... e5 and ... Bb4 .   In addition, White can also play b4 . Many high-level GMs have been using this line recently. Black now has some options.} g6 {The fianchetto is one of the standard ways to complete the development in such a symmetrical pawn structure, directing the game toward a Grünfeld-like position. Black, however, is not in time to achieve the desired setup.} 8. b4 ({The queen suddenly cannot find a comfortable square. I think that either the d8 or h5 squares are the most reasonable as on b6 it runs under Be3 ideas, while Qe5 is strongly met with} 8. f4 $1) 8... Qh5 9. Ndb5 Na6 {White has many good moves, but the strongest is Bd2 .} 10. Bd2 {With the idea of e4 , intending to trade queens and recapture with the rook on d1 .} *

