{Of course, with such a strong knight and Black's bad pawn structure, White must be much better. In the game followed Nc6 Bc4 Bg7 O-O O-O and only here I would play Qf3!± an improvement over Qe2?! played by Matlakov, which allows f5 . However, with Qf3 , everything is well defended and next Rac1 and Rfd1 come in with a big advantage.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c5 {This is a rare line. It became quite popular in mid 2010s, and Shakhriyar Mamedyarov played it many times.} 3. cxd5 {I think this is the most challenging.} Qxd5 ({Black should recapture the pawn right away.} 3... cxd4 $2 4. Qxd4 {White is just up a pawn. Next, Nc3 and e4 follow with a winning position.}) 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nc3 Qa5 ({Other moves are just bad.} 5... Qd8 $2 6. Qxd4 $1 {is just terrible for Black due to the lag in development.}) 6. Nxd4 Nf6 7. a3 {This is not the most common move, and at first I thought it was simply unnecessary - why should White play a3 when there is no need? However, after taking a closer look, I realized what is going on: it is simply prophylactic, since Black's main idea here is ... e5 and ... Bb4 .   In addition, White can also play b4 . Many high-level GMs have been using this line recently. Black now has some options.} e5 {A standard way of playing as Black, but we will be able to see a benefit of having a3 : Black cannot play ... Bb4 now.} 8. Nb3 Qc7 {Here, White has a pleasant choice between Nb5!? and Bg5 .} 9. Bg5 {This is very natural, and also good.} Be6 {Played in Matlakov-Mamedyarov (2019).} 10. Bxf6 {Here too White has a big advantage.} gxf6 11. Nd5 Qd8 12. e4 *

