[White "42) Dutch: Introduction"]
[Black "Dutch Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A88"]
[PlyCount "21"]

1. d4 {Playing the Dutch Defense, Black has three possible options: the Leningrad Dutch, the Classical Dutch or the Stonewall. In general, in all cases, I recommend setups with g3 .} f5 (1... e6 {When Black begins with this move, we need to play 2.c4 to stay in our repertoire.} 2. c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 {Black can now choose between 4... Be7 , the Classical Dutch, and 4... d5 (or 4... c6 first and then ... d5 ) entering the Stonewall Variation.} d5 (4... Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. b3 $5 {This is what I recommend in the Classical Dutch - delaying Nc3 and playing b3 - Bb2 first. I think it is pretty unpleasant for Black.}) 5. Nf3 c6 6. O-O Bd6 {Here, the main lines involve the b3 - Ba3 idea, but because of ... Qe7 I don't think they are that great. Instead, I would opt for quick action on the queenside.} (6... Be7 {allows us to develop the bishop to f4 .} 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Bf4 {with an advantage.}) 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Qc2 {I think this plan is troublesome for Black.}) 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {The main line of the Leningrad Dutch. Black has a decent choice, but only 7... c6 has been played recently at the highest level.} c6 ({• After} 7... Qe8 {I recommend} 8. Re1 {and try to play e4 . In case of} Qf7 9. d5 {is my main line, but e4!? is extremely testing as well.}) ({•} 7... Nc6 8. d5 Ne5 {It seems a bit odd, but from a practical point of view perhaps it is not so bad. Black's idea is to get Nxe5 - dxe5 and then play ... e4 which, although dubious, may not be so easy for White. For this reason, I recommend} 9. Qb3 $5 {, which is way less common, but it is much simpler and also offers an advantage. Na5? b3 is just horrible for Black as the Na5 is completely out of play. Also, ... Ne4 ideas do not work for Black at all.}) ({•} 7... e6 {With this move, Black tries to avoid d5 (8. d5  e5 !). But given that Black wants to play ... e5 in the future, ... e6 could be a waste of time. Here I also recommend playing e4 . Therefore:} 8. Re1 Ne4 9. Qc2 Nxc3 10. bxc3 $1 {is very good for White.}) 8. Qc2 {I would recommend this line against 7... c6 . The idea is to play e4 if possible, but there is also an idea of Rb1 - b4 - b5 .} Na6 {This is the best reply, but I cover alternatives as well.} 9. Rb1 Qe8 ({After} 9... Nc7 10. b3 {is good, keeping an option of Ba3 if needed, to stop Black's ... e5 .}) 10. b4 Nc7 11. b5 {And White puts Black under uncomfortable pressure on the queenside.} *

