1. d4 e6 {If Black decides to play Stonewall, this is a tricky move order. We are pretty much obliged to play c4 (well, e4 is the French, which belongs to a 1. e4 repertoire!) while Nf3 is not necessarily part of our repertoire, as we play Nc3 against the Nimzo.} 2. c4 f5 {And now we reach Dutch. There are many available setups for White. My recommendation is to play g3 .} 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 d5 ({Here I only focus on Stonewall setups, but I will analyze moves like} 4... Be7 {and Bb4 in another section. Black can begin with c6 as well.}) 5. Nf3 c6 ({Black achieves a Stonewall pawn formation.} 5... Bd6 {The recent trend is to play without ... c6 , but I don't see much difference from the standard 5... c6 move order.} 6. Nc3 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Qc2 {and we are back at the main line.}) (5... Be7 {see 6... Be7 . I admit though that Black can play ... Ne4 , ... O-O in some various move orders, delay one thing or another, but we play nonetheless O-O and Nc3 which will pretty much result in a transposition.}) 6. O-O {Here, Black can develop the bishop either to d6 or e7 .} Be7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Bf4 {Now that Black's bishop is not on d6 , we can comfortably develop our bishop actively to f4 .} Ne4 {Black can try to play ... g5 but it could weaken Black’s kingside.} 9. Ne5 g5 10. Be3 {At this point, we might decide to take on e4 and try to exploit the g5 -pawn that overextends Black's pawn structure on the kingside.} Nd6 11. b3 Nd7 12. f4 {White's position is better. Our Ne5 is very strong and it is not so easy to deal with it. If Black decides to trade, dxe5 will release a lot of pressure in the center. With f4 we surely weakened the e4 -square too, but the difference is that we may simply trade and retain a powerful Ne5 .} *

