{I think it is very simple and better for White. For example: Nd7 Ne2 g5 Nc1 Qe7 Nd3⩲} 1. d4 e6 {If Black decides to play Stonewall, this is a tricky move order. We are pretty much obliged to play c4 (well, e4 is the French, which belongs to a 1. e4 repertoire!) while Nf3 is not necessarily part of our repertoire, as we play Nc3 against the Nimzo.} 2. c4 f5 {And now we reach Dutch. There are many available setups for White. My recommendation is to play g3 .} 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 d5 ({Here I only focus on Stonewall setups, but I will analyze moves like} 4... Be7 {and Bb4 in another section. Black can begin with c6 as well.}) 5. Nf3 c6 ({Black achieves a Stonewall pawn formation.} 5... Bd6 {The recent trend is to play without ... c6 , but I don't see much difference from the standard 5... c6 move order.} 6. Nc3 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Qc2 {and we are back at the main line.}) (5... Be7 {see 6... Be7 . I admit though that Black can play ... Ne4 , ... O-O in some various move orders, delay one thing or another, but we play nonetheless O-O and Nc3 which will pretty much result in a transposition.}) 6. O-O {Here, Black can develop the bishop either to d6 or e7 .} Bd6 {This looks a bit more active than 6... Be7 .} 7. Nc3 ({I do not recommend} 7. b3 {as Black plays} Qe7 {and to play Ba3 , we need to spend some time ( a4 - Ba3 for instance) but this not only seems like a waste of time, but it also weakens the b4 -square.}) 7... O-O 8. Qc2 {I recommend this configuration for White against the Stonewall. It can be reached by many move orders, making it very flexible and universal. White's idea is to play Rb1 , followed by b4 and b5 , and open the queenside. We can keep the idea of Bf4 for the future as well.} Qe7 {Black anticipates Rb1 - b4 idea and blocks it right away, making a useful move and keeping ideas of ... Ne4 , ... Bd7 or ... Nbd7 for later.} 9. Bg5 {This looks the strongest. Now, White's positional threat of e3 ! (with idea Bf4 and recapturing with the e-pawn) makes 9... h6 necessary.} ({After Qe8 I recommend} 9. c5 {and White is better due to the awkward placement of the queen. Here, however, it does not work that well. c5} Bc7 10. Bf4 Bxf4 11. gxf4 Bd7 $1 {the bishop has a path out now and Black should be on time with generating some counterplay (... Kh8 , ... Rg8 and preparing ... g5 ).}) 9... h6 ({Other moves are much worse. Now, White has some choice: Be3 or Bxf6 .} 9... Nbd7 10. cxd5) (9... Bd7 10. e3 h6 11. Bf4) 10. Bxf6 {Perhaps it is a bit surprising to give away the bishop pair, but I find it the easiest.} (10. Be3 {Is the main move of the engine. It looks a little strange to me, at least at first glance, but if the engine likes it, it must be good. However, I think taking on f6 is easier.}) 10... Qxf6 (10... Rxf6 $2 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nxd5 $1) 11. e3 {In fact, we made Black lose time with the queen and exchanged the knight that often goes to e4 . Now White has a very simple plan: Ne2 - Nf4 ( c1 )- Nd3 and occupy the e5 -square. In addition, we can continue with b4 - b5 on the queenside.} *

