1. d4 e6 {If Black decides to play Stonewall, this is a tricky move order. We are pretty much obliged to play c4 (well, e4 is the French, which belongs to a 1. e4 repertoire!) while Nf3 is not necessarily part of our repertoire, as we play Nc3 against the Nimzo.} 2. c4 f5 {And now we reach Dutch. There are many available setups for White. My recommendation is to play g3 .} 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 d5 ({Here I only focus on Stonewall setups, but I will analyze moves like} 4... Be7 {and Bb4 in another section. Black can begin with c6 as well.}) 5. Nf3 c6 ({Black achieves a Stonewall pawn formation.} 5... Bd6 {The recent trend is to play without ... c6 , but I don't see much difference from the standard 5... c6 move order.} 6. Nc3 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Qc2 {and we are back at the main line.}) (5... Be7 {see 6... Be7 . I admit though that Black can play ... Ne4 , ... O-O in some various move orders, delay one thing or another, but we play nonetheless O-O and Nc3 which will pretty much result in a transposition.}) 6. O-O {Here, Black can develop the bishop either to d6 or e7 .} Bd6 {This looks a bit more active than 6... Be7 .} 7. Nc3 ({I do not recommend} 7. b3 {as Black plays} Qe7 {and to play Ba3 , we need to spend some time ( a4 - Ba3 for instance) but this not only seems like a waste of time, but it also weakens the b4 -square.}) 7... O-O 8. Qc2 {I recommend this configuration for White against the Stonewall. It can be reached by many move orders, making it very flexible and universal. White's idea is to play Rb1 , followed by b4 and b5 , and open the queenside. We can keep the idea of Bf4 for the future as well.} Bd7 {This is a standard idea in many Stonewall structures - Black tries to improve a terrible light-squared bishop. I found a very interesting and new idea here for White.} 9. Na4 {Potentially we may play Nc5 , but this is not the main idea. The point of Na4 is to bring the knight to d3 ! Such an idea is possible after 8... Bd7 as Black cannot play ... Nbd7 quickly enough to play ... e5 , which means we are on time with our maneuver.} Be8 ({•} 9... Ne4 10. c5 Bc7 11. b4 {intending the Nb2 - d3 maneuver.}) ({•} 9... Qe7 10. c5 Bc7 11. b4 {with the same idea.}) 10. b4 {Preparing Nc5 , but also Nb2 - Nd3 maneuver.} ({After Nbd7} 10. Nc5 {is quite unpleasant for Black. Nxc5 bxc5}) 10... Qe7 11. c5 Bc7 12. Nb2 {Just in time, before Black successfully plays ... e5 .} Nbd7 13. Nd3 {With control over the e5 -square. If Black plays ... e5 he must concede the dark-squared bishop which is not ideal. And otherwise, Bf4 may be played, cementing control over the e5 -square.} *

