1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O d6 {This is the initial position of the Classical Dutch.} 7. b3 {I would recommend delaying Nc3 . Since Black intends ... Ne4 , I think it makes sense to initially develop the bishop to b2 and only then play Nc3 , Nbd2 or even Nfd2 to counter Ne4 . White's plan here is very simple: Bb2 , Nc3 or Nbd2 , Qc2 and prepare e4 . We can try to play on the queenside as well, but that is a rather secondary plan. Black should generally play ... Ne4 sooner or later, but there are other possible plans as well.} ({After} 7. Nc3 Ne4 {we risk messing up our pawn structure on the queenside and if we play} 8. Nxe4 fxe4 9. Nd2 d5 {things get complicated in the center, and I am not convinced we are ready for that.}) 7... Qe8 {Black can try to bring the queen to the kingside and try to use it for some attack. However, I don't really see it happening.} 8. Bb2 Qg6 {This move was tried in some games by GM Amin Bassem. The idea is to help control the e4 -square and ideally play ... Ne4 , followed by quick ... Nd7 and ... Ndf6 .} 9. Nc3 Nbd7 (9... Ne4 {seems a bit premature, as we can even take on e4 , or just use the Ne1 idea as after 9... Nbd7 .} 10. Ne1 $5) 10. Qc2 Ne4 11. Rad1 Ndf6 {Black has achieved his goal and appears to be in full control of the e4 square. In reality, however, this is not quite the case.} 12. Ne1 {Black's Ne4 is not really stable. The idea is Nd3 ; once our knight gets there, the threat will be Nf4 and Black will lose control over the e4 -square.} *

