{And if Bd7 trying to support the c6 -pawn, then Rb3± leaves Black in big trouble.} 1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {In the Leningrad Dutch I would choose the more classical line, where I think Black struggles even though he has many possible plans.} Qe8 {The old move. Black intends to play ... e5 . Here we can play 8. d5 , but I don't like it very much.} 8. Re1 {Instead, I would recommend this move, trying to play e4 . In this way, when Black plays ... e5 we can react with e4 and put pressure on the center.} Qf7 ({The main move, targeting the c4 -pawn. If White spends time to defend this pawn (e.g. b3 ) then} 8... Ne4 {can be played and White cannot trade on e4 as the f2 -pawn would be weak. I would recommend 9. d5 , which in my opinion is the objectively strongest move, but alternatively I can also show 9. e4 !?.}) (8... e5 9. e4 $1 {looks great for White.} fxe4 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Ng5 Nc6 12. Be3) 9. d5 {The simplest solution. With the queen on f7 White has the strong threat of Ng5 and retains the e4 idea for later.} h6 10. Nd4 {Looks great for White. Some ideas involve using Ne6 , but we must not forget to also prepare e4 at some point.} c6 (10... a5 11. Bd2 Na6 12. Ne6 $1 {works greatly for White.} Bxe6 13. dxe6 Qxe6 14. Bxb7 Ra7 15. Bg2) 11. a4 a5 12. Ra3 {Taking advantage of the pressure on the long diagonal, we can even weaken the c5 -square in such a way that Black cannot develop Nb8 .} *

