1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {In the Leningrad Dutch I would choose the more classical line, where I think Black struggles even though he has many possible plans.} Nc6 {Just like after 7... Qe8 , Black intends to play ... e5 . But now the knight gets attacked.} 8. d5 ({Black can play either} 8. Ne5 {or} Na5 {.}) 8... Na5 {This is another move, but I find it just bad for Black.} 9. b3 {This is the problem for Black. The Na5 is misplaced and all the tactics along the long diagonal work for White.} Ne4 {Perhaps the only justification behind 8...Na5 , trying to take advantage of weakened diagonal. But it does not work.} 10. Nxe4 Bxa1 11. Neg5 {White's pieces are way too active and the Na5 is completely out of play.} h6 (11... c5 {is met by} 12. e4 $1 fxe4 13. Nh4 {.}) 12. Ne6 Bxe6 13. dxe6 Bg7 14. e4 {Black collapses on the light squares.} *

