1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {In the Leningrad Dutch I would choose the more classical line, where I think Black struggles even though he has many possible plans.} Nc6 {Just like after 7... Qe8 , Black intends to play ... e5 . But now the knight gets attacked.} 8. d5 ({Black can play either} 8. Ne5 {or} Na5 {.}) 8... Ne5 {This is the old main line of the Leningrad Dutch. It seems odd from a strategic point of view since White can simply take e5 and get a better pawn structure, but things are not entirely trivial. In his course, Sam Shankland argues that although 9. Nxe5 is probably the strongest, it may not be so easy to learn and recommends 9. Qb3 . I completely agree with him, and for that reason 9. Qb3 is also my recommendation.} 9. Qb3 Nxf3+ 10. exf3 {It is important to recapture with the pawn and open the e-file. If White is on time with f4 , Re1 etc., Black's position will be strategically lost. Because of this Black must play ... e5 , but it does not offer equality either.} e5 11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Rd1 {I would begin with this useful move. We may want to take on b7 in the next move. And if Black defends it he may be in even bigger trouble.} (12. Qxb7 Bxc4 13. Rd1 {is recommended by Sam Shankland and it is simply better for White too - White will attack the hanging c and d pawns soon. The plan is Be3 , Rac1 and f4 at some point.}) 12... Rb8 (12... b6 13. f4 Rb8 14. Nb5 {When Nxa7 is threatened, together with Nd4 , exploiting the weakness of Black's light squares.}) 13. Be3 b6 14. Rac1 {With a clear advantage for White.} *

