1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {In the Leningrad Dutch I would choose the more classical line, where I think Black struggles even though he has many possible plans.} Nc6 {Just like after 7... Qe8 , Black intends to play ... e5 . But now the knight gets attacked.} 8. d5 ({Black can play either} 8. Ne5 {or} Na5 {.}) 8... Ne5 {This is the old main line of the Leningrad Dutch. It seems odd from a strategic point of view since White can simply take e5 and get a better pawn structure, but things are not entirely trivial. In his course, Sam Shankland argues that although 9. Nxe5 is probably the strongest, it may not be so easy to learn and recommends 9. Qb3 . I completely agree with him, and for that reason 9. Qb3 is also my recommendation.} 9. Qb3 Nfd7 {Probably the best move, bringing the knight to c5 and keeping Ne5 active.} 10. Be3 {Following Sam's recommendation. Black has here some choice.} Nxf3+ ({An alternative that deserves attention that Sam does not mention. The idea is to meet exf3 with} 10... f4 $5 {, a positional exchange sacrifice.}) 11. exf3 f4 12. Bxf4 Nc5 13. Qa3 {The best square for the queen, keeping the rooks connected and not wasting time on running away.} Rxf4 14. gxf4 Nd3 ({After} 14... Bf5 15. Ne4 {Black's initiative is pretty much done.}) 15. Ne2 Bf5 16. Rab1 {We keep everything guarded and we will push back Black's pieces very soon thanks to moves like Rfd1 , or even Bh3 .} *

