1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {In the Leningrad Dutch I would choose the more classical line, where I think Black struggles even though he has many possible plans.} e6 {This relatively rare move prevents ideas connected with d5 . However, as White, we are mostly interested in playing e4 here.} 8. Re1 Ne4 9. Qc2 {Challenging the knight.} Nxc3 (9... d5 10. Bf4 {looks like a dream Stonewall.}) 10. bxc3 {Much stronger than recapturing with the queen. Now, e4 is pretty much unstoppable.} Nc6 (10... e5 11. e4 {is roughly the same.}) 11. e4 fxe4 ({After} 11... e5 {we can play} 12. exf5 $1 Bxf5 13. Qb3 $1 {and Black faces problems on the b7 -pawn and with c5 discovery.}) 12. Qxe4 e5 13. Bg5 Qe8 (13... Qd7 14. Qe3) 14. Qh4 {With a big advantage.} *

