1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {In the Leningrad Dutch I would choose the more classical line, where I think Black struggles even though he has many possible plans.} c6 {The only move played in the last few games at the highest level. Everything else has gone out of fashion and most likely for good reason.} 8. Qc2 {I like this line for White. There are two main ideas: trying to play e4 , or Rb1 followed by b4 - b5 , challenging Black on the queenside.} ({Sam Shankland recommends} 8. d5 {, and it is also a decent option, but I disagree with one thing he says in the next line:} e5 $1 9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. b3 Na6 11. Ng5 Qe7 $1 12. Nxe6 Qxe6 13. Bb2 {where he argues that White is better because of the bishop pair and the subsequent Qc2 - Rad1 .   On the one hand, sure, it is nice, but I've played it myself as Black (Hort-Swiercz in 2012), and I'm not sure what White's plan is specifically, especially when Black installs the knight on e4 , potentially trying ... h5 -... h4 !?. Certainly, some strategic elements are clearly in White's favor, but I would not underestimate Black's counterplay.}) 8... Qc7 {Black prepares ... e5 but White is just faster to play e4 .} 9. e4 fxe4 (9... e5 {is met by} 10. c5 $1 {which is a standard idea in similar positions. Black's center crumbles.}) 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 (10... Bf5 11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. Qe2) 11. Qxe4 Bf5 12. Qh4 {White's ideas involve Bh6 , Ng5 , Re1 in various move orders.} e5 {An alternative to ... Nd7 which does not solve Black's problems.} 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Rd1 Na6 (14... Nd7 $2 {suddenly loses to} 15. g4 $1 {and the bishop is trapped as} Be6 {is met with} 16. Ng5 $1) 15. Be3 {With a strong initiative.} *

