1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {In the Leningrad Dutch I would choose the more classical line, where I think Black struggles even though he has many possible plans.} c6 {The only move played in the last few games at the highest level. Everything else has gone out of fashion and most likely for good reason.} 8. Qc2 {I like this line for White. There are two main ideas: trying to play e4 , or Rb1 followed by b4 - b5 , challenging Black on the queenside.} ({Sam Shankland recommends} 8. d5 {, and it is also a decent option, but I disagree with one thing he says in the next line:} e5 $1 9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. b3 Na6 11. Ng5 Qe7 $1 12. Nxe6 Qxe6 13. Bb2 {where he argues that White is better because of the bishop pair and the subsequent Qc2 - Rad1 .   On the one hand, sure, it is nice, but I've played it myself as Black (Hort-Swiercz in 2012), and I'm not sure what White's plan is specifically, especially when Black installs the knight on e4 , potentially trying ... h5 -... h4 !?. Certainly, some strategic elements are clearly in White's favor, but I would not underestimate Black's counterplay.}) 8... a5 {With this move Black makes sure that b4 - b5 will not happen. Additionally, in the event of White playing d5 , Black will control the c5 -square. Temporarily, it appears that 9. e4 does not work that well, but we can prepare it.} 9. Re1 {Preparing e4 .} ({It is unfortunate that} 9. e4 {is not that great due to the surprising} e5 $1 {, and unfortunately I could not find here anything special for White. The best try is perhaps} 10. exf5 (10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nxe5 fxe4 $1 {is unclear as well.}) 10... Bxf5 11. Qb3 {and it all looks nice for White if not for} Nbd7 $1 {and according to the engine Black is doing OK. The critical line is perhaps} 12. Qxb7 Rc8 13. Qb3 e4 $1 14. Nh4 Be6 $1 {where Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn:} 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Bxd4 17. Bh6 Re8) 9... Na6 10. Bg5 {A somewhat unusual move. It may seem that normally White does not give away the bishop pair, yet ... a5 may be simply a waste of time (and weakening of Black's position) if we manage to play e4 quickly.} Qc7 {Black can try to play ... e5 but again White is faster.} 11. e4 fxe4 (11... e5 {is as usually met by} 12. c5 $1 {with unpleasant pressure in the center.} dxc5 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. dxe5 Bg7 (14... Bxe5 $2 {runs into} 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Qb3+ {and White wins a piece.}) 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Ne4) 12. Nxe4 Bf5 13. Bxf6 {Giving away the bishop pair, but it does not matter much.} exf6 14. Qd2 {Thanks to the control over the center and more active pieces, White is better.} *

