1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {In the Leningrad Dutch I would choose the more classical line, where I think Black struggles even though he has many possible plans.} c6 {The only move played in the last few games at the highest level. Everything else has gone out of fashion and most likely for good reason.} 8. Qc2 {I like this line for White. There are two main ideas: trying to play e4 , or Rb1 followed by b4 - b5 , challenging Black on the queenside.} ({Sam Shankland recommends} 8. d5 {, and it is also a decent option, but I disagree with one thing he says in the next line:} e5 $1 9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. b3 Na6 11. Ng5 Qe7 $1 12. Nxe6 Qxe6 13. Bb2 {where he argues that White is better because of the bishop pair and the subsequent Qc2 - Rad1 .   On the one hand, sure, it is nice, but I've played it myself as Black (Hort-Swiercz in 2012), and I'm not sure what White's plan is specifically, especially when Black installs the knight on e4 , potentially trying ... h5 -... h4 !?. Certainly, some strategic elements are clearly in White's favor, but I would not underestimate Black's counterplay.}) 8... Na6 {The best response by Black. Everything else seems uncomfortable to say the least.} 9. Rb1 ({Black is ready to meet} 9. e4 {with} Nb4 $1 (9... e5 $5 {∞ is fine too.}) 10. Qb3 fxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxb4 Bg4 {with a double-edged position.}) 9... Nc7 {This is a decent alternative. It appears that even though White can play with b4 , in this particular version it is perhaps not that great.} 10. b3 {The issue with ... Nc7 is that it is simply more passive there than it was on a6 . It does not control the b4 or c5 squares. Black's plans with ... e5 are now not really existent either, as White always has ideas of Ba3 that kill ... e5 altogether. As White, apart from the Ba3 idea, we want to play positionally: Bb2 , e3 , Ne2 , Nf4 is a recurring theme in this line.} (10. b4 {is met by} Be6 $1 {and we have some issues with the c4 -pawn.}) 10... Kh8 {Black prepares ... Be6 , making space for the bishop on g8 in case of Ng5 .} 11. Bb2 Be6 12. e3 {With simple positional play, White has a very promising position. We keep ideas of both e4 and b4 - b5 for the future. The most important is that Black cannot use the ... e5 pawn break.} *

