 Bb2 ({This seems quite easy to play for White, but} 14. Qd3 {is very interesting and challenging as well. I would highly recommend that you familiarize yourself with both ways of playing this position.}) 14... Kh8 {A kind of waiting move, but also a waste of time in this case.} 15. Qd3 {Now this is even stronger than the immediate 14. Qd3 .} e5 (15... b6 16. d5) 16. dxe5 dxe5 17. e4 {Again this move. With Kh8 on the board Black can win an exchange now but in fact it is irrelevant.} (17. Qd6 e4 18. Ne5 Be6 19. Rfc1 {is also clearly better.}) 17... fxe4 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. Qxe4 Bf5 20. Qxb7 Bxb1 21. Rxb1 {With such a strong bishop pair, the weak e5 -pawn, and such a pawn majority on the queenside White is clearly better.} *

