1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {In the Leningrad Dutch I would choose the more classical line, where I think Black struggles even though he has many possible plans.} c6 {The only move played in the last few games at the highest level. Everything else has gone out of fashion and most likely for good reason.} 8. Qc2 {I like this line for White. There are two main ideas: trying to play e4 , or Rb1 followed by b4 - b5 , challenging Black on the queenside.} ({Sam Shankland recommends} 8. d5 {, and it is also a decent option, but I disagree with one thing he says in the next line:} e5 $1 9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. b3 Na6 11. Ng5 Qe7 $1 12. Nxe6 Qxe6 13. Bb2 {where he argues that White is better because of the bishop pair and the subsequent Qc2 - Rad1 .   On the one hand, sure, it is nice, but I've played it myself as Black (Hort-Swiercz in 2012), and I'm not sure what White's plan is specifically, especially when Black installs the knight on e4 , potentially trying ... h5 -... h4 !?. Certainly, some strategic elements are clearly in White's favor, but I would not underestimate Black's counterplay.}) 8... Na6 {The best response by Black. Everything else seems uncomfortable to say the least.} 9. Rb1 ({Black is ready to meet} 9. e4 {with} Nb4 $1 (9... e5 $5 {∞ is fine too.}) 10. Qb3 fxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxb4 Bg4 {with a double-edged position.}) 9... Qe8 {This typical idea for Black, preparing ... e5 is the most logical move for Black.} ({•} 9... Qc7 $6 {works less good than 9... Qe8 as it takes away the c7 -square from the knight.} 10. b4) ({•} 9... Qa5 10. a3) 10. b4 {We continue with our plan.} Nc7 {Black needs to go away from the b5 tempo.} 11. b5 cxb5 {Necessary, as Black should not allow White to take on c6 .} (11... Be6 $6 {is worse as White can open b-file with big advantage.} 12. bxc6 bxc6 13. Nd2) 12. cxb5 {This position looks better for White. After removing the c6 -pawn, our Bg2 is pretty strong on the long diagonal.} Bd7 13. a4 Rc8 14. Bb2 ({This seems quite easy to play for White, but} 14. Qd3 {is very interesting and challenging as well. I would highly recommend that you familiarize yourself with both ways of playing this position.}) 14... b6 {Black perhaps should guard the b7 -pawn in advance, stabilizing the queenside. However, it has a certain drawback too - now, the c6 -square becomes an outpost.} (14... Be6 {runs into} 15. Ng5 $1 {±}) 15. Qd2 {The strongest move according to the engine. We are stepping aside from the c-file, we prepare d5 - Nd4 idea and we avoid ... e5 (which would happen after 15. Qd3 ).} (15. Qd3 {is less precise due to} e5 $1 16. dxe5 dxe5 {and I don't see a way to stop ... e4 . If we play} 17. e4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 fxe4 19. Qxe4 Bf5 {then we don't win the b7 -pawn, as we did in the case of 14... Kh8 .}) 15... h6 {Black needs to play this move to play ... Qf7 without running into Ng5 .} ({• We don't mind} 15... Ne4 16. Nxe4 fxe4 17. Nh4 d5 18. f3 {where we undermine Black's center with an advantage.}) ({•} 15... e5 $2 {does not work now due to} 16. dxe5 dxe5 17. Ba3 $1 {+- and ... e4 does not come with a tempo. And if} Rf7 {then} 18. Ng5 {wins an exchange.}) 16. d5 Qf7 {Black needs to put pressure on the d4 -pawn as otherwise Nd4 - Nc6 would occur.} 17. Nd4 {Possible too, but it is quite double-edged. We bring our knight to c6 , but we also sac a pawn.} Ncxd5 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. Nc6 Bxc6 20. bxc6 Nc7 {White has clearly very good compensation, but I find Black's position solid and possibly tough to break. Still, with such a strong c6 -pawn, we are not really at risk.} 21. Bxg7 (21. Ba3 $5 {is an interesting alternative.}) 21... Qxg7 22. Rfe1 {This is probably the way to go, with an idea e4 , but also a5 !? might be useful one day.} *

