1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {In the Leningrad Dutch I would choose the more classical line, where I think Black struggles even though he has many possible plans.} c6 {The only move played in the last few games at the highest level. Everything else has gone out of fashion and most likely for good reason.} 8. Qc2 {I like this line for White. There are two main ideas: trying to play e4 , or Rb1 followed by b4 - b5 , challenging Black on the queenside.} ({Sam Shankland recommends} 8. d5 {, and it is also a decent option, but I disagree with one thing he says in the next line:} e5 $1 9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. b3 Na6 11. Ng5 Qe7 $1 12. Nxe6 Qxe6 13. Bb2 {where he argues that White is better because of the bishop pair and the subsequent Qc2 - Rad1 .   On the one hand, sure, it is nice, but I've played it myself as Black (Hort-Swiercz in 2012), and I'm not sure what White's plan is specifically, especially when Black installs the knight on e4 , potentially trying ... h5 -... h4 !?. Certainly, some strategic elements are clearly in White's favor, but I would not underestimate Black's counterplay.}) 8... Na6 {The best response by Black. Everything else seems uncomfortable to say the least.} 9. Rb1 ({Black is ready to meet} 9. e4 {with} Nb4 $1 (9... e5 $5 {∞ is fine too.}) 10. Qb3 fxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxb4 Bg4 {with a double-edged position.}) 9... Qe8 {This typical idea for Black, preparing ... e5 is the most logical move for Black.} ({•} 9... Qc7 $6 {works less good than 9... Qe8 as it takes away the c7 -square from the knight.} 10. b4) ({•} 9... Qa5 10. a3) 10. b4 {We continue with our plan.} Nc7 {Black needs to go away from the b5 tempo.} 11. b5 cxb5 {Necessary, as Black should not allow White to take on c6 .} (11... Be6 $6 {is worse as White can open b-file with big advantage.} 12. bxc6 bxc6 13. Nd2) 12. cxb5 {This position looks better for White. After removing the c6 -pawn, our Bg2 is pretty strong on the long diagonal.} Bd7 13. a4 Rc8 14. Qd3 {This is a good alternative which also pushes Black to the limit.} e5 {This is the most critical. After everything else White enjoys a nice advantage, while here things get sharp.} 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Nxe5 {Of course, we cannot allow Black to play ... e4 .} Qxe5 17. Bf4 Qc5 18. Bd6 ({Continuing direct and dynamic play.} 18. Bxb7 Ne6 19. Bxc8 Nxf4 20. gxf4 Bxc8 {looks unclear.}) 18... Qb6 19. a5 Qxa5 20. b6 {If after such an assault by Black, in which we 'blitz' our moves, our opponent keeps calm and plays the better move, we can still count on an advantage.} Ne6 21. Bb4 Nc5 ({Another only move.} 21... Qe5 22. bxa7) 22. Bxa5 (22. Qc4+ Be6 23. Qxe6+ Nxe6 24. Bxa5 axb6 25. Bb4 {also looks a bit better.}) 22... Nxd3 23. bxa7 Nc5 24. Rfd1 {White here is playing for a win, despite being down a piece. The a7 -pawn is very far advanced, the pressure on the b7 -pawn is serious, and Black needs to be very careful.} ({With perfect play Black can probably get a 4 vs 3 rook endgame (see the clickable line) but even there, White retains some chances due to Black's not ideal pawn structure on the queenside.} 24. Bc6 Bxc6 {Rxc6} 25. Bd8 {Rc8 Bxf6 Bxf6} Nd5 {Ra8} 26. Rb5 Ne6 27. Rxb7 Bd4 {Ne7+ Kh8 Nc6 Nd8 Nxd8 Rfxd8} 28. Kg2 Bxa7 {Rxd8+ Rxd8} 29. Rxa7 {Of course, with correct defense it is a draw, but due to the f5 -pawn we might try h3 - g4 or bring our king closer to the f4 - g5 squares.}) ({Another possible line is Rfe8} 24. Nb5 Ra8 25. Nc7 Rxa7 26. Bb6 Rc8 27. Nd5 Raa8 28. Bxc5 Rxc5 29. Nxf6+ Bxf6 {Rxd7⩲}) *

