1. d4 {In this introduction, I will show what I recommend in some miscellaneous lines.} d6 {This move order allows White to immediately take control of the center with e4 . This definitely seems the right way, although Black can play 2... Nf6 , which unfortunately does not allow us to build a center with c4 and transpose to the Pirc or the Philidor. However, I think we should not fear these openings and I think my recommendations are quite convincing! Therefore: 2. e4 !} (1... e6 2. c4 {here with ... f5 we can reach the Dutch. But there are other moves I haven't covered yet. •} Bb4+ {The Keres Defense is similar to the Nimzo and the Bogo-Indian. I would recommend} 3. Bd2 {, which I think is the simplest. Here, I cover all the moves like} Bxd2+ {, a5 , c5 or Qe7 but in general, due to the knight still on g8 , we can play e4 quite often. • b6 The English Defense allows White to quickly build a center, but Black can attack it in truly hypermodern style. e4 Bb7 Bd3 Bb4+ is not as great due to Kf1! and White comfortably holds the center.}) ({Bb4+ This is a new trend and probably the best move. Nd2!? is an interesting alternative, recently tried by Vincent Keymer. Bd2 Bxd2+ Qxd2} 1... d5 {Black immediately strikes in the center. But by guarding it with Bd3 we retain an advantage, as I show in the course.}) 2. e4 {Don't worry about having to study too many lines: my suggestions are relatively easy to learn, and we have an edge almost everywhere because of the space advantage.} Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 (3... g6 4. Be3 Bg7 5. Qd2 {I recommend this line against the Pirc. It is aggressive, and we have a clear plan of attacking on the kingside.}) ({After} 3... Nbd7 {we can transpose with} 4. Nf3 {, or try the even stronger f4!}) 4. Nf3 Nbd7 {The Classical Philidor.} (4... exd4 5. Nxd4 {is possible too.} g6 {is similar to the Pirc, and we go for the same plan.} 6. Be3 Bg7 7. Qd2 O-O 8. O-O-O {There is no need to waste time for f3 as ... Ng4 is not dangerous due to Bg5 or Bf4 .}) (4... Be7 5. Bf4 $5 {is the most recent trend in this line. White intends Qd2 , O-O-O and Bf4 is actively positioned against Black's ideas of ... d5 . There are a few things to remember, but in general Black is in trouble. The main line follows after} O-O 6. Qd2 d5 {and now Ndb5! is an issue for Black. We can see the benefit of having a bishop on f4 !}) 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 {I recommend this classical approach against the Philidor. I don't think Black equalizes, and White generally plays natural moves, while Black struggles because of a lack of space.} *

