1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+ {The Keres Defense can be considered a variant of the Nimzo or Bogo Indian. Before developing the Ng8 , Black quickly brings out the bishop, perhaps intending to make ... f5 in the future. But it is still worse than the standard Nimzo, since now White is not pinned.} 3. Bd2 ({An alternative is} 3. Nd2 {which is also good, but} Bxd2+ {is the simplest to learn in my opinion. Of course, White does not play Nc3 as there are better options than transposing back to the Nimzo!}) 3... a5 4. a3 {This would be my recommendation. Essentially, we are getting the same position as after 3...Bxd2  with the inclusion of a3 -... a5 , which does not change much.} ({Instead,} 4. e4 d5 $1 {is not that clear.}) 4... Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 Nf6 6. Nc3 {With the idea of e4 . Black should prevent it.} d5 7. e3 O-O {Now we go again for a Carlsbad with Bd3 - Nge2 setup.} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bd3 {For more details on this, please look at the 3...Bxd2 line, as the inclusion of a3 and ... a5 does not change much.} *

