1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+ {The Keres Defense can be considered a variant of the Nimzo or Bogo Indian. Before developing the Ng8 , Black quickly brings out the bishop, perhaps intending to make ... f5 in the future. But it is still worse than the standard Nimzo, since now White is not pinned.} 3. Bd2 ({An alternative is} 3. Nd2 {which is also good, but} Bxd2+ {is the simplest to learn in my opinion. Of course, White does not play Nc3 as there are better options than transposing back to the Nimzo!}) 3... a5 4. a3 {This would be my recommendation. Essentially, we are getting the same position as after 3...Bxd2  with the inclusion of a3 -... a5 , which does not change much.} ({Instead,} 4. e4 d5 $1 {is not that clear.}) 4... Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 f5 {Here White can play with g3 again, like after 3...Bxd2 , but there is also another plan.} 6. Nc3 ({Or} 6. g3 Nf6 7. Bg2 O-O 8. Nc3 d6 9. Nf3 {with a position similar to the 3...Bxd2 line.}) 6... Nf6 7. e3 {Followed by Bd3 - Nge2 and f3 , it is also an interesting setup for White. For example:} O-O 8. Bd3 d6 9. Nge2 e5 10. f3 {With this setup, Black can never really push ... e4 .} Nc6 11. Bc2 Ne7 12. O-O-O {With potential play on the kingside.} *

