1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+ {The Keres Defense can be considered a variant of the Nimzo or Bogo Indian. Before developing the Ng8 , Black quickly brings out the bishop, perhaps intending to make ... f5 in the future. But it is still worse than the standard Nimzo, since now White is not pinned.} 3. Bd2 ({An alternative is} 3. Nd2 {which is also good, but} Bxd2+ {is the simplest to learn in my opinion. Of course, White does not play Nc3 as there are better options than transposing back to the Nimzo!}) 3... Qe7 {A standard Bogo Indian move. With the inclusion of Nf3 - Nf6 , this would be a normal setup for Black but now White has an option of playing e4 right away.} 4. e4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nf6 {Attacking White's center in this way does not cause any problems.} 6. Bd3 e5 {When this move is played without ... d6 earlier, this gives White an option to transfer into the Maroczy bind pawn structure.} 7. dxe5 (7. d5 {is playable as well.}) 7... Nxe5 8. Nxe5 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 Qxe5 10. O-O O-O 11. Nc3 d6 12. h3 {White is better thanks to the space advantage. There are many setups available. You can play positionally Rad1 , Rfe1 , and b3 , making sure to restrict Black's play. But I would be in favor of more aggressive ideas connected with Rae1 , f4 , maybe Nd5 in a good moment and try to make use of the strong center to develop the initiative on the kingside one day.} *

