1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+ {The Keres Defense can be considered a variant of the Nimzo or Bogo Indian. Before developing the Ng8 , Black quickly brings out the bishop, perhaps intending to make ... f5 in the future. But it is still worse than the standard Nimzo, since now White is not pinned.} 3. Bd2 ({An alternative is} 3. Nd2 {which is also good, but} Bxd2+ {is the simplest to learn in my opinion. Of course, White does not play Nc3 as there are better options than transposing back to the Nimzo!}) 3... Qe7 {A standard Bogo Indian move. With the inclusion of Nf3 - Nf6 , this would be a normal setup for Black but now White has an option of playing e4 right away.} 4. e4 d5 ({Black needs to hit the center right away.} 4... Nf6 $6 5. Bd3 {White should play this move first to prepare e5 .}) 5. e5 Nc6 6. Nf3 {White needs to seize the center when given a chance. This position looks amazing. Only someone really well-prepared could willingly go for it as Black, as there is only one path to avoid a really bad position.} dxc4 {Black must play this move. The point is that now the d4 -pawn may be somewhat weak, especially as Black has the ... Nh6 -... Nf5 ! idea.} 7. Bxc4 Bxd2+ 8. Nbxd2 (8. Qxd2 Qb4 $1 {is nothing special.}) 8... Nh6 {Black has some counterplay against the d4 -pawn. But White retains decent chances:} 9. Qe2 {Bringing the queen to e4 to secure the d4 -pawn.} Nf5 10. Qe4 Na5 {A tough engine move. Who would place the knight on the rim just like that when you can play 10... Bd7 followed by ... O-O-O ?!} 11. Bd3 {Keeping an eye on Nf5 .} Bd7 12. Qf4 O-O-O (12... Nc6 13. O-O Nb4 14. Be4 $1 {is also far away from equality.}) 13. O-O {I think this looks promising for White. Now that Black castled queenside, there are ideas of Nb3 !? to open the a-file! Additionally, the pressure on Nf5 can be a bit unpleasant.} *

