1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+ {The Keres Defense can be considered a variant of the Nimzo or Bogo Indian. Before developing the Ng8 , Black quickly brings out the bishop, perhaps intending to make ... f5 in the future. But it is still worse than the standard Nimzo, since now White is not pinned.} 3. Bd2 ({An alternative is} 3. Nd2 {which is also good, but} Bxd2+ {is the simplest to learn in my opinion. Of course, White does not play Nc3 as there are better options than transposing back to the Nimzo!}) 3... c5 {Without a knight on f6 , White again can play via e4 .} 4. Bxb4 cxb4 5. Nd2 ({There is no need to rush with e4 as Black may be able to play ... d5 , similarly as after a5} 5. e4 d5 {.}) 5... Nf6 6. e4 {Here we can already play this move as with Nf6 on the board, White always has an option of e5 with tempo.} d6 {Here White has a huge choice.} 7. Qa4+ ({This leads to a very comfortable endgame. For example, Nc6} 7. d5 Qa5 {Qxa5 Nxa5} 8. Ngf3) (7. f4 $5 {is also good.}) *

