1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+ {The Keres Defense can be considered a variant of the Nimzo or Bogo Indian. Before developing the Ng8 , Black quickly brings out the bishop, perhaps intending to make ... f5 in the future. But it is still worse than the standard Nimzo, since now White is not pinned.} 3. Bd2 ({An alternative is} 3. Nd2 {which is also good, but} Bxd2+ {is the simplest to learn in my opinion. Of course, White does not play Nc3 as there are better options than transposing back to the Nimzo!}) 3... c5 {Without a knight on f6 , White again can play via e4 .} 4. Bxb4 cxb4 5. Nd2 ({There is no need to rush with e4 as Black may be able to play ... d5 , similarly as after a5} 5. e4 d5 {.}) 5... d5 {White should react in a positional manner.} 6. e3 Nf6 7. cxd5 exd5 (7... Nxd5 8. Ngf3 O-O 9. Bd3 a5 10. O-O {with such a strong center, White should be better.}) 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Qa4 O-O 10. Ne2 {Sooner or later White will play a3 and Black will suffer in the long-term because of the worse pawn structure.} ({Grabbing the pawn with} 10. Bxd7 Qxd7 11. Qxb4 {is also possible, but Black can have some activity here:} Qg4 12. Kf1 Nc6 {with compensation.}) *

