1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+ {The Keres Defense can be considered a variant of the Nimzo or Bogo Indian. Before developing the Ng8 , Black quickly brings out the bishop, perhaps intending to make ... f5 in the future. But it is still worse than the standard Nimzo, since now White is not pinned.} 3. Bd2 ({An alternative is} 3. Nd2 {which is also good, but} Bxd2+ {is the simplest to learn in my opinion. Of course, White does not play Nc3 as there are better options than transposing back to the Nimzo!}) 3... Bxd2+ {This was recently tried by Magnus Carlsen, following up with ... f5 , which is one of the main benefits of playing without ... Nf6 . Please note that White wants to play e4 and quickly control the center, so Black should do something about it. Alternatives involve 3... a5 , 3... Qe7 and 3... c5 .} 4. Qxd2 {Black must do something right now about e4 .} Nf6 5. Nc3 {Renewing the idea of e4 . This pretty much leaves Black with little choice.} d6 6. e4 e5 {Black may try ... d6 - e5 , to get control over the dark squares - but it isn't good.} 7. O-O-O ({The engine's top choice, but other moves also should give White an edge. Now, the tension in the center gets unpleasant for Black. exd4 Qxd4 Nc6} 7. Qe3 Be6 8. h3) *

