1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+ {The Keres Defense can be considered a variant of the Nimzo or Bogo Indian. Before developing the Ng8 , Black quickly brings out the bishop, perhaps intending to make ... f5 in the future. But it is still worse than the standard Nimzo, since now White is not pinned.} 3. Bd2 ({An alternative is} 3. Nd2 {which is also good, but} Bxd2+ {is the simplest to learn in my opinion. Of course, White does not play Nc3 as there are better options than transposing back to the Nimzo!}) 3... Bxd2+ {This was recently tried by Magnus Carlsen, following up with ... f5 , which is one of the main benefits of playing without ... Nf6 . Please note that White wants to play e4 and quickly control the center, so Black should do something about it. Alternatives involve 3... a5 , 3... Qe7 and 3... c5 .} 4. Qxd2 {Black must do something right now about e4 .} f5 {A logical continuation that takes advantage of the delayed development of Ng8 . The position resembles the Dutch, but with the bishops already exchanged, which helps White. For example, if Black opts for a Stonewall, the lack of the dark-squared bishop will certainly be a problem.} ({•} 4... d5 5. Nc3 Nf6 {- for this line, see here .}) ({•} 4... d6 5. Nc3 Nf6 {- see here .}) ({•} 4... b6 5. Nc3 Bb7 {This plan is also not great for Black. White gets a comfortable version of the Owen Defense.} 6. e4) 5. g3 {I think that going for the bishop's fianchetto is the best approach. White could have started with 5.Nc3 as well but sooner or later the bishop should come to g2 .} Nf6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nc3 d5 {Going for the Stonewall is another option. But without the dark-squared bishops, it is unlikely good.} 8. Nf3 c6 9. O-O Nbd7 {Black's usual plan here is ... b6 -... Bb7 , eventually trying to play .... c5 , or ... Ne4 and some ... g5 ideas. As White, one of the main ideas is to expand on the queenside with b4 - b5 , but also maneuvering the Nc3 towards e5 -square is an option, as we will see.} 10. Qc2 {A good square for the queen - in the event of opening the c-file White will be ready for it. Additionally, there is some pressure on the f5 -pawn, making it not possible to recapture it with the e-pawn!} Qe7 11. e3 {Supporting the center, but also potentially preparing the path for the knight: Ne2 - Nf4 - Nd3 .} b6 ({After} 11... dxc4 12. Nd2 Nb6 13. Ne2 {the c4 -pawn will fall anyway.} e5 14. dxe5 Qxe5 15. Nd4) 12. cxd5 {Generally White waits for ... b6 to capture on d5 . Then, the queenside is already somewhat compromised.} exd5 13. Rfc1 ({With the Qe7 , Black may have some compensation after} 13. Qxf5 Ba6 {as the e6 -square is covered and White cannot play Qe6 himself.}) 13... g6 14. Ne2 {With a nice positional advantage.} *

