1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+ {The Keres Defense can be considered a variant of the Nimzo or Bogo Indian. Before developing the Ng8 , Black quickly brings out the bishop, perhaps intending to make ... f5 in the future. But it is still worse than the standard Nimzo, since now White is not pinned.} 3. Bd2 ({An alternative is} 3. Nd2 {which is also good, but} Bxd2+ {is the simplest to learn in my opinion. Of course, White does not play Nc3 as there are better options than transposing back to the Nimzo!}) 3... Bxd2+ {This was recently tried by Magnus Carlsen, following up with ... f5 , which is one of the main benefits of playing without ... Nf6 . Please note that White wants to play e4 and quickly control the center, so Black should do something about it. Alternatives involve 3... a5 , 3... Qe7 and 3... c5 .} 4. Qxd2 {Black must do something right now about e4 .} f5 {A logical continuation that takes advantage of the delayed development of Ng8 . The position resembles the Dutch, but with the bishops already exchanged, which helps White. For example, if Black opts for a Stonewall, the lack of the dark-squared bishop will certainly be a problem.} ({•} 4... d5 5. Nc3 Nf6 {- for this line, see here .}) ({•} 4... d6 5. Nc3 Nf6 {- see here .}) ({•} 4... b6 5. Nc3 Bb7 {This plan is also not great for Black. White gets a comfortable version of the Owen Defense.} 6. e4) 5. g3 {I think that going for the bishop's fianchetto is the best approach. White could have started with 5.Nc3 as well but sooner or later the bishop should come to g2 .} Nf6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nc3 d6 {Black goes for a flexible center, trying to play ... e5 .} 8. Nf3 {Black should try to prepare ... e5 here. There are two moves that attempt to do so.} Qe7 9. O-O e5 {Possible, but Nd5 -ideas are again an issue.} 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nd5 {With unpleasant pressure.} Qd6 {The only move that does not lose! Here, White has a couple of options.} 12. Qa5 (12. Nxf6+ Rxf6 13. Qxd6 cxd6 {is simply better for White as well.} 14. Rfd1 Nc6 15. Rd2) 12... Nxd5 13. Qxd5+ Qxd5 14. cxd5 {The c7 -pawn is extremely weak and will fall soon. Black needs to be extremely careful not to lose the game quickly.} Nd7 15. Rfc1 e4 16. Nd4 Nf6 {Black must target the d5 -pawn. But here White retains a clear positional advantage.} 17. Rxc7 Nxd5 18. Rc5 Rd8 19. e3 {With a better position.} *

