1. d4 e6 2. c4 b6 {This is the English Defense. It is similar to the Owen Defense that begins with 1. e4  b6 and against which Wesley So found some interesting lines, playing without c4 and choosing Nc3 instead, in his LTR. In our move order, however, we do not have this option since the pawn is already on c4 , and this is considered an improvement for Black. But not to worry: White is better anyway, as we shall see in a moment!} 3. e4 {Given that our opponent did not stop us from building a strong center, we should take advantage of it!} Bb4+ {This is a new trend here, as recommended by modern engines.} 4. Bd2 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 Ne7 6. Nc3 d5 {Similar to immediate 5... d5 .} 7. Bd3 Ba6 ({After} 7... Nbc6 {we can transpose with} 8. cxd5 {at least. Or, Nf3!?} Nb4 9. Be2 {is also possible. dxe4 Nxe4} Bb7 {Ng3⩲}) 8. cxd5 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 exd5 10. e5 {Followed by f4 and Nf3 , with a small plus for White.} *

