1. d4 e6 2. c4 b6 {This is the English Defense. It is similar to the Owen Defense that begins with 1. e4  b6 and against which Wesley So found some interesting lines, playing without c4 and choosing Nc3 instead, in his LTR. In our move order, however, we do not have this option since the pawn is already on c4 , and this is considered an improvement for Black. But not to worry: White is better anyway, as we shall see in a moment!} 3. e4 {Given that our opponent did not stop us from building a strong center, we should take advantage of it!} Bb4+ {This is a new trend here, as recommended by modern engines.} 4. Bd2 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 Bb7 {This is too slow in challenging White's center.} 6. Nc3 Nf6 (6... Nh6 $6 {was played in some old games, most notably by late GM Tony Miles. White has many possible moves that lead to a huge advantage. Karpov played} 7. f4 f5 8. e5 Nf7 9. O-O-O g5 10. Nf3) 7. f3 {White enjoys a significant advantage thanks to his strong center.} *

