1. d4 e6 2. c4 b6 {This is the English Defense. It is similar to the Owen Defense that begins with 1. e4  b6 and against which Wesley So found some interesting lines, playing without c4 and choosing Nc3 instead, in his LTR. In our move order, however, we do not have this option since the pawn is already on c4 , and this is considered an improvement for Black. But not to worry: White is better anyway, as we shall see in a moment!} 3. e4 {Given that our opponent did not stop us from building a strong center, we should take advantage of it!} Bb4+ {This is a new trend here, as recommended by modern engines.} 4. Bd2 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 d5 6. Bd3 {The best move here.} Nc6 ({•} 6... Ba6 {is inaccurate.} 7. cxd5 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 exd5 9. e5 {White has an advantage thanks to the great control over the center.}) ({•} 6... dxc4 $6 {Black should not give up the center just like that.} 7. Bxc4 Bb7 8. Nc3 Nf6 9. Qe3 $1 O-O 10. Nf3) ({•} 6... dxe4 $2 7. Bxe4 {is of course bad for Black.}) 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nc3 Nge7 9. Nge2 {Here, Black has some choice.} Nb4 10. Bb1 dxe4 11. Bxe4 c6 {It may seem that Black has equalized. But it has not.} 12. a3 Nbd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 (13... Nxd5 14. O-O) 14. Bf3 {This is similar to the 4. e3 Nimzo covered in the part 1. Due to bad Bc8 and weakened queenside, White has better chances. There are ideas of Nf4 !?} *

