1. d4 e6 2. c4 b6 {This is the English Defense. It is similar to the Owen Defense that begins with 1. e4  b6 and against which Wesley So found some interesting lines, playing without c4 and choosing Nc3 instead, in his LTR. In our move order, however, we do not have this option since the pawn is already on c4 , and this is considered an improvement for Black. But not to worry: White is better anyway, as we shall see in a moment!} 3. e4 {Given that our opponent did not stop us from building a strong center, we should take advantage of it!} Bb4+ {This is a new trend here, as recommended by modern engines.} 4. Bd2 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 d5 6. Bd3 {The best move here.} Nc6 ({•} 6... Ba6 {is inaccurate.} 7. cxd5 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 exd5 9. e5 {White has an advantage thanks to the great control over the center.}) ({•} 6... dxc4 $6 {Black should not give up the center just like that.} 7. Bxc4 Bb7 8. Nc3 Nf6 9. Qe3 $1 O-O 10. Nf3) ({•} 6... dxe4 $2 7. Bxe4 {is of course bad for Black.}) 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nc3 Nge7 9. Nge2 {Here, Black has some choice.} dxe4 ({After} 9... O-O 10. f3 {we have a possible transposition. And if Black does not play ... dxe4 - well, we have a great version of a Carlsbad where we already comfortably played f3 and e4 !}) 10. Bxe4 Bf5 {White has a couple of options. One of the most challenging moves is somewhat surprising.} 11. f3 {White reinforces Be4 . Black does not have the luxury of trading on e4 now, since White will have a very strong center. Moreover, White will play O-O-O and h4 , with the idea of attacking on the kingside.} ({For instance,} 11. O-O {O-O-O} Qd7 12. h4 $5 {with the idea of g4 and h5 .}) *

