1. d4 e6 2. c4 b6 {This is the English Defense. It is similar to the Owen Defense that begins with 1. e4  b6 and against which Wesley So found some interesting lines, playing without c4 and choosing Nc3 instead, in his LTR. In our move order, however, we do not have this option since the pawn is already on c4 , and this is considered an improvement for Black. But not to worry: White is better anyway, as we shall see in a moment!} 3. e4 {Given that our opponent did not stop us from building a strong center, we should take advantage of it!} Bb4+ {This is a new trend here, as recommended by modern engines.} 4. Nd2 {Another interesting approach. Recently, it was tried by Vincent Keymer. It leads to very unbalanced positions. I focus on 4. Bd2 instead, but it's worth covering this new idea (less than 20 games vs 200+ after 5. Bd2 ) to some extent, as it can be challenging.} Bb7 5. Qc2 f5 {This is interesting too.} 6. exf5 Nf6 7. a3 {The simplest. White should not chase the pawns and instead focus on completing the development.} Be4 8. Qd1 ({A safe square for the queen. But not} 8. Qb3 $6 Nc6 $3) 8... Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 Bxf5 10. Nf3 O-O 11. Be2 {White is slightly better. We will castle soon and very likely b3 - Bb2 is the right setup. The bishop pair and the control over the center should give White good chances.} *

