1. d4 e6 2. c4 b6 {This is the English Defense. It is similar to the Owen Defense that begins with 1. e4  b6 and against which Wesley So found some interesting lines, playing without c4 and choosing Nc3 instead, in his LTR. In our move order, however, we do not have this option since the pawn is already on c4 , and this is considered an improvement for Black. But not to worry: White is better anyway, as we shall see in a moment!} 3. e4 {Given that our opponent did not stop us from building a strong center, we should take advantage of it!} Bb4+ {This is a new trend here, as recommended by modern engines.} 4. Nd2 {Another interesting approach. Recently, it was tried by Vincent Keymer. It leads to very unbalanced positions. I focus on 4. Bd2 instead, but it's worth covering this new idea (less than 20 games vs 200+ after 5. Bd2 ) to some extent, as it can be challenging.} Bb7 5. Qc2 c5 (5... Nh6 6. Ngf3 f5 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O {± was much better for White in Keymer-Meier (2023).}) 6. d5 f5 {This was tried in another game between Keymer and Meier (2023). Keymer had an excellent idea.} 7. a3 Ba5 (7... Bxd2+ 8. Bxd2 fxe4 9. O-O-O {! This had to be prepared by Keymer. The key line here goes as follows:} exd5 10. cxd5 Nf6 11. Bg5 O-O 12. Ne2 h6 13. Bh4 d6 {and here White has a pleasant choice between many moves:} 14. Nc3 {, Nf4 or even g4 . I would choose between g4 or Nc3 . Nc3} Nbd7 15. g4) 8. b4 cxb4 9. Qb2 {A surprising double attack!} bxa3 ({An absolutely forced move.} 9... Qf6 $2 {Meier made a serious mistake by playing this move. Now White is borderline winning.} 10. e5 Qe7 11. d6 bxa3 12. Rxa3 Bxd2+ 13. Bxd2 Qh4 14. Rg3 {with a winning advantage. Keymer-Meier (2023).}) 10. Rxa3 Bxd2+ 11. Bxd2 Nf6 {White has some choice here. The engine likes Rg3 !? the most.} 12. Rg3 {With some pressure and a generally complex struggle. That said, 5. Nd2 is a decent alternative if one wants to explore this line further.} *

