1. d4 e6 2. c4 b6 {This is the English Defense. It is similar to the Owen Defense that begins with 1. e4  b6 and against which Wesley So found some interesting lines, playing without c4 and choosing Nc3 instead, in his LTR. In our move order, however, we do not have this option since the pawn is already on c4 , and this is considered an improvement for Black. But not to worry: White is better anyway, as we shall see in a moment!} 3. e4 {Given that our opponent did not stop us from building a strong center, we should take advantage of it!} Bb7 {Throughout the years, it has been considered the correct move. As we will see - it is not.} 4. Bd3 ({Defending the center and avoiding getting pinned with} 4. Nc3 Bb4 {. Black has many options available now.}) 4... f5 {This is one of the main ideas behind playing ... b6 -... Bb7 as Black uses the ... f5 pawn break to attack the center, taking advantage of the soft g2 -pawn. However, it leads to a borderline lost position for Black.} 5. exf5 Bxg2 {This move is already losing for sure.} 6. Qh5+ g6 7. fxg6 Bg7 (7... Nf6 {loses to a classical trick} 8. g7+ $1) 8. gxh7+ Kf8 {In this case, to win White simply should not take the knight.} 9. Bg5 Nf6 10. Qh4 Bxh1 11. Ne2 {Despite being a whole rook down, White wins. Black's king is very weak and the idea of Nf4 - Ng6 is just lethal. Also, White may play Nd2 and O-O-O with a super strong attack.} Nc6 {The best defense. Now White should not rush with Nf4 .} 12. Nd2 (12. Nf4 $2 e5 $1 {is suddenly not entirely clear!} 13. Ng6+ Kf7 14. dxe5 Rxh7 15. Qg3 Nh5) 12... e5 13. O-O-O ({And I believe that White should win here quite easily: e4} 13. Be4 Bxe4 14. Nxe4 Rxh7 15. Qf4 Kf7 (15... Qe7 16. Bxf6 Qf7 17. Ng5 Qxc4 18. Nc3) {Rd3! Qe7} 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 {Rf3+-}) *

