1. d4 e6 2. c4 b6 {This is the English Defense. It is similar to the Owen Defense that begins with 1. e4  b6 and against which Wesley So found some interesting lines, playing without c4 and choosing Nc3 instead, in his LTR. In our move order, however, we do not have this option since the pawn is already on c4 , and this is considered an improvement for Black. But not to worry: White is better anyway, as we shall see in a moment!} 3. e4 {Given that our opponent did not stop us from building a strong center, we should take advantage of it!} Bb7 {Throughout the years, it has been considered the correct move. As we will see - it is not.} 4. Bd3 ({Defending the center and avoiding getting pinned with} 4. Nc3 Bb4 {. Black has many options available now.}) 4... f5 {This is one of the main ideas behind playing ... b6 -... Bb7 as Black uses the ... f5 pawn break to attack the center, taking advantage of the soft g2 -pawn. However, it leads to a borderline lost position for Black.} 5. exf5 Bb4+ (5... exf5 6. d5 {is of course terrible for Black.}) 6. Kf1 {With this move White pretty much just wins. Black has no counterplay whatsoever.} Nf6 {White has here many good options.} 7. a3 ({Probably the simplest.} 7. h4 $5 {is what the engine likes a lot too, but later a3 and Nc3 is played anyway.}) 7... Bd6 (7... Be7 {is similar but more passive.} 8. Nc3 O-O 9. h4 $5 {+-}) 8. Nc3 O-O 9. h4 ({There were also many other options, but this is the one the engine likes best. The point is that we intend to bring the rook into play via h3 and perhaps even launch an attack. White is on the verge of victory, e.g.} 9. c5 {d5 exd5 cxd5} Be5 10. Nge2) ({Qe8 Rh3 exf5} 9. Nf3 Ne4 {h5+- Stockfish is merciless: +2.5! But it makes sense: Black's king is pretty weak, and the idea of c5 is really hard to stop.}) *

