1. d4 e6 2. c4 b6 {This is the English Defense. It is similar to the Owen Defense that begins with 1. e4  b6 and against which Wesley So found some interesting lines, playing without c4 and choosing Nc3 instead, in his LTR. In our move order, however, we do not have this option since the pawn is already on c4 , and this is considered an improvement for Black. But not to worry: White is better anyway, as we shall see in a moment!} 3. e4 {Given that our opponent did not stop us from building a strong center, we should take advantage of it!} Bb7 {Throughout the years, it has been considered the correct move. As we will see - it is not.} 4. Bd3 ({Defending the center and avoiding getting pinned with} 4. Nc3 Bb4 {. Black has many options available now.}) 4... Nc6 {With this move Black attacks the d4 -pawn and if the pawn is defended, then he intends to play ... Nb4 next to get the pair of bishops. It is not a problem for White though - the strong center is more important than the pair of bishops.} 5. Ne2 g6 {Alireza Firouzja tried it in Titled Tuesday, but I don't think it can be good.} 6. Nbc3 Bg7 7. Be3 Nge7 8. O-O ({We got some version of the Hippopotamus Opening, which to start with does not have a good reputation for a reason. I think White is clearly better. If Black tries to open the center with} 8. d5 {the easiest would be cxd5} exd5 9. e5) *

