1. d4 e6 2. c4 b6 {This is the English Defense. It is similar to the Owen Defense that begins with 1. e4  b6 and against which Wesley So found some interesting lines, playing without c4 and choosing Nc3 instead, in his LTR. In our move order, however, we do not have this option since the pawn is already on c4 , and this is considered an improvement for Black. But not to worry: White is better anyway, as we shall see in a moment!} 3. e4 {Given that our opponent did not stop us from building a strong center, we should take advantage of it!} Bb7 {Throughout the years, it has been considered the correct move. As we will see - it is not.} 4. Bd3 ({Defending the center and avoiding getting pinned with} 4. Nc3 Bb4 {. Black has many options available now.}) 4... Bb4+ ({•} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Qc2 {transposes to Queen's Fianchetto.}) ({•} 4... d5 $2 {is just bad due to} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. e5 {and White gets a stable control over the center. Stockfish evaluates +1.7!}) 5. Kf1 {The most ambitious move. White does not want to trade pieces and instead intends to keep them all on the board to take advantage of having more space.} Be7 ({Black should retreat right away, as the bishop has done its job on b4 .} 5... Nc6 {The knight is misplaced here, and it can only run into d5 ideas in the future.} 6. Nf3 Be7 7. Nc3) ({After} 5... c5 6. a3 {the bishop is forced to go back to a5 where it is out of play, similarly (but in a worse version) to the Nimzo with e3 b6 Nge2 c5 a3} Ba5 {.}) 6. Nc3 d6 7. Nf3 Nd7 {Black tries to create some flexible setup and play ... e5 in the future. If White had castled, this would be of course bad, but here this is what Black's strategy relies on. However, no worries - the king on f1 is safe and we can bring in the h1 -rook in another way.} 8. h4 {Expanding on the kingside and potentially making use of the rook on h1 . Maybe Rh3 will be an idea in the future.} h5 {This move weakens the g5 -square, which White will likely exploit this soon.} 9. Qe2 (9. Rh3 $5 {is also interesting.}) 9... Ngf6 10. Ng5 {White is clearly better.} *

