1. d4 e6 2. c4 b6 {This is the English Defense. It is similar to the Owen Defense that begins with 1. e4  b6 and against which Wesley So found some interesting lines, playing without c4 and choosing Nc3 instead, in his LTR. In our move order, however, we do not have this option since the pawn is already on c4 , and this is considered an improvement for Black. But not to worry: White is better anyway, as we shall see in a moment!} 3. e4 {Given that our opponent did not stop us from building a strong center, we should take advantage of it!} Bb7 {Throughout the years, it has been considered the correct move. As we will see - it is not.} 4. Bd3 ({Defending the center and avoiding getting pinned with} 4. Nc3 Bb4 {. Black has many options available now.}) 4... Bb4+ ({•} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Qc2 {transposes to Queen's Fianchetto.}) ({•} 4... d5 $2 {is just bad due to} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. e5 {and White gets a stable control over the center. Stockfish evaluates +1.7!}) 5. Bd2 {If you want to play something more standard, you can try Bd2 .} Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 {This variation leads to White's advantage as well. White's plan is Nc3 , Nge2 , O-O and enjoy some space advantage, which means Black must react quickly.} f5 7. Nc3 ({I think White should be better here as well.  • fxe4 Bxe4 Bxe4 Nxe4 Nf6} 7. Nc3 $1 {Keeping more pieces on the board to enjoy the space advantage. O-O Nf3} Nc6 {O-O ⩲}) ({• Nf6} 7. f3 Nc6 8. e5 {Nh5} ({Ng8} 8. Qf4 $1 d6 {exd6} 9. Qxd6 Qxd6 {cxd6} 10. Ne2) {O-O-O} 8... Nxd4 9. Qe3 c5 10. Ne2) *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "49) Philidor Defense (1.d4 d6"]
[Black "Philidor - 3...Nbd7 4.f4 e5 5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]
[PlyCount "31"]

1. d4 d6 {This move order allows White to immediately take control of the center with e4 . This definitely seems the right way, although Black can play 2... Nf6 , which unfortunately does not allow us to play c4 and transpose to the Pirc or Philidor. However, I think we should not fear these openings, and I think my recommendations are quite convincing! Therefore: 2. e4 !} 2. e4 {Don't worry about having to study too many lines: my suggestions are relatively easy to learn, and we have an edge almost everywhere because of the space advantage.} ({• I would have loved to recommend here} 2. Nf3 {but unfortunately in the event of a transposition to the King's Indian after} Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 O-O {we don't get the Be2 - Be3 system, which I covered in part 1, as we already have Nf3 on the board.}) ({• After} 2. c4 {Black can play} e5 $1 {and unfortunately, we cannot get our King's Indian setups with Be2 - Be3 . We never want to play d5 so early,} 3. Nc3 {is met by} exd4 {and recapturing with the queen is not ideal. So the only reasonable move here seems} 4. Nf3 {but now Black can play e4! Ng5} f5 {and this line is pretty good for Black.}) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 {Here, Black can choose between Philidor and Pirc.} Nbd7 ({This move order, a specialty of Oleksandr Bortnyk, is usually played when a player is unwilling to enter an endgame after} 3... e5 4. dxe5 {. But here the problems are even greater.}) 4. f4 {Building a strong center and threatening e5 .} e5 5. Nf3 exd4 6. Qxd4 c6 7. Be3 {Simply completing development.} d5 {The main move. Black hits in the center, looking to create a mess on the board. It is not great, but alternatives are hardly any better.} ({•} 7... Be7 8. O-O-O O-O 9. e5) ({•} 7... Qb6 8. O-O-O Qxd4 9. Bxd4) 8. e5 {Black has two moves here.} Bc5 (8... Ng4 9. Bg1 {is similar as Bc5 needs to be played sooner or later and White will at some point play h3 - g4 . For example:} Bc5 10. Qd2 Bxg1 11. Rxg1 Qb6 12. Na4 Qe3+ 13. Qxe3 Nxe3 14. Bd3) 9. Qd2 Bxe3 ({The most popular recently. After} 9... Ne4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Nd4 Nb6 12. O-O-O {Black is still in trouble.}) 10. Qxe3 Ng4 11. Qd2 ({It is important to retreat here and avoid an unfavorable queen trade. For instance, Kramnik played} 11. Qd4 {and after} Qb6 {Black was doing OK.}) 11... Qb6 12. O-O-O Nc5 13. Nd4 Nh6 14. h3 Nf5 15. g4 Nxd4 16. Qxd4 {Black is nearly busted.} *

