1. d4 d6 {This move order allows White to immediately take control of the center with e4 . This definitely seems the right way, although Black can play 2... Nf6 , which unfortunately does not allow us to play c4 and transpose to the Pirc or Philidor. However, I think we should not fear these openings, and I think my recommendations are quite convincing! Therefore: 2. e4 !} 2. e4 {Don't worry about having to study too many lines: my suggestions are relatively easy to learn, and we have an edge almost everywhere because of the space advantage.} ({• I would have loved to recommend here} 2. Nf3 {but unfortunately in the event of a transposition to the King's Indian after} Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 O-O {we don't get the Be2 - Be3 system, which I covered in part 1, as we already have Nf3 on the board.}) ({• After} 2. c4 {Black can play} e5 $1 {and unfortunately, we cannot get our King's Indian setups with Be2 - Be3 . We never want to play d5 so early,} 3. Nc3 {is met by} exd4 {and recapturing with the queen is not ideal. So the only reasonable move here seems} 4. Nf3 {but now Black can play e4! Ng5} f5 {and this line is pretty good for Black.}) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 {Here, Black can choose between Philidor and Pirc.} e5 {The Philidor Defense does not have a great reputation and White should be better in many ways. My recommendation is fairly simple and easy to learn.} 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 {Here, Black can develop the bishop either to e7 or to g7 .} g6 {If Black plays this way, we obtain some sort of King's Indian with a pawn on c2 . This offers less control over the center, but we can more comfortably castle queenside and attack on the kingside.} 6. Be3 Bg7 (6... Ng4 7. Bf4 {does not change much. We will play f3 , Qd2 , and O-O-O with an advantage.} Bg7 8. f3 Ne5 9. Qd2 Nbc6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. O-O-O O-O 12. Bg5) 7. Qd2 {There is no need to spend time on f3 as we have always Bg5 with tempo.} O-O 8. O-O-O Re8 9. f3 Nc6 10. g4 {White controls the center and has attacking prospects on the kingside.} *

