1. d4 d6 {This move order allows White to immediately take control of the center with e4 . This definitely seems the right way, although Black can play 2... Nf6 , which unfortunately does not allow us to play c4 and transpose to the Pirc or Philidor. However, I think we should not fear these openings, and I think my recommendations are quite convincing! Therefore: 2. e4 !} 2. e4 {Don't worry about having to study too many lines: my suggestions are relatively easy to learn, and we have an edge almost everywhere because of the space advantage.} ({• I would have loved to recommend here} 2. Nf3 {but unfortunately in the event of a transposition to the King's Indian after} Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 O-O {we don't get the Be2 - Be3 system, which I covered in part 1, as we already have Nf3 on the board.}) ({• After} 2. c4 {Black can play} e5 $1 {and unfortunately, we cannot get our King's Indian setups with Be2 - Be3 . We never want to play d5 so early,} 3. Nc3 {is met by} exd4 {and recapturing with the queen is not ideal. So the only reasonable move here seems} 4. Nf3 {but now Black can play e4! Ng5} f5 {and this line is pretty good for Black.}) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 {Here, Black can choose between Philidor and Pirc.} e5 {The Philidor Defense does not have a great reputation and White should be better in many ways. My recommendation is fairly simple and easy to learn.} 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 {Here, Black can develop the bishop either to e7 or to g7 .} Be7 {White has many good plans and setups now. I would recommend the most popular lately.} 6. Bf4 O-O 7. Qd2 {The bishop is placed on f4 instead of e3 to avoid ... Ng4 ideas (as there would not be Bg5 with tempo) and also to put pressure in the center. White wants to castle queenside and if Black doesn't do anything concrete, a kingside attack will follow.} d5 ({Perhaps the most critical line where we need to memorize something.} 7... Nc6 {is a normal move, but it hardly offers equality.} 8. O-O-O Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Be6 10. f3 {White is simply better.}) 8. Ndb5 {We can see the benefit of having Bf4 ! We enter some forced line now but everything works out nicely for White.} Bb4 9. O-O-O c6 (9... Ba5 10. exd5 {is hardly an alternative for Black.} a6 11. Nd4 Bxc3 12. Qxc3 Nxd5 13. Qg3 Nxf4 14. Qxf4) 10. Nc7 Nxe4 11. Qd4 {White pretty much wins the a8 -rook and the compensation is extremely speculative...} Bxc3 12. bxc3 Qe7 {Looks scary for White, but we are just fine.} 13. c4 {Guarding everything.} Qa3+ 14. Qb2 Qa5 15. Nxa8 Nxf2 16. Bd2 ({I think this is the best, but} 16. Be2 {also looks like an advantage.}) 16... Qd8 17. cxd5 Nxd1 18. Kxd1 cxd5 (18... Qxd5 19. Kc1) 19. Bf4 Bg4+ 20. Kc1 Qe7 21. Bd3 ({And the knight is ready to escape. The only way to stop it is Rc8 but after} 21. Nc7 {Rxc7 Bxc7} Qxc7 {Re1 Be6} 22. Qe5 {we have great winning chances anyway.}) *

