1. d4 d6 {This move order allows White to immediately take control of the center with e4 . This definitely seems the right way, although Black can play 2... Nf6 , which unfortunately does not allow us to play c4 and transpose to the Pirc or Philidor. However, I think we should not fear these openings, and I think my recommendations are quite convincing! Therefore: 2. e4 !} 2. e4 {Don't worry about having to study too many lines: my suggestions are relatively easy to learn, and we have an edge almost everywhere because of the space advantage.} ({• I would have loved to recommend here} 2. Nf3 {but unfortunately in the event of a transposition to the King's Indian after} Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 O-O {we don't get the Be2 - Be3 system, which I covered in part 1, as we already have Nf3 on the board.}) ({• After} 2. c4 {Black can play} e5 $1 {and unfortunately, we cannot get our King's Indian setups with Be2 - Be3 . We never want to play d5 so early,} 3. Nc3 {is met by} exd4 {and recapturing with the queen is not ideal. So the only reasonable move here seems} 4. Nf3 {but now Black can play e4! Ng5} f5 {and this line is pretty good for Black.}) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 {Here, Black can choose between Philidor and Pirc.} e5 {The Philidor Defense does not have a great reputation and White should be better in many ways. My recommendation is fairly simple and easy to learn.} 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 {I would recommend the classical approach against the Philidor. It seems like there is a lot of theory but I will simplify it - in fact, there are only a couple of lines you need to know and it is mostly about navigating through these positions by ideas.} Be7 6. O-O c6 {Black can try to play without ... O-O but it is quite dubious.} 7. a4 {Of course we prevent ... b5 .} h6 8. Re1 Qc7 {Black intends ... g5 , ... Nf8 and ... Ng6 .} 9. h3 g5 ({An ultra aggressive plan that has a high chance of simply being punished.} 9... Nf8 {is worse due to} 10. Nh4 $1) 10. a5 Nf8 11. d5 {With the idea of a6 and all the light squares are going to be terribly weak for Black.} Ng6 (11... a6 {does not help much as it weakens the b6 -square.} 12. Nd2) 12. a6 b5 13. Bb3 {Black is in big trouble.} b4 14. Ba4 {The main idea. Black is borderline lost.} *

