1. d4 d6 {This move order allows White to immediately take control of the center with e4 . This definitely seems the right way, although Black can play 2... Nf6 , which unfortunately does not allow us to play c4 and transpose to the Pirc or Philidor. However, I think we should not fear these openings, and I think my recommendations are quite convincing! Therefore: 2. e4 !} 2. e4 {Don't worry about having to study too many lines: my suggestions are relatively easy to learn, and we have an edge almost everywhere because of the space advantage.} ({• I would have loved to recommend here} 2. Nf3 {but unfortunately in the event of a transposition to the King's Indian after} Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 O-O {we don't get the Be2 - Be3 system, which I covered in part 1, as we already have Nf3 on the board.}) ({• After} 2. c4 {Black can play} e5 $1 {and unfortunately, we cannot get our King's Indian setups with Be2 - Be3 . We never want to play d5 so early,} 3. Nc3 {is met by} exd4 {and recapturing with the queen is not ideal. So the only reasonable move here seems} 4. Nf3 {but now Black can play e4! Ng5} f5 {and this line is pretty good for Black.}) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 {Here, Black can choose between Philidor and Pirc.} e5 {The Philidor Defense does not have a great reputation and White should be better in many ways. My recommendation is fairly simple and easy to learn.} 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 {I would recommend the classical approach against the Philidor. It seems like there is a lot of theory but I will simplify it - in fact, there are only a couple of lines you need to know and it is mostly about navigating through these positions by ideas.} Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 {White supports his center in advance. Sometimes, we may make use of the f1 -square for the bishop. Black has many possible plans here, but White retains an edge everywhere.} a6 8. a4 b6 {Another plan for Black. White has many ways to continue here.} 9. Be3 Bb7 (9... c6 {transposes to 7...c6 .}) 10. d5 {I think that the resulting position is better for White and the plan is also relatively simple. Black faces issues as ... c6 is always strategically suspicious and another type of counterplay (... f5 ) will result in the weakening of the kingside. As White, we want to play b4 , a5 and put pressure on the queenside. In the event of ... a5 by Black, we can take advantage of weak light squares on the queenside with Bb5 , Nc4 and maybe Bc6 . Also, we can prepare the pawn break f4 , or b4 .} Kh8 11. b4 {Expanding on the queenside.} Ng8 12. Qe2 g6 {Black prepares ... f5 but we are way faster.} 13. a5 b5 14. Nxb5 ({A strong piece sacrifice. White's passed pawn should decide the game. For example, axb5} 14. Bxb5 f5 {a6+-}) *

