e resulting position is better for White and the plan is also relatively simple. Black faces issues as ... c6 is always strategically suspicious and another type of counterplay (... f5 ) will result in the weakening of the kingside. As White, we want to play b4 , a5 and put pressure on the queenside. In the event of ... a5 by Black, we can take advantage of weak light squares on the queenside with Bb5 , Nc4 and maybe Bc6 . Also, we can prepare the pawn break f4 , or b4 .} a5 ({•} 10... g6 {allows} 11. Bh6 {and Black's rook will be displaced on f8 .}) ({•} 10... Ng4 11. Bd2 {does not change much.}) 11. Nd2 Kh8 12. Bb5 Ng8 13. Rf1 ({Intending f4 next. Also interesting is} 13. Nc4 $5) *

