1. d4 d6 {This move order allows White to immediately take control of the center with e4 . This definitely seems the right way, although Black can play 2... Nf6 , which unfortunately does not allow us to play c4 and transpose to the Pirc or Philidor. However, I think we should not fear these openings, and I think my recommendations are quite convincing! Therefore: 2. e4 !} 2. e4 {Don't worry about having to study too many lines: my suggestions are relatively easy to learn, and we have an edge almost everywhere because of the space advantage.} ({• I would have loved to recommend here} 2. Nf3 {but unfortunately in the event of a transposition to the King's Indian after} Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 O-O {we don't get the Be2 - Be3 system, which I covered in part 1, as we already have Nf3 on the board.}) ({• After} 2. c4 {Black can play} e5 $1 {and unfortunately, we cannot get our King's Indian setups with Be2 - Be3 . We never want to play d5 so early,} 3. Nc3 {is met by} exd4 {and recapturing with the queen is not ideal. So the only reasonable move here seems} 4. Nf3 {but now Black can play e4! Ng5} f5 {and this line is pretty good for Black.}) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 {Here, Black can choose between Philidor and Pirc.} e5 {The Philidor Defense does not have a great reputation and White should be better in many ways. My recommendation is fairly simple and easy to learn.} 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 {I would recommend the classical approach against the Philidor. It seems like there is a lot of theory but I will simplify it - in fact, there are only a couple of lines you need to know and it is mostly about navigating through these positions by ideas.} Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 {White supports his center in advance. Sometimes, we may make use of the f1 -square for the bishop. Black has many possible plans here, but White retains an edge everywhere.} a6 8. a4 b6 {Another plan for Black. White has many ways to continue here.} 9. Nd5 {This is also a good option, trying to get the bishop pair. It takes advantage of Black's pawn being still on c7 .} Bb7 (9... Nxd5 10. Bxd5 Rb8 {is possible but quite sad for Black.} 11. Qe2 a5 12. Be3 Bb7 13. Bxb7 Rxb7 14. Rad1) 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Bd3 {Supporting the center. Having won the bishop pair this looks better for White.} exd4 12. Nxd4 Rfe8 13. Nf5 Qf8 14. Ng3 Nc5 15. f3 {White is better due to the space advantage. In case of ... d5 , White will play e5 , and this would open the door to potential attacks on the kingside.} *

