1. d4 d6 {This move order allows White to immediately take control of the center with e4 . This definitely seems the right way, although Black can play 2... Nf6 , which unfortunately does not allow us to play c4 and transpose to the Pirc or Philidor. However, I think we should not fear these openings, and I think my recommendations are quite convincing! Therefore: 2. e4 !} 2. e4 {Don't worry about having to study too many lines: my suggestions are relatively easy to learn, and we have an edge almost everywhere because of the space advantage.} ({• I would have loved to recommend here} 2. Nf3 {but unfortunately in the event of a transposition to the King's Indian after} Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 O-O {we don't get the Be2 - Be3 system, which I covered in part 1, as we already have Nf3 on the board.}) ({• After} 2. c4 {Black can play} e5 $1 {and unfortunately, we cannot get our King's Indian setups with Be2 - Be3 . We never want to play d5 so early,} 3. Nc3 {is met by} exd4 {and recapturing with the queen is not ideal. So the only reasonable move here seems} 4. Nf3 {but now Black can play e4! Ng5} f5 {and this line is pretty good for Black.}) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 {Here, Black can choose between Philidor and Pirc.} e5 {The Philidor Defense does not have a great reputation and White should be better in many ways. My recommendation is fairly simple and easy to learn.} 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 {I would recommend the classical approach against the Philidor. It seems like there is a lot of theory but I will simplify it - in fact, there are only a couple of lines you need to know and it is mostly about navigating through these positions by ideas.} Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 {White supports his center in advance. Sometimes, we may make use of the f1 -square for the bishop. Black has many possible plans here, but White retains an edge everywhere.} exd4 8. Nxd4 {Here we can recapture both with the knight and the queen. 8. Qxd4 is completely playable too.} Nb6 {With the idea of a quick ... d5 is possible but not great for Black.} 9. Bf1 ({This can also arise after Nb6} 9. Bf1 {exd4 Nxd4 .}) 9... d5 10. e5 Ne8 {This position may be not so easy to evaluate at first, especially if one is unfamiliar with it. Black's central pawn has the potential of quickly advancing and pushing back White's pieces. However, it is not that great for Black, as we will see shortly.} 11. a4 a5 ({Now, if ... c5 then the b5 -square will be weak. Advancing the pawns with} 11... c5 12. Nde2 d4 13. Ne4 {actually results only in the weakening of Black's position. White will play c3 soon.} Nd7 14. f4) 12. Nce2 c6 13. Nf4 {White is definitely better. b3 could be played next, controlling c4 but also making room on the long diagonal for the dark-squared bishop.} *

