1. d4 d6 {This move order allows White to immediately take control of the center with e4 . This definitely seems the right way, although Black can play 2... Nf6 , which unfortunately does not allow us to play c4 and transpose to the Pirc or Philidor. However, I think we should not fear these openings, and I think my recommendations are quite convincing! Therefore: 2. e4 !} 2. e4 {Don't worry about having to study too many lines: my suggestions are relatively easy to learn, and we have an edge almost everywhere because of the space advantage.} ({• I would have loved to recommend here} 2. Nf3 {but unfortunately in the event of a transposition to the King's Indian after} Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 O-O {we don't get the Be2 - Be3 system, which I covered in part 1, as we already have Nf3 on the board.}) ({• After} 2. c4 {Black can play} e5 $1 {and unfortunately, we cannot get our King's Indian setups with Be2 - Be3 . We never want to play d5 so early,} 3. Nc3 {is met by} exd4 {and recapturing with the queen is not ideal. So the only reasonable move here seems} 4. Nf3 {but now Black can play e4! Ng5} f5 {and this line is pretty good for Black.}) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 {Here, Black can choose between Philidor and Pirc.} e5 {The Philidor Defense does not have a great reputation and White should be better in many ways. My recommendation is fairly simple and easy to learn.} 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 {I would recommend the classical approach against the Philidor. It seems like there is a lot of theory but I will simplify it - in fact, there are only a couple of lines you need to know and it is mostly about navigating through these positions by ideas.} Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 {White supports his center in advance. Sometimes, we may make use of the f1 -square for the bishop. Black has many possible plans here, but White retains an edge everywhere.} exd4 8. Nxd4 {Here we can recapture both with the knight and the queen. 8. Qxd4 is completely playable too.} Ne5 9. Bf1 {We don't have the a2 square available, but this is fine as well.} Re8 ({Making space for the bishop on f8 .} 9... Ng6 $6 10. Nf5 $1 {and White gets the bishop pair.}) 10. h3 {White has two good plans here: Bf4 , Qd2 , Rad1 , or f4 !?. It is simply a matter of taste.} c6 11. f4 (11. Bf4 Ng6 12. Bh2 {is also very good.}) 11... Ng6 12. a4 {Preventing any ideas connected to ... b5 in advance. Black's position is passive. Anytime Black plays via ... d5 we react with e5 . We can proceed with g3 - Bg2 or Bd3 .} Bd7 13. g3 (13. Kh1 $5 Bf8 14. Bd3 {is a different plan: Nf3 - f5 comes soon, hoping to launch an attack on the kingside (even a pawn storm could be possible).}) 13... Bf8 14. Bg2 {Black does not have much counterplay here.} *

