{Black does not have enough compensation. exd5 Qxd5+ Kh8 Rf1! +- is the point. Qe3 Rae1+- Qf4+ g3 Qf2+ Bg2+-} 1. d4 d6 {This move order allows White to immediately take control of the center with e4 . This definitely seems the right way, although Black can play 2... Nf6 , which unfortunately does not allow us to play c4 and transpose to the Pirc or Philidor. However, I think we should not fear these openings, and I think my recommendations are quite convincing! Therefore: 2. e4 !} 2. e4 {Don't worry about having to study too many lines: my suggestions are relatively easy to learn, and we have an edge almost everywhere because of the space advantage.} ({• I would have loved to recommend here} 2. Nf3 {but unfortunately in the event of a transposition to the King's Indian after} Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 O-O {we don't get the Be2 - Be3 system, which I covered in part 1, as we already have Nf3 on the board.}) ({• After} 2. c4 {Black can play} e5 $1 {and unfortunately, we cannot get our King's Indian setups with Be2 - Be3 . We never want to play d5 so early,} 3. Nc3 {is met by} exd4 {and recapturing with the queen is not ideal. So the only reasonable move here seems} 4. Nf3 {but now Black can play e4! Ng5} f5 {and this line is pretty good for Black.}) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 {Here, Black can choose between Philidor and Pirc.} e5 {The Philidor Defense does not have a great reputation and White should be better in many ways. My recommendation is fairly simple and easy to learn.} 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 {I would recommend the classical approach against the Philidor. It seems like there is a lot of theory but I will simplify it - in fact, there are only a couple of lines you need to know and it is mostly about navigating through these positions by ideas.} Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 {White supports his center in advance. Sometimes, we may make use of the f1 -square for the bishop. Black has many possible plans here, but White retains an edge everywhere.} c6 8. a4 a5 {Possible too but here Black does not have ideas with ... b5 anymore.} 9. h3 exd4 ({•} 9... h6 10. Be3 Re8 11. d5 $5 {I think that after gaining space Black's position is unpleasant.} Nb6 12. Nd2 ({Nf8} 12. Nd2 {Ng6 Bf1±})) ({•} 9... Nb6 {is similar to exd4 Nxd4 Nb6 . The presence of the a4 and a5 pawns does not really matter.} 10. Bf1 exd4 11. Nxd4 d5 12. e5 Ne8 13. Nce2 {- see here for more details on such a structure.}) 10. Nxd4 Nc5 {Black goes for ... Be6 . This position is in fact pretty solid for Black.} 11. Bg5 {I would recommend this line. The idea is to provoke ... h6 and only then play Bf4 . It is quite deep, but as we will see, it is actually very important.} ({The main move is} 11. Bf4 {, but after} Be6 {apparently Black is not doing that badly.} 12. Bf1 {This is what we do with the inclusion of 11. Bg5  h6 12. Bf4 .} (12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. e5 Nfd7 14. exd6 Rxf4 15. dxe7 Qxe7 {looks acceptable for Black.}) 12... Re8 13. Qf3 {So far, we follow the game Navara-Plat (2017). Here Black can equalize with} d5 $1 {Ν as after} 14. Rad1 dxe4 $1 15. Qg3 {Black can just step aside with} Qc8 {with an unclear position.}) ({However, the inclusion of} 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bf4 {would make the h6 -pawn vulnerable to the immediate Bxh6 ! That is the key difference between 11. Bg5 and 11. Bf4 .}) 11... Be6 12. Nxe6 fxe6 {Black generally needs to recapture with the pawn and try to play ... d5 . But we are the first ones to develop an initiative.} (12... Nxe6 13. Be3 {is just better for White.}) 13. e5 Nd5 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. exd6 Qh4 {This move may be tempting, but it does not work.} 16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. Bxd5 Qxf2+ 18. Kh2 *

