ter gaining space Black's position is unpleasant.} Nb6 12. Nd2 ({Nf8} 12. Nd2 {Ng6 Bf1±})) ({•} 9... Nb6 {is similar to exd4 Nxd4 Nb6 . The presence of the a4 and a5 pawns does not really matter.} 10. Bf1 exd4 11. Nxd4 d5 12. e5 Ne8 13. Nce2 {- see here for more details on such a structure.}) 10. Nxd4 Nc5 {Black goes for ... Be6 . This position is in fact pretty solid for Black.} 11. Bg5 {I would recommend this line. The idea is to provoke ... h6 and only then play Bf4 . It is quite deep, but as we will see, it is actually very important.} ({The main move is} 11. Bf4 {, but after} Be6 {apparently Black is not doing that badly.} 12. Bf1 {This is what we do with the inclusion of 11. Bg5  h6 12. Bf4 .} (12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. e5 Nfd7 14. exd6 Rxf4 15. dxe7 Qxe7 {looks acceptable for Black.}) 12... Re8 13. Qf3 {So far, we follow the game Navara-Plat (2017). Here Black can equalize with} d5 $1 {Ν as after} 14. Rad1 dxe4 $1 15. Qg3 {Black can just step aside with} Qc8 {with an unclear position.}) ({However, the inclusion of} 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bf4 {would make the h6 -pawn vulnerable to the immediate Bxh6 ! That is the key difference between 11. Bg5 and 11. Bf4 .}) 11... Be6 12. Nxe6 fxe6 {Black generally needs to recapture with the pawn and try to play ... d5 . But we are the first ones to develop an initiative.} (12... Nxe6 13. Be3 {is just better for White.}) 13. e5 Nd5 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. exd6 Qxd6 16. Ne4 {Black will struggle due to the isolated and weak e6 -pawn.} Nxe4 (16... Qf4 17. Qd4 Nxe4 18. Rxe4 Qf6 19. Rae1 Qxd4 20. Rxd4 {and White has a clearly better endgame.}) 17. Rxe4 Rf6 18. Qd4 Raf8 19. Rae1 Kh8 20. R1e2 {This is also great for White. In a game Solozhenkin-Kunin (2009) followed ... Qb4 , when we simply need to cover the f4 -square.} Qb4 21. g3 ({Instead, the} 21. Rxe6 $4 {blunder was played and after} Nf4 $1 {Black won.}) 21... Qxa4 22. Qe5 {Black's queen will run into some discovery.} *

