1. d4 d6 {This move order allows White to immediately take control of the center with e4 . This definitely seems the right way, although Black can play 2... Nf6 , which unfortunately does not allow us to play c4 and transpose to the Pirc or Philidor. However, I think we should not fear these openings, and I think my recommendations are quite convincing! Therefore: 2. e4 !} 2. e4 {Don't worry about having to study too many lines: my suggestions are relatively easy to learn, and we have an edge almost everywhere because of the space advantage.} ({• I would have loved to recommend here} 2. Nf3 {but unfortunately in the event of a transposition to the King's Indian after} Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 O-O {we don't get the Be2 - Be3 system, which I covered in part 1, as we already have Nf3 on the board.}) ({• After} 2. c4 {Black can play} e5 $1 {and unfortunately, we cannot get our King's Indian setups with Be2 - Be3 . We never want to play d5 so early,} 3. Nc3 {is met by} exd4 {and recapturing with the queen is not ideal. So the only reasonable move here seems} 4. Nf3 {but now Black can play e4! Ng5} f5 {and this line is pretty good for Black.}) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 {Here, Black can choose between Philidor and Pirc.} e5 {The Philidor Defense does not have a great reputation and White should be better in many ways. My recommendation is fairly simple and easy to learn.} 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 {I would recommend the classical approach against the Philidor. It seems like there is a lot of theory but I will simplify it - in fact, there are only a couple of lines you need to know and it is mostly about navigating through these positions by ideas.} Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 {White supports his center in advance. Sometimes, we may make use of the f1 -square for the bishop. Black has many possible plans here, but White retains an edge everywhere.} c6 8. a4 b6 ({The main move.} 8... Qc7 {This move seems a bit weird to me as I am not sure what is the follow-up. Perhaps there could be some transposition, but this move order just seems a bit odd. Anyway, we go for same setups.} 9. h3 h6 10. Be3 Re8 11. a5 {or} d5) 9. Be3 {Not the most common move here, but I like it a lot. I don't think we need to worry about ... Ng4 for now, as Be3 has a certain tactical idea which h3 lacks.} ({•} 9. d5 {is a typical idea here, which I recommend after the inclusion of 9. Be3  a6 , because here White cannot hold comfortably a piece on the d5 square.} cxd5 10. Bxd5 (10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. Bxd5 Rb8 {and Nf6 is coming.}) 10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Nf6 {and in comparison with what we have in the main line, this would not be possible as thanks to inclusion of Be3 and ... a6 moves, the b6 -pawn would hang.}) ({• After} 9. h3 a6 10. d5 {(trying the same thing as in the main line)} cxd5 11. Bxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 {the b6 -pawn is not under pressure and this allows Black to play} Nf6 {and fight off the Nd5 . This is not the case after 9. Be3 . Still, White is a bit better here, but it feels like Black managed to deal with at least some of his problems...}) 9... Ng4 {Possible of course, but we drop back to d2 and considering the knight will have to return sooner or later anyway, we get a similar position with Bd2 instead of Bc1 , which can be a useful tempo as our rooks are connected in any case.} 10. Bd2 Ngf6 ({Black probably needs to go back. After} 10... a6 $6 {we can transpose with} 11. h3 {or try} d5 $5 {which with the knight on g4 makes a lot of sense as in the event of trades we can obtain the d5 square easily.}) 11. h3 (11. b4 $5 {is also interesting, fighting for the light squares.}) 11... a6 ({A little prophylaxis, preparing ... Bb7 .} 11... Bb7 {can be met with} 12. a5 $5) 12. Ba2 Rb8 {In comparison with the normal line, we have an extra tempo of Bd2 which can be useful.} 13. Qe2 b5 14. axb5 axb5 15. b4 {White is slightly better. We will play Bb3 , at some point maybe d5 too.} *

