nsposition, but this move order just seems a bit odd. Anyway, we go for same setups.} 9. h3 h6 10. Be3 Re8 11. a5 {or} d5) 9. Be3 {Not the most common move here, but I like it a lot. I don't think we need to worry about ... Ng4 for now, as Be3 has a certain tactical idea which h3 lacks.} ({•} 9. d5 {is a typical idea here, which I recommend after the inclusion of 9. Be3  a6 , because here White cannot hold comfortably a piece on the d5 square.} cxd5 10. Bxd5 (10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. Bxd5 Rb8 {and Nf6 is coming.}) 10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Nf6 {and in comparison with what we have in the main line, this would not be possible as thanks to inclusion of Be3 and ... a6 moves, the b6 -pawn would hang.}) ({• After} 9. h3 a6 10. d5 {(trying the same thing as in the main line)} cxd5 11. Bxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 {the b6 -pawn is not under pressure and this allows Black to play} Nf6 {and fight off the Nd5 . This is not the case after 9. Be3 . Still, White is a bit better here, but it feels like Black managed to deal with at least some of his problems...}) 9... Bb7 {Possible but it declares the intention of the bishop a bit early. Now, we may go for Nh4 - Nf5 ideas at some point.} 10. Ba2 {If we intend to make use of the f5 -square, it may be useful to remove the bishop from the c4 -square. That way dxe5 -... Nxe5 does not come with a tempo.} a6 11. dxe5 Nxe5 (11... dxe5 $6 12. Nh4 $1) 12. Nd4 {With a clear advantage.} *

