1. d4 d6 {This move order allows White to immediately take control of the center with e4 . This definitely seems the right way, although Black can play 2... Nf6 , which unfortunately does not allow us to play c4 and transpose to the Pirc or Philidor. However, I think we should not fear these openings, and I think my recommendations are quite convincing! Therefore: 2. e4 !} 2. e4 {Don't worry about having to study too many lines: my suggestions are relatively easy to learn, and we have an edge almost everywhere because of the space advantage.} ({• I would have loved to recommend here} 2. Nf3 {but unfortunately in the event of a transposition to the King's Indian after} Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 O-O {we don't get the Be2 - Be3 system, which I covered in part 1, as we already have Nf3 on the board.}) ({• After} 2. c4 {Black can play} e5 $1 {and unfortunately, we cannot get our King's Indian setups with Be2 - Be3 . We never want to play d5 so early,} 3. Nc3 {is met by} exd4 {and recapturing with the queen is not ideal. So the only reasonable move here seems} 4. Nf3 {but now Black can play e4! Ng5} f5 {and this line is pretty good for Black.}) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 {Here, Black can choose between Philidor and Pirc.} c6 {The idea of this move is to play ... Qa5 and put pressure on White's center. We can easily deal with it.} 4. f4 Qa5 5. Bd3 e5 6. Nf3 {This line is simply bad for Black, but some ideas we should know some ideas anyway.} exd4 (6... Nbd7 7. O-O Be7 8. Kh1 O-O 9. Be3 {with such control over the center White is much better.}) 7. Nxd4 g6 {One of the setups for Black.} 8. O-O Bg7 9. Kh1 O-O 10. f5 Nbd7 11. Qe1 {White launches an attack on the kingside.} *

