1. d4 d6 {This move order allows White to immediately take control of the center with e4 . This definitely seems the right way, although Black can play 2... Nf6 , which unfortunately does not allow us to play c4 and transpose to the Pirc or Philidor. However, I think we should not fear these openings, and I think my recommendations are quite convincing! Therefore: 2. e4 !} 2. e4 {Don't worry about having to study too many lines: my suggestions are relatively easy to learn, and we have an edge almost everywhere because of the space advantage.} ({• I would have loved to recommend here} 2. Nf3 {but unfortunately in the event of a transposition to the King's Indian after} Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 O-O {we don't get the Be2 - Be3 system, which I covered in part 1, as we already have Nf3 on the board.}) ({• After} 2. c4 {Black can play} e5 $1 {and unfortunately, we cannot get our King's Indian setups with Be2 - Be3 . We never want to play d5 so early,} 3. Nc3 {is met by} exd4 {and recapturing with the queen is not ideal. So the only reasonable move here seems} 4. Nf3 {but now Black can play e4! Ng5} f5 {and this line is pretty good for Black.}) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 {Here, Black can choose between Philidor and Pirc.} g6 {Against the Pirc, I would recommend an aggressive plan, yet still quite easy to learn.} 4. Be3 {White wants to play Qd2 , O-O-O and attack on the kingside. However, there are also ideas connected with f4 and building a strong center. Using the move order 4. Be3 avoids many lines after the immediate 4. f4 that are considered OK for Black.} Bg7 {The main move but there are ideas here of delaying ... Bg7 as well.} 5. Qd2 c6 {Black should not rush with castling and begin some counterplay on the queenside with ... b5 , or some ... Qa5 .} (5... Nbd7 {is possible, but I am not sure if it makes sense to declare the knight's intentions so early.} 6. Bh6 O-O 7. O-O-O) ({I don't like f3} 5... b5 {where it seems like Black gets a strong counterplay. In the event of O-O-O , Black's attack can be quite fast, especially since Black has not castled yet!}) 6. Bh6 {I tried to make Bh6 work, but unfortunately I could not find anything convincing.} Bxh6 7. Qxh6 e5 {Followed by ... Qe7 , ... Nbd7 and ... b5 . There are some ideas of course for White, but nothing I particularly like...} 8. O-O-O ({Trying to transpose to the main line with} 8. Nf3 Qe7 9. O-O-O {does not work that great, as Black does not have to play} Nbd7 {with a transposition, but can play at first Bg4!⇆ and then ... Nbd7 next with a comfortable position for Black.}) 8... Qe7 9. f3 ({•} 9. Be2 Nbd7 10. f4 b5) ({•} 9. d5 cxd5 10. exd5 a6) 9... exd4 10. Rxd4 Be6 *

